<SLUG> BC-Australia-Bougainville </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Neighbors beg Papua New Guinea on Bougainville government
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALAN THORNHILL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Pacific neighbors Australia and New
Zealand jointly appealed to Papua New Guinea on Thursday to quickly
set up a reconciliation government on the secessionist island of
Bougainville.
	   Papua New Guinea's Parliament adjourned Wednesday without
passing the legislation needed to set up the proposed all-party
government, agreed upon as part of cease-fire arrangements after a
secessionist conflict lasting some 10 years on Bougainville.
	   Parliament is not due to reconvene in Papua New Guinea until
next July 13.
	   Australia's Foreign Minister Alexander Downer and his New
Zealand counterpart Don McKinnon made the appeal together in
Canberra, after regular talks between the two governments.
	   The Papua New Guinea opposition blamed that country's Prime
Minister Bill Skate for the failure, saying he had adjourned
Parliament early to avoid a no-confidence motion that would have
brought down his government.
	   Papua New Guinea opposition leader Bernard Narakobi said Skate
had put the entire country's political and social stability at
risk.
	   Both Downer and McKinnon urged the Papua New Guinea Parliament
to reconvene, however briefly, to pass the legislation needed to
set up the reconciliation government.
	   McKinnon said the women of Bougainville, in particular, are
anxious for peace and stability to be restored on the island, the
site of what was once the world's biggest copper mine.
	   ``The important thing is to get things back to normal,''
McKinnon said.
	   He said children on the island had not attended school for 10
years, because of the secessionist conflict.
	   Bougainville became part of Papua New Guinea when that country
gained independence from its colonial ruler, Australia, in 1975.
	   But racial and financial differences quickly led to the
secessionist conflict.
	   Despite its riches, Bougainville is one of the least developed
places on earth, and the schools and hospitals it had all ceased to
operate during the war.
	   New Zealand helped to broker the cease-fire that brought the
fighting to at least a temporary end.
	   Australia is supporting it logistically with peace monitoring
troops and other resources, costing some 4 million Australian
dollars (U.S. dlrs 2.5 million) a month.
	   The interim reconciliation government was to have been made up
of a mix of elected and appointed representatives from all factions
involved in the conflict on Bougainville, which ended with the
signing of the peace accord early this year.
	   An interim government will continue to rule the island until the
reconciliation government is established. 	   
</TEXT>
