<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Human Rights, HFR,0899 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
For release at 1430 GMT
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Human Rights Watch report says U.S. 'out of step' &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID BRISCOE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The Clinton administration has ``large blind
spots'' with regard to human rights, ignoring abuses in many
countries and being ``severely out of step with most of the rest of
the world'' on major issues, Human Rights Watch said Thursday.
	   The largest U.S.-based human rights organization, which monitors
conditions everywhere with offices in 10 countries, also praised
Kofi Annan for showing ``a greater commitment to human rights than
any other U.N. secretary-general.''
	   But it had harsh words in its annual report for several
governments and accused both the United States and the European
Union of failures and inconsistencies.
	   The organization's 1999 report analyzes human rights in 68
countries and says that nearly all governments now realize they can
no longer dismiss abuses as a purely domestic matter.
	   ``Today, human rights are well established as the legitimate
concern of all humanity,'' said the report, released a week before
the 50th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
	   The group cited a growing willingness by countries to raise
concerns with each other over matters that previously might have
been dismissed as internal.
	   The outcry by leaders of Indonesia and the Philippines against
the detention of Malaysian official Anwar Ibrahim and the possible
extradition of former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet from
Britain to Spain are cited as examples.
	   ``Pinochet's arrest makes a very nice 50th-anniversary
present,'' said Kenneth Roth, Human Rights Watch executive
director.
	   The report harshly rebukes several governments for outright
abuses and reserves some of its toughest criticism for the U.S.
government for its reluctance to join key international treaties on
landmines and the setting up of an International Court of Justice
and for lack of leadership in trying to end a variety of abuses.
	   By refusing to sanction the court, which needs only one more
ratifying government to be set up, ``Washington revealed itself
once more to be severely out of step with most of the rest of the
world,'' the report said.
	   Fearing U.S. soldiers could face politically motivated charges,
the United States has refused to sign without the option of vetoing
the prosecution of any American citizen.
	   ``The Clinton administration's efforts to promote human rights
around the world were subject to large blind spots,'' the report
said. ``Major parts of Africa, the Middle East and the former
Soviet Union never made it to the administration's human rights
agenda.''
	   State Department officials did not immediately return phone
calls seeking comment on the report. But in the past, the White
House has defended its leadership in human rights, citing its
sanctions, its annual report of abuses and frequent statements
critical of repressive regimes.
	   While praising the European Union for conditioning aid and trade
preferences on respect for human rights, the report said the EU
applied its policies inconsistently and is slow in responding to
crises because of its practice of requiring a consensus before
taking action.
	   But the report does not focus solely on the role of outsiders in
stopping abuses.
	   In Africa, it finds backsliding by several governments just a
year after the continent appeared to be heading toward
unprecedented progress.
	   ``African leadership repeatedly stumbled in finding solutions to
the continent's grave political and human rights problems of
1998,'' the report said.
	   In the Middle East, it says civil strife in Algeria, trouble
over weapons inspections and suffering from sanctions in Iraq, and
moribund Israeli-Palestinian negotiations generated ``largely
negative human rights consequences.''
	   In former Soviet states, the report cites near chaos and
economic collapse in Russia, a deterioration of human rights in
several other former Soviet States and growing religious
persecution in the region.
	   In Latin America, Human Rights Watch says impunity for powerful
criminals, a ``yawning gap between rich and poor'' and corrupt and
ineffective police and judiciaries left many nations ``victims to
seemingly uncontrollable crime.''
	   In Asia, the report cites the economic crisis as the key factor
in denial of human rights in East Asia, while South Asia's human
rights landscape remained ``depressingly familiar,'' with abuses
linked to armed conflict, violence against women and failure to
protect refugees.
	   While focusing largely on abuses, the report also cited some
positive developments since the 1948 declaration in which world
governments vowed to protect human rights.
	   It said concern now extends beyond the victims of political
repression to include human rights protection for women, children,
refugees, civilians in wartime, gays, and ethnic and religious
minorities.
	   In praising Annan and the United Nations, it noted an October
decision to bar the use of children under 18 in U.N. peacekeeping
forces and the inclusion of human rights in the programs of several
U.N. agencies.
	   It credited U.N. High Commissioner of Refugees Mary Robinson for
shifting the agency's focus from distribution of relief goods to
its more critical role of protecting refugees from abuse. 	   
</TEXT>
