w1271 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HumanRights-Glance HFR   12-03 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Human Rights-Glance, HFR,0677 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
For release at 1430 GMT
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Human Rights Watch report cites abuses worldwide &QL; 
 &UR; With Human Rights &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The annual Human Rights Watch report released
Thursday cites abuses in countries around the world, covering the
year through November. Some of its conclusions on individual
countries:
	   AFGHANISTAN _ Afghanistan remained ``one of the world's most
intractable human rights disasters,'' with fighting between the
dominant Taliban and opposition forces. The ultraconservative
Islamic Taliban conducted many public executions and established a
pattern of repression of women on religious grounds.
	   ANGOLA _ Human rights abuses were widespread on the part of the
government and the armed opposition. Both restricted citizens'
movement, arbitrarily abducted or detained civilians, censored
information and conscripted children.
	   ARGENTINA _ Police brutality continued to be the major human
rights concern, followed by threats and attacks on independent
journalists and the government's unwillingness to provide justice
for abuses committed under the military dictatorship that ended in
1983.
	   CHINA _ Despite some ``encouraging developments'' with greater
freedom to debate allowed among intellectuals on political and
economic reform, China maintained generally strict controls on
expression, association and assembly, with political and religious
dissidents facing arrest and detention. Repression continued in
Tibet.
	   CUBA _ Pope John Paul II's visit in January sparked hope the
government would ease repressive tactics. But violations continued
throughout the year, with the government stepping up the
prosecution and harassment of dissidents and refusing to grant
amnesty to remaining political prisoners, marking ``a disheartening
return to heavy-handed repression.''
	   IRAQ _ The government engaged in a broad array of violations,
including mass arrests, torture, summary executions and forced
relocations. In the Kurdistan region, both armed Kurdish political
parties and the Iraqi military were responsible for abuses. Despite
oil sales for humanitarian purposes, s public health crisis
continued.
	   MEXICO _ Although President Ernest Zedillo acknowledged human
rights violations, his government failed to respond to individual
cases of abuse, to strengthen human rights safeguards or to promote
the rule of law.
	   MYANMAR _ More than 1,000 people were imprisoned during the year
in the standoff between opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi and the
military rulers in a country that continued to be ``one of the
world's pariah states.''
	   NIGERIA _ The new government of General Abdulsalami Abubakar
offers new hope for democracy, but decrees allowing detention
without trial, suspension of constitutional guarantees of human
rights and prohibitions against the courts from reviewing executive
acts remained in force.
	   RUSSIA _ Political freedoms established at the end of the Cold
War were under increasing attack during the year, both on the
federal and regional level. Russia's provinces continued to
``develop into fiefdoms that engage in civil and political rights
violations with impunity from Moscow.''
	   SAUDI ARABIA _ The government continued to violate a broad array
of civil and political rights, allowing no criticism of the
monarchy, no political parties, arbitrary arrests and
institutionalized discrimination against women.
	   UNITED STATES _ The country that has long regarded itself ``a
beacon of human rights'' had incidents of police abuse,
mistreatment of prisoners, unjust rejection of asylum seekers,
reliance on the death penalty when other countries are rejecting
it, and racial inequality.
	   YUGOSLAVIA _ The government of President Slobodan Milosevic
continued its ``blatant disregard for human rights in 1998,''
carrying out breaches of human rights in Kosovo province,
suppressing independent media and the autonomy of Serbia's
universities and failing to cooperate with the prosecution of
accused war criminals from the conflict in Bosnia.
</TEXT>
