<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian president meets House leaders on election
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ President B.J. Habibie and key Cabinet
ministers met Thursday with legislative leaders in Parliament to
discuss plans for general elections next year.
	   Habibie, who took office from former President Suharto after
riots and protests in May, has allowed political parties to form
and has promised to hold parliamentary elections in June.
	   But many student protesters who have staged near-daily rallies
for weeks want Habibie to step down, saying he is stalling on
democratic reforms and is a stooge of his authoritarian
predecessor.
	   Habibie arrived Thursday morning at Parliament with Attorney
General Andi Mohamad Ghalib as well as 10 ministers, including
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas and military chief Gen. Wiranto, the
defense minister.
	   Students have demanded that Wiranto be held accountable for the
Nov. 13 shooting deaths of nine students by riot officers during a
controversial government assembly on political reforms.
	   Protesters also want Suharto to be investigated for corruption
and sent to trial before the general election is held.
	   Some government officials have said that the election will be
held on June 7, followed by the election of a new president by the
nation's highest legislative body.
	   Critics say the 1,000-member People's Consultative Assembly is
full of holdovers from the Suharto era and does not have the
credibility to choose a new leader for the nation of 202 million
people.
	   Indonesia is enduring its worst economic crisis in decades as
well as rising religious tension. Earlier this week, Christian mobs
burned mosques in a provincial capital in retaliation for attacks
by Muslim rioters on churches in the capital, Jakarta. 	   
</TEXT>
