w1289 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-Pakistan-Ter     12-03 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Pakistan-Terrorism </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wronged Pakistanis still in custody; Thais accused of beatings
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Also moved on sports wires as BC-Sports-Asian Games-Terrorism &QL; 
 &UR; By DON PATHAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Pakistan attacked the Thai police as
brutal and incompetent Thursday, saying four Pakistanis wrongly
arrested as terrorists planning to attack the Asian Games were
severely beaten in a bid to coerce confessions.
	   Though senior police officers verbally retracted the allegations
Wednesday, the four remained in custody because the Immigration
Police branch _ which arrested the men and charged them with
possessing gear to make bombs _ had not formally dropped the
charges yet.
	   Pakistan's Embassy accused the police _ who are on high alert to
foil possible terrorist attacks during Asia's premier sporting
event _ of systematically labeling Pakistanis terrorists. The games
open Sunday.
	   The men were arrested by the Immigration Police at a rented
house on Bangkok's outskirts. But subsequent tests by experts of
what arresting officers reported as ``bomb-making equipment''
showed it was junk.
	   Under police procedure, the men were turned over by the
Immigration Police to a local police station and interrogated.
Station commander Col. Songvudh Thawankitdamrong said one had
already apparently been beaten before arriving.
	   Songvudh said that since the Immigration Police had made the
arrest and filed charges, they would also need to drop the case.
One man would probably still face charges for overstaying his visa.
	   ``It's just a technicality now,'' Songvudh said. ``All senior
officials involved in the investigations have pretty much agreed
that there is not enough evidence to make the charges stick. The
issue will be dealt with accordingly. It's a matter of national
interest.''
	   Songvudh denied that officers at his station tried to coerce
confessions, saying it did not happen under his supervision.
	   ``They don't look like the terrorist type,'' Songvudh said.
	   Two are dishwashers and one exports low-end garments.
	   The case embarrassed the Immigration Police. Chief Chidchai
Wannasathit was cited in The Nation newspaper Thursday as saying
that his men would be investigated to find why a reporter had been
invited to join the arrest.
	   The embassy suggested that the Thai police reach first for
Pakistanis when they fear terrorism, noting that several Pakistani
citizens were arrested on similar grounds in June. The charges were
never substantiated and the police apologized.
	   ``It is most likely that the present case is also being blown
out of proportion for reasons best known to the police,'' the
embassy said.
	   Embassy officials tried to contact senior police officers
Wednesday and were unable to find any who could speak English and
substantiate or elaborate on the charges, the statement said. A
diplomat eventually went to the station and visited the detainees.
	   ``The police were hesitant to allow access to one of the four
persons because he had been severely beaten,'' the statement said.
``The police also tried to get `confessional statements' signed by
the accused persons under duress.''
	   Songvudh said the embassy officials arrived at a hectic moment
and should have brought a Thai-speaker with them. The station did
not have a good English-speaker.
	   Security awareness has been heightened with the looming opening
of the 13th Asian Games bringing together 6,000 athletes from 41
nations. Thailand has deployed 16,000 officers for security and
traffic control.
	   Nervousness has been increased by a publicly unexplained
security exercise which closed the U.S. Embassy for a day late last
month. The United States linked the closure to recent terrorism
warnings. 	   
</TEXT>
