w1291 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-Brazil-Loan     12-03 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Brazil-Loan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australia to lend to IMF Brazil fund
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Australia will lend up to 500 million
Australian dollars (U.S. dlrs 315 million) to an International
Monetary Fund rescue package for Brazil, Treasurer Peter Costello
announced Thursday.
	   Although Australia has contributed billions of dollars to IMF
rescue packages for Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea, this is
the first time money has been lent to help a country outside the
local region.
	   Costello said the loan was an interim measure under the IMF's
New Arrangements to Borrow (NAB), which he chairs, and the funds
should be repaid early in the new year.
	   ``They are being provided at an above-market interest rate,''
Costello said in a statement.
	   ``Australia will bear no credit risk, but will carry some
exchange risk.''
	   Costello said the loan, which would be repayable by the IMF and
would bear interest, would have no impact on the budget because it
would be secured by the IMF and repaid.
	   The treasurer defended Australia's assistance for a country far
removed from its local region.
	   ``The focus of Australia's bilateral balance of payments support
has been in its own region,'' Costello said.
	   ``However, our membership of the NAB represents a global
obligation and the Brazilian program is crucial for efforts to
control the current international financial crisis, which began in
Asia but has since spread more widely.
	   ``Stability in Brazil is important for stability elsewhere in
Latin America and for stability in the international financial
system.''
	   The NAB came into effect just two weeks ago, bringing together
25 developed nations into a more streamlined operation for
assisting with IMF financial rescue packages.
	   The Brazil package is the first time the NAB has been activated.
</TEXT>
