w1302 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Election 1stLd-Writethru   12-03 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesia plans elections on June 7 and presidential poll Aug. 29
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with election dates. One name correct for Suharto and
Harmoko &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) - The Indonesian government will hold
general elections on June 7 and elect a new president at the end of
August next year, a legislative leader said Thursday.
	   The announcement of the election dates came amid widespread
suspicion among student protesters that President B.J. Habibie
would delay the elections and stall other democratic reforms.
	   Yet many students were unlikely to be satisfied with the
election timetable. They have demanded the immediate resignation of
Habibie, who took office from former President Suharto in May after
riots and protests against his 32-year authoritarian rule.
	   Protesters say Habibie, who has urged students to halt their
near-daily street rallies, is a stooge of his former mentor.
	   House Speaker Harmoko announced the election timetable after
meeting with Habibie and key Cabinet ministers in Parliament. The
nation's highest legislative body will elect a new president on
Aug. 29, he said.
	   However, the 1,000-member People's Consultative Assembly is
beset by controversy. It is full of holdovers from the Suharto era
and critics say it does not have the credibility to choose a new
leader for the nation of 202 million people.
	   The assembly, which consists of all 500 members of Parliament as
well as presidential appointees, met last month to plan the
election and approve other political reforms.
	   ``The president will consistently and effectively implement the
decrees of the recent (assembly) meeting,'' Harmoko said.
	   Students who want swifter democratic change protested the
meeting of the assembly, and fought battles with security forces in
the streets surrounding Parliament. Nine students were fatally
shot.
	   Students want military chief Gen. Wiranto, who as defense
minister attended the meeting Thursday morning in Parliament, to be
held accountable for the Nov. 13 shootings.
	   Protesters also want Suharto to be investigated for corruption
and sent to trial before the general election is held.
	   Indonesia is enduring its worst economic crisis in decades as
well as rising religious tension. Earlier this week, Christian mobs
burned mosques in a provincial capital in retaliation for attacks
by Muslim rioters on churches in the capital, Jakarta. 	   
</TEXT>
