<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Orphanage Fire, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
At least 28 killed in Philippine orphanage fire
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES and RECASTS throughout with new details &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available
 &UR; By CLARO CORTES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Neighbors watched helplessly as a
pre-dawn fire raged Thursday through an aging orphanage in a Manila
squatter area, killing at least 28 people, mostly children.
	   Young children shouted for help from the second-floor windows,
which were covered with metal grills to protect against intruders.
Neighbors were unable to open the padlocked main gate.
	   The dozens of children at the Catholic-run Bahay Kalinga
orphanage had been looking forward to a Christmas party the next
day. Instead, at least 23 children died and Christmas decorations
were scattered, along with toys and children's clothes, among the
buildings' debris.
	   ``I'm afraid my playmates were burned,'' said Brian De Mesa, 5,
who survived along with his twin brother. ``I saw their burned
bodies. I don't want to go back.''
	   About 70 people were inside the orphanage and children's home
when the fire broke out at about 2 a.m., officials said.
	   Rescuers gingerly lifted the bodies of small infants wrapped in
blankets from the remains of the buildings, which included a
two-story main structure and two cottages, all built between 1913
and 1927.
	   Thirteen dead children were found huddled together in one room.
In another, a dead adult was found clinging to two children, all
charred beyond recognition.
	   Staff members said the fire spread so quickly that they did not
have time to rescue many children.
	   ``I was sleeping on the ground floor when I was woken up,'' said
Carina Bellosillo, a teacher. ``Already, the ceiling was on fire
and the stairs going up to the second floor were burning. I wanted
to go upstairs to save the babies, but my companions pulled me
back.''
	   The ceiling soon collapsed, and many of the children's bodies
were found on the ground.
	   Some children of working parents also stayed at the orphanage in
the slum area in Manila's Paco district, and parents and relatives
wept as they waited for word of their children.
	   ``He was my only joy,'' said Anabel Sambriano, 21, whose
9-month-old boy died in the blaze. ``I want my baby.''
	   President Joseph Estrada visited the gutted buildings Thursday
afternoon and pledged to help the orphanage recover.
	   ``I will raise funds personally. I will do everything I can to
rebuild this place,'' he said.
	   Fire officials said about 70 percent of the orphanage was
already burning when they arrived shortly after 2 a.m.
	   ``We couldn't even go near because of the intense heat,'' said
Major Pablito Cordeta, operations chief of the Manila Fire
Department. ``A few seconds after we arrived, part of the roof
collapsed.''
	   Investigators said faulty electrical wiring may have triggered
the fire.
	   ``Most probably the electrical system was also old,'' said Capt.
Pennimore Jaudian, chief arson unit investigator. 	   
</TEXT>
