<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese stock prices finish lower, dollar falls against yen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing Nikkei, mid-afternoon dollar and bond

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stock prices finished sharply lower
Thursday amid uncertainties about the outlook for U.S. stocks. The
U.S. dollar dropped against the yen.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 289.54 points,
or 1.93 percent, closing the day's trading at 14,697.08 points. On
Wednesday, the index closed up 151.21 points, or 1.02 percent.
	   In mid-afternoon trading, the dollar bought 119.46 yen, down
2.42 yen from late in Tokyo Wednesday and also below its late New
York level of 119.93 yen overnight.
	   Unfounded rumors that a U.S. hedge fund was selling dollars to
cover emerging market losses and a drop in Standard and Poor's 500
futures auguring another decline on Wall Street sent the dollar to
its lowest level in almost two weeks, traders said.
	   ``The biggest reason for the dollar's fall is the drop on the S
and P,'' said Yuhiko Kaji, vice president of foreign exchange at
Sakura Bank.
	   Also hurting the dollar's value was a rumor that a U.S. hedge
fund was selling the greenback to make up for losses in Brazil,
traders said.
	   The dollar was relatively stable as institutional investors
bought the U.S. currency for new investments in dollar-denominated
assets earlier in the session, traders said.
	   Many traders said, however, that the dollar could face more
selling pressure given uncertainly over the outlook for U.S.
financial markets.
	   On Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 69 points to
9,064.54 on concerns about the deteriorating corporate earnings
outlook because of weak demand from Asia.
	   On the Tokyo stock market, share prices moved lower following an
overnight drop in U.S. stocks and the dollar's overnight retreat
against the yen.
	   Investors also turned bearish amid uncertainty about the
Japanese government's upcoming economic measures, traders said.
	   ``The market lacks both buying and selling incentives and
activities are sparse,'' said Yasuo Ueki, general manager at Nikko
Securities Co.
	   The ruling Liberal Democratic Party and opposition Liberal Party
are currently coordinating economic policies, including what to do
about the country's unpopular consumption tax.
	   The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 18.26 points, or 1.59 percent, to 1,128.89 points.
The TOPIX rose 4.89 points, or 0.43 percent, the previous day.
	   The benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government bond fell to
1.110 percent from Wednesday's close of 1.155 percent, driving its
price up to 105.94 yen from the previous day's 105.53 yen. 	   
</TEXT>
