<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-Webber Trial,0370 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Webber cleared of most serious charges
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DERRILL HOLLY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UPPER MARLBORO, Maryland (AP) _ Chris Webber vowed to work
harder to uphold his name and reputation after being cleared of
charges that could have sent the Sacramento Kings forward to jail.
	   A jury of nine women and three men on Wednesday found him guilty
of willfully disobeying a police officer, and two minor traffic
violations. The judge assessed him dlrs 560 in fines in the case.
	   The same jury acquitted the former Washington Wizards star of
charges of possession of marijuana, driving under the influence of
the drug, resisting arrest and second-degree assault.
	   ``When you face charges of any type, you definitely are tense,''
Webber said outside of the Prince George's County Courthouse,
expressing relief that the Jan. 20 incident has been resolved.
	   The outcome could have been far different. Prosecutors had
planned to seek jail time if Webber was convicted of the most
serious charges.
	   ``The jury was swayed by the fact that he is very young man and
had never been in trouble,'' Maryland State's Attorney Jack Johnson
said of the 25-year-old Webber.
	   Jurors deliberated three hours before returning the unanimous
verdicts. Earlier Wednesday, they heard closing arguments from
Webber's defense attorney, Steve Levy, who used the recurrent theme
``It never happened'' to whittle away at the prosecution's case.
	   ``I don't believe, knowing Chris Webber, that he ever intended
to assault a police officer,'' Levy said.
	   The arrest was one of several off-court matters that prompted
the Wizards to trade Webber to the Kings in May. He was accused of
sexual assault in April, but that charge was later dropped. He also
paid a dlrs 500 fine in August after marijuana was found in his
carry-on bag at an airport in Puerto Rico. That incident cost
Webber his endorsement contract with Fila. Officials with the
athletic-wear manufacturer said he violated the company's conduct
clause.
	   Webber said he is looking forward to getting back to basketball,
although he regrets he will not be returning to the Wizards.
</TEXT>
