<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Hair </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hair to avoid Sri Lanka games
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Controversial Australian cricket
umpire Darrell Hair has decided to stand down from matches
involving Sri Lanka to avoid clashes over the Muttiah Muralitharan
throwing affair.
	   Hair admitted Thursday that comments he made in a book about
Muralitharan were ``inappropriate.''
	   Hair caused a furore when he no-balled the offspinner seven
times in the 1995 Boxing Day test between Australia and Sri Lanka.
An International Cricket Council inquiry later cleared
Muralitharan's action.
	   Sri Lanka's wounds were reopened recently with the release of a
book by Hair, Australia's leading umpire.
	   Hair wrote, ``I don't think he straightens his arm all the time,
just on some occasions. I could have called him 27 times or even
more but I did not want the matter to become a complete farce.''
	   That angered Sri Lankan officials who protested to the ICC.
	   Hair has decided to stand aside from games involving Sri Lanka,
which will arrive after Christmas for a three-nation series
involving Australia and England.
	   ``As an international umpire I understand the timing of my book
is inappropriate,'' Hair said Thursday.
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
