<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Anwar Search </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-Anwar-Trial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Defense council for Malaysia's former No. 2 leader complains of
police raid

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ A court hearing a case against
former No. 2 Malaysian leader Anwar Ibrahim was rocked Thursday by
defense accusations of harassment during a police raid on one of
its attorney's offices
	   The chief counsel for the jailed ex-deputy prime minister, Raja
Aziz Addruse, told the court that police searched Pawancheek
Merican's office Wednesday, ostensibly to look for papers reported
missing by prosecutors.
	   ``I wish to register a strong protest against this kind of
measure towards the defense counsel,'' said Raja Aziz. ``It amounts
to harassment.''
	   The lawyer accused prosecutors of using heavy-handed tactics,
saying they simply could have asked Anwar's legal team for the lost
documents before going to the police.
	   With the high-profile abuse of power trial poised to enter its
fourth week, the acrimony between defense and prosecution lawyers
has grown. Earlier this week, the prosecution was furious when one
of Anwar's lawyers accused them of forcing a man to fabricate
evidence.
	   The lawyer, Zainur Zakaria, was sentenced to three months
imprisonment for contempt of court. Another lawyer, whose statement
was used by Zainur in an affidavit containing the accusations,
escaped imprisonment by apologizing on Wednesday.
	   Zainur will go to jail if he loses an appeal that is scheduled
to be heard on Friday.
	   On Thursday, Judge Augustine Paul said he could not interfere
with police investigations or stop any searches.
	   ``Do you want me to tell the police to stop their
investigations? I cannot do that,'' he said.
	   But Raja Aziz persisted, demanding the judge order the
prosecution to end the harassment. ``There must be a stop to it.''
	   The judge replied: ``I've also been investigated by the police
when they came to my office to take statements from me.''
	   It was not known in what connection or when police questioned
the judge, who is trying Malaysia's former deputy premier on four
counts of abuse of power. Anwar, 51, will be tried at a later date
for one more count of corruption and five counts of illegal sex
acts.
	   He has denied all the charges, saying they were cooked up to
demolish his political career and end the challenge he poses to
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad's 17-year-rule.
	   Prosecutors defended their actions in seeking the missing
documents.
	   ``If they (the defense) are not happy with the police, file a
civil suit against them or if they are not happy with us, then file
a police report against us,'' said Prosecutor Abdul Gani Patail.
	   He said it was mandatory to lodge a police report in the case of
missing government documents.
	   ``We never accused anybody.'' 	   
</TEXT>
