w1342 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-ChineseFi     12-03 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Chinese Fishermen </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Estrada orders filing of charges against 20 Chinese fishermen
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ President Joseph Estrada ordered
Thursday the filing of charges against 20 Chinese who were found
fishing in the disputed Spratly Islands.
	   ``They violated some Philippine laws so they should be
charged,'' Estrada told reporters.
	   Estrada said he is not afraid of possible reprisals from China.
	   ``Anybody who violates the law of the country should be
charged,'' he said. ``We have jurisdiction over both foreigners and
local violators.''
	   A Philippine navy patrol arrested the 20 Chinese fishermen and
seized their six boats on Sunday near Alicia Annie reef, which is
claimed by both the Philippines and China.
	   China on Tuesday asked the Philippines to free the fishermen.
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Tang Guoquiang said Beijing
views the detentions as illegal and wants Manila to take measures
to avoid such arrests in the future.
	   The Philippine navy said the Chinese were arrested for illegally
fishing in Philippine waters and using sodium cyanide to catch fish
in violation of a Philippine law that bans the practice.
	   Cyanide is poured into the sea by some fishermen to stun fish so
they can be caught and sold alive to restaurants. Cyanide kills
many other fish and destroys coral reefs.
	   Philippine Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said the mother
ship of the six smaller boats fled during the arrest and headed for
nearby Mischief Reef, also in the Spratly Islands, where the
Chinese maintain several structures that the Philippines claims can
have military uses.
	   The arrests were the latest in a series of recent incidents
between Manila and Beijing over territories in the South China Sea.
	   The Spratlys are believed to be rich in oil, gas and minerals.
China, Vietnam and Taiwan claim all of the Spratlys, while the
Philippines, Malaysia and Brunei claim parts of the chain.
	   Many Chinese fishermen have been arrested in the past but have
been freed after serving short jail sentences.
</TEXT>
