<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-MLS-United Coach,0334 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rongen returns to Washington to take United's helm
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOSEPH WHITE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Big-time pro soccer in the United States is
finally showing some age. When D.C. United's new coach accepted the
job, he started talking about the good old days.
	   Thomas Rongen, taking over from Bruce Arena, will lead United at
the same RFK Stadium where he played for the Washington Diplomats
of the long-defunct North American Soccer League in 1980.
	   ``The fact that we play at a stadium that holds such great
memories for me as a player is the icing on an otherwise delicious
cake,'' Rongen said Wednesday.
	   United will be Rongen's third Major League Soccer team. He was
coach of the year in 1996 after leading Tampa Bay to a 20-12
regular season record, then moved to the New England Revolution the
following year and posted records of 15-17 and 8-18 before he was
fired Aug. 22.
	   In Washington, the pressure will be greater. Arena led United to
four major titles _ the MLS Cup in 1996 and 1997, the U.S. Open Cup
in 1996 and the CONCACAF Champions Cup this year _ before being
named coach of the U.S. national team on Oct. 27.
	   ``Obviously, his are big shoes to fill,'' United general manager
Kevin Payne said. ``Ultimately, I had to trust my initial instinct
that a coach with roots in the American game would be best suited
to D.C. United.''
	   A product of the famed Dutch club Ajax Amsterdam, Rongen has
been playing and coaching in the United States for 20 years. His
pro coaching career began in 1989 with the Fort Lauderdale Strikers
of the American Soccer League.
	   Coincidentally, Rongen's first assignment with his new team will
be in Fort Lauderdale, where United plays Saturday in the second
leg of the Interamerican Cup against Brazil's Vasco da Gama. Arena
will coach the game, his last with United, with Rongen along as an
observer. Vasco da Gama won the first leg 1-0.
</TEXT>
