<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Guerrillas kill suspected collaborator in school classroom
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ Separatist rebels in disputed East Timor
shot and killed an elementary school teacher in front of a
classroom full of students, the military said Thursday.
	   The attack, which took place on Wednesday, was the latest in a
recent surge in violence in East Timor, a former Portuguese colony
invaded by Indonesia in 1975.
	   Several months of relative calm have given way recently to
sporadic fighting between guerrillas and the Indonesian military.
	   Rebels killed the 46-year-old teacher, Fransisco Amaral, because
he was suspected of collaborating with security forces, police
said.
	   Assailants fired on him from a classroom doorway at a school in
Viqueque, 125 miles (200 kilometers) east of Dili, the capital of
East Timor, said military commander Col. Tono Suratman.
	   Indonesia and Portugal are currently engaged in a new round of
U.N.-sponsored talks over East Timor's fate. Indonesia has offered
a degree of autonomy in exchange for recognition of its
sovereignty.
	   Indonesia annexed East Timor a year after invading it, but the
United Nations and Portugal do not recognize the Southeast Asian
nation's claim to the half-island territory.
</TEXT>
