<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Tax Evasion, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine tycoon moves to avert arrest on tax evasion charges
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Philippine president saying charges against Tan
show his administration does not practice favoritism in new
9th-10th grafs

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Businessman Lucio Tan, one of the
Philippines' richest men, asked a court Thursday not to issue an
arrest warrant against him in connection with tax evasion charges.
	   The Department of Justice has charged Tan, his Fortune Tobacco
Corp. and nine dummy companies of defrauding the government of 25.6
billion pesos (dlrs 656 million) in taxes between 1990 and 1992.
	   If convicted, Tan could face two years in jail on each of the
nine charges, as well as being required to repay the taxes.
	   Tan also has interests in brewing and banking and is chairman
and chief stockholder of ailing Philippine Airlines.
	   In a motion filed with the Marikina trial court, Tan's lawyer,
former Justice Minister Estelito Mendoza, called the charges
baseless.
	   The Department of Justice filed the charges Tuesday, saying it
has enough evidence to convict Tan.
	   Mendoza claimed that the tax evasion charges were filed without
the approval of the head of the Bureau of Internal Revenue, a
requirement under the country's tax law.
	   The BIR had already charged Tan with tax evasion in 1993. But
that case did not proceed because Tan, in a series of appeals that
reached the Supreme Court, managed to get the charges suspended
pending an investigation by the justice department. The Supreme
Court said the tax bureau violated Tan's right to due process when
the case was filed without a preliminary investigation.
	   Tan has denied the allegations, and claimed the tax cases were
brought against him for not supporting former President Fidel
Ramos' candidacy in 1992. In this year's election, however, Tan
reportedly contributed heavily to the campaign of President Joseph
Estrada.
	   Estrada said the charges show that ``nobody is above the law''
under his administration.
	   ``If there is evidence, nothing can stop the charges, so nobody
is exempted,'' Estrada said.
	   The Bureau of Internal Revenue, however, has changed its view of
the case since Estrada's election. Revenue chief Beethoven Rualo
was quoted by a local newspaper last week as saying the case
against Tan would not succeed because the evidence ``will not stand
up to the scrutiny of the court.''
	   Rualo, who took office after Estrada assumed the presidency on
June 30, reversed his predecessor's position that there was
voluminous evidence supporting the government's charges against
Tan.
</TEXT>
