<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Australia-Defense </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australian defense minister visits Death Railway
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MICOOL BROOKE &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KANCHANABURI, Thailand (AP) _ Australia's commitments to peace
and security in Asia in the wake of the economic crisis will be
spelled out in a security review early next year, Defense Minister
John Moore said Thursday on a pilgrimage to the infamous Death
Railway.
	   ``This place is a special chapter in Australian World War II
history,'' Moore said. ``These Australians buried here symbolize
our country's past commitment to peace and security in the
Asia-Pacific.''
	   Moore viewed row upon row of gravestones in the Kanchanaburi War
Cemetery, where some of the 2,700 Australian prisoners of war who
died building a rail line for their Japanese captors are buried.
	   The railway, linking Japanese forces in Thailand and Burma, now
known as Myanmar, included the infamous Bridge on the River Kwai,
the subject of a Hollywood film depicting the disease, starvation,
torture and killings inflicted on the prisoners.
	   Moore was the highest-ranking Australian official to visit since
Prime Minister John Howard opened an Australian-funded memorial at
hand-hewn gorge known as Hellfire Pass, which had some of the
highest death rates.
	   Moore said Australia wants its neighbors to know the country is
just as committed to Asia's peace and security now as during World
War II. He is scheduled to hold security talks with Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai and others during his four-day visit.
	   Australia's commitment to Thailand and the region would be
spelled out in a new security review to be published in March 1999,
taking into account the ongoing economic crisis.
	   The review looks at Australia's commitment to its treaty allies,
including Thailand, Malaysia, Singapore and Indonesia, and the
threats to their stability which may affect Australia, Moore said.
	   The visit follows Ambassador William Fisher's recent
announcement that Australia had increased military aid and
assistance to Thailand as a result of the economic crisis.
</TEXT>
