</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Australian Open, 2nd Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With AP Photos
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Appleby takes first-round lead &QL; 
 &UR; EDs: UPDATES with end of play Thursday &QL; 
 &UR; By DENNIS PASSA
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   ADELAIDE, Australia (AP) _ Australian Stuart Appleby, tuning up
for next week's Presidents Cup and still trying to overcome his
wife's death, shot a 3-under-par 69 Thursday to take the
first-round lead at the Australian Open.
	   On a day when the tough par-72 Royal Adelaide Golf Club course
lived up to its reputation, only 13 players in the 126-man field
broke par. The field will be cut to low 60s and ties after Friday's
second round, a figure that could be as high as 8-over par if
Thursday's scores are any indication.
	   One stroke back of Appleby after first-round 70s are Greg
Norman, Canadian Rick Gibson, Australians Peter Senior and Kenny
Druce and New Zealander Stephen Scahill. Appleby and Norman will
both play for the International team against the United States at
next week's Presidents Cup at Royal Melbourne.
	   A group of seven Australian golfers was another stroke back at
71.
	   Appleby, playing for the first time in Australia since the death
of his wife, Renay, in a London traffic accident in July, had
back-to-back birdies to start the back nine, took consecutive
bogeys on 14 and 15 then finished with a pair of birdies.
	   ``I'm generally pretty happy with the day,'' Appleby said. ``I'm
under-golfed a bit so I'm trying to get enough good shots in the
bag.''
	   Appleby said it's difficult concentrating without his wife
nearby on the golf course. Renay, a former promising golfer, was a
constant companion on the tour and caddied for Appleby when he
played the Nike circuit in the United States.
	   ``It is hard to even say it, not having her all the time is
hard,'' said Appleby. ``I suppose I have lived the nightmare for
four months and it's not easier. One minute I'm good, one minute
I'm bad.''
	   Englishman Nick Faldo was among the course casualities,
finishing with a 77 and telling organizers he'd ``just played
badly'' and was heading straight for the practice range. His round
included six bogeys and a birdie.
	   John Huston, a member of the U.S. team in the Presidents Cup,
shot 75, one better than American Fred Couples, who will also play
at Royal Melbourne next week. International team member Carlos
Franco of Paraguay shot 75, as did teammate Craig Parry of
Australia.
	   On the difficult par-4, 442-meter 15th, there were 76 bogeys and
16 double bogeys.
	   Under relatively good weather conditions _ temperatures of 18C
(65F) and a light morning breeze that became gusty in the afternoon
_ Norman, playing his first 72-hole tournament since undergoing
shoulder surgery eight months ago, was at 3-under through eight
holes after birdies on the par-5 second, the par-3 seventh and
par-4 eighth.
	   But Norman, a five-time winner of this tournament and who lost
in a playoff to England's Lee Westwood last year, took a
double-bogey seven after hitting into the high green-side rough on
the ninth to make the turn in 36, one under the card.
	   ``It was just missing a shot in the wrong place,'' Norman said
of his problems on the ninth. ``There is no intermediate rough. You
can almost be unplayable.''
	   Norman made successive birdies on 10 and 11 before bogeying the
tough par-4, 395-meter 13th, bogeyed 15 and birdied 17 before his
15-foot downhill right-to-left birdie putt on 18 was short.
	   ``I think it's going to be hard for anyone to go around this
course without hitting two or three bogeys,'' Norman said. ``I
don't care how good you are hitting the ball. The course forces you
to play defensively.''
	   Five-time British Open champion Peter Thomson was commissioned
by the Australian Golf Union to revamp Royal Adelaide for the Open.
	   Thomson, who is also captain of the International team, added
about 300 meters to the now 6,565-meter (7,178-yard) course, grew
out the rough and extended it further into the fairways and added
20 bunkers.
	   (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Golf-Australian Open, 2nd Ld Writethru; CT:s; 
