r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Skiing-WorldCu     12-03 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Skiing-World Cup,0605 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Austria's Gotschl early favorite for donhill title
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MIKE CLARK &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MAMMOTH MOUNTIN, California (AP) _ Renate Goetschl is quiet,
even for an Austrian, so she'd be the last one to claim she's been
one of the world's best ski racers for several years. She might
just be the best by the end of this season.
	   Goetschl doesn't display the bouncy personality of a Picabo
Street or the steely determination of a Katja Seizinger. Yet she
always manages to work her way up among the leaders in the downhill
and overall standings.
	   Overlooked amid the German domination of the women's tour last
season was Goetschl's second place behind Seizinger in the downhill
standings and a final placing of seventh overall.
	   With victories in the season's first two downhills last weekend
at Lake Louise, Alberta, the 23-year-old Goetschl has already taken
a strong lead in pursuit of a second downhill title.
	   With Seizinger out this season with a knee injury, the overall
title is up for grabs as well, and Goetschl, who excels in the
speed events of downhill and super-G, might just be a darkhorse
contender.
	   A lot of people forget that Goetschl came to the World Cup as a
slalom skier, winning a race in only her second start in 1993. The
Austrian federation, recognizing her talent, made her a four-event
skier, which took away from her slalom training. But she still
knows how to get through the gates, as witnessed by a gold medal in
the combined in the 1997 world championships. It will take that
kind of skiing to win an overall title.
	   ``It's really difficult to win the overall title because you
have to ski well in every discipline,'' she said. ``In giant
slalom, I'm not so good. In slalom, I'm getting better than the
last years and I'll try to make better results than I have. For the
overall, I don't think I have quite enough yet.''
	   Luc Alphand of France, a downhill-super G specialist, proved a
speed skier could win the overall by taking the title in 1997.
	   ``But you have to win a lot,'' Goetschl pointed out. ``Maybe
then it's possible. Last year, Katja Seizinger always skied well in
slalom and giant slalom, and I'm not the best.''
	   When she kicks out of the start in Friday's super-G here, she'll
find out whether the overall title is a viable target. After
winning the two downhills at Lake Louise, she led deep into the
super-G, only to miss a gate near the end of the course.
	   ``I was a little bit sorry about that, but I had a good weekend,
and I also know that I'm fast in super-G. I know I can go to the
start here without any pressure.''
	   That bobble at Lake Louise cost her 100 points, a mistake she
can't afford to repeat too often if she's to challenge for the
overall. A victory here Friday would go a long way in boosting her
chances at skiing's highest honor.
	   Despite her youth, Goetschl has finished in the top 10 of the
overall standings the last three years. She was the downhill
champion two years ago and runnerup to Seizinger last season.
	   ``Katja's not here this year but every year it changes,'' she
said. ``You don't know how the next season will be.''
	   The best thing Goetschl has going for her this year, it would
seem, is being Austrian.
	   ``We are now a really good team and it took a lot of hard work
to get here,'' she said. ``In the past, we were always looking to
the Germans and we tried to do the same as them. But I think now we
have caught them and everybody is happy about that and wants to
make it better and better.''
</TEXT>
