<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Letter Bomb, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bomb scares evacuate NT Parliament, Sydney and Melbourne towers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Photos
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with new bomb scare clearing Sydney's Centrepoint
Tower; CHANGES byline and dateline
 &UR; By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ A day after a letter-bomber targeted
government officials, bomb scares wreaked havoc nationwide Thursday
as major buildings in Sydney and Melbourne and the Northern
Territory Parliament were evacuated.
	   Police began manhunt for one suspect, a former Australian Tax
Office worker who lost his job a few years ago.
	   Police cordoned off Sydney's Centrepoint Tower, a major tourist
attraction that also houses the headquarters of the Australian Tax
Office, which had been targeted by letter bombs.
	   Similar scares over suspicious packages found in Melbourne's ANZ
Tower and the Northern Territory Parliament Building in Darwin
turned out to be false alarms.
	   But the spreading fear showed that the letter-bomb terrorist was
able to halt business, suspend government and incite panic _ all at
the price of 2.30 Australian dollars in postage for each of the 26
letter bombs found so far.
	   Police in Queensland detonated the 26th bomb found at a home in
the normally idyllic oceanfront vacation community of the Gold
Coast.
	   Downtown Melbourne's ANZ Tower was evacuated until police
determined that a package mailed to Victorian state Small Business
and Tourism Minister Louise Asher was harmless.
	   On Wednesday, a nationwide alert was issued after 21 letter
bombs were found at the Canberra mail sorting center after one
exploded, slightly injuring two postal workers.
	   The previous day a letter bomb had been delivered to a private
Sydney address but it was defused by the police bomb squad when the
person became suspicious.
	   Another two parcel bombs were delivered to homes in Sydney and
Melbourne on Wednesday.
	   Most of the potentially deadly parcels had been addressed to
former or current Australian Taxation Office staff, but some
members of the Human Rights Commission also had been targeted.
	   One was reportedly sent to the Sydney home of federal privacy
commissioner Moira Scollay and another to the Melbourne home of
former federal sex discrimination commissioner Sue Walpole.
	   The federal human rights commission has contacted all past and
present staff believed endangered by a mail bomber targeting tax
office and commission workers, it said Thursday.
	   All mail was now being screened and staff had been warned to
check their home mail carefully before opening it, Human Rights and
Equal Opportunity Commission executive director Diana Temby said.
	   Police announced they were looking for 43-year-old Colin George
Dunstan of Canberra, whom they said was suspected of mailing at
least 25 letter bombs, which would make this Australia's biggest
terrorist campaign.
	   Dunstan's neighbors said he was a former Australian Taxation
Office employee who had been out of work for several years.
	   Police were concerned more letter bombs could still be on their
way to past and present tax officials, sent by what they believe to
be a disgruntled, disturbed person. Police were investigating a
common link between all addressees.
	   The devices are designed to explode when opened, although the
bomb that exploded at the Canberra Mail Center went off when it was
thrown into a sorting basket, slightly injuring the workers.
</TEXT>
