<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Shrine Controversy,0549 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police brace for Hindu rally at Muslim shrine
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGALORE, India (AP) _ Hundreds of police officers on Thursday
surrounded a southern Indian shrine where Hindus and Muslims have
traditionally worshipped together in peace, fearing violence during
a rally planned by Hindu fundamentalists.
	   The fundamentalist Vishwa Hindu Parishad, or World Hindu
Council, says the Muslim family that has traditionally maintained
the site should hand it over to Hindus.
	   The council known as the VHP, a sister organization to the
Bharatiya Janata Party that leads India's national governing
coalition, had threatened to take over the site by force, but later
said it planned only a rally Thursday evening. Hundreds of VHP
followers began converging on the site Wednesday.
	   Local police minister Phillipose Matthai told The Associated
Press he was in control of the situation at Chikamagalur, where
Muslims believe a Sufi holy man is buried in a cave. Hindus believe
one of their gods entered the cave in ancient times and
disappeared, but will one day re-emerge at the site 300 kilometers
(190 miles) south of the Karnataka state capital of Bangalore.
	   The tussle over the shrine comes just days before the sixth
anniversary of the day a Hindu mob tore down a mosque at Ayodhya in
northern India following a campaign spearheaded by the VHP, which
has vowed to build a Hindu temple at the site. The Ayodhya issue
helped bring the BJP to political prominence, while the mosque's
destruction prompted deadly religious rioting across India.
	   In Chikamagalur, more than 2,000 police officers were deployed
at barricades erected to control crowds. Worshippers approach the
shrine by climbing a wooded hill, then descend stone stairs to the
underground cave. A stone slab marks what is believed to be the
tomb of Sufi holy man Dada Hayath Khalandar who lived centuries
ago, while a pair of shoes said to belong to the Hindu Lord
Dattatraya sit in a case in a corner.
	   ``The shrine is a Hindu religious place according to available
government records,'' VHP leader Raghavendra Rao said Thursday.
	   ``It is not a Hindu temple, but a Muslim holy place containing
the tomb of a Sufi saint,'' countered Mohamed Sharief, editor of a
local newspaper. ``However both Hindus and Muslims should be
allowed unhindered access.''
	   Both Hindus and Muslims believe that if a childless woman comes
to the shrine to ask for a child, her prayers will be answered. It
is not uncommon for Indians of different faiths to share shrines
and even rites _ the music and dance of mystic Sufi Muslims
sometimes borrows from Hindu traditions.
	   Opposition parties in the national parliament this week
questioned BJP leaders sharply about the trouble brewing in
Chikamagalur. Federal police minister L.K Advani, chief of the
BJP's hard-line faction, said his government was working with
Karnataka officials to ensure both Hindus and Muslims could
continue to worship peacefully at the shrine.
	   The BJP has only recently made inroads in southern states like
Karnataka, which is now controlled by the leftist Janata Dal party.
In 1990, the BJP controlled the government in Uttar Pradesh, where
the Ayodhya mosque was located.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-India-Shrine Controversy; CT:i; 
