<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Australian Open-Appleby </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Still hurting after wife's death, patient approach pays off for
</HEADLINE>
Appleby &QL; 
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADELAIDE, Australia (AP) _ For Stuart Appleby, life _ and golf _
is not getting any easier since the death in a car crash of his
wife Renay earlier this year. But he's getting used to it.
	   ``I have lived the nightmare for four months and its not
easier,'' Appleby said Thursday after playing in his home country
of Australia for the first time since his wife's death in London in
July.
	   ``I'm getting used to going to bed by myself, or waking up and
not having
	   her around. It does not change the fact that I can do without
her _ I don't have that feeling. The fact is that it's never going
to happen.''
	   Appleby shot a 3-under-par 69 Thursday to take a one-stroke lead
in the Australian Open.
	   After being distracted during the U.S. PGA Championship, Appleby
said he was now working on rebuilding his rhythm and improving his
concentration.
	   ``Not having Renay at the PGA was really, really hard,'' he
said. ``Not having her all the time is hard.''
	   Appleby said he was still suffering from mental fatigue and was
easily frustrated.
	   ``I find myself a bit more edgy, temperamental sometimes,'' he
said. ``One minute I'm good, one minute I'm bad.
	   ``I feel like I can concentrate well at times but I'm not far
away from having trouble. It is very hard to keep the flame
constant.''
	   Admitting to being ``under-golfed,'' he said he was trying to
remain relaxed and unemotional.
	   ``I played some pretty bad shots today but I played some pretty
good ones
	   as well. I tried not to let either of them make much of a
difference.
	   ``When I hit a bad shot, I felt angry, but it did not last for
more than a
	   minute. I haven't got the energy to be angry.''
	   Appleby says he realizes there will be tough times ahead.
	   ``My goals, not just in golf, are to be patient,'' he said.
``It's a long
	   road. It's more than getting a swing change that can take a year
to fix.
	   ``What I am trying to do this week (is) just be patient and not
expect too much of myself.'' (rs/djp) 	   
</TEXT>
