<SLUG> BC-Japan-Economy, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's economy still stuck in recession
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS thruout to ADD official comment in 5th-7th grafs,
economist comment in 13th-14th grafs; TRIMS outdated material.
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The Japanese economy shrank for the fourth straight
quarter, continuing to wallow in the nation's deepest recession in
decades, the government said Thursday.
	   Japan's gross domestic product _ the measure of all goods and
services produced in the country _ declined by 0.7 percent in the
three months from July through September, compared to the previous
quarter, the Economic Planning Agency said.
	   The economy contracted at an annual rate of 2.6 percent, the
agency said.
	   Japan has been battered by Asia's financial meltdown, which has
slashed exports, long the mainstay of its economic growth.
	   Economic Planning Agency head Taichi Sakaiya expressed hopes
that the economy may be hitting bottom and nearing ``a dawn.''
	   But he reiterated that the economy's performance during this
fiscal year, which ends next March, may turn out to be worse than
the government prediction of a 1.8 percent contraction.
	   ``These figures actually were a little better than I expected,''
he said. ``The pace of decline is slowing.''
	   Thursday's figures do not reflect the main steps the government
has taken to prevent the recession from dragging on further, which
came after September.
	   Those steps, announced last month, include public works spending
and income tax cuts. The government has also passed a package of
bills to bailout Japan's many troubled banks.
	   The banks' massive bad loans, leftover from the excessive
lending and speculation of the 1980s, have been a big obstacle to
turning around the economy.
	   The ensuing credit crunch has sent unemployment and bankruptcies
shooting to record highs. Consumer spending has been plummeting.
	   Economists were pessimistic about when the effects of the
government steps might be felt.
	   ``The government is shrugging this off as ancient history, but
there are problems still plaguing this economy,'' said Andrew
Shipley, economist at Schroders Japan in Tokyo. ``The prospect for
recovery is quite remote.''
	   The Japanese economy was so ``fossilized'' that movements in
investments and labor weren't responding to market demand, Shipley
said in a telephone interview.
	   Tokyo-based economists surveyed by Dow Jones Newswires had
forecast on average a 0.5 percent drop in GDP for the period from
July through September from the prior quarter.
	   The economy shrank by 0.7 percent for the April-June period,
compared to the previous quarter. That marked the third straight
quarter of decline and the worst record since the government began
releasing GDP data in 1955.
	   Initially, the EPA had reported the drop as 0.8 percent but
revised it on Thursday.
	   Japan's economy shrank by 0.7 percent for the last fiscal year
ended in March 1998, its first annual drop since 1974. The Japanese
economy hasn't shrunk two years in a row since the end of World War
II.
 &UR; (dj-yk)
</TEXT>
