<SLUG> BC-Romania-Ambassador </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Romania's outgoing ambassador to Bulgaria may become journalist
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ Romania's outgoing ambassador to
Bulgaria who formerly headed the country's foreign intelligence may
become a journalist, he said Thursday.
	   Ioan Talpes, 54, who headed the country's international spy
agency from 1992 to 1997 quit as head of foreign intellignce in
1997 after admitting to a long-running contact between a Swiss
contact and Romanian intelligence officers that had compromised
Swiss-Romanian relations.
	   His resignation as ambassador which will become effective Dec.
20 was not connected to the reasons for leaving his previous job,
he said. He was named ambassador to Bulgaria by President Emil
Constantinescu a year ago.
	   ``I feel being embassador is not the right thing for me,'' said
Talpes by telephone. ``I have several offers and I will probably
express myself in the media.''
	   A military historian by training, Talpes has written dozens of
books, mainly on defense and diplomatic issues.
	   (am/rr)
</TEXT>
