<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Cocaine Haul </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police seize huge shipment of cocaine mixed with Colombian rum
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANDREW SELSKY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ Police have made what they
believe is the largest cocaine seizure in South Africa's history,
confiscating between 180 and 360 kilos (396 to 792 pounds) of the
drug which was dissolved in Colombian rum.
	   The precise amount of the cocaine seized Tuesday night was not
known because police haven't extracted it yet from the 11,600
bottles of Ron (rum) de Medellin. The central Colombian city was
the home of the Medellin cartel, a notorious and bloody drug
syndicate which had its heyday in the 1980s until its leaders were
killed or imprisoned.
	   At a minimum 15 grams of cocaine per bottle, the rum would have
been lethal to any unsuspecting person drinking it.
	   Police Inspector Frik Rabe said the shipment apparently
originated in Medellin. Investigators were still tracking down
shipping documents to confirm its point of origin.
	   Informers had told police the cocaine was to be delivered to a
Nigerian drug syndicate operating in the Johannesburg area. They
tipped police to the container's arrival at a harbor in Durban, an
eastern city on the Indian Ocean, on Nov. 25.
	   Police said they followed the container as it was trucked to a
Johannesburg depot and staked it out. When police felt it was
obvious the shipment was not going to be claimed, they seized it.
	   The value of the cocaine was estimated at between dlrs 8 million
and 16 million.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
