<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese stocks tumble amid uncertainties about Wall Street, dollar
</HEADLINE>
down &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Wraps up with late dollar, closing bond, other details &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stock prices tumbled Thursday amid
uncertainties about U.S. financial markets and Japan's economy. The
U.S. dollar fell sharply against the yen.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 289.54 points,
or 1.93 percent, closing the day's trading at 14,697.08 points. On
Wednesday, the index rose 151.21 points, or 1.02 percent.
	   The dollar bought 119.23 yen in late afternoon, down 2.65 yen
from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level
of 119.93 yen overnight.
	   The Tokyo stock market started lower as an overnight decline on
Wall Street discouraged investors in Tokyo.
	   Also making many investors bearish was uncertainty about the
Japanese government's upcoming economic measures, traders said.
	   ``The market lacks both buying and selling incentives and
activities are sparse,'' said Yasuo Ueki, general manager at Nikko
Securities Co.
	   After Thursday's market closed, the Economic Planning Agency
reported Japan's economy shrank for a fourth straight quarter,
confirming what many had feared: The country remains in its deepest
recession in decades.
	   Japan's gross domestic product _ the measure of all goods and
services produced in the nation _ contracted 0.7 percent in the
July to September quarter from the previous term for an annual rate
of 2.6 percent.
	   The government announced a stimulus package last month including
public works spending at the urging of Japan's trading partners,
but economists said the effects of the steps remain unclear.
	   The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 18.26 points, or 1.59 percent, to 1,128.89 points.
The TOPIX rose 4.89 points, or 0.43 percent, the previous day.
	   Trading was moderate, with about 324 million shares changing
hands on the exchange's first section, compared with Wednesday's
turnover of 324 million shares. Declines overwhelmed advancers
1,034 to 153, with 117 issues unchanged.
	   On the foreign exchange market, rumors that a U.S. hedge fund
was selling dollars to cover emerging market losses and a drop in
Standard and Poor's 500 futures auguring another decline on Wall
Street sent the dollar to its lowest level in almost two weeks,
traders said.
	   ``The biggest reason for the dollar's fall is the drop on the S
and P,'' said Yuhiko Kaji, vice president of foreign exchange at
Sakura Bank.
	   The dollar ranged between 118.95 yen and 120.52 yen in
Thursday's trading.
	   The benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government bond fell to
1.090 percent from Wednesday's close of 1.155 percent, driving its
price up to 106.13 yen from the previous day's 105.53 yen.
 &UR; (km-dj)
</TEXT>
