<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Semiconductors </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's Fujitsu, Toshiba link-up to produce advanced computer chips
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Two of Japan's largest computer electronics makers,
Fujitsu Ltd. and Toshiba Corp., announced Thursday they will join
hands to develop advanced semiconductors.
	   The two companies plan to spend more than 30 billion yen (dlrs
252 million) on the joint project, which will involve a team of
about 100 researchers, they said in a statement.
	   The move comes amid a prolonged slump in prices for computer
memory chips, which has forced many chipmakers to reassess plans to
single-handedly invest huge sums in development and production of
the latest semiconductors.
	   Fujitsu and Toshiba said they expect to benefit by sharing the
cost and risk of developing next-generation computer chips, such as
one-gigabit dynamic random access memory (DRAM) chips.
	   A one-gigabit DRAM can store the equivalent of 100,000 pages of
newspaper text, or about four times more than the current
generation of top-line 256-megabit computer memory chips.
	   Fujitsu and Toshiba hope to make one-gigabit chips commercially
available by March 2002, at least one year earlier than industry
forecasts had estimated, said Kazunari Shirai, senior
vice-president at Fujitsu.
 &UR; (cd-dj)
</TEXT>
