w1427 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AsiaBusinessBriefs     12-03 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asia Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korea. Some of these stories also moved earlier today as
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Hong Kong, Japan, the Philippines and
separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The Japanese economy shrank for the fourth straight
quarter, continuing to wallow in the nation's deepest recession in
decades, the government said Thursday.
	   Japan's gross domestic product _ the measure of all goods and
services produced in the country _ declined by 0.7 percent in the
three months from July through September, compared to the previous
quarter, the Economic Planning Agency said.
	   The economy contracted at an annual rate of 2.6 percent, the
agency said.
	   Japan has been battered by Asia's financial meltdown, which has
slashed exports, long the mainstay of its economic growth.
	   Economic Planning Agency head Taichi Sakaiya expressed hopes
that the economy may be hitting bottom and nearing ``a dawn.''
	   But he reiterated that the economy's performance during this
fiscal year, which ends next March, may turn out to be worse than
the government prediction of a 1.8 percent contraction.
	   ``These figures actually were a little better than I expected,''
he said. ``The pace of decline is slowing.''
	   Economists were more pessimistic about when the effects of the
government steps might be felt.
	   ``The government is shrugging this off as ancient history, but
there are problems still plaguing this economy,'' said Andrew
Shipley, economist at Schroders Japan in Tokyo. ``The prospect for
recovery is quite remote.''
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Two of Japan's largest computer electronics makers,
Fujitsu Ltd. and Toshiba Corp., announced Thursday they will join
hands to develop advanced semiconductors.
	   The two companies plan to spend more than 30 billion yen (dlrs
252 million) on the joint project, which will involve a team of
about 100 researchers, they said in a statement.
	   The move comes amid a prolonged slump in prices for computer
memory chips, which has forced many chipmakers to reassess plans to
single-handedly invest huge sums in development and production of
the latest semiconductors.
	   Fujitsu and Toshiba said they expect to benefit by sharing the
cost and risk of developing next-generation computer chips, such as
one-gigabit dynamic random access memory (DRAM) chips.
	   A one-gigabit DRAM can store the equivalent of 100,000 pages of
newspaper text, or about four times more than the current
generation of top-line 256-megabit computer memory chips.
	   Fujitsu and Toshiba hope make one-gigabit chips commercially
available by March 2002, at least one year earlier than industry
forecasts had estimated, said Kazunari Shirai, senior
vice-president at Fujitsu.
	   ___
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ After thrice failing to auction it off
lock, stock and barrel, creditors said Thursday they were willing
to sell bankrupt Hanbo Steel Industry Co. piece by piece if
necessary.
	   ``We've decided to open our doors to all kinds of offers'' in a
new auction tentatively set for Dec. 15, said Chung Ki-hyun, a
spokesman for Korea First Bank, the failed steelmaker's chief
creditor.
	   ``Bidders can seek to buy facilities only or the entire
company,'' Chung said. ``There will be no minimum price, either.''
	   Local media, quoting unidentified sources, said U.S. Steel and
other steelmakers from China, Taiwan, India, Brazil and the
Netherlands have shown interest.
	   Three previous auctions last year failed because potential
buyers wanted to take over only certain facilities, not the whole
company including its debts.
	   As the sell-off efforts dragged on, the number of Hanbo
employees decreased from 3,100 to 1,300 and the steelmaker was
forced to shut down parts of its production lines earlier this
year.
	   Like many other big South Korean businesses, Hanbo had borrowed
heavily to finance its aggressive expansion in the early 1990s. But
sales lagged amid a prolonged economic slowdown, creating a serious
cash crunch.
	   Hanbo is the second major South Korean firm to be put up for
sale. Kia Motors Co. which collapsed last year with dlrs 1 billion
in bank loans was recently sold to South Korean carmaker Hyundai
Motor Co.
	   ___
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ British banking giant HSBC Holdings will freeze
salaries for more than 13,000 employees at its flagship unit, Hong
Kong and Shanghai Banking Corp. in Hong Kong.
	   The decision was made recently, to ``reflect economic
conditions'' in the territory, Gareth Hewett, a company spokesman,
said Thursday. He declined to say if the bank expects the Hong Kong
economy to deteriorate further.
	   HSBC makes up about 25 percent to 30 percent of the blue-chip
Hang Seng Index on the Hong Kong stock exchange.
	   Since the Asian financial turmoil hit Hong Kong in October 1997,
the economy has suffered rising unemployment and massive lay-offs
and freezes on salaries.
	   HSBC's other local subsidiary, Hang Seng Bank Ltd., said it
hasn't yet decided on employees' pay scales for next year, a
spokeswoman for the bank said Thursday.
	   The board usually makes decisions on salaries before late
December every year, she said.
	   Hang Seng Bank employs about 7,800 staff in Hong Kong.
	   ___
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong will increase the lending ceiling for
mortgages offered by banks early next year, a change expected to
stimulate the territory's beleaguered property and banking sectors,
the financial secretary announced Thursday.
	   The Hong Kong Monetary Authority, the territory's de facto
central bank, will raise its 70 percent ceiling on mortgages
offered by banks to 85 percent next year, Donald Tsang said.
	   The move is expected to increase bank loans for property
transactions. It will shrink the down payment required of real
estate buyers and allow banks to earn more interest by expanding
lending without taking on additional risk.
	   Tsang said the new, higher ceiling, expected to take effect
early next year, will not apply to all mortgages, but he didn't
immediately provide further details on the selection criteria.
	   Hong Kong's property market has been in a slump since the fourth
quarter of last year as potential buyers, spooked by falling
property prices, ballooning unemployment and high interest rates
hold off on investment plans.
	   ___
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Bad loans of the 54 commercial banks
operating in the Philippines rose sharply in September as more
companies failed to meet their debt obligations on time.
	   Central bank Governor Gabriel Singson said Thursday the
non-performing loan ratio of the country's commercial banks hit
11.04 percent at the end of September, up from the previous month's
10.51 percent.
	   There are no comparative year-earlier figures since the central
bank only began tracking banks' non-performing loan ratios on a
monthly basis in January. In previous years, it monitored bad loan
ratios on a quarterly basis.
	   During the quarter that ended in September 1997, the
non-performing loan ratio of commercial banks was 3.96 percent.
	   Singson was not disturbed by the rise in bad loans.
	   ``We have the lowest non-performing loan ratio in the (Asian)
region, at least among those affected by the regional crisis,'' he
said.
	   He did not provide comparative figures for the other countries
in the region. 	   
</TEXT>
