<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Pay Freeze, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong's largest bank announces pay freeze
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: LEADS throughout to RECAST and UPDATE with quotes, background &QL; 
 &UR; By PRISCILLA CHEUNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong workers were dealt another blow
Thursday when British banking giant HSBC Holdings announced it will
freeze salaries for more than 13,000 employees in the territory at
its flagship unit, Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corp.
	   Union officials said they expect more companies to follow HSBC's
lead in freezing or cutting salaries ahead of Chinese New Year in
February, the time when most companies review and restructure
operations.
	   Unemployment is already at 5.3 percent, the highest level since
1981 when officials started collecting such data, and is expected
to climb even further.
	   Gareth Hewett, an HSBC spokesman, said the decision was made
recently to ``reflect economic conditions'' in the territory. He
declined to say if the bank expects the Hong Kong economy to
deteriorate further.
	   The bank, which makes up about 25 percent to 30 percent of the
blue-chip Hang Seng Index on the Hong Kong stock exchange, reported
that profits in the first half of this year dropped 41 percent from
a year before to 6.09 billion Hong Kong dlrs (U.S. dlrs 783
million). Officials blamed dwindling profits on more bad loans and
falling asset values in Asia.
	   Most Hong Kong Bank employees reacted to the news calmly.
	   ``We've been anticipating some changes for some time, and most
of us were glad to hear that at least our salaries won't be cut,''
said a bank manager, who would only identify herself by her
surname, Wong.
	   ``It's quite natural for the bank to follow the market trend''
in cutting costs, she said.
	   Since the Asian financial turmoil hit Hong Kong in October 1997,
Hong Kong's economy has suffered rising unemployment and massive
lay-offs and freezes on salaries.
	   The government announced last Friday that the economy slid 7
percent in the third quarter, the biggest decline since records
were kept in Hong Kong.
	   Local banks are caught in the global liquidity crunch and a
property market slump, which has seen land prices tumble 50
percent.
	   More companies are expected to fold or to announce massive
layoffs and salary cuts ahead of the Chinese New Year.
	   More than 450 people have lost their jobs so far this week as
two major companies _ Hong Kong Aircraft Engineering Company and
Citibank _ announced layoffs.
	   In September, Hong Kong Telecommunications, the territory's
largest employer, announced across-the-board pay cuts, which were
later rejected by union leaders. The company is still in
negotiation with union officials on cost-cutting plans.
	   HSBC's other local subsidiary, Hang Seng Bank Ltd., said it
hasn't yet decided on employees' pay scales for next year, a
spokeswoman for the bank said Thursday.
	   The board will make a decision on salaries of Hang Seng's 7,800
employees in Hong Kong by late December, she said.
</TEXT>
