<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Burundi-Killings </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Burundian rebels kill more than 20 fellow Hutus, army says
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) _ Rebels killed more than 20 fellow
Hutus who sought refugee in a camp, accusing them of collaborating
with the Tutsi-led army, a military spokesman said Thursday.
	   Rebels attacked Gihungwe, 20 kilometers (13 miles) north of
Bujumbura, early Wednesday, killing more than 20 Hutus, including
children, and wounding at least 33, local officials said.
	   It was the second attack on the camp since November. In the
first, rebels killed 26 Hutus. On Nov. 23, rebels killed 23 Hutus
who lived in the nearby village.
	   Col. Mammert Sinarinzi, army spokesman, said in all three cases
Hutu rebels took revenge on Hutu civilians they believed were
cooperating with the army, rather than backing their rebellion.
	   Hutu rebels are fighting to topple the military rule of Pierre
Buyoya, a member of the Tutsi minority, which accounts for 14
percent of Burundi's population of 6 million. Hutus account for 85
percent.
	   More than 200,000 people have been killed since 1993 when
violence erupted in the East African nation after Tutsi
paratroopers killed the country's first democratically elected
president, a Hutu.
	   (cn-kjd)
</TEXT>
