</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Indy-Formula One,0781 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Speedway president bringing Formula One to Indianapolis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HANK LOWENKRON &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) _ Tony George is reaching deep into his
pockets to bring Formula One racing to the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway.
	   He's investing millions to create a road course to bring the
international circuit into the United States for the first time
since 1991, but he will have to wait until next year before
learning when the race will be held.
	   George and Bernie Ecclestone, the chief executive of the
international circuit, announced Wednesday they reached an
agreement for a multiyear agreement that will begin with the
running of the U.S. Grand Prix in 2000.
	   ``There is a lot that remains to be done to have our facility
ready for the new millennium, and this is going to be a very
important event for us,'' George said. ``This will establish the
face of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway heading into the new
millennium.''
	   George said making a profit on the event is not a major goal.
His initial cost for the first race, including construction and
promoter's fees could top dlrs 25 million, and Ecclestone said that
Formula One will retain all television revenue from the event.
	   Major renovations will be made at the famed 2 1/2-mile
(4-kilometer) oval, and work already has begun on the first
reconfiguration at the speedway since it was built in 1909.
	   ``Today marks the realization of a personal dream of mine since
becoming president of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway in 1990. That
is to give the United States Grand Prix a permanent home that it
deserves here in Indianapolis,'' George said. ``The U.S. Grand Prix
will join the Indianapolis 500 and the Brickyard 400 to give us
three world-class events.''
	   The F-1 race will be run on a 13-turn course that, unlike other
races at the track, will include both right and left turns. The F-1
cars will race in the opposite direction than the Indy 500 and
Brickyard 400. The new course will be constructed using part of the
existing track and part of the current infield.
	   ``This isn't a huge construction project. It is an incredibly
logistically complicated project,'' said Kevin Forbes, the track's
director of engineering and construction.
	   Forbes said construction is scheduled to be completed by either
April or August of 2000 and could be ongoing during the next two
Indianapolis 500s and Brickyard 400s.
	   Thirty-six pitside garages with suites above them will be
constructed in what is now a seating area, and demolition of a
portion of the tower terrace will begin within a week. A new press
box with seating space for 400 writers, lockers and darkrooms for
photographers and 40 television broadcast booths is included in the
construction plans, along with a new media center and control
tower.
	   The race date and possible dates for testing by F-1 teams will
be determined by the circuit next year.
	   Formula One has only one event scheduled in North America on its
1999 schedule, which includes 17 events in 16 countries. The
Canadian Grand Prix is scheduled in Montreal next June 13.
	   ``It was proposed that we run two weeks after the Canadian Grand
Prix,'' George said. ``That would definitely be a challenge.''
	   The challenge comes because the Indy 500 is run in late May and
the Brickyard 400 is held in early August.
	   ``To change the facility over from the end of May to a road race
and then turn it back around for an oval race within a span of 65
days ... From a timing standpoint, in the interest of all three
events we would like to not have to work with that (time frame),''
George said. ``In the interest of all three of our events, a fall
date would work nice.''
	   No matter when the race is held, George was delighted to have an
agreement after months of talks over bringing it to his facility.
	   ``The U.S. Grand Prix will join the Indianapolis 500 and the
Brickyard 400 at the world's most famous speedway, underscoring the
words that are chiseled in stone over the entrance of this building
_ `The racing capital of the world,''' George said.
	   The facility was used only for the Indianapolis 500 from 1911 to
l993. The Brickyard 400, a NASCAR Winston Cup event, became an
annual event in 1994. This year, the International Race of
Champions made Indy part of its series.
	   Seating for the F-1 race will be over 200,000.
	   This is not the first time the track has been associated with
Formula One. From 1950-1960, Formula One points were given in the
Indianapolis 500, but few regulars competed in the event.
</TEXT>
