<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Real Estate Stimulus, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong to relax mortgage ceiling to stimulate property sector
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADs thruout to ADD details, comments and CLARIFY that only
selected banks are eligible &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong will ease restrictions on bank
lending to home buyers early next year in a move aimed at reviving
the territory's beleaguered real estate and banking sectors, the
financial secretary announced Thursday.
	   The Hong Kong Monetary Authority, the territory's de facto
central bank, will allow banks to lend up to 85 percent of the
value of the dwelling to be purchased, lifting the current ceiling
of 70 percent.
	   The change will permit home buyers to purchase properties with a
smaller down payment. Home buyers will need to put down just 15
percent of the home's value, instead of the current 30 percent
requirement, making it easier for young and low-income families to
buy homes.
	   The move is expected to boost bank lending for property
transactions, said financial secretary Donald Tsang.
	   The government-backed Hong Kong Mortgage Corporation, which was
set up to buy mortgages from selected banks, will secure the extra
15 percent of the mortgages at a fee, he said.
	   That will allow banks to earn more interest by expanding lending
without taking on additional risk, Tsang said.
	   Real estate-related stocks rallied on the news. The index
tracking property shares closed up 2.5 percent, defying the
blue-chip Hang Seng Index, which slipped 9.63 points to 10,046.15.
	   Henderson Land shares closed up 2.6 percent at 38.90 Hong Kong
dollars, and Sun Hung Kai Properties rose 3.2 percent to end at
56.50.
	   Tsang said the new, higher ceiling, expected to take effect
early next year, will only apply to 31 banks already approved to do
business with the Hong Kong Mortgage Corporation.
	   The change will also be limited to buyers who will live in the
residence.
	   Hong Kong's property market has been in a slump since the fourth
quarter of last year as potential buyers, spooked by falling
property prices, ballooning unemployment and high interest rates,
hold off on investment plans.
	   Average prices have fallen by over 50 percent, prompting the
government to suspend a land sales program in June. Analysts are
split over whether a recent slight rebound in property sales
indicates the market has begun to bottom out.
	   The analysts said Thursday the benefits of the change for
property developers would be minimal. That's because property
companies still won't be able to significantly raise prices after
the change, and many are selling new projects at such low prices
they barely make a profit.
	   ``I don't think buyers are going to start accepting higher
prices,'' said David Faulkner, an executive at Brooke
International, a property consulting firm.
</TEXT>
