<BODY>
<SLUG> BC_Sports-Golf Nippon Series </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Miyamoto takes four-stroke first round lead
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   INAGI, Japan (AP) _ Japan's young pro Katsumasa Miyamoto sank an
eagle en route to a six-under-par 64 and took a four-stroke
first-round lead in the 100 million yen (dlrs 833,000) Golf Nippon
Series JT Cup, a tournament for the year's top golfers in Japan.
	   The 26-year-old Miyamoto, seeking his second career victory this
year, sank a 17-meter (56-foot) putt eagle on the 541-yard, par-5
sixth hole.
	   Miyamoto also had six birdies and two bogeys on the 6,960-yard,
par-70 Tokyo Yomiuri Country Club course in the outskirts of Tokyo.
	   Four strokes off Miyamoto at 68s were two Japanese _ Masashi
``Jumbo'' Ozaki and Nobuhito Sato.
	   Jumbo Ozaki is the eldest of three Ozaki brothers and leads the
Japan PGA money ranking list with two tournaments left this season.
	   Ozaki has earned 166.63 million yen (dlrs 1.4 million) with
three victories so far this season. Brandt Jobe of the United
States stood second with 95.17 million yen (dlrs 793,000).
	   Frankie Minoza of the Philippines shot a 69 and tied fourth
place with Toshimitsu Izawa of Japan.
	   Teeing off in the cold cloudy weather were an elite field of 26
made up of this year's tournament winners, the defending champion
and the top 20 on the Japan PGA money earning list.
	   The temperature on the course was a chill 4 Celsius degrees (39
F).
	   Defending champion Shigeki Maruyama shot a 74 and tied 22th
place with his fellow Japanese Keiichiro Fukabnori and Todd
Hamilton of the United States.
	   The winner will collect 30 million yen (dlrs 250,000).
 &UR; (sk) 	   
</TEXT>
