r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Election 2ndLd-Writethru   12-03 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Election, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesia releases election timetable, drops Suharto probe
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with riot police blocking student marchers. One name
correct for Suharto and Harmoko.
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By HARIS SYAMAUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia on Thursday announced an
election timetable for next year, a move that failed to appease
1,000 student protesters who marched down Jakarta's main road to
demand a trial of former President Suharto.
	   Rows of riot police and several light tanks blocked the students
from reaching the palace of President B.J. Habibie, who has pledged
democratic reforms but is deeply unpopular among students, who say
he is a stooge of his predecessor.
	   The government dropped plans to set up an independent panel to
investigate Suharto, the target of students who want him to be
tried on charges of corruption and human rights abuses.
	   Parliamentary elections will be held on June 7, and the top
legislative body that is empowered to elect a new president will
convene Aug. 29, House Speaker Harmoko said.
	   The announcement of the election dates came amid widespread
suspicion among critics that Habibie would delay the elections and
stall other political reforms.
	   Some students welcomed the timetable, but others who want an
immediate transitional government rejected it. Many have demanded
the ouster of Habibie, who took office from Suharto in May after
riots and protests against Suharto's 32-year authoritarian rule.
	   ``Is there any guarantee that the election under President
Habibie will be fair?'' said student activist Irwan Sukatmawijaya.
``We don't trust the honesty of Habibie since he is just a shadow
of Suharto.''
	   Habibie, meanwhile, abandoned plans for an independent
corruption inquiry of Suharto. The government had trouble finding
public figures who were willing to join the panel, which was viewed
as a cosmetic gesture by critics.
	   Instead, Habibie again ordered Attorney General Andi Mohamad
Ghalib to investigate Suharto. A previous inquiry by Ghalib turned
up no evidence of wrongdoing, and opponents labeled it a whitewash.
	   ``The president has instructed the attorney general to
immediately investigate and question former President Suharto,''
State Secretary Akbar Tanjung said. In recent months, Ghalib has
met Suharto twice to discuss corruption allegations.
	   In one of several protests Thursday, about 200 students said the
government was unwilling to conduct a serious probe of Suharto's
wealth.
	   ``So far, what the government has said is just lip service,''
protester Ricky Andarsa said.
	   Harmoko announced the expected June date for parliamentary
elections after a meeting with Habibie and key Cabinet ministers at
Parliament.
	   The nation's highest legislative body, the People's Consultative
Assembly, will then meet to elect a new president. There is no
direct presidential poll.
	   ``It will be up to (the assembly delegates) to set the date of
the presidential election,'' Tanjung said.
	   However, the 1,000-member assembly is packed with holdovers from
the Suharto era, including military appointees, and critics say it
does not have the credibility to choose a new leader for the nation
of 202 million people.
	   The assembly, which consists of all 500 members of Parliament as
well as delegates chosen by the president, met last month to plan
the election and approve other political reforms.
	   ``The president will consistently and effectively implement the
decrees of the recent (assembly) meeting,'' Harmoko said.
	   Habibie is expected to run for president, but his ruling Golkar
party has lost credibility because of its role as an instrument of
Suharto's rule for decades.
	   Students who want swifter democratic change protested the
assembly meeting and fought battles with security forces in the
streets surrounding Parliament. Nine students have been fatally
shot.
	   Students want military chief Gen. Wiranto, who as defense
minister attended the meeting Thursday morning at Parliament, to be
held accountable for the Nov. 13 shootings.
	   Indonesia is enduring its worst economic crisis in decades as
well as rising religious tension. Earlier this week, Christian mobs
burned mosques in a provincial capital in retaliation for attacks
by Muslim rioters on churches in the capital, Jakarta.
</TEXT>
