<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-Obit-Oda </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's first Olympic gold medalist Mikio Oda dies at 93
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to sports wires

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Mikio Oda, Japan's first Olympic gold medalist and
a contributor to the nation's track and field development, has died
of a ruptured artery, his family said Thursday. He was 93.
	   Oda, who died Wednesday, won the gold in the triple jump at the
1928 Amsterdam Olympics with a leap of 15.21 meters, boosting
Japanese interest in the world's most prestigious international
event. Three years later, he set a world record by improving his
Olympic record to 15.58 meters.
	   Oda, a native of Hiroshima, had previously set a national record
at the age of 17.
	   Known for his self-discipline and commitment in training, Oda
forced himself to work so hard he once fell asleep over dinner
while holding chopsticks, the national newspaper Asahi wrote
Thursday in its front-page obituary.
	   Oda later became a sports writer for the Asahi before becoming a
professor in the athletics department at Waseda University, his
alma mater.
	   Oda also served as a member of the Japanese Olympic Committee
and an honorary president of the Japan Amateur Athletic Federation.
	   He is survived by his two sons.
 &UR; (may)
</TEXT>
