</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Blair pushes forward deal on next steps in Belfast accord
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: PMs; NEW throughout &QL; 
 &UR; By SHAWN POGATCHNIK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Late-night negotiations led by
Prime Minister Tony Blair have narrowed the gap between Protestant
and Catholic leaders over how to make Northern Ireland's peace
accord work, both sides said Thursday.
	   Blair made no comment as he left Stormont Parliamentary Building
in east Belfast about 1 a.m. after overseeing seven hours of
discussions.
	   But senior negotiators from the major British Protestant party,
the Ulster Unionists, and the major Irish Catholic party, the
Social Democratic and Labor Party or SDLP, confirmed that a deal
was close thanks to Blair's intervention. They resumed their
haggling early Thursday but weren't sure whether a formal
announcement was still hours or days away.
	   Both sides said the Ulster Unionists agreed to create 10
departments in the new multi-party administration for Northern
Ireland envisaged in April's peace accord. The British government,
which has ruled Northern Ireland directly since 1972 and is
supposed to hand over some local powers in early 1999 under terms
of the accord, operates six departments in its Northern Ireland
Office.
	   Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble had hoped to restrict the
new administration, to be called the Executive, to six posts as
well. This would have created only one prospective position each
for the extremes of Northern Irish opinion, both hostile to
Trimble: the IRA-allied Sinn Fein party on the Catholic side and
the Democratic Unionist Party on the Protestant side.
	   Seamus Mallon of the SDLP, the would-be deputy leader of the
Executive, said Blair had ``provided the focal point'' in reaching
agreement on all 10 departments, which include areas of special
concern to Catholics.
	   Reflecting their levels of electoral support, the Ulster
Unionists and SDLP would hold three Executive posts each, not
counting Trimble and Mallon, who were appointed in July to oversee
the cabinet-style administration. Sinn Fein and the Democratic
Unionists would be entitled to two posts each.
	   To encourage this concession, the Catholic side softened its
demand for the new Northern Ireland administration to coordinate
economic development with the Irish government. However, Mallons
said the north's Catholics still expected to forge common economic
cause with the predominantly Catholic south.
	   April's accord called for the new Northern Ireland government to
form at least six joint policy-making committees with the Irish
Republic, which won independence from Britain in 1922.
	   Both the SDLP and Sinn Fein consider cross-border cooperation a
key way to promote the eventual unification of Ireland.
	   But actually forming the Executive will remain an elusive goal.
Trimble is refusing to accept that Sinn Fein can participate in
government if its allies in the Irish Republican Army won't start
disarming. The IRA insists it won't do this.
	   (sp-rb)
</TEXT>
