<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Strikes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Customs workers continue strike as government ponders action
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ With fuel supplies running critically low,
the government and striking customs workers were on a collision
course Thursday after union leaders ignored a court order to return
to work.
	   The walkout, which began Monday, has severely cut the flow of
gasoline and heating oil _ which mostly arrives in Greece via
non-European Union nations. Goods shipped from EU partners are not
affected by the strike.
	   Many gas stations have run dry and heating oil is growing scarce
_ a particular problem in chilly northern Greece.
	   A judge declared the strike illegal Wednesday, but the workers
refused to obey. Union leaders sought legal loopholes to bypass the
ruling.
	   Labor Minister Miltiades Papaioannou warned that the
``government will take those steps necessary for the public good.''
Papaioannou didn't specify the possible measures, but one option
would be declaring a national emergency and forcing the workers
back to their posts.
	   The Socialist government is determined not to back pedal on
proposed reforms aimed at qualify Greece for the EU single currency
group by 2001.
	   The customs workers were protesting plans to consolidate their
pension fund with other agencies. But they considered changing
their demands as part of maneuvering to circumvent the judge's
order.
	   Other labor groups have launched a barrage of strikes that have
disrupted life around the country.
	   On Thursday, railway workers continued a work stoppages.
Teachers also stayed off the job as part of rallies against
proposed education reforms, including adding competency tests for
teacher candidates.
	   The main labor unions also plan a nationwide general strike Dec.
15.
	   pq-bm 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Greece-Strikes; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:MEST;)
