w1503 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-India-Movie     12-03 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Movie,0425 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hindu activists vandalize theater showing controversial movie
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Hindu activists went on a rampage
Thursday in a movie theater screening a film with lesbian scenes
and themes challenging Indian family traditions.
	   About a half dozen men and women smashed glass display cases
with movie posters outside the theater, windows and the snack bar
in the lobby of the Regal Theater and trashed the restaurant next
door in New Delhi's colonial-era Connaught Circus business
district.
	   No one was injured, and the vandals were blocked from entering
the hall where the film was showing, which was filled for the
afternoon performance.
	   Reporters were given advance warning of the attack on the
theater by activists of the Shiv Sena, a Hindu fundamentalist
political party allied with the governing Bharatiya Janata Party.
	   J.B. Goel, president of Shiv Sena's New Delhi chapter, said
scenes in the film ``Fire'' of women making love were
``objectionable and not in keeping with Indian culture.''
	   ``Fire'' tells the story of women in unhappy marriages to two
brothers living in New Delhi in what is called a joint family _ the
brothers, both their wives and their mother under one roof. The
sisters-in-law, seeking comfort from each other, develop a lesbian
relationship.
	   The film tackles issues rarely addressed in India, including the
unhappiness of women in tradition-minded families who are expected
to suppress their desires while serving their men and their elders.
Homosexuality also is rarely discussed in India.
	   Regal's manager, Ravi Sharma, said the movie would continue to
be shown at the theater.
	   ``If they continue to show the film, we will take action,'' Goel
said, refusing to elaborate.
	   India's massive film industry churns out hundreds of films every
year, but most are song-and-dance romances or thrillers that
reinforce traditional themes rather than question them.
	   On Wednesday, more than 100 Shiv Sena activists stormed two
theaters in Bombay, India's film capital, and prevented the
screening of the film.
	   ``Fire,'' filmed in both English and Hindi, has won several
international awards. Film critics were amazed when the Indian
censorship board allowed the movie to be screened almost uncut and
did not snip the scenes of the two women kissing.
	   The movie has been showing for several weeks across India,
sparking little comment until this week. Goel said he had only
recently learned of the movie.
</TEXT>
