<HEADLINE>
Precede SARAJEVO
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Muslims cheer the arrest of a Bosnian Serb general; Serbs downgrade
relations with NATO troops
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Bosnian Serb reaction; changes byline
 &UR; By IRENA GAJIC
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANJA LUKA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ While drawing praise from
the Muslim leadership, the arrest of a Bosnian Serb general
indicted for war crimes has united Serb moderates and radicals in
condemnation.
	   On Wednesday, NATO troops arrested Gen. Radislav Krstic on
charges of alleged involvement in massacres of Muslims that
occurred after his troops overran the eastern enclave of Srebrenica
in summer 1995.
	   Krstic was arrested in the northern part of Bosnia, in the
sector controlled by U.S. troops.
	   Reacting to the arrest, parliament meeting in the city of Banja
Luka in the Serb half of Bosnia late Wednesday passed a resolution
saying the government would ``reduce to a minimum'' relations with
the Bosnia's NATO-led peace force.
	   The resolution, which mentioned no specifics, said relations
would be downgraded until the peace force stops what Bosnian Serbs
allege are violations of its mandate, including the arrest of
Krstic.
	   Bosnian Serb President Nikola Poplasen said the arrest caused
``revolt and alarm'' among Bosnian Serbs. It suggests that ``every
Serb is a potential war criminal if he in any way too part in the
past war,'' said Poplasen.
	   Moderates normally at odds with Poplasen also condemned the
arrest, on an indictment from the U.N. war crimes tribunal. Zivko
Radisic, the Serb member of Bosnia's three-person presidency, said
it ``can jeopardize the overall process of democratization and ruin
efforts to rebuild trust and tolerance.''
	   Bosnia's Muslims praised Krstic's detention.
