w1509 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Cycling-Doping     12-03 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-Doping </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Virenque and Herve took EPO 100 times a year, says former masseur
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ French cyclists Richard Virenque and Pascal Herve,
who both flatly deny claims they took banned drugs, have been
accused by a former masseur of using EPO about 100 times a year.
	   Willy Voet, in an interview published Thursday in the newspaper
France-Soir, said Virenque and Herve, both members of the disgraced
Festina team, regularly took EPO, or erythropoietin, and other
drugs.
	   ``They consumed more than anybody. On average they received
between 90 and 100 (EPO) injections per year,'' Voet was quoted as
saying.
	   Voet also said Virenque would take a cocktail including heroin,
cocaine and amphetamines, although he said the star cyclist was
``very prudent'' regarding consumption.
	   Voet said Virenque also took growth hormones to prepare for the
Tour de France, which he said was the cyclists's top priority.
	   Medical tests suggest cyclists on the Festina team, expelled
from the Tour de France this summer, took banned drugs, judicial
sources said Tuesday citing a judge's report.
	   In addition to the presence of EPO, a banned drug Festina
officials had already admitted using, the report included
revelations that amphetamines were found in the tests of four
cyclists.
	   The four named were Laurent Brochard, the 1997 world road racing
champion; Christophe Moreau; Didier Rous; and Herve.
	   Virenque said the figures vindicate his claim that he didn't
take banned substances.
	   According to judicial sources who saw the report, the results
showed Virenque had a hematocrit level of 49.3 percent. The
hematocrit level measures the proportion of red blood cells in a
blood sample _ one sign of doping, since the substances increase
red blood cells.
	   But Virenque's level is just within the limit of 50 percent set
by the International Cycling Union, the sport's governing body.
	   Herve had a level of 52.6.
	   Virenque and Herve both deny they knowingly took any banned
substances.
	   Three Festina officials have been put under formal
investigation, one step short of being formally charged: Voet; team
doctor Eric Ryckaert; and sporting director Bruno Roussel.
	   (ip-jn) 	   
</TEXT>
