<HEADLINE>
Bosnia rail workers halt strike as government promises back pay
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ Rail workers in Muslim-Croat
controlled Bosnia halted a one-day strike Thursday after the
government promised to pay unpaid wages.
	   The Muslim-Croat Federation government said workers will be paid
in the next few days. Complaints that the government was four
months in arrears with wages sparked the one day strike Wednesday,
which delayed some commuter lines.
	   The strike was also meant to protest the failure of the
government and international authorities to link railway service
across Bosnia and to other countries.
	   The postwar unification of the Bosnian railroad is required
under the 1995 peace agreement. But Bosnian Serbs insist on a
separate railroad company for their half of the country.
	   The 3 1/2 year war ended in 1995 with a peace agreement that
divided the country between the Bosnian Serbs and a federation of
Muslims and Croats.
