w1528 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-WorldBank     12-03 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-World Bank </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia seeks new World Bank loan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia has asked the World Bank
for loans totaling dlrs 3 billion this year to revive its sagging
economy, a top finance ministry official said Thursday.
	   An application for a dlrs 2 billion loan was submitted in July
in addition to earlier requests for loans of dlrs 300 million and
dlrs 700 million, Bernama news agency quoted Junior Finance
Minister Mustapa Mohamed as saying.
	   It was the first time that Malaysia has disclosed it made the
July application.
	   Mustapa said the dlrs 300 million loan was given in June, but
the World Bank would need more time to process the other two loan
applications.
	   Malaysia is also trying to borrow money from Singapore and Japan
to shore up its recession-hit economy.
	   ``We haven't borrowed from the World Bank for quite some time
now,'' Mustapa was quoted as saying. The last time Malaysia went to
the bank was in 1994 for a dlrs 70 million loan.
	   Malaysia had no need to borrow because its economy was growing
at more than 8 percent annually. But since the Asian financial
crisis last year, the economy began to sputter, collapsing into
recession this year.
	   The new loans were mostly for low-cost housing, agriculture,
infrastructure, transportation and education.
	   Mustapa said the World Bank sent six missions to Malaysia last
month to assess the loan requirements and make recommendations to
its board of directors.
	   Malaysia is also looking for alternatives to international
capital markets and the International Monetary Fund to finance its
recapitalization needs. It is unlikely to be able to raise money by
selling bonds overseas because of progressive downgrades.
	   On Thursday, Moody's Investors Services announced that its
outlook for Malaysia and five of the country's banks was negative,
perhaps setting the stage for a further downgrade of Malaysian
bonds.
	   Authorities estimate the country will need 62 billion ringgit
(dlrs 16.31 billion) to fix its ailing banking system and revive
the economy, which shrank 8.6 percent in the third quarter of 1998.
</TEXT>
