r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-US-STARTII     12-03 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-US-START II </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian parliament inches its way toward decision on START II
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Senior Russian lawmakers voiced hopes Thursday
that parliament would soon ratify the START II arms reduction
treaty with the United States.
	   Parliament's lower house, the State Duma, agreed to finish its
work by next Tuesday on a measure that outlines Russia's nuclear
weapons program, said Duma speaker Gennady Seleznyov. The bill will
then be sent to President Boris Yeltsin.
	   ``It will spell out Russia's military doctrine and guidelines
for developing new weapons that would ensure Russia's security,''
Seleznyov told reporters.
	   Some Duma members in the past have talked about setting
conditions for ratification _ a move that might require the U.S.
Senate to review the treaty again. However, Seleznyov didn't
mention any proposals that would make ratification conditional on
additional actions by the United States.
	   Vladimir Lukin, the head of the Duma's foreign affairs
committee, said he expected the president to return the bill to the
Duma without any major alterations. That could set the stage for
approval of the START II treaty.
	   Yeltsin previously submitted the START II treaty to the Duma for
ratification.
	   But Russian lawmakers wanted to outline priorities for
developing the country's nuclear arsenal before approving the
treaty.
	   START II, which the two countries signed in 1993, would halve
Russian and American nuclear arsenals to 3,000-3,500 warheads each.
	   The U.S. Senate ratified it in 1996, but the Communist-led
opposition in the Russian parliament has balked, claiming that
dismantling strategic weapons would harm Russia's security and be
too expensive.
	   The Russian government and military leaders have strongly pushed
for ratification, saying that Russia will have to soon decommission
its aging missiles anyway.
	   There's been some progress in recent weeks, and Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov has made a renewed push to convince lawmakers to
ratify the document.
	   (vi/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
