<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taipei mayoral candidates square off over China, ethnicity
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo TPE101 &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER BODEEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Taipei mayoral challenger Ma Ying-jeou
said Thursday he offers voters a stark choice: ethnic
reconciliation and security, or social schism and the potential for
a rockier relationship with mainland China.
	   Ma hopes to retake the capital for the ruling Nationalists and
is running a tight race against incumbent Chen Shui-bian in a
contest that has become the focal point for Saturday's elections.
	   Speaking to foreign and Taiwanese journalists, Ma tore into
Chen, accusing him of sowing division by reopening old ethnic
wounds. Ma branded himself himself a ``New Taiwanese,'' a label to
encompass natives as well as those who immigrated from the mainland
after the 1949 civil war.
	   ``My election would symbolize the new spirit of integration. I
want to accelerate integration, not divide,'' Ma said.
	   If Chen's opposition Democratic Progressive Party makes further
gains, the island could find itself steering onto a dangerous
course of confrontation with Beijing, Ma warned.
	   If Chen can fend off Ma's challenge, it would raise the prospect
of a strong DPP challenger for the presidency in 16 months, when
President Lee Teng-hui is set to retire.
	   A DPP government could bring to a head the issue of Taiwan's
precarious relationship with prickly neighbor China, as the party
has advocated formal independence from the mainland.
	   Amid threats of Chinese military attack, Chen has avoided
talking about independence, though he stresses his willingness to
stand up to Chinese intimidation.
	   Ma's conciliatory stance and charismatic personality have placed
him in a statistical dead heat with Chen, according to the latest
polls. Voters will also choose a new Legislature, a mayor for
Taiwan's second largest city, Kaohsiung, and city councils for
Taipei and Kaohsiung.
	   Observers have said there is little difference in the positions
taken by the candidates _ but the outcome of the race could
influence Taiwanese politics when voters choose their next
president.
	   Knocking Chen out of office could put the Nationalists on course
to retain the presidency and thwart the DPP's hopes of building on
huge gains made in last year's local elections.
	   Chen has campaigned on his record as Taipei's first opposition
mayor and played up the Nationalists' reputation for corruption.
	   Ma, whose youthful looks have earned him the nickname ``Sonny
Boy Ma,'' counters he wants to clean things up. He adds that Taipei
needs more investment in infrastructure and public safety to
compete as a world-class city.
	   He casts himself as a reformer from within, someone who held key
policymaking posts within the Nationalist government at a time when
Chen was leading street protests demanding more democracy.
	   The national identity question has loomed over the election,
both in the campaign rhetoric and in the minds of many voters.
	   ``I'm against Taiwan independence because it's dangerous. Ma is
smart and clean. He's my hero,'' said Charlene Wang, a 29-year old
accountant attending a Ma rally at a downtown park.
	   Ma's good looks don't hurt him either, Wang added.
	   Both Chen and Ma are lawyers and graduates of Taiwan's best
university but differ greatly in their public images. Chen styles
himself the country boy made good, while Ma exudes the
sophistication of the Wall Street legal consultant he once was.
	   Ma has sought to transform himself for the podium, studying the
earthy Taiwanese dialect and revving up his low-key style to
compete with Chen, who learned his fiery oratory as an outspoken
city councilor and legislator.
	   Ma, who moved to Taiwan when he was just a year old, told a news
conference he resents questions raised by Chen's camp over his
loyalty to the island.
	   Chen, who like most of the island's residents traces his roots
here for generations, has called Ma a pawn of a secret conspiracy
to betray Taiwan to China.
	   Ma insisted Thursday he would fight the Chinese if necessary,
adding that he jogs every day to keep fit.
</TEXT>
