</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Anwar Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Key prosecution witness admits meeting Mahathir
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS with prosecution witness saying he met with prime
minister, other details
 &UR; With BC-Malaysia-Anwar Search
 &UR; By ALVIN UNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ A key prosecution witness
testifying against jailed politician Anwar Ibrahim admitted
Thursday to meeting Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad 10 days before
the Malaysian leader sacked his deputy.
	   Azizan Abu Bakar, a former driver of Anwar's wife, has testified
that Anwar repeatedly sodomized him.
	   Allegations by Azizan and Ummi Hafilda Ali, the sister of
Anwar's former private secretary, are among the most damning
revealed during the month-long trial. Ummi alleges that while Anwar
was deputy prime minister, he had an affair with her brother's
wife.
	   When defense attorney Christopher Fernando asked Azizan how many
times he had met Mahathir, he replied: ``Just once.''
	   Azizan did not give any details of the Aug. 24 meeting with
Mahathir.
	   Prosecutors are trying to prove Anwar abused his powers by
forcing police to obtain retractions from Azizan and Ummi and cover
up his sexual trysts.
	   The defense, however, insists there was a high-level conspiracy
involving senior Cabinet ministers to destroy Anwar politically.
	   Anwar is charged with 10 counts of corruption and illegal sex
acts, charges he vehemently denies.
	   When Fernando asked why it took Azizan five years, until 1997,
to make the allegations against Anwar, he said: ``Because Ummi made
me realize that the things Anwar was doing to me were vile.''
	   He said he did not remember the time and dates of the acts of
sodomy in 1992. Sodomy is a crime in this predominantly Muslim
nation.
	   Azizan also told the court he was frequently called by the
then-deputy prime minister and ordered to hinder police
investigations into allegations contained in a book.
	   He alleged that Anwar used intimidation and surveillance to
block him from cooperating with the police probe.
	   The probe into accusations in ``Fifty Reasons Why Anwar Ibrahim
Cannot Become Prime Minister'' became the basis for the charges for
which Anwar is being tried.
	   It alleges that the 51-year-old heir apparent to Mahathir had
sexual flings while in office.
	   Before the book was published, Azizan had written to authorities
alleging that he was repeatedly sodomized by Anwar. He said he was
forced to retract those allegations under duress but now stood by
them.
	   ``Ummi Hafilda and I felt very scared because we were tailed by
people we didn't know,'' Azizan told the trial court Thursday.
	   He said he received phone calls from Anwar questioning him on
how he could have been involved in writing the sworn statement
containing the allegations.
	   Mahathir fired Anwar Sept. 2, saying he had personally
determined Anwar was morally unfit for office. Anwar's sacking led
to his demands for political reforms and dozens of massive
anti-government protests in the Southeast Asian capital.
	   On Wednesday, Azizan shocked the court by saying he was once
Anwar's ``homosexual slave.''
	   ``This heinous act was committed several times in 1992 against
my will. It regularly took place in luxury hotels ... without the
knowledge of the public and his wife,'' he said.
	   Acrimony in court between the defense and prosecution deepened
Thursday as more evidence was piled against Anwar.
	   The prosecutors accused defense lawyers of stealing court
documents from them and even lodged a police report. The police
acted quickly by sending officers armed with a search warrant to
one of the defense attorney's office on Wednesday.
	   ``You should make a strong statement asking the prosecution not
to harass the defense counsel,'' Haji Sulaiman, a leading defense
lawyer told Judge Augustine Paul.
	   ``We are being accused of theft, my Lord,'' he said.
</TEXT>
