<SLUG> BC-Italy-Secessionist Murder </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Appeals court overturns conviction of university professor in
</HEADLINE>
secessionist slaying &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BOLZANO, Italy (AP) _ An appeals court has overturned the
conviction of a university professor sentenced to 22 years in
prison for the slaying of the leader of a German-speaking
separatist movement in northern Italy.
	   The court ruled on Wednesday that Peter Paul Rainer's confession
was coerced.
	   He was convicted of the Feb. 15, 1997, shooting to death
Christian Waldner, one of the founders of Freihetliche or Freedom
Movement.
	   Rainer was a member of Freihetliche, one of several groups
seeking autonomy for the predominantly German-speaking regions of
northern Italy that were annexed from Austria at the end of World
War I.
	   Rainer, an Italian citizen who taught history at the University
of Innsbruck in Austria, said initially that he shot Waldner
because Waldner threatened to reveal that he'd never finished high
school and had used a falsified diploma to enter college.
	   Rainer later retracted the confession.
	   Although the appeals court overturned his murder conviction, it
upheld his six-month prison sentence for illegal possession of a
firearm.
	   Rainer has been in jail since he was arrested shortly after the
slaying. He was convicted by a trial court in the northern city of
Bolzano in August, 1997.
	   (vg/cph)
</TEXT>
