<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Obit-Holy Man </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Romanian holy man persecuted by communists dies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Orthodox Monks have one name

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ Cleopa, the charismatic Romanian monk
persecuted by communists and admired by pilgrims, has died in his
secluded wilderness monastery, a church official announced
Thursday. He was 87.
	   Cleopa, who hid in forests from communists and was known for
comforting words for common people, succumbed to age-related
illnesses Wednesday in the Sihastria monastery deep in the forest
of northern Romania, said the Romanian Orthodox Church in Iasi.
	   Hounded by the Securitate communist secret police, who feared
his popular appeal, Cleopa fled to the forest in 1953 building an
underground den where he lived in hiding for almost a decade.
	   Every month, a woodcutter brought him a sack of potatoes. Cleopa
said he ate one potato a day _ all he needed to survive.
	   In an interview with the Associated Press in October, Cleopa
talked about his 60 years of work as a spiritual father or
``duhovnic'' in the Romanian Orthodox Church.
	   ``The spiritual father is the soul of the monastery and of the
village. He should be the light of the world by his life and
sermons,'' he said.
	   Born into a family of peasants in a village in northern Romania,
	   Cleopa became a monk at 25. After he entered the monastery he
worked as a shepherd for 12 years, gaining a good knowledge of the
countryside which helped him when he took refuge in the forest.
	   He was best known for his understanding of ordinary peoples'
problems and his healing words which tens of thousands sought both
under communism and in the years of hardship that followed the
toppling of communist rule in 1989.
	   ``He knew the needs and soul of the Romanian people,'' said Dan
Ciachir, a Christian Orthodox expert. ``He didn't have a very
elevated language, but he knew how to comfort people.''
	   Cleopa will be buried Saturday at the Sihastria monastery, 320
kilometers (200 miles) north of Bucharest where he had lived for 30
years. Thousands of people are expected to attend the funeral.
	   Romanian Orthodox monks are buried sitting in a chair, which is
lowered directly into the ground.
	   (am/amb/gj)
</TEXT>
