<SLUG> BC-Uganda-U.S. Embassy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Road reopened outside U.S. Embassy in Uganda
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ A thoroughfare outside the U.S. Embassy
in Kampala, closed after terrorists attacked American embassies in
neighboring Tanzania and Kenya, reopened Thursday, a spokesman
said.
	   U.S. officials closed four-lane Parliament Avenue in the
aftermath of the bombings that killed 224 people on Aug. 7, fearing
other embassies could be targeted.
	   Embassy spokesman Virgil Bodeen said Parliament Avenue reopened
to one lane of traffic Thursday. ``The merchants along the road
must be quite relieved,'' Bodeen said, adding the closure hut their
businesses.
	   Concrete barriers were being laid to block off much of the road
near the embassy, and parking, which previously was allowed on both
sides of Parliament Avenue, was now prohibited near the embassy, he
said.
	   Concrete blocks also were being placed on roads around other
U.S. facilities, including the U.S. Agency for International
Development and the Peace Corps, Bodeen said.
	   Eventually, the embassy will be moved to a safer location, but
not for several years, he said. The land has been purchased, but
construction plans have not been drafted, Bodeen said.
	   The U.S. mission has been in the location since its
establishment in 1962, but it was closed during civil war from 1972
to 1979.
	    &UR; (dmc-kjd)
</TEXT>
