<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine stocks plunge on inflation worries; index down 4.2
</HEADLINE>
percent
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with peso closing nearly 1 percent higher

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine stocks fell sharply
Thursday because of worries over a possible surge in inflation and
its impact on interest rates, traders said.
	   The peso, meanwhile, hit a new six-month high against the
dollar, lifted by a large influx of U.S. currency sent from
overseas Filipino workers, dealers said.
	   The 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange Index plunged 78.97
points, or 4.2 percent, to 1,807.03 after retreating 35.79 points
Wednesday.
	   While economists are predicting a slight improvement in November
inflation, the market was awash with speculation that the actual
figures could be worse and might even hit 11 percent, a rate the
country hasn't seen since January 1996.
	   Inflation data are to be released either Friday or Monday.
	   Interest rates have been steadily declining in recent months,
but a surge in inflation could reverse the trend.
	   The broader All Shares Index was down 19.87 points at 585.29
following Thursday's 9.70-point decline. Losers beat gainers 88 to
26, with 22 issues unchanged.
	   Hit hardest by the drop, initiated by foreign brokerage houses,
were interest rate-sensitive property stocks.
	   Economists are expecting inflation in November to slow slightly
to 10.1 percent from October's 10.2 percent.
	   But Erwin Balita, analyst for Securities 2000, said market
speculation placed the November inflation at closer to 11 percent
due to spikes in food prices in the aftermath of strong typhoons in
late October.
	   Even if true, Balita said, the sudden rise in inflation should
not be cause for worry because food prices have since declined.
Nevertheless, he added, the talk provided the trigger to an
underlying pressure to sell.
	   ``More than anything else it was panic,'' said Cesar Tanquincen,
portfolio manager for IB Jimenez Securities, noting that local
brokerage houses joined the sellers' bandwagon when foreign
brokerages started selling.
	   Tanquincen said a rebound is likely Friday, especially if
inflation numbers don't confirm market rumors.
	   In currency trading, the yen's buoyant performance against the
U.S. dollar also helped lift the peso.
	   The peso hit an intraday high of 38.700 pesos per dollar, its
highest level since reaching 38.626 pesos on May 27.
	   For the day, the dollar averaged 38.759 pesos, down nearly 1
percent from Wednesday's 39.101 pesos. It traded in a thin range
between 38.700 pesos and 38.870 pesos.
	   An estimated 4.5 million Filipinos work abroad, sending home at
least dlrs 6 billion last year. Their foreign-exchange remittances
provide an important contribution to the Philippine economy and are
expected to help support the peso over the rest of the year.
	   The central bank wasn't active in the spot market. It held its
overnight borrowing and lending rates at 13.375 percent and 15.375
percent, respectively.
</TEXT>
