<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong Stocks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong property shares rally, easing market's losses
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Shares fell slightly Thursday, with a strong
rebound by property stocks staving off a heftier drop.
	   The blue-chip Hang Seng Index slipped 9.63 points, or 0.1
percent, to close at 10,046.15.
	   A smaller index tracking Hong Kong real estate companies dropped
as much as 3 percent in early trading but then bounced back to show
a gain of 2.5 percent.
	   On Wednesday, the Hang Seng had risen 0.8 percent after plunging
7.5 percent in the previous three sessions.
	   The sharp turnaround by property companies late Thursday was
triggered by news that the Hong Kong Monetary Authority _ the
territory's de facto central bank _ will raise the ceiling on
mortgage lending to 85 percent of the purchase price from 70
percent.
	   That prompted some investors who had sold off real estate stocks
to buy them back, said Andrew To, sales director at Tai Fook
Securities Co.
	   Market turnover rose as investors cashed in on early gains,
hitting 5.61 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 719 million),
compared with Wednesday's 4.54 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs
582 million).
	   Property giants led the gainers, with Henderson Land rising 1.10
to close at 38.90 and Sun Hung Kai Properties rising 1.75 to close
at 56.50.
	   Hang Seng Bank was up 1.00 to close at 66.25.
	   Market heavyweight HSBC Holdings led the losers, falling 2.50 to
close at 186.50. Hong Kong Electric also fell 0.65 to close at
25.00, while China Telecom fell 0.60 to close at 25.00.
	   Hong Kong's flag carrier Cathay Pacific remained unchanged at
7.65, while conglomerate Swire Pacific ``A'' rose 0.60 to close at
35.30.
</TEXT>
