<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian prime minister calls for more detailed economic plan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: NEW grafs 13-15 with state savings bank releasing money from
private accounts. &QL; 
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government needs to come up with a more
detailed economic recovery plan, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
said Thursday, just a day after the International Monetary Fund
chief left without promising Moscow any new loans.
	   Primakov's government has produced an anti-crisis program, but
the measures have not reversed the country's economic slide, nor
have they found favor with the IMF or other international lenders
that have frozen loans to Russia.
	   Primakov acknowledged the need to spell out the government's
intentions more clearly and called on the Cabinet to approve a more
detailed document.
	   ``Without such a concrete action plan, containing concrete tasks
and time frames, the government's steps will look merely like
intentions,'' Primakov said.
	   IMF chief Michel Camdessus left Russia on Wednesday after
meeting with Primakov and other top officials. He praised
Primakov's ``pragmatic'' course in dealing with the crisis, but
said an IMF team would have to return to Russia next month for
further negotiations on loans to Russia.
	   The IMF organized a dlrs 22.6 billion bailout package this
summer, but only about dlrs 5 billion was disbursed before Russia's
economic crisis hit in August and the loans were frozen.
	   The IMF has indicated that Russia's draft budget for next year
appears overly optimistic, and it also does not like moves to
increase the government's role in the economy.
	   Meanwhile, the speaker of Russia's parliament lashed out at the
IMF for refusing to release loans.
	   ``Look how they are mocking our government, sending one group
after another,'' said Gennady Seleznyov, a Communist who serves as
speaker for the State Duma, parliament's lower house. ``Now
Camdessus has come and again asked us to wait until tomorrow.''
	   Seleznyov suggested that Russia print more money to pay off its
debts and then refuse to take any more loans.
	   ``It's high time to take these shackles off Russia's feet,'' he
told reporters.
	   In other economic developments Thursday:
	   _ Sberbank, the giant state-savings bank, has begun to service
individual accounts that were transferred to the bank from six
ailing commercial banks.
	   The government in September guaranteed the savings accounts of
all depositors who moved their money from the troubled commercial
banks into Sberbank.
	   Many individuals took the offer, though some keep their money in
commercial banks, which are still struggling to survive.
	   _ Inflation was up 5.7 percent in November, compared to 4.5
percent in October, the State Statistics Committee said.
	   Inflation has calmed since shooting up in August and September
in the immediate aftermath of the crisis. However, inflation is up
about 70 percent compared to last December, Central Bank chief
Viktor Gerashchenko said Wednesday.
	   _ Russia's hard currency reserves dropped by dlrs 200 million in
the last week of November and stood at dlrs 12.8 billion on Nov.
27, the Central Bank said Thursday. It didn't give a reason, though
the government spent some of its reserves to service foreign debts
during this period.
	   (vi/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
