<HEADER>
w1609 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AsianMarkets     12-03 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Most Asian markets fall on Wall Street's overnight drop
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Most Asian markets fell Thursday on an
overnight drop on Wall Street that was prompted by a deteriorating
corporate earnings outlook in the United States.
	   In Tokyo, shares fell sharply following U.S. stocks, which also
pulled the U.S. dollar down against the yen.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 289.54 points,
or 1.93 percent, to close at 14,697.08.
	   In mid-afternoon trading, the dollar bought 119.46 yen, down
2.42 yen in Tokyo late Wednesday and also below its late New York
level of 119.93 yen overnight.
	   Rumors that a U.S. hedge fund was selling dollars to cover
emerging market losses also helped send the dollar to its lowest
level in almost two weeks.
	   On Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 69 points to
9,064.54 on worries that weak demand from Asia would hit earnings
at American companies.
	   In Hong Kong, shares fell slightly although a strong rebound in
property stocks staved off a heftier drop.
	   The blue-chip Hang Seng Index dropped 9.63 points, or 0.1
percent, to close at 10,046.15.
	   A smaller index tracking Hong Kong real estate companies dropped
as much as 3 percent in early trading but then bounced back to show
a gain of 2.5 percent.
	   The turnaround by property companies was triggered by news that
the Hong Kong Monetary Authority _ the territory's de facto central
bank _ was easing restrictions on bank loans to home buyers in a
move seen as helping the territory's ailing property market.
	   ELSEWHERE:
	   BANGKOK: Shares dropped despite local buying. The SET index lost
5.26 points, or 1.5 percent, to end at 337.86.
	   JAKARTA: Shares fell, with the Indonesian government's upbeat
forecast for next year's budget having little impact. The JSX
Composite Index was down 3.169 points, or 0.8 percent, at 393.795.
	   KUALA LUMPUR: Shares dropped as investors cashed out of the
market after a series of recent gains. The Composite Index fell
4.99 points, or 0.94 percent, to finish at 521.76 points.
	   MANILA: Shares fell sharply on worries over possible inflation
and its impact on interest rates. The PSE Index plunged 78.97
points, or 4.2 percent, to 1,807.03.
	   SINGAPORE: Pessimistic traders pushed shares lower. The STI fell
40.16 points, or 2.9 percent, to close at 1,343.43.
	   SYDNEY: Shares fell as traders shrugged off a cut in local
interest rates. The All Ordinaries index was down 40.7 points, or
1.47 percent, to close at 2,720.3.
	   SEOUL: Share prices rose on expectations of progress in
corporate restructuring. The KOSPI index was up 1.76 points, or
0.40 percent, to close at 448.11.
	   TAIPEI: Shares fell on caution over mayoral and legislative
elections Saturday. The Weighted Price Index was down 17.11 points,
or 0.24 percent, to close at 7,140.11.
	   WELLINGTON: Shares fell for the third consecutive session. The
NZSE-40 was down 27.86 points, or 1.4 percent, to close at
1,903.64.
</TEXT>
