</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Ousted Bank Chief </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tearful ex-bank boss says he was set up in major depositors' run
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ The ousted boss of a bank whose troubles
sparked the biggest run on deposits in Taiwan's history emerged
from seclusion Thursday and tearfully complained he was set up.
	   ``Personally, I'm not a bad guy,'' said Tseng Chen-jen, who was
thrown out as chairman of the Taichung Business Bank on Nov. 25
amid allegations of improper lending. ``I will not evade a problem
and I will not flee.''
	   After regulators removed Tseng, panicked depositors lined up and
pulled out 40 billion Taiwan dollars (U.S. dlrs 1.2 billion) in
less than 24 hours.
	   Authorities said Tseng was appointed to his post on Oct. 31 and
within days the bank had made loans of up to 7.4 billion Taiwan
dollars (U.S. dlrs 227 million) to six shaky investment and
property companies that had suspected ties to Tseng.
	   Speaking to reporters, Tseng avoided questions about any loans
being made without proper collateral, but said he was talking to
several parties about taking an interest in his conglomerate, Kuang
Shan Group.
	   Although Tseng said he was set up, he did not provide any
details.
	   Several other directors were also removed from the bank in
Taichung, which is in central Taiwan about 120 miles (200
kilometers) south of the capital, Taipei. The government ordered
new supervisors to take control of the bank and provide emergency
cash to reassure people that their money would be safe.
	   The day after the bank run, authorities barred Tseng from
leaving Taiwan pending investigations into allegations that he
abused his position.
	   A newspaper reported Tseng had gotten into financial trouble
during a property slump several years ago, but he bailed himself
out by going to a Las Vegas casino where he won U.S. dlrs 30
million.
</TEXT>
