w1653 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APNewsSummary     12-03 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0925 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   Here is a summary of news from The Associated Press. Stories
carried ``i'' or ``f'' category codes. Some of the items below have
moved on this circuit in expanded form:
	   CAPE CANAVERAL, Florida (AP) _ An alarm that went off in the
cockpit just minutes before liftoff forced NASA to scrub Thursday's
launch of space shuttle Endeavour on the first space station
construction flight. The alarm sounded with about five minutes
remaining in the countdown. NASA counted down to the 31-second mark
and debated what might have caused the master alarm to go off.
Managers counted down several more seconds before calling off the
attempt for the day. Until practically the last minute, NASA
worried that rain and accompanying clouds would foil the launch.
But the rain drifted away in time for the targeted 3:58 a.m. (0858
GMT) liftoff _ and then the alarm went off. Endeavour's pilots
reported that the alarm sounded right around the time shuttle
hydraulic power units were turned on. But launch controllers
quickly determined that all three units were working fine.
(US-SPACE STATION)
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said Thursday
that an attack on a soldier near the West Bank city of Ramallah was
a direct result of incitement by the Palestinian Authority against
Israel. ``I cannot allow myself to see Israeli citizens being
lynched, or about to be lynched by a crazed mob that received
incitement from Palestinian officials,'' Netanyahu said in
explaining his decision to suspend the Israeli troop withdrawal.
Netanyahu said he would only resume implementation of the agreement
once Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat publicly dropped plans to
announce a state in May and accepted Israel's criteria for the
release of Palestinian prisoners. U.S. State Department spokesman
James Rubin sided with the Palestinians, saying the Wye River peace
agreement ``should be implemented as signed.''
(ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS)
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia announced an election
timetable for next year Thursday, but it failed to appease 1,000
student protesters who marched down Jakarta's main road to demand a
trial of former President Suharto. Rows of riot police and several
light tanks blocked the students from reaching the palace of
President B.J. Habibie, who has pledged democratic reforms but is
deeply unpopular among students, who say he is a stooge of his
predecessor. The government dropped plans to set up an independent
panel to investigate Suharto, who students want tried on charges of
corruption and human rights abuses.
	   Parliamentary elections will be held on June 7, and the top
legislative body that is empowered to elect a new president will
convene Aug. 29, House Speaker Harmoko said. (INDONESIA-ELECTION)
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Neighbors watched helplessly as a
pre-dawn fire raged Thursday through an aging orphanage in a Manila
squatter area, killing at least 28 people, mostly children. Young
children shouted for help from the second-floor windows, which were
covered with metal grills to protect against intruders. Neighbors
were unable to open the padlocked main gate. The dozens of children
at the Catholic-run Bahay Kalinga orphanage had been looking
forward to a Christmas party the next day. Instead, at least 23
children died and Christmas decorations were scattered, along with
toys and children's clothes, among the buildings' debris. ``I'm
afraid my playmates were burned,'' said Brian De Mesa, 5, who
survived along with his twin brother. ``I saw their burned bodies.
I don't want to go back.'' (PHILIPPINES-ORPHANAGE FIRE)
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Late-night negotiations led by
Prime Minister Tony Blair have narrowed the gap between Protestant
and Catholic leaders over how to make Northern Ireland's peace
accord work, both sides said Thursday. Blair made no comment as he
left Stormont Parliamentary Building in east Belfast at about 1
a.m. after overseeing seven hours of discussions. But senior
negotiators from the major British Protestant party, the Ulster
Unionists, and the major Irish Catholic party, the Social
Democratic and Labor Party or SDLP, confirmed that a deal was close
thanks to Blair's intervention. They resumed their haggling early
Thursday but weren't sure whether a formal announcement was still
hours or days away. Both sides said the Ulster Unionists agreed to
create 10 departments in the new multi-party administration for
Northern Ireland envisaged in April's peace accord. (NORTHERN
IRELAND)
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Any trial of surviving Khmer Rouge
leaders implicated in genocide and other crimes against humanity
should take place on Cambodian soil, Prime Minister Hun Sen said in
an interview published Thursday. Hun Sen said in the interview that
he had told a visiting team of U.N.-appointed legal experts last
month that an international tribunal organized by the United
Nations would be ``impossible.'' ``It would be easier if the
tribunal is set up by Cambodians in accordance with Cambodian law
with international assistance,'' Hun Sen said in the interview,
conducted Monday by the Hong Kong-based news magazine Asiaweek. The
U.N. team spent a week in Cambodia to assess existing evidence for
a possible trial of top Khmer Rouge leaders held responsible for
the deaths of as many as 2 million people during the Maoist
guerrillas' 1975-79 rule of Cambodia. (CAMBODIA-GENOCIDE)
</TEXT>
