<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0749 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1200 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Most Asian markets fell Thursday on an
overnight drop on Wall Street that was prompted by a deteriorating
corporate earnings outlook in the United States. In Tokyo, shares
fell sharply following U.S. stocks, which also pulled the U.S.
dollar down against the yen. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock
Average shed 289.54 points, or 1.93 percent, to close at 14,697.08.
In mid-afternoon trading, the dollar bought 119.46 yen, down 2.42
yen in Tokyo late Wednesday and also below its late New York level
of 119.93 yen overnight. (ASIAN MARKETS)
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The Japanese economy shrank for the fourth straight
quarter, continuing to wallow in the nation's deepest recession in
decades, the government said Thursday. Japan's gross domestic
product _ the measure of all goods and services produced in the
country _ declined by 0.7 percent in the three months from July
through September, compared to the previous quarter, the Economic
Planning Agency said. The economy contracted at an annual rate of
2.6 percent, the agency said. Japan has been battered by Asia's
financial meltdown, which has slashed exports, long the mainstay of
its economic growth. Economic Planning Agency head Taichi Sakaiya
expressed hopes that the economy may be hitting bottom and nearing
``a dawn.'' But he reiterated that the economy's performance during
this fiscal year, which ends next March, may turn out to be worse
than the government prediction of a 1.8 percent contraction.
(JAPAN-ECONOMY)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government needs to come up with a more
detailed economic recovery plan, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
said Thursday, just a day after the International Monetary Fund
chief left without promising Moscow any new loans. Primakov's
government has produced an anti-crisis program, but the measures
have not reversed the country's economic slide, nor have they found
favor with the IMF or other international lenders who have frozen
loans to Russia. Primakov acknowledged the need to spell out the
government's intentions more clearly and called on the Cabinet to
approve a more detailed document. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong workers were dealt another blow
Thursday when British banking giant HSBC Holdings announced it will
freeze salaries for more than 13,000 employees in the territory at
its flagship unit, Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corp. Union
officials said they expect more companies to follow HSBC's lead in
freezing or cutting salaries ahead of Chinese New Year in February,
the time when most companies review and restructure operations.
Unemployment is already at 5.3 percent, the highest level since
1981 when officials started collecting such data, and is expected
to climb even further. Gareth Hewett, an HSBC spokesman, said the
decision was made recently to ``reflect economic conditions'' in
the territory. He declined to say if the bank expects the Hong Kong
economy to deteriorate further. (HONG KONG-PAY FREEZE).
	   MADRID, Spain (AP)_ Spanish workers were planning mass
demonstrations in 51 cities Thursday to demand a 35-hour week and
protest both low unemployment benefit levels and a government tax
reform. The country's two main labor federations _ the General
Workers Union and the Workers' Commissions _ put aside recent
differences to call on their members to participate in marches
around the country from 7 p.m. onwards. In a joint statement the
federations demanded a reduction of the working week to 35 hours
``as an efficient way of creating more and better jobs.''
(SPAIN-LABOR PROTESTS)
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Two of Japan's largest computer electronics makers,
Fujitsu Ltd. and Toshiba Corp., announced Thursday they will join
hands to develop advanced semiconductors. The two companies plan to
spend more than 30 billion yen (dlrs 252 million) on the joint
project, which will involve a team of about 100 researchers, they
said in a statement. The move comes amid a prolonged slump in
prices for computer memory chips, which has forced many chipmakers
to reassess plans to single-handedly invest huge sums in
development and production of the latest semiconductors.
(JAPAN-SEMICONDUCTORS)
</TEXT>
