r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-ReformParty     12-03 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Reform Party </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Anwar supporters may form political party
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Supporters of jailed former Deputy
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim may form a political party to further
their crusade for democratic reforms, a newspaper reported
Thursday.
	   Leaders of the political reform movement that Anwar launched
soon after he was fired on Sept. 2 are scheduled to meet with a
government official who registers new parties, the Sun newspaper
said, quoting a spokesman for the group.
	   Spokesman Abdul Malek Hussein was quoted as saying that he would
meet Anwar's wife Azizah Ismail to discuss the formation of the
party. Anwar has said she would lead the movement in his absence.
	   On Tuesday, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad dared Anwar's
supporters to form a party to challenge him in the general election
in 2000.
	   ``(If) they want to set up a political party, it's OK, if they
dare,'' Mahathir said.
	   The Malaysian leader said authorities would approve the
formation of a new political party if it eschewed street protests
and promised not to hold demonstrations.
	   ``But if they say they want to form a political party (because
they want) to shoot and kill people and hold demonstrations every
day, we will not give the approval,'' he said.
	   Pro-reform activists have gathered repeatedly in the capital
city of Kuala Lumpur in recent weeks to hold mostly peaceful
anti-government demonstrations.
	   They have shouted slogans demanding an end to Mahathir's 17-year
rule and burned portraits of the prime minister.
	   Mahathir fired Anwar alleging that he was too immoral to rule.
Anwar is facing trial on 10 counts of abuse of office and illegal
sex.
	   He has denied all the charges against him, saying they were
politically motivated.
</TEXT>
