w1671 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-Centennia     12-03 0243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Centennial Bills </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Estrada launches 2,000-peso notes to commemorate Philippine
</HEADLINE>
centennial

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ President Joseph Estrada launched
Thursday a 2,000-peso (dlrs 51) note to commemorate the centennial
of the Philippines' declaration of independence from Spain.
	   Philippine Central Bank Gov. Gabriel Singson presented one of
the notes to Estrada in a ceremony at the president's home.
	   Singson said 300,000 notes were printed and will be sold for
3,000 pesos (dlrs 77) each. The notes, which will be sold to the
public beginning Friday, are legal tender but are aimed primarily
at collectors.
	   They measure about five inches by eight inches (12.7 centimeters
by 20.3 centimeters), about three times the size of usual
Philippine bank notes.
	   The front features Estrada taking his oath as the country's 13th
president at the Barasoain church in Bulacan province. The church
is where the first Philippine constitution was signed and where the
first Philippine president, Gen. Emilio Aguinaldo, was proclaimed.
	   The back carries an image of former President Fidel Ramos waving
a Philippine flag during a re-enactment of the declaration of
Philippine independence in Cavite province earlier this year. The
image is a reproduction of an Associated Press photograph of the
event.
	   Gabriel said the government expects to raise 290 million pesos
(dlrs 7.4 million) from sale of the notes.
</TEXT>
