w1676 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Netherlands-Schip     12-03 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Netherlands-Schiphol on Sea,0673 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gripped by growing pains, Dutch airport looks to the sea
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MIKE CORDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ Determined to keep growing,
Amsterdam's landlocked airport wants to expand into choppy waters
by building new runways on a manmade island in the North Sea.
	   Wary pilots warn of offshore fog and tricky crosswinds.
Environmentalists fear for the future of marine life. But the
airport chief and the national airline see ``Schiphol-on-Sea'' as
the only way the airport, already one of Europe's busiest hubs, can
keep pace with soaring demand.
	   ``This issue is so important that it doesn't lend itself to
compromises,'' said Schiphol's director, Gerlach Cerfontaine.
	   An island airport would provide a uniquely Dutch answer to a
typically Dutch problem: Reclaiming land is a traditional way to
alleviate overcrowding in the Netherlands, Europe's most densely
populated nation.
	   It also would end the engine noise afflicting 15,000 households
living near the current airport on the outskirts of Amsterdam,
although residents would have to endure another 12 years of
low-flying aircraft before it would be ready.
	   The Dutch government, which owns 76 percent of the airport, is
expected to outline its view of Schiphol's future by the end of the
year.
	   Although no detailed plans have been released, Schiphol and KLM
Royal Dutch Airlines want the island in operation by 2010.
Passengers would check in at the current terminal before being
whisked to the island on high-speed trains through an undersea
tunnel.
	   The Dutch aviation industry is pressing the government to
subsidize part of the dlrs 18.6-21.3 billion it says the island
would cost. Such expansion, it says, is the only way Schiphol can
remain Europe's No. 4 airport, behind London Heathrow, Paris'
Charles De Gaulle and Frankfurt.
	   The payback, KLM and Schiphol argue, would be thousands of new
jobs and economic growth. Failure to upgrade the facility, they
caution, could cost 30,000 jobs and millions in lost business.
	   Already, U.S.-based Northwest Airlines has threatened to break
its lucrative partnership with KLM if Schiphol's wings are clipped.
	   Its point isn't lost on the government, which recently agreed to
ease noise pollution limits on Schiphol. That will allow the
airport, which expects 10 percent growth this year alone, to more
than double the number of passengers it now handles to 80 million a
year _ the equivalent of 600,000 takeoffs and landings.
	   With a fifth runway due to come into use in 2003, Schiphol could
handle all the expected traffic on its present site. But it says
aviation growth could require it to handle 900,000 takeoffs and
landings later in the next century, making the island necessary.
	   Before one of the Netherlands' greatest feats of civil
engineering can begin, Schiphol and KLM must also overcome the
powerful Dutch environmental lobby.
	   ``An island would lead to unlimited growth of the airline
sector, with all the air and noise pollution it carries, plus
damage to the marine environment,'' said Kees Kodde, aviation
policy adviser for the activist group, Environment Defense.
	   It says Schiphol can stay where it is and accommodate
international growth simply by scrapping domestic flights.
	   Airline pilots, meanwhile, say the maritime weather would create
tricky conditions for island takeoffs and landings.
	   ``Mist and low-hanging clouds _ extremely undesirable for
landing aircraft _ are particularly difficult to predict on the
North Sea,'' the Association of Dutch Pilots warned recently.
``Wind is also much more powerful over the sea than on land.''
	   Engineers say making an island isn't as difficult as it sounds
because of the shallow continental shelf that extends seven miles
from the Dutch coast.
	   Using floating dredgers, sand would be sucked up from one area
of the seabed and dumped elsewhere. Once the land mass was above
sea level, it would be surrounded by protective dikes.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
