w1678 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Britain-Lords     12-03 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Lords </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tory leader faces rebellion in House of Lords
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The deputy leader of Conservatives in the House of
Lords resigned Thursday in a rebellion against Tory leader William
Hague, in a dispute centering on the government's plan to abolish
hereditary peers.
	   Lord Fraser of Carmyllie said he was ``disgusted and appalled''
at Hague's decision Wednesday to dismiss Lord Cranborne as Tory
leader in the Lords.
	   Hague is determined to fight against Prime Minister Tony Blair's
plan to eliminate hereditary voting rights in the Lords, and was
apparently caught by surprise when Cranborne accepted an agreement
with the government to phase out the nobles in two stages. That
agreement was strongly backed by Conservatives in the House of
Lords including Lord Strathclyde, Cranborne's successor.
	   Given the government's large majority in the House of Commons,
Hague conceded he was bound to lose the fight. ``But that does not
mean that the Conservative Party has to withdraw its objections,''
Hague said in a radio interview Thursday.
	   ``You shouldn't fiddle about with the House of Lords or the rest
of the British constitution without knowing what you're going to
put in its place.''
	   The government had made the abolition of hereditary peers one of
its main legislative goals in the current session of Parliament,
and it was anxious to avoid a drawn-out fight with the
Conservative-dominated House of Lords to get the bill through. The
split between Hague and the Conservative peers should make the
government's task easier.
	   Blair intends to appoint a commission to recommend the future
method of selecting members. One of Blair's main complaints about
the House of Lords now is that nearly all of the 759 hereditary
peers are Conservatives, giving the party a permanent majority.
	   Reform of the Lords was one of the Labor Party's pledges before
the 1997 election. By convention, the House of Lords is obliged to
consent eventually to any legislation based on the governing
party's election manifesto.
	   	   Lord Cranborne is the heir of one of Britain's most
distinguished noble lines, the Cecil family, which has played a
prominent political role for 400 years.
	   He admitted that he had been operating ``quite outrageously''
behind Hague's back and deserved to be sacked.
	   Hague said Cranborne had been prepared to let the government
have its way without a fight.
	   ``When I asked Robert Cranborne whether a deal on this matter
would mean we had to support the legislation through the House of
Commons and the Lords, he said yes. It was a deal which, if
accepted, would mean that the Conservative party would support the
government's changes to the House of Lords lock, stock and
barrel,'' Hague said.
	   (rb)
</TEXT>
