<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-ADB </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADB approves loan for infrastructure projects in six Indian cities
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The Asian Development Bank approved
Thursday a dlrs 250 million loan to help finance several
infrastructure projects in India's Rajasthan province.
	   The Manila-based bank said up to 7 million people would benefit
from the projects.
	   The projects, covered by the Rajasthan Urban Infrastructure
Development Project, include improvements to water and sanitation
facilities, slum areas and traffic management.
	   In particular, the project will benefit the cities of Ajmer,
Bikaner, Jaipur, Kota and Udaipur.
	   Rapid population growth in cities, spurred by the arrival of
people from the countryside searching for a better life, has put a
heavy strain on urban services, the bank said.
	   It said many households in the cities receive water for only one
and half hours daily. Sewage collection is available only in
limited areas, and only half of all urban households have toilets,
it said.
	   The total cost of the projects is dlrs 362 million. The
remainder of the financing will come from the national government
of India and the local government of Rajasthan.
	   The interest rate on the ADB loan will be determined by the
Manila-based bank's variable lending rate system for U.S. dollar
loans.
	   The loan is payable in 25 years, with a five-year grace period.
</TEXT>
