<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Saddam's Brother </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Al-Tikriti begins three-day memorial rite for wife
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Barzan al-Tikriti, a half-brother of Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein, on Thursday began a three-day memorial
rite for his late wife.
	   Black mourning banners were put up on many buildings and at road
intersections from Baghdad to al-Tikriti's home village to the
north, where he received relatives and friends expressing
condolences for the death of his wife, Ahlam.
	   Journalists were barred from covering the rite.
	   Al-Tikriti, who served as Iraq's ambassador to the United
Nations in Geneva, Switzerland, for a decade, had been recalled to
Iraq last summer along with about two dozen other diplomats.
	   But he delayed his departure because his wife was being treated
for breast cancer. She died in Switzerland last month.
	   Ahlam, 44, was the half-sister of Saddam's first wife, Sajida,
who is the mother of Odai and Qusai, Saddam's two powerful sons.
	   Al-Tikriti returned to Baghdad on Dec. 1 after denying rumors
that he had delayed his return because he was seeking to defect
amid disputes with Saddam.
	   He said he did not want a new government post so that he could
spend more time with his family. The couple had six children, aged
11 to 26.
