<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Jordan-Norway-Accident </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Norwegian reporter says he's ``pained'' for colleague's death
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo available
 &UR; By JAMAL HALABY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ The two Norwegian TV journalists flipped
the coin to see who would get to sit in the back seat of the car
and recline during the 12-hour drive across the desert to Iraq.
	   Cameraman Knut Andre Denielsen won the round which turned out to
be fatal.
	   ``I watched Danielsen and the driver fly out of the car as it
overturned in the middle of the highway in Iraq,'' Anders Saether
who survived the Wednesday accident, told The Associated Press
Thursday. Their four-wheel drive taxi ran off the road and
overturned five times.
	   The Jordanian driver, Khaled Shawkat, 30, was also hurt in the
6:30 a.m. (0430 GMT) crash which occurred 350 kilometers (210
miles) east of the Iraqi capital Baghdad.
	   The two Norwegians were sent to Iraq by Norway's TV2 to produce
a feature film on the plight of Iraqis under U.N. sanctions,
imposed following Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
	   The desert highway is one of the few ways into Iraq because of
the sanctions that also ban air travel to that country.
	   Saether, a correspondent, arrived in Jordan on Wednesday with a
British Television crew that found him on the side of the highway.
He was admitted to hospital in Amman with whiplash, bruises and a
fractured ankle.
	   Saether, 30, speaking from his hospital bed Thursday, said he
was ``pained'' for the death of ``my very dear friend.''
	   ``I am going to miss him,'' he added.
	   He kept saying he was ``lucky to have buckled up.''
	   ``Had I not done so, like the driver and Danielsen, I would have
maybe been dead,'' he said. He said he did not know what caused the
crash.
	   He said Iraqi doctors were performing autopsy on Danielsen,
whose body is expected to be sent home for burial on the weekend.
	   Danielsen, 33, was single and lived in Bergen, which is 500
kilometers (300 miles) west of Oslo. He had a degree as a TV
director and was an experienced traveler.
 &UR; jjh-snm-sf
</TEXT>
