<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Registration </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Africa struggles to compile first all-race voters list
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By ANDREW SELSKY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ South Africans trekked in the
rain to voter registration stations Thursday but washed-out roads
and other problems hampered the nation's attempt to create its
first all-race voters list.
	   The massive registration effort is seen as a test of the
Independent Electoral Commission's ability to hold free and fair
elections next year _ only the second since the end of white rule.
	   Problems also plagued the registration for 12.7 million
potential voters in South Africa's five northern provinces last
weekend, with voters including President Nelson Mandela having been
directed to the wrong sites. Only about 28 percent of potential
voters in the north registered.
	   But the process appeared smoother Thursday as it began in the
southern half of the country. Even Marthinus van Schalkwyk, the
leader of the National Party which ruled during apartheid and
denied non-whites the vote, said as he registered in Cape Town:
``It seems as if the Independent Electoral Commission has done its
homework in this province.''
	   IEC spokesman Victor Dlamini said over 90 percent of
registration stations were open. Election officials were
determining why the remaining 800 stations had not opened.
	   State TV reported that some remained closed because civil
servants ordered to staff them didn't show up after learning they
would not be paid for the work, state TV reported. At some,
scanners used to register voters by their bar-coded ID cards were
not working properly.
	   Thousands of soldiers called up last week to assist in the
registration manned many sites. The military has also agreed to fly
staff and materials by helicopter into areas isolated by flooding,
the IEC said.
	   The 12 million potential voters in the four southern provinces
were being given three days to register.
	   In the first all-race elections in 1994, which marked the end of
apartheid and brought President Nelson Mandela's African National
Congress to power, people simply had to show up at any polling
station and produce any of several versions of an official ID card.
	   In the 1999 election, only South Africans on the voter list will
be able to vote, using only the bar-coded ID card.
	   The National Party says it will ask a court to allow any
official ID card to be used.
	   The greatest proportion of the millions of South Africans
without the bar-coded IDs are white. With the fall of apartheid,
blacks rushed to replace their restrictive apartheid-era IDs with
the new ones.
	   However, van Schalkwyk used his bar-coded ID to register at a
school in Cape Town, and urged all voters to acquire the cards,
saying: ``We do not know how the court will rule,'' the South
African Press Association reported.
	   A few days will also be set aside for registration early next
year for the whole country.
	   No election date has been set. Media reports say it will likely
be in May.
	   (aos-pr) 	   
</TEXT>
