<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Nippon Series,0273 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Miyamoto takes four-stroke first round lead
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: REPEATING to CORRECT category code. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   INAGI, Japan (AP) _ Katsumasa Miyamoto eagled the par-5 sixth
hole as part of 6-under-par 64 and took a four-stroke first-round
lead in the 100 million yen (dlrs 833,000) Golf Nippon Series JT
Cup, a tournament for the year's top golfers in Japan.
	   The 26-year-old Miyamoto, seeking his second career victory this
year, sank a 17-meter (56-foot) putt on the 541-yard sixth hole.
	   Miyamoto also had six birdies and two bogeys on the 6,960-yard
(6,272-meter) Tokyo Yomiuri Country Club course in the outskirts of
Tokyo.
	   Four strokes behind Miyamoto were two Japanese _ Masashi
``Jumbo'' Ozaki and Nobuhito Sato.
	   Jumbo Ozaki is the eldest of three Ozaki brothers and leads the
Japan PGA money list with two tournaments left this season.
	   Ozaki has earned 166.63 million yen (dlrs 1.4 million) with
three victories so far this season. Brandt Jobe of the United
States stood second with 95.17 million yen (dlrs 793,000).
	   Frankie Minoza of the Philippines shot a 69 was tied with
Toshimitsu Izawa of Japan.
	   Teeing off in the cold cloudy weather were an elite field of 26
made up of this year's tournament winners, the defending champion
and the top 20 on the Japan PGA money earning list.
	   The temperature on the course was a chilly 4 degrees Celsius (39
Fahrenheit).
	   Defending champion Shigeki Maruyama shot a 74 and was tied with
fellow Japanese Keiichiro Fukabnori and Todd Hamilton of the United
States.
	   The winner will collect 30 million yen (dlrs 250,000).
</TEXT>
