<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Wimbledon-Betting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FA demands explanation on Kinnear's `betting' comments
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Wimbledon manager Joe Kinnear could get his club
in trouble for his comments on betting.
	   The Football Association on Thursday demanded an urgent
explanation for Kinnear's comments following Wimbledon's 2-1
victory over Chelsea in the League Cup quarterfinals.
	   ``We were 66-1 (to win the cup) at the start of the season and I
think a few of the lads had a few quid on,'' he said.
	   Wimbledon players could face misconduct charges, fines and even
suspensions if the FA finds they broke rules on betting.
	   ``We are writing to Wimbledon for a full explanation,'' an FA
spokesman said. ``The rules state that it shall be deemed to be
misconduct to bet on any football match, other than those
registered for the football pools.''
	   The FA drew up new anti-betting rules last year in the wake of
the match-fixing trial of Bruce Grobbelaar, John Fashanu and Hans
Segers. The players were cleared in court but sanctioned by the FA
after admitting they forecast the results of games for an Asian
gambling syndicate.
	   The FA issued a blanket ban on all types of betting by players,
managers and directors.
	   (sw)	   
</TEXT>
