<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Saddam's Brother,0220 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Al-Tikriti begins three-day memorial rite for wife
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Saddam Hussein's half-brother began a
three-day memorial rite Thursday for his wife, who died last month
in Switzerland where Barzan al-Tikriti was Baghdad's ambassador to
the United Nations.
	   Black mourning banners were put up on many buildings and at road
intersections from Baghdad to al-Tikriti's home village to the
north, where he received relatives and friends expressing
condolences for the death of his wife, Ahlam.
	   Al-Tikriti returned to Baghdad on Dec. 1 after denying rumors
that he had delayed his return because he was seeking to defect
amid disputes with the Iraqi president.
	   He had been recalled to Iraq last summer along with about two
dozen other diplomats. But he delayed his departure because his
wife was being treated for breast cancer.
	   Ahlam, 44, was the half-sister of Saddam's first wife, Sajida,
who is the mother of Odai and Qusai, Saddam's two powerful sons.
	   Al-Tikriti, who served as Iraq's U.N. ambassador in Geneva for a
decade, has said he didn't want a new government post so he could
spend more time with his family. The couple had six children, aged
11 to 26.
	   Journalists were barred from covering the memorial rite.
</TEXT>
