<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Ukraine-Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Ukrainian premier arrested in Switzerland
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) _ Former Ukrainian premier Pavlo
Lazarenko has been arrested in Switzerland, a spokesman for the
Basel state prosecutor's office said Thursday.
	   Lazarenko was arrested by customs officials as he crossed by car
from France into Switzerland on Wednesday, spokesman Markus Melzl
said.
	   He was transferred to Geneva, where an investigating judge had
ordered his arrest.
	   Switzerland's Office of Police Affairs says it has received 20
separate requests from Ukraine for legal aid in the case of
Lazarenko, accused of corruption, since February 1997.
	   A spokesman for the office last month said Switzerland is
helping Ukrainian authorities in their attempts to track down money
he allegedly stashed away in Swiss banks.
	   Switzerland has handed over some bank documents to Ukraine, he
added.
	   Lazarenko was prime minister in 1996-97, when he was sacked by
President Leonid Kuchma. He now leads the centrist opposition
Hromoda party and has accused Kuchma and his allies of trying to
blacken his name by the corruption charges.
	   In October, he alleged that authorities were plotting to kill
him.
	   As well as Geneva, investigations are under way in the cantons
(states) of Fribourg and Zurich.
	   Under Switzerland's decentralized legal system, individual
cantons are responsible for investigating charges of money
laundering.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
