<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Looting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Villagers loot town in eastern Indonesian province
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ An unspecified number of villagers
have looted a shopping complex in town in an eastern Indonesian
province that was recently rocked by a wave of religious-related
violence, a news report said Thursday.
	   The looting occurred Wednesday night in the Lobalaen district of
the island of Rote in the province of East Nusa Tenggara, said the
daily Suara Pembaruan.
	   Shopkeepers as well as security forces in the remote district
were outnumbered and could do nothing to stop the looters from
taking whatever they wanted, the report said.
	   Rote is an island in southeastern Indonesia, just south of the
East Nusa Tenggara provincial capital of Kupang, which is located
1,875 kilometers (1,172 miles) southeast of Jakarta.
	   Earlier this week, Christian mobs in Kupang burned and ransacked
Muslim mosques and houses in retaliation for the burning of
churches in Jakarta last month.
	   The civil disturbances come as Indonesia faces its worst
economic crisis in decades. The Southeast Asian country is beset by
mass unemployment, food shortages and huge foreign debt loads. 	   
</TEXT>
