<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Two armed men who took two bank
employees hostage during a robbery in Lower Saxony state Thursday
freed both in a Frankfurt suburb, police said.
	   The men, armed with automatic pistols, fled toward Frankfurt in
a car belonging to one of the bank employees after bursting into
the bank in the Lower Saxony town of Bad Pyrmont shortly after it
opened.
	   Police said the men abandoned the car after freeing the
hostages, and fled on foot. Neither hostage was injured.
	   The armed men had threatened to shoot the hostages if they saw
any police vehicles along the road, and demanded that a police
helicopter trailing them be pulled back, police said.
	   It was not immediately clear how much, if any, money they took.
	   Police were talking with the men by mobile telephone for much of
the journey, but lost contact around midday.
