<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Christo Trees,0295 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Christo's wrapped trees to be uncovered early
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIEHEN, Switzerland (AP) _ Husband-and-wife artists Christo and
Jeanne-Claude have decided to unwrap about 178 trees in a Swiss
museum park a few weeks early _ for artistic reasons.
	   The exhibit, which transformed this quiet suburb of Basel when
it opened last month, was expected to remain on show until late
January.
	   But the artists decided for aesthetic reasons to start
unwrapping the trees Dec. 14, in an operation open to the public.
	   ``With all our previous temporary works of art, the 14-day
duration of the project's exhibition had been an aesthetic
choice,'' they said in a statement.
	   Although less grandiose than previous projects such as the 1995
wrapping of Berlin's Reichstag, the trees project involves 55,000
square meters (461,000 square feet) of woven polyester fabric and
23 kilometers (14 miles) of rope.
	   ``All materials will be recycled'' when the exhibit is
dismantled, Christo and Jeanne-Claude said.
	   The display coincides with a ``Magic of Trees'' exhibition
inside the Beyeler museum featuring works of art from Picasso,
Chagall, Cezanne and Giacometti, to name but a few.
	   The museum said it ``respects the artists' decision because it
was clear from the beginning that they alone would determine how
long the `Wrapped Trees' installation would last.''
	   ``We are deeply grateful to Christo and Jeanne-Claude for giving
us this unique experience and eagerly look forward to their next
project,'' it added.
	   With up to 20,000 people expected on a typical weekend, local
authorities put in place stringent traffic regulations to ensure
that the village of Riehen was not overwhelmed.
</TEXT>
