<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-US-Bananas </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU trade negotiator asks Washington to reconsider fast-track WTO
</HEADLINE>
panel &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The chief European Union trade
negotiator appealed to the U.S authorities on Thursday to
reconsider an EU proposal for a speedy settlement of the
transatlantic banana dispute at the World Trade Organization.
	   Washington alleges the 15-nation EU banana regime,which allows
preferential import terms to certain African and Pacific nations,
is unfair to South American distributors, most of which are owned
by US companies.
	   EU Trade Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan told journalists that the
EU had offered a speedier process of 170 days to resolve the
dispute through an accelerated WTO panel. Under the normal
procedure, it takes 449 days, he said.
	   Brittan said Washington's insistance that the banana row should
be resolved before March 3 was ``ridiculous.'' March 3 is the
deadline under US trade law for the enforcement of a dlrs 1.5
billion fine the United States has slapped on the EU.
	   However, Brittan said the EU has assured Washington it will not
press for this time limit to be applied if the United States agrees
to the fast-track plan.
	   The WTO ruled earlier this year that the EU's banana import
system violates its rules. The EU operates a special banana trade
regime with certain developing countries - grouped in the so-called
African-Caribbean-Pacific bloc.
	   The WTO ruling was in response to a complaint by the United
States, Honduras, Ecuador, Guatemala and Mexico that the EU system
unfairly restricted their banana exports.
</TEXT>
