<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-US-China </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine official cautions U.S. on its ties with China
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The Philippine foreign secretary on
Thursday called some of China's policies ``disturbing'' and
cautioned the United States against forging deep ties with Beijing
at the expense of other nations.
	   Foreign Affairs Secretary Domingo Siazon cited China's
``exuberant'' efforts to modernize its military at a time when
external threats have diminished and other countries in the region
are undertaking only modest defense upgrades because of the Asian
financial crisis.
	   ``Some aspects of Beijing's policies are, bluntly speaking,
disturbing for many observers in the region,'' Siazon told a forum
on Philippine-American relations.
	   He also cited as problematic China's claim to the entire South
China Sea, which has brought it into territorial conflicts with
other Asian countries, and its revived defense cooperation with
Russia.
	   Manila recently protested China's construction of additional
structures on the disputed Mischief Reef in the Spratly island
chain.
	   Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado has called the Chinese action
a ``creeping invasion.''
	   China, Vietnam and Taiwan claim all of the islands. The
Philippines and Malaysia claim some of them and Brunei claims one
reef.
	   The Spratlys straddle vital sea lanes and are believed to be
rich in minerals.
	   Foreign Affairs Secretary Siazon said Beijing's intransigence on
the Spratly issue has harmed its relations with neighboring states
and damaged its ability to assume a greater leadership role in the
region.
	   He also warned Washington against becoming too cozy with China.
	   ``The Philippines supports the U.S. policy of engaging China as
better than any attempt at confrontation or containment,'' he said.
``The issue here is that Washington may be tempted to invest too
much in its strategic partnership with Beijing to the detriment of
the interests of its regional allies.''
	   He said the ``greatest value'' of a Chinese-American strategic
partnership is in being able to ``leverage China into accepting
more encompassing regional discussions on such problems as the
South China Sea.''	   
</TEXT>
