 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Uganda, Zimbabwe, Guinea-Bissau, Kenya &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ----
	   ENTEBBE, Uganda (AP) _ Rebels have killed the fathers of 55
percent of children living in northern Uganda's Kitgum district, an
aid group said.
	   The International Service Volunteers Association also found that
15 percent of the children's mothers had been killed by the Lord's
Resistance Army.
	   Keith Wright, program coordinator for the U.N. Children's Fund,
said at a seminar Wednesday that at least two children a day had
been kidnapped from Kitgum by the rebels for the past two years.
	   ``When abducted, children are subjected to extreme brutality to
force them to become fighters, porters or sex slaves,'' Wright told
university scholars from France, England, West and East Africa and
representatives of nongovernmental organizations.
	   Wright said UNICEF was helping the volunteer association train
counselors to help families in Kitgum. The counselors also assist
families when an abducted child returns.
	   He said these interventions are made more difficult and
dangerous because of the continuing armed conflict, waged by the
LRA for the past 12 years to oust President Yoweri Museveni.
	   -----
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Kenya's fertility rate has fallen from 5.4
children per woman in 1993 to 4.7 per woman this year, an official
said.
	   The recent survey showed nearly 40 percent of Kenyan women were
using some form of contraception to space children and safeguard
their reproductive health, Health Minister Jackson Kalweo said at a
conference Wednesday.
	   Despite the decline in fertility rates, health workers still
need to reach more men and convince them of the crucial role they
ought to play in promoting safer sexual and reproduction health
practices, he said.
	   ------
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Representatives of Guinea-Bissau's
ruling party and military rebels reportedly have agreed to appoint
Francisco Fadul, a former aide to President Joao Bernardo Vieira
who backed the June 7 army revolt against him, as interim prime
minister.
	   Fadul is to head the West African nation's planned government of
national unity which will sit until legislative and presidential
elections are held in March, the Portuguese news agency Lusa
reported Thursday.
	   The appointment was a political victory for the rebels who are
in negotiations with Vieira's supporters on appointments to the new
17-member cabinet.
	   Fadul, who split with Vieira in 1993, is currently political
adviser to Brig. Ansumane Mane who led the five-month army revolt
in the former Portuguese colony.
	   The two sides were due to continue their talks Thursday, Lusa
said.
	   A Nigerian-led regional force is due to arrive in the former
Portuguese colony later this month to oversee implementation of the
Nov. 2 peace pact.
	   -----
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ A man drowned in a sewer when he was
dragged beneath downtown Harare for more than a kilometer (mile)
after heavy rains, police said.
	   In a statement, police said the man parked his car near a
downtown hotel to collect his child from a nearby church nursery
school on Tuesday.
	   He stepped into what he believed was a puddle of water, slipping
into an open sewer drain that workers failed to mark with warning
signs.
	   Police divers recovered his body in a drain near the main train
station after it had been sucked beneath Harare's main shopping
district.
	   The rare drowning in the city center highlighted growing
accusations of negligence by city authorities that has led to the
decline of public utilities and street maintenance in the city of
1.5 million people.
	   Power and water supplies have been frequently cut off in recent
weeks amid allegations of mismanagement and corruption by city
officials, including Mayor Solomon Tawengwa.
	   The drowning victim was not identified.
	   (var-pr)
