<SLUG> BC-Australia-Philippines-Ramos </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former president Fidel Ramos awarded law doctorate
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Former Philippines president Fidel
Ramos was received an law honorary degree by the University of
Sydney to the chants of angry demonstrators.
	   The ceremony awarding Ramos an honorary doctorate of laws
competed with the small band of demonstrators yelling for the
honour to be withdrawn.
	   University Vice-Chancellor Professor Gavin Brown told the
assembly Ramos had made a significant contribution to the stability
and economic growth of his country and to the Asia Pacific region.
	   The former president had been a consensus-building leader who
had transformed the ``Sick Man of Asia'' into a vibrant and stable
economy, better placed than many of its neighbors to weather the
financial turbulence which had engulfed the region, Brown said.
	   During Ramos' six year term in office, Ramos had presided over a
period of economic recovery which had renewed national confidence
and won respect for his leadership throughout the region.
	   Brown said Ramos had an outstanding track record of tolerance
for cultural and ethnic differences.
	   But the Philippines Australia Union Link condemned Ramos for a
series of human rights abuses they said he was responsible for
while martial law administrator and later armed forces chief of
staff under President Ferdinand
	   Marcos.
	   As Ramos accepted his doctorate, speaking of the need for
Australia and the Philippines to intensify their ties, the
protesters vowed to continue to lobby until the university withdrew
the honour.
	   Spokesman Peter Murphy said trade unionists and Filipino
community activists were outraged by the university's actions.
	   ``If it (the university) wants to demonstrate its positive
orientation to Asia, it should confer its honours on long-term
democracy advocates, not on a
	   military figure like Fidel Ramos,'' Murphy said.
	   ``He has blood on his hands stretching back to the declaration
of Martial Law in September 1972.''
	   Ramos accepted the honour in the name of the Filipino people.
	   He said it came at a special time, 1998 marking the 100th-year
of the proclamation of Philippine independence from Spain.
	   pjs
</TEXT>
