<SLUG> BC-Sports-Asian Games-Flame Lit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Despite bad weather, Thai king lights up royal flame for Asian
</HEADLINE>
Games
 &UR; AP Photo planned

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Bad weather forced a change of plan,
but Thailand's King Bhumibol Adulyadej successfully lit the flame
Thursday for the 13th Asian Games, three days before they
officially start.
	   With rain-filled clouds covering the skies above his palace,
Bhumibol, the world's longest-reigning monarch, was forced to
abandon plans to light the flame with a magnifying glass and
instead used a lantern.
	   The king touched a candle to the lantern flame, then held it to
a larger ceremonial candle that covered in a gold-and-glass case.
It was paraded by bearers to Bangkok's Sanam Luang, or royal
fields, where it will be displayed for three days of colorful
ceremonies.
	   The flame will light the torch that will open the two-week event
Sunday. Two hundred and sixteen people led off by Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai will relay the torch to the main athletic center on
Bangkok's outskirts.
	   Somluck Kamsing, a Thai boxer who won a gold medal at the last
Asian Games in 1994 and was Thailand's first Olympic gold-medalist
ever in 1996, will carry the torch last and light the brazier that
will burn until the games close Dec. 20.
	   Somluck hopes to repeat his gold-medal performances as one of
the 6,000 athletes from 41 countries at the Olympic-style event,
billed by organizers as the last great sporting competition of the
20th Century.
</TEXT>
