<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Interest Rates </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German central bank cuts key interest rate, leaves others
</HEADLINE>
unchanged &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ In a suprise move, Germany's central
bank Thursday cut the country's key interest rate to 3 percent from
3.3 percent, reflecting concern over a weakening economy.
	   Germany's securities repurchase rate, known as the repo rate,
had been unchanged at 3.3 percent since October 1997.
	   President of the Deutsche Bundesbank Hans Tietmeyer said the
bank cut the rate because of the gloomy outlook for European
economies. The German government says growth, hit by the Asian and
Russian economic crises, will shrink to 2 percent in 1999 from this
year's expected 2.75 percent.
	   Tietmeyer said the Bundesbank was not responding to political
pressure to cut rates. The bank has come under sustained pressure
from Germany's Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine to drop rates to
stimulate the flagging economy and create jobs.
	   The bank left the other two main interest rates unchanged. The
Lombard rate stayed at 4.5 percent and the discount rate at 2.5
percent. Both have been at historic lows since April 1996.
	   The repo rate mainly influences money market transactions.
	   The decision was taken after a meeting of the bank's
policy-making central committee.
	   The move means Europe's interest rate for the 11 countries
launching a common currency on Jan. 1 might be lower than expected.
The euro rate is expected to be at or near Germany's rate,
reflecting Germany's status as the biggest economy among
participating countries.
 &UR; dkt-dj-cb
