<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Non-Drunk Camel Driving </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Drunk-driving camel charge dismissed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COOBER PEDY, Australia (AP) _ An Alice Springs man has escaped
charges of
	   driving a team of camels while drunk.
	   Ricky Wilson Hall, 36, had been on trial in Coober Pedy
Magistrates Court
	   over an incident that police compared to something on
Australia's Funniest Home Videos.
	   Hall had pleaded innocent to two counts of driving camels under
the influence, one of assaulting police and one of resisting police
following an incident near Oodnadatta in South Australia in
September 1997. He did plead guilty to using offensive language.
	   Magistrate Alan Moss on Thursday dismissed a second drink
driving charge -- a first charge was dismissed earlier in the
hearing -- saying there was insufficient evidence to convict Hall.
	   And, while the offensive language charge was proved, Moss
dismissed it.
	   Moss found the assault and resisting police charges proven but
recorded no convictions.
	   But he placed Hall on a 100 Australian dollars (U.S. dlrs 63)
good behaviour bond for 12 months and ordered him to pay 140
Australian dollars (U.S. dlrs 83) in costs.
	   The court heard earlier that Hall had been driving a wagon
pulled by camels when then police Sgt. Garry Griffiths saw he was
drunk and told him to stop.
	   Police said Hall ignored the warning and, when warned a second
time by the police officer, untied a young camel from the wagon and
tried to ride off.
	   After a short distance, the young camel returned to its mother,
bringing Hall back to the waiting policeman.
	   Hall then leapt cowboy-style onto the back of one of the other
camels and
	   tried to ride off shouting, ``Yahoo!'' the court was told.
	   Griffiths likened the incident to something from Australia's
Funniest
	   Home Videos.
	   The police officer arrested Hall.
	   Moss earlier dismissed a first drunk driving charge relating to
the young camel, saying Hall was merely a hopeful passenger as he
held on to the animal's hump with his legs hanging over its back.
	   Moss also said he ``had concerns that Griffiths exaggerated
evidence and was a brusque and unreliable officer who handled the
situation poorly.''
	   pjs
</TEXT>
