w1792 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Track-Germany-     12-03 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Track-Germany-Doping </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two runners admit taking plasma substance
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Two German medal-winning runners have
admitted taking a blood-thinning substance but have denied blood
doping.
	   Damian Kallabis, the 3,000-meter steeplechase champion at the
European Championship in Budapest in August, and Stephane Franke,
the 10,000 bronze medalist, confirmed taking the so-called blood
plasma expander HES, which helps the circulation of blood.
	   The substance was not banned at the time but the German
Athletics Federation (DLV) put it on the list of banned drugs as
soon as their confession was made public Thursday.
	   The two athletes made their admission in a fax to the newspaper
Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung (FAZ) and in an interview with the
same newspaper, both of which were published Thursday.
	   ``Yes, we used the substance HES in Budapest,'' they said in the
fax.
	   Kallabis and Franke said they used the substance because the
weather was hot and humid in the Hungarian capital during the
European Championship.
	   ``But we never took EPO. We are ready to undergo blood tests any
time,'' they said in their statement.
	   EPO is a synthetic hormone that stimulates the production of
oxygen-carrying red blood cells and cannot be detected by existing
doping tests.
	   The two athletes disputed statements by the chief DLV doctor
Karlheinz Graff that HES is used only to mask the usage of EPO.
	   ``Taking HES in no way means blood doping,'' they said.
	   Doctors involved in the case confirmed giving it to the athletes
at their request.
	   Franke said he took HES already at the 1995 World Championship
in Goteborg, Sweden, getting it from team doctor Wilfried
Kindermann, who is now chief doctor of the German soccer team.
	   ``Blood plasma substitutes like HES can, among other things,
improve the circulation of blood and allow better cooling off of
the body,'' Kindermann told FAZ.
	   Kindermann said he saw nothing wrong in giving the substance to
the athletes if they asked for it and it was not on the list of
banned drugs.
	   The DLV is investigating the case, which was brought to light by
Graff last month when he said some athletes had asked for HES in
Budapest.
	   The DLV doctor did not give any names.
	   Franke and Kallabis have been suspected by the German media of
being the two athletes. The two said they had kept silent until now
at the advice of their lawyers.
	   (ns) 	   
</TEXT>
