<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Asian Games-Soccer </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan advances; Kazakstan hat-trick; Uzbekistan-Kuwait tie; Qatar
</HEADLINE>
wins

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Kenji Fukuda fired his third Asian
Games goal Thursday to secure a second-round berth for Japan's
young soccer squad in an otherwise unremarkable 1-0 victory over a
spirited India.
	   Viktor Zubarev scored a second-half hat-trick to seal
Kazakstan's 5-0 victory against an over-matched Laos in the kind of
lop-sided win that has characterized the 23-nation preliminary
round.
	   Uzbekistan tied Kuwait in a 3-3 thriller, while Qatar edged
Tajikistan, 2-1.
	   India's tough defense held Japan, playing in the southern city
of Trang, to a scoreless first half. But the Japanese quickly went
ahead in the second half when Fukuda took a headed pass from
Masahiro Koka and fired from five meters (yards).
	   Japan, which had a disappointing World Cup, brought an under-21
squad coached by Frenchman Philippe Troussier to prepare for the
2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia. Thursday's win follows a 5-0
victory over Group C weaklings Nepal.
	   Kuwait, winner of the Gulf Cup, went up against far stiffer
opposition in the northern city of Chiang Mai than in Tuesday's
11-0 humiliation of Mongolia, the weakest team in the games.
	   Uzbekistan kept the tough Kuwaiti attack at bay and drew the
keeper out of the penalty area in the 5th minute, letting Andrey
Fyodorov score a 25-meter (yard) shot into the open goal.
	   Kuwaiti star Jassem al-Huwaidi equalized in the early moments of
the second half, bringing his Asian Games total to five.
	   Uzbekistan went back ahead 20 minutes later when Alexander
Khvostunov beat two defenders and fired from 12 meters (yards) to
make it 2-1. Andrey Akopyants added insurance in the 31st minute.
	   Farj Laheeb quickly replied to keep Kuwait's hopes alive,
sliding into a shot that had just bounced off the crossbar and
squeezing it past three surprised defenders. Laheeb scored again in
the final seconds to pull out a 3-3 draw and his sixth Asian Games
goal.
	   Uzbekistan faces Mongolia on Saturday in the final Group G match
and is expected to win and advance.
	   In Group H in the northeastern city of Sisaket, Kazakstan used
greater height and weight to overcome the gritty Laotian defense,
which was was sharp in midfield but too often left the keeper
unsupported.
	   Guram Makeyev slotted in from directly before the goal in the
32nd minute. Azamat Niyazymbetov pushed the half-time advantage to
2-0. In the second half, Zubarev netted three, the last in the
final minute.
	   Kazakstan lost its Group H opener to Iran, one of the favorites
in the 13th Asian Games, but should move into the second round if
Iran beats Laos as expected Saturday.
	   In Group D in Suphan Buri, Ahmed al-Obaidly took Qatar ahead in
the first half. The scoreline increased to 2-0 early in the second.
	   Tajikistan, which routed the Maldives on Tuesday, was unable to
score until a penalty taken in injury time by Shokrat Djabarov
after Qatar's N. al-Khater was sent off after a rough tackle in the
penalty area. Qatar is favored to win Saturday's clash with the
Maldives.
</TEXT>
