<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Fugitive Banana </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mandela meets with fugitive leader convicted of sodomy in Zimbabwe
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo JOH103 &QL; 
 &UR; By PAT REBER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ South Africa and Zimbabwe were
on a potential collision course over gay issues Thursday after
President Nelson Mandela met Zimbabwean former President Canaan
Banana, a fugitive convicted in his country of sodomy.
	   Banana, president of Zimbabwe from 1980 to 1987, was convicted
last week of sodomy and homosexual assault. He had been free on
bail and fled Zimbabwe for neighboring Botswana shortly before his
conviction.
	   After Zimbabwe requested Banana's extradition from Botswana, he
crossed into South Africa. On Wednesday, he met with Mandela at his
official residence in Pretoria.
	   Banana had requested the meeting, but there was no indication he
would seek asylum or whether he intended to stay in South Africa
for long, said Mandela's spokesman, Parks Mankahlana.
	   Zimbabwe President Robert Mugabe has launched a campaign against
homosexuality, saying it was brought to Africa by the West. He has
described same-sex partners as ``lower than pigs and dogs.''
	   But in South Africa, the nation's highest court in October
struck down apartheid-era laws banning homosexual relations.
	   If a crime for which someone has been sentenced in another
country is not punishable in South Africa, then South Africa's
courts would likely reject any extradition request, said Paul
Setsetse, spokesman for Justice Minister Dullah Omar.
	   Said Mankahlana: ``This is a very sensitive matter. South Africa
and Zimbabwe have adopted totally different approaches to this
issue (of homosexual sex). What is considered unlawful in Zimbabwe
is not considered unlawful in South Africa.''
	   Officials at the Zimbabwe embassy could not be reached for
comment on whether Zimbabwe would seek Banana's extradition from
South Africa.
	   Banana, a 62-year-old Methodist minister, was convicted on Nov.
26 in Harare, Zimbabwe's capital, of 11 counts of sodomy and
homosexual assault. While he was president, he allegedly threatened
his bodyguards, a cook and a gardener with their jobs unless they
performed homosexual acts.
	   Banana was brought to trial after a police inspector who worked
as his bodyguard killed a colleague who had taunted him for his
alleged relationship with the former president.
	   Sentencing for Banana has been scheduled for Dec. 10 in Harare.
He faces a possible maximum jail term of 22 years.
	   (pr-aos)
</TEXT>
