<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinian Airport,0430 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel requests that Clinton not land at Palestinian airport
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DINA KRAFT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LOD, Israel (AP) _ Israel has asked that U.S. President Bill
Clinton not land at the newly opened Palestinian airport during an
upcoming visit, arguing it would give a boost to Palestinian claims
to independence, a senior Israeli official said Thursday.
	   The Clinton administration is considering the request, said a
U.S. official who spoke on condition of anonymity. The official
said Clinton's travel plans had not yet been finalized.
	   Clinton is to arrive in Israel on Dec. 12. Two days later he is
to fly to the Gaza Strip to usher in the second stage of the Wye
River land-for-peace agreement he helped negotiate.
	   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's senior adviser, David
Bar-Illan, said Thursday that the Israeli government asked for a
change in plans.
	   ``We have suggested this would not be appropriate,'' Bar-Illan
said. ``We have always said it (a landing) was something we felt
was tantamount to recognizing (Palestinian) sovereignty.''
	   The Palestinians consider the airport, their first gateway to
the world, a strong symbol of fledgling independence. The airport
opened, as part of the Wye agreement, after more than two years of
disputes between Israel and the Palestinians over security
arrangements.
	   Israel's government, for the time being, doesn't permit Israeli
citizens to use the airport, citing security concerns.
	   On Thursday, an Israeli charter flight from Ben Gurion
International Airport to Gaza International was canceled after the
Defense Ministry imposed restrictions on who could fly.
	   The flight was to have carried Israeli legislators, peace
activists and dozens of journalists who were to have been greeted
at the Gaza airfield by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
	   The legislators tried to persuade Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai to rescind his decision, but ultimately decided not to go
after the government offered to let the lawmakers fly, but without
the peace activists and only with 10 journalists.
	   Arafat's security chief in the Gaza Strip, Mohammed Dahlan, who
had been waiting for the Israeli visitors at Gaza International,
said he was disappointed.
	   ``The aim of this plane trip to Gaza today was to support peace,
to build strong confidence between the two peoples and to give more
support to the peace process,'' Dahlan said. ``It looks to us that
this government doesn't want this to be.''
</TEXT>
