<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Russia-Mafia Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ex-FBI agent: Russian mafia had NY, LA clubs, ties to Miami,
</HEADLINE>
Houston &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo GEV101 &QL; 
 &UR; By NAOMI KOPPEL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ An alleged boss of the Russian mafia had
operations extending to New York, Houston and Los Angeles and used
Miami as a base to plan operations, a former FBI agent testified
Thursday.
	   Retired special agent Robert Levinson said the Solntsevskaya
organization headed by Sergei Mikhailov took over a nightclub in
New York's Brighton Beach area and another in an unspecified part
of Los Angeles.
	   ``They became a center for drugs and a meeting place for
racketeers,'' Levinson, who spent four years investigating the
Russian mafia, told the Geneva correctional court.
	   Mikhailov, who is being tried in Geneva on charges of membership
in a criminal organization, also invested several hundred thousand
dollars in a Houston car dealership, added Levinson.
	   ``When the individual who was involved didn't come up with the
cars that Mr. Mikhailov had ordered, he became in fear of his life.
He thought he was going to be murdered,'' said Levinson. He gave no
more details.
	   Mikhailov, 40, denies he has anything to do with the
organization. He also is charged with breaking Swiss laws on
purchase of property by foreigners and has been in custody in
Geneva for more than two years.
	   Levinson told the court that Mikhailov and his associates headed
Solntsevskaya and had a series of ``brigades'' below them.
	   ``The organization was engaged regularly in the extortion of
businesses, the distribution of drugs including cocaine,
counterfeiting of currency and trafficking in arms,'' he said.
	   Mikhailov personally directed two ``combat'' brigades,
specialized groups in assassination, said Levinson.
	   ``They would commit murders in Russia and other countries in
Europe and then come to Miami, Florida, where they would stay by
the beach and wait for the heat to cool off,'' he said.
	   Levinson also worked on the case of Russian mafia godfather
Vyacheslav Ivankov, imprisoned for nearly 10 years in New York last
year.
	   ``In Miami one or more meetings took place between the
Solntsevskaya leaders, including Mikhailov, with Ivankov during
which time the takeover and control of several Moscow hotels was
discussed,'' said Levinson.
	   The trial of Mikhailov, which began on Nov. 30, is expected to
hear evidence from more than 90 witnesses speaking six different
languages. If convicted, he faces a maximum of seven-and-a-half
years in prison.
	   Among witnesses who, for their own safety, testified by
closed-circuit television from an adjacent room Wednesday were two
Russians who fled to the United States and have since received FBI
protection. They told the court that they had been subjected to
extortion in Russia.
 &UR; (nk-agh)
</TEXT>
