<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Galatasaray-Juventus-Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turks celebrate violence-free Galatasaray-Juventus match
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: New throughout. TRIMS &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By SELCAN HACAOGLU &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ Turks had two reasons to celebrate on
Thursday: A draw between Galatasaray and Juventus assured Turkey's
team a shared first-place in their Championship League _ and the
violence-free game proved Turks could separate sports and politics.
	   ``Friendship was the winner,'' a headline in Turkey's Yeni
Yuzyil declared.
	   ``Turkey won,'' said the Radikal daily, alluding to the peaceful
atmosphere that reigned at the Ali Sami Yen stadium on Wednesday
night.
	   Apart from slogans denouncing Kurdish guerrilla groups and some
habitual chanting of obscenities by Galatasaray supporters, the
match ended with a 1-1 draw and none of the feared disturbances.
	   Turkey and Italy are locked in a bitter dispute over Abdullah
Ocalan, a Kurdish Turk rebel leader seeking asylum in Italy, and
there were fears the political tensions might spill onto the soccer
field.
	   Turkey deployed 22,000 police officers for the game and the
Juventus team flew home immediately afterward to avoid possible
trouble. The Italians face possible disciplinary action for
arriving Wednesday, in defiance of a UEFA rule that requires teams
to arrive a day before a match.
	   The draw brings Galatasaray to share the first place in Group B
with Norway's Rosenborg at 8 points, while Juventus _ which has yet
to win a game in the tournament _ is third with 5 points.
	   Turks tuned into the match: some out of passion for the game,
others worried that the security would not be enough to stop
clashes.
	   In Italy, too, where the Juventus players had expressed deep
concern for their security, the game got a 40 percent share of the
TV audience, with an estimated 12 million viewers.
	   No Italian fans attended the match because of security concerns,
leaving the pitch in a deadly silence after Juventus scored.
	   UEFA had postponed the match by one week for fear of violence.
``I hope Europe and the world is ashamed,'' said Haluk Ulusoy, the
president of Turkey's Football Federation, referring to the
European doubts that Turks would be able to restrain their anger.
	   Thousands of Turks poured out into the streets to celebrate
Galatasaray's new position as joint group leader.
	   Police in Ankara, the Turkish capital, used water cannons to
block off a main street leading to the Italian Embassy _ a frequent
target of anti-Italy, anti-Ocalan protests.
	   About 100 people gathered in front of the cannons to shout
slogans denouncing the rebel group. Hundreds of cars formed a
convoy through the streets with passengers waving flags and
chanting ``Down with the PKK.''
	   Italy's sports and foreign trade ministers met with Turkey's
justice and sports ministers before the game. Premier-designate
Bulent Ecevit said ``an encouraging dialogue has begun with
Italy.''
	   (ht-sf) 	   
</TEXT>
