<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-British Preview </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yorke aims to knock former Villa colleagues off top spot
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT MILLWARD &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Manchester United striker Dwight Yorke returns to
Aston Villa on Saturday to try and knock his old club off the top
of the Premier League.
	   Only one point separates the two teams and Yorke, who faces
Aston Villa for the first time, has the chance of adding to his 12
Manchester United goals and putting United on top.
	   He's likely to get a less-than-friendly reception from the fans
at Villa Park, if not the players and coaching staff too.
	   After nine happy years at Villa, the Tobagan striker moved to
Old Trafford for 12.6 million pounds (dlrs 20.5 million) in August,
prompting Villa manager John Gregory to say: ``If I had a gun, I
would have shot him.''
	   Gregory says he still feels the pain.
	   ``It felt like being told by your wife or lover that she had
found somebody else,'' the Villa manager said in the buildup to
Saturday's game. ``That was how bad it felt when Dwight told me he
wanted to leave Villa. It really hurt.
	   ``On Saturday the fans should give Dwight a warm welcome for the
nine years loyal service he gave to Villa,'' Gregory said. ``But at
3 p.m. will be playing for the enemy.''
	   Although Gregory still fumes at the fact that Yorke left a club
he joined as an 18-year-old in 1989, he can say that the club has
barely missed him.
	   Villa opened up a 4-point lead at one stage at the top of the
standings and Yorke's replacement, Dion Dublin, scored seven goals
in his first three appearances after transfering from Coventry.
	   While it's Yorke vs. Dublin at Villa Park, it should be Shearer
and Ferguson at the Riverside on Sunday.
	   England captain Alan Shearer has recovered from a hamstring
problem and is expected to team up with new signing Duncan Ferguson
in a 22-million-pound (dlrs 36.75 million) Newcastle strikeforce at
Middlesbrough.
	   Ferguson scored twice on his debut in a 3-1 victory over
Wimbledon last week and Magpies fans can't wait to see the two
playing together, especially if they can put one over on neighbor
Middlesbrough, which stands four places higher in seventh.
	   West Ham, which has climbed to third, has a tough game at
sixth-place Leeds on Saturday while defending titlist Arsenal,
which has slipped to fourth, needs a win at Derby to stay in
contention. The Gunners hope to end a winless run of six games
which also saw them eliminated from the Champions Cup and domestic
League Cup.
	   Fifth place Chelsea, whose 19-game unbeaten streak ended Tuesday
when it lost to Wimbledon in the League Cup quarterfinal, goes to
Everton, which climbed to 14th last week by winning at Charlton
even without the departed Ferguson.
	   Rejuvenated under new manager George Graham, Tottenham ousted
Manchester United's weakened lineup from the League Cup on
Wednesday.
	   Now Spurs bid to improve their league position by beating
Liverpool for the second time in four weeks. When the two teams met
in the League Cup fourth round last month, Spurs won 3-1 at Anfield
and this time they meet at White Hart Lane.
	   After knocking defending champion Chelsea out of the League Cup
on Tuesday to set up a semifinal date with Tottenham, 10th place
Wimbledon has a more mundane league game at home to struggling
Coventry.
	   Last place Blackburn bids to lift its season by beating promoted
Charlton at home. Although Charlton is five places higher, it has
won only three of its 15 games.
	   Southampton, which beat Blackburn three weeks ago to climb away
from last, visits Leicester while Nottingham Forest is also in
danger of slipping to last because it doesn't play until Monday,
when it visits Sheffield Wednesday.
	   Division One leader Sunderland, which is four points clear of
its rivals, should gain three more from a home game against
Stockport, even though the visitor has managed to tie 11 of its 21
league games.
	   Second place Ipswich has a tricky home game against fifth place
Birmingham.
	   Scottish league leader Rangers hosts last place Dunfermline and
hopes to improve on its 2-point lead over Kilmarnock, which
welcomes Aberdeen.
	   Defending champion Celtic, which is third, goes to fifth-place
Hearts on Sunday.
	   (rjm) 	   
</TEXT>
