<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Davis Cup, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swedes drop Johansson; Norman to open against Gaudenzi
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS, UPDATES with detail, quotes, ADDS byline. AMs will be
filed. &QL; 
 &UR; By PIERO VALSECCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ Defending champion Sweden on Thursday
dropped its highest-ranked player from the Davis Cup team, leaving
to No. 31 Magnus Gustafsson the leading role in the three-day final
against Italy at the Assago Forum.
	   Thomas Johansson, ranked 17th in the ATP lists, was excluded at
the last minute from the Swedish quartet because of his uncertain
form and his questionable efficiency on clay.
	   Johansson, who's nursing a sore right knee, had been training
along with his teammates in Milan this week.
	   Thursday's draw, in Milan's 16th century city council hall, set
up opening day singles matches Friday between Italy's top player
Andrea Gaudenzi and Magnus Norman, followed by Gustafsson against
Italy's No. 2, Davide Sanguinetti.
	   They'll switch opponents for Sunday's two singles matches, while
the doubles is Saturday.
	   It's the first time in the 99 years of tennis' premier team
event that there is no one in the top 30 of the ATP lists playing
singles in the final.
	   Gaudenzi is 44th in the ATP lists, Sanguinetti 47th and Norman
52nd.
	   ``From practice this week it seems like Gustafsson and Norman
are the most ready for this challenge,'' said Sweden's non-playing
captain Carl-Axel Hageskog. ``I decided to go with Norman because
his clay court season this year was good, and he's a good clay
player.''
	   Italy, in its first Davis Cup final since 1980 and first ever at
home, decided to play on clay on the grounds Gaudenzi and
Sanguinetti may take advantage of a slower court against the
favored Swedes.
	   Sweden, a six-time Davis Cup titlist, is in its 12th final.
	   ``It's very special playing at home, but it also adds extra
pressure,'' said Italian captain Paolo Bertolucci, who played on
the team which won Italy's only Davis Cup title, in Chile, in 1976.
	   The hosts reached the final this time by upsetting a
second-string U.S. team in the semifinals, while Sweden swept
Spain.
	   Italian organizers expect sellout crowds of 13,000 each of the
final's three days and Gaudenzi said playing at home is exciting.
``What's going to be really special is the crowd cheering for us,''
he said.
	   Jonas Bjorkman, who will team with Nicklas Kulti in doubles
against the Italian pair of Gaudenzi and Diego Nargiso, said the
home crowd should not give Italy any extra advantage.
	   ``We have too much experience to get into a situation where it
bothers us,'' he said.
	   Gustafsson said he felt more relaxed as the matches approached.
	   ``One or two weeks ago I was looking at (the final) as too big a
thing,'' he said. ``Then in recent days I relaxed a bit more and
realized it's just two tennis matches.''
	   (pv/hjf)
</TEXT>
