<SLUG> AM-Space Station, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0771,0588 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Astronauts board shuttle: `Let's go build a space station!'
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with astronauts boarding shuttle,
quotes, CORRECT spelling of Albright's first name; picks up 6th
graf pvs, `The mission ...'; SUBS penultimate graf to DELETE now
redundant first reference to commander; Launch scheduled for about
4 a.m. EST Thursday; launch window lasts just 10 minutes. &QL; 
 &UR; By MARCIA DUNN &QC; 
 &UR; AP Aerospace Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) _ With the weather on both sides of
the Atlantic vastly improving, astronauts boarded the shuttle
Endeavour for a Thursday liftoff of the first space station
construction flight.
	   ``All right, let's go build a space station!'' commander Robert
Cabana shouted, flashing a thumb's up, on his way to the pad. He
said it again as he strapped into Endeavour.
	   ``Amen, I'm with you,'' a launch controller replied.
	   All week, forecasters feared clouds and rain might delay
Endeavour's pre-dawn launch with the first American-built piece of
the international space station.
	   But by Wednesday night, the rain had stopped and the full moon
could be seen peeking from behind scattering clouds.
	   The weather also improved at an emergency landing site in Spain.
NASA would not launch unless at least one site in Spain or Morocco
was available.
	   Dignitaries from around the world gathered to see Endeavour and
its crew of six off following a year's delay caused by a cash crush
in Russia, NASA's chief partner in the space station project. Most
were representatives of the 16 countries participating in the space
station effort. The guest list included Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
	   The mission promises to be one of the most difficult in space
shuttle history. And the entire space station project promises to
be the most difficult undertaking since the Apollo moon landings
nearly 30 years ago.
	   ``We're not testing just hardware as part of this program,''
said Mikhail Sinelschikov, a Russian space official. ``We're
testing our relationship very much and our mutual trust and our
confidence in each other.''
	   Two weeks ago, the Russians put the first piece of the space
station into orbit.
	   During Endeavour's 12-day flight, the astronauts will use the
shuttle robot arm to capture the Russian piece and attach it to the
American component. Then, two astronauts will perform three
spacewalks to hook up all the electrical connections and cables
between the two cylinders.
	   The U.S. piece, named Unity, is a connecting passageway. It is
essentially an aluminum can with big holes where other chambers
eventually will attach. It contains six miles of wiring and more
than 50,000 mechanical pieces.
	   The Russian component, named Zarya, which means sunrise,
contains the power and propulsion systems that will keep the
station aloft until the Russians can launch a permanent control
module.
	   In all, more than 100 components weighing 1 million pounds are
to be launched over the next five years, requiring 45 U.S. and
Russian flights.
	   ``It's going to start out kind of small, but it's going to grow
to the size of a football field,'' said shuttle commander Cabana.
	   Unity should have been put in orbit last December. But station
assembly was put on hold because of Russia's economic crisis, which
prevented the country's space agency from completing the permanent
control module. NASA has since bailed out the Russian Space Agency.
</TEXT>
