<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Kuwait, Jordan, Iraq, Egypt. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The price index of the Kuwait Stock Exchange
continued to dip this week, falling 4.8 percent to 1,723.4 points,
the National Investments Co. said Thursday.
	   The company warned in its weekly report that if ``clear
measures'' are not taken to correct the market, the index will fall
even lower, erasing all the gains of several years.
	   Investors say that the exchange, which lists 77 companies, is
suffering from lack of liquidity. But the Central Bank disagrees
and is conducting a survey before it decides what should be done.
	   Trading in the first day of the week was interrupted shortly
after it started by a bomb hoax.
	   Some 110.04 million shares changed hands this week, down 32.76
percent from last week, according to the report. The value of these
shares dropped 40.61 percent to 18.17 million dinars (dlrs 60.16
million).
	   Of the 66 companies that were traded, only 3 closed higher while
58 closed lower. The others were unchanged.
 &UR; ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Share prices shored up but turnover slipped
on the stock exchange this week because trading centered on shares
of lucrative commercial banks, brokers said Thursday.
	   A stock market report, reflecting activity for five business
days ending Wednesday, said the 60-company general share prices
index nudged up 1.26 percent to 164.94 points.
	   Shares of commercial banks increased 1.86 percent. But shares of
industrial firms dropped 0.13 percent, insurance companies 0.95
percent and the services sector 0.35 percent.
	   Turnover also fell about 20 percent to 5.29 million Jordanian
dinars (dlrs 7.4 million), the report said.
	   It said stocks of 103 firms were traded during the week.
 &UR; ___
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Trading was off sharply at the Baghdad
Stock Exchange this week amid instability in the exchange rate of
the dinar.
	   The market bulletin released Thursday said the number of shares
traded slumped 65 per cent to 28.48 million from 80.8 million the
previous week.
	   The value of these shares fell 30 per cent to 294 million dinars
(dlrs 172,000).
	   The bulletin, reflecting activity for the three business days
ending Wednesday, said trading was concentrated in banking and
industrial stocks.
	   The Iraqi dinar this week weakened to about 1,800 to the dollar,
firmed to 1,600 and then settled back to 1,750 amid concerns over
Iraqi cooperation on U.N. weapons inspections.
 &UR; ___
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh left
for Egypt on Thursday for talks aimed at boosting trade
cooperation, the official Iraqi News Agency reported.
	   Saleh will head the Iraqi side in meetings of the joint
Iraqi-Egyptian Committee that coordinates cooperation in trade,
economic, and cultural fields, the agency said.
	   Egypt has been a major participant in the U.N.-approved
oil-for-food program, which allows Iraq to sell limited quantities
of oil to buy needed food and medicine. The program is an exception
from U.N. trade sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
	   Iraq has been importing soap, detergent, sugar and
pharmaceuticals from Egypt under the oil-for-food program. Egyptian
ready-made clothes and household utensils also are available in
Baghdad shops.
 &UR; ___
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Oil and gas discoveries _ two of them in the
Western Desert and one in the Mediterranean _ were made in Egypt
last month, Al-Akhbar daily reported Thursday.
	   The newspaper quoted Oil Minister Hamdy el-Banbi as saying that
Khalda Oil Co. struck gas in the desert southeast of the
Mediterranean city of Mersa Matrouh.
	   He said the find was expected to produce 19 million cubic feet
(570,000 cubic meters) of natural gas and 732 barrels of
condensates per day, the paper said.
	   The second discovery was made by Gupco Co. in the Mediterranean
north of Port Said at a depth of 80 meters (yards), said the paper.
It was expected to produce 40 million cubic feet (1.2 million cubic
meters) of natural gas and 2,200 barrels of condensates a day.
	   The third, discovered by Agiba Co. in the Qattara depression in
the Western Desert, is expected to produce 800 barrels of oil a
day, Al-Akhbar said.
	   El-Banbi said there have been 22 oil and 14 natural gas
discoveries this year.
 &UR; buros-eap
</TEXT>
