w1861 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-Sweden-Defense     12-03 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PM-Sweden-Defense,0586 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sweden defense forces falling after Cold War
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HARALD MOLLERSTROM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ At the height of the Cold War, Sweden
had one of the world's strongest militaries. Now, the thaw between
East and West has melted its might.
	   Sweden's formidable defense forces have helped keep it out of
war since 1814, even during the decades when the nearby Soviet
Union was seen as a threat.
	   After the Soviet Union collapsed and the Russian military was
revealed as poorly maintained and badly fed, Sweden began cutting
back its armed forces.
	   Top commanders watched uneasily as defense outlays were shaved _
from 11 percent of the national budget in 1975 to 6.9 percent last
year. The air force, which had been the world's fifth-largest 40
years ago with 850 planes, is now down to 220.
	   The Swedish navy has been pared from a fleet of more than 130
warships, including a dozen destroyers and 26 submarines, to just
24 lightly armed surface vessels and nine submarines. The army that
once comprised 31 brigades and 155,000 soldiers has seen its force
reduced to 13 brigades and 65,000 men.
	   In the latest blow to the military, the government on Tuesday
announced that it would not appropriate more money to pay for new
equipment that was ordered years ago. Instead, the government
suggested, the military could cover some of the $1.16 billion debt
by borrowing against future defense budgets.
	   Supreme Commander Owe Wiktorin found that suggestion
humiliating.
	   ``We have always kept our budgets. To borrow money to solve your
problems is a bad solution. Every breadwinner knows that,''
Wiktorin said. ``This is the worst possible scenario.''
	   Wiktorin says the current $5.5 billion defense budget falls $375
million short. To close the gap, Wiktorin says, the military may
have to limit itself to 6,000 conscripts next year instead of the
usual 25,000, and postpone or cancel equipment orders.
	   Halting weapons procurement would be a crushing blow to Sweden's
defense industry, which makes submarines, surface vessels,
armaments and planes. Especially vulnerable would be Saab, the
maker of the JAS Gripen warplane. Sweden is the only country using
the Gripen, although South Africa has indicated it wants to order
some two dozen of the planes.
	   The weapons were ordered in the waning years of the Cold War,
when the Soviet Union still looked intimidating and commanders were
concerned that Sweden's military equipment was becoming dangerously
outdated.
	   The curtain of Russian invincibility has slipped away.
Coincidentally, as the government was discussing military funding
on Tuesday, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov was briefing Prime
Minister Goeran Persson on Russia's 40-percent force reduction in
the northwest.
	   The latest military budget decision reflects not only the new
post-Cold War politics but a new political balance in Sweden.
	   After weak election results in September, the governing Social
Democrats now rely on the Greens and the former communist Left
Party to stay in power _ and those two parties used their strength
to block more money to the military.
	   ``It's unthinkable that defense policy should rest on the Left
Party's and the Greens' views,'' Defense Minister Bjoern von Sydow
complained Tuesday.
	   Early next year the defense staff will submit a report on
threats to Sweden's security. On the basis of the study, the
government will decide whether to cut the defense budget further.
</TEXT>
