<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Slave Labor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German court blocks compensation for Nazi-era slave labor
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TONY CZUCZKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ A German court denied compensation Thursday
to a Polish-born Jewish woman who was forced into slave labor under
the Nazis, dampening hopes for other survivors in eastern Europe.
	   The state superior court in Cologne threw out an award of 15,000
marks (dlrs 9,000) for Rywka Merin, who toiled for the Union
munitions factory under Nazi SS guard while imprisoned at the
Auschwitz camp during World War II.
	   A court in Bonn had ordered the payment last November because
Merin lived behind the Iron Curtain until 1968 and missed a 1965
deadline for seeking health and imprisonment compensation from
Germany.
	   But the higher court upheld the government's appeal against the
award, citing postwar German restitution laws that paid reparations
for suffering or health loss but give former slave workers no
possibility to sue for back pay.
	   It also rejected appeals on behalf of 22 other former Jewish
slave laborers who were denied back wages in last year's ruling
because they had already been compensated by Germany.
	   Lawyers for the survivors or their families were expected to
appeal further.
	   All plaintiffs were slave workers while interned at Auschwitz
during 1943-1945 _ 12 hours a day, six days a week for periods
ranging from 27 to 68 weeks. Most were Polish citizens.
	   Germany has paid more than 100 billion marks (dlrs 60 billion)
in reparations to Nazi victims, but it has refused to honor wage
claims by slave workers, who were technically working for private
companies.
	   About 7 million slave laborers were forced to work in Nazi
Germany during the war. Most were from Poland and the Soviet Union,
and many were Jews.
	   Under pressure from lawsuits against German companies in the
United States, new Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has launched talks
on a government foundation to compensate Nazi-era slave laborers, a
step refused by his predecessor Helmut Kohl.
	   It's still unclear whether the government will pay into the
fund, or only industry.
	   ``The German government will work for a solution that satisfies
former Nazi-era slave laborers,'' the Finance Ministry said after
Thursday's verdict.
 &UR; (tc-cb)
</TEXT>
