<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-European Award, HFR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lee Westwood gets Player of Year prize
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; FOR RELEASE AT 2300 GMT, Thursday, Dec. 3; time set by source

<TEXT>
	   VIRGINIA WATER, England (AP) _ England's Lee Westwood, who
captured seven titles in six countries in 1998, has won the
European Tour's golfer of the year award.
	   Westwood, 25, was a unanimous winner in the voting by a panel of
golf writers, beating out Colin Montgomerie and Darren Clarke.
	   Montgomerie had won the award the past three years and finished
as the top money-winner in Europe this season for the sixth
straight year.
	   Westwood won European Tour events in Germany, England, Scotland
and Belgium on the way to finishing third in the order of merit
(behind Montgomerie and Clarke) with 814,386 pounds (dlrs 1.3
million).
	   Westwood also won for the first time on the U.S. tour when he
captured the Freeport-McDermott Classic in New Orleans. Last month,
he won back-to-back tournaments in Japan. This week, he's playing
in the Million Dollar Challenge in Sun City, South Africa.
	   ``I'd almost given up hope of getting an award this year after
missing out on golfer of the month all season,'' Westwood said.
``Had the award been purely for Europe, I probably wouldn't have
won it because I finished third in the Volvo Ranking. My win in
America and the two in Japan probably swung it for me.
	   ``My results throughout the world have been the best of any
European this year and nobody else won four times in Europe so I
know I must have been in with a chance. But I was still shocked and
delighted to have won it.''
	   (sw)	   
</TEXT>
