<SLUG> BC-Somalia-Fighting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Church agency denies labor dispute caused Somali fighting
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ A Swedish church aid agency denied
Thursday that a labor dispute involving its workers led to fighting
that killed at least 60 people in a southwestern Somalia town.
	   Fighting in Sakow erupted Nov. 15 because of a dispute over the
sharing of a levy at a roadblock normally mounted by militiamen
belonging to two subclans, Swedish Church Relief said.
	   The church group said the division of the tariffs among the
subclans as well as the number of employees and contracts that go
to each are agreed on by elders and the Sakow district committee,
without the participation of the SRC.
	   ``Reports concerning labor equity being the cause of the latest
fighting are false,'' the church group said in a statement.
	   It said there were reports of widespread looting in Sakow, 380
kilometers (240 miles) southwest of Mogadishu, during the fighting,
but the church group's compound was protected by a joint force of
militiamen from the warring subclans.
	   The church group said the warring Geldle and Maclinwein subclans
of the Rahanwein clan agreed on a cease-fire Monday, and Tuesday a
55-member peace committee was formed.
	   On Thursday, negotiations were underway on a venue for peace
negotiations, the agency said.
	   Since Somalia descended into civil war after the ouster of
dictator Mohamed Siad Barre in 1991, militiamen loyal to clans or
subclans have carved out territories. Squabbles over jobs and
contracts from aid agencies often lead to shootouts.
	    &UR; (HO-cm)
</TEXT>
