<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Farmers Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Farmers protest government policy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo available &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Despite frigid weather, several thousand
farmers from across Poland gathered Thursday in downtown Warsaw to
demand government protection for farms and fewer imports.
	   The farmers, with banners reading ``Polish bread from Polish
grain'' and ``Polish authorities betray farmers,'' demanded
government guarantees their products will be bought and more
spending on agriculture in the draft budget for 1999.
	   Farmers carried an effigy of Finance Minister Leszek
Balcerowicz, a stringent supporter of fiscal discipline, who they
blame for what they call insufficient spending on agriculture. Some
protesters beat the effigy with rods.
	   Balcerowicz introduced so-called ``shock therapy'' measures
promoting market-led reforms after communist rule ended in 1989.
The reforms have included a reduction in state subsidies for Polish
agriculture products.
	   A government statement expressed surprise that farmers organized
the protest a day before scheduled talks between farmers and
agriculture ministry officials,
	   Farmers have repeatedly demonstrated throughout Poland,
sometimes blocking roads and border crossings, to protest grain
imports and low prices for Polish-grown products.
	   Poland's agriculture sector is considered inefficient and
ill-equipped, and analysts say the industry needs major reforms in
preparation for the country's bid to join the European Union.
	   But the powerful 4-million-strong farm lobby has resisted
reforms, fearing a shift from small, family-owned farms to large
farming conglomerates will force many people to give up
agriculture.
	   (bp-tsc)
</TEXT>
