<HEADLINE>
South Africa struggles to compile first all-race voters list
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with IEC chief saying one-third of
voters registered in the north last week; TIGHTENS 4th graf &QL; 
 &UR; Photos planned
 &UR; By ANDREW SELSKY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ South Africans trekked in the
rain to voter registration stations Thursday but washed-out roads
and other problems hampered the nation's attempt to create its
first all-race voters list.
	   The massive registration effort in the southern half of the
country is seen as a test of the Independent Electoral Commission's
ability to hold free and fair elections next year _ only the second
since the end of white rule.
	   Problems also plagued the registration for 12.7 million
potential voters in South Africa's five northern provinces last
weekend, with voters including President Nelson Mandela having been
directed to the wrong sites. About one-third of potential voters in
the north registered, IEC chairman Johann Kriegler told reporters.
	   The process appeared smoother Thursday as it began in the
southern half of the country.
	   Marthinus van Schalkwyk, the leader of the National Party which
ruled during apartheid, said as he registered in Cape Town: ``It
seems as if the Independent Electoral Commission has done its
homework in this province.''
