w1988 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Syria-Elections     12-03 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Syria-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AP Photos DAM-101
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Syria's ruling coalition wins expected majority in parliament

<TEXT>
	   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) _ Syria's ruling coalition, the National
Progressive Front, as expected won the majority of seats in the
250-member Parliament, the government announced Thursday.
	   The front, led by the Baath Party of President Hafez Assad, can
win up to 167 seats in the Parliament, and Interior Minister
Mohammed Harba announced it won its full allotment.
	   He said 7.1 million people, or nearly 82 per cent of the more
than 8 million eligible voters, cast ballots Monday and Tuesday. He
said the elections took place in a ``quiet ... and democratic
atmosphere'' and called the turnout ``distinguished.''
	   Voting was repeated in one polling station at Deir al-Zour in
eastern Syria after a ballot box was found to contain more votes
than registered voters, Harba told a news conference.
	   The National Assembly, or parliament, has limited legislative
power, with effective control held by Assad, who came to power in a
bloodless coup in 1970.
	   Five of Syria's most powerful businessmen won seats running as
independents. The private sector hopes to gain more say in the new
parliament, following government efforts to encourage more private
investment.
	   Twenty-six women were among winning candidates, compared to 24
who held seats in the last parliament, Harba said.
	   The control of seats was the same in the previous four-year
term, which ended in September. The Baath got 135 seats, and 32
went to the six allied parties. Independents make up the remaining
83 seats.
	   Among seats held by the National Progressive Front, 51 percent
are controlled by workers and peasants, who form the backbone of
the Baath party, in power since 1963.
	   Some 7,350 candidates ran in the elections.
 &UR; damas-ms-sf
</TEXT>
