<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/03/1998 09:55:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1989 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EU-CentralBank     12-03 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Central Bank,0363 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Duisenberg: labor market reform, not interest rates, key to
</HEADLINE>
job-creation

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ European Central Bank President Wim
Duisenberg on Thursday suggested governments should reform rigid
labor markets to create jobs rather than pressure him into cutting
interest rates.
	   ``The high unemployment rate in Europe is far more the
consequence of structural rigidities within the European labor and
product markets than a result of adverse cyclical developments,''
Duisenberg said in a speech.
	   Duisenberg has been under pressure from the left-leaning French
and German governments to lower rates when his bank takes over
monetary policy for the 11 nations that adopt the euro currency on
Jan. 1.
	   Speaking to European business and labor representatives,
Duisenberg said the ECB would do ``its utmost'' to help solve the
euro-zone's unemployment problem, but he insisted the bank's role
was ``very limited.''
	   In another message to European governments he stressed that
successful monetary policy must be supported by sound fiscal
policies and responsible wage settlements.
	   With inflation in the euro-zone nations at just 1 percent, and
unemployment stubbornly high at 10.9 percent, governments are
urging Duisenberg to boost business by setting lower rates.
	   He says the bank will resist political pressure, pointing out
that rates in the EU's core-economies are already low. The ECB is
expected to set the benchmark rate in the euro-zone close to
Germany's 3.3 rate.
	   Answering questions after his speech, Duisenberg stressed price
stability would be the main factor dictating ECB monetary policy,
but that currency exchange rates would also play a role.
	   He said exchange rate of the euro against the dollar will be
``one of a broad range of indices'' that will help the bank shape
policy.
	   ``We aren't concerned at present about the level of the euro
against the dollar,'' he said. ``What will be a concern is the
volatility, not the levels as such?''
	   Duisenberg said the ECB's focus on price stability matches that
of its U.S. counterpart the Federal Reserve.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
