w1993 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Egypt-HumanRights 1stLd-Writethru   12-03 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Human Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EOHR freezes activities after government detains leader
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in grafs 8-9 with second statement of support. &QL; 
 &UR; By BASSEM MROUE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egypt's largest human rights group announced
Thursday that it was suspending its activities because of a
government campaign that ``aims to terrorize the organization and
eliminate its role.''
	   The decision was made at a Wednesday night meeting of the
15-member board of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights.
	   The announcement came two days after Egyptian security officials
detained the group's secretary-general, Hafez Abu Saada, on grounds
he accepted a donation from the British government without Egyptian
government approval. He can be held for 15 days for investigation.
	   The statement said the board decided to ``freeze the
activities'' of the organization ``in all parts of the republic.''
	   This means the EOHR won't send investigators into the field and
will not issue any public statements on human rights cases, the
board decided. If citizens come with complaints, they will be
referred to other human rights groups, it said.
	   Also Thursday, the Land Center for Human Rights, which deals
with property disputes, charged in a statement that the
government's campaign against the EOHR ``aims to weaken the human
rights movement in Egypt.''
	   The Land Center urged authorities to release Abu Saada, saying
his detention is ``part of a campaign aiming to terrorize people
working in the human rights field.''
	   Meanwhile, the Cairo-headquartered Arab Center for the
Independence of the Judiciary issued a statement charging that the
government was targeting the human rights movement ``to threaten
its very existence.''
	   The Arab Center expressed concern that Egyptian police would not
disclose where Abu Saada was being detained and interrogated.
	   The government to date has refused to register a single Egyptian
human rights group, putting them in the precarious position of
operating without the status of officially approved
non-governmental organizations.
	   The donation of dlrs 25,703 from a British Parliament committee
to the EOHR became the subject of controversy after an Egyptian
weekly, Al-Osboa, alleged last month that it was ``payment'' for a
report charging that Egyptian police had arrested and tortured
hundreds of Coptic Christians in a criminal investigation in
August.
	   Al-Osboa has close ties to the Interior Ministry, which is
responsible for internal security in Egypt. The government has
denied the torture allegations.
	   In its announcement, the board said it believed the government
was trying to stop human rights work in Egypt.
	   ``This campaign aims to terrorize the organization and eliminate
its role in protecting human rights and revealing these violations
sincerely and faithfully,'' the statement said.
	   The statement said the board would pursue the release of Abu
Saada and would continue to communicate with local and
international human rights groups.
 &UR; bm-eap
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
