<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Airline </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss airline's operating license suspended
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ Switzerland's transport ministry
Thursday suspended the operating license of newcomer Swiss World
Airways, which has halted flights just three months after taking to
the skies.
	   SWA, which started flying from Geneva to Newark, New Jersey, in
September, suspended flights until further notice Wednesday and
announced it was applying to defer its payments.
	   It had been operating six return flights a week with its single
Boeing 767 jet.
	   State authorities in western Switzerland and private investors
helped finance the airline, whose launch followed months of
bureaucratic and financial delays.
	   The airline said last week it needed 3 million Swiss francs
(dlrs 2.15 million) immediately to keep flying. Geneva state
authorities on Monday refused to bail SWA out.
	   Western Swiss states had invested almost 7 million francs (dlrs
5 million) in the transatlantic newcomer. The suspension of
operations left more than 100 staff without work.
	   SWA was founded in 1996 following national flag carrier
Swissair's controversial decision to cut costs by transferring most
long-haul flights to Zurich. The move caused outrage among the
French-speaking population of western Switzerland.
	   Swissair still operates a daily return flight between Geneva and
New York.
	   SWA had planned to operate its first flight last December, but
delays in sorting out contractual issues prevented it getting
government clearance. Its license was initially valid for one year.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
