<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Spanish Preview </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Barcelona in crisis and Real Madrid in intercontinental heaven
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOHANNA TUCKMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Much more than just a league match, FC
Barcelona's game Saturday against Deportivo La Coruna could prove
decisive for Dutch coach Louis Van Gaal.
	   ``Van Gaal knows his head could roll, and the team knows that
there is much more at stake than just a result,'' the
Barcelona-based daily El Mundo Deportivo said Thursday about the
13th-round match.
	   Upset at being knocked out of European soccer at an
embarrassingly early stage, and languishing in fifth place in the
domestic league, Barcelona fans are calling for Van Gaal's head.
	   Sports dailies reported that the dour coach on Tuesday pleaded
with the players to help him stay in his job by doing their best
against Deportivo.
	   Relatively humble Deportivo sits at No. 4 in the table with 20
points, two points behind leader Mallorca and one above No. 5
Barcelona.
	   Meanwhile, the imminent return of team captain Pep Guardiola
after more than a year out of action through injury is being
treated as a glimmer of hope within the Barcelona crisis.
	   ``Guardiola carries the heavy load of savior,'' wrote La
Vanguardia Thursday.
	   It pointed to the midfielder's reputation for team play and his
status as the only link to Johan Cruyff's ``dream team'' that won
the European Cup and three consecutive league championships.
	   ``If the fans want to ask me for the moon, let them ask for it.
I am not a magic solution but I will do my best,'' said Guardiola,
one of Spain's most respected internationals.
	   In the meantime, El Mundo Deportivo published an unconfirmed
report that club chairman Jose Luis Nunez is thinking of hiring
Italian coach Fabio Capello to replace Van Gaal.
	   The paper said a three-year pre-contract already exists that if
firmed up would be worth 500 million pesetas (dlrs 3.5 million) a
year to Capello.
	   Real Madrid, the other traditional powerhouse of Spanish soccer,
also plays away from home on Saturday, against lower-half Espanyol.
	   Although Madrid is also struggling in the domestic league,
currently four points behind the leader at No. 8, the team is
euphoric with Tuesday's 2-1 victory in Tokyo over Brazilian team
Vasco da Gama to claim the Intercontinental Cup.
	   ``We needed this great victory,'' Raul Gonzalez, scorer of the
class goal that won Madrid the game, told the state-owned news
agency EFE Thursday.
	   ``We had had many defeats and a lot of criticism and we were not
receiving the respect we deserve,'' the born-again golden boy of
Spanish soccer said.
	   Also in action Saturday are first-placed Mallorca, second-placed
Celta and third-placed Celta.
	   Mallorca plays at home against Betis. Leading the table with 22
points, Mallorca heads the list of relatively humble clubs who this
season have wiped some of the shine off the superteams.
	   But Betis could prove a tough rival with team confidence growing
as it overcomes a dismal start to the season by moving from bottom
place to No. 9, despite being joint bottom scorer with only eight
goals.
	   Fresh from its 1-0 triumph over Barcelona last week,
third-placed Atletico de Madrid hosts Athletic de Bilbao. The
latter, like Barcelona, is also celebrating its 100th anniversary
this year with a disappointing season.
	   Celta, meanwhile, travels to play lower-half Salamanca in search
of the victory that could mean snatching the No. 1 spot from
Mallorca.
	   Saturday's only other game pits mid-table Real Sociedad against
struggling Extremadura.
	   Sunday wraps up the 13th-round sending No. 6 Valencia away to
play division newcomer Alaves, last-placed Tenerife at home to No.
7 Zaragoza, a midtable battle between Oviedo and Racing and a
lower-half tussle pitting Villarreal against Valladolid
	   (jt/dw)
</TEXT>
