<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Future </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top international official sets goals for next year
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By AIDA CERKEZ-ROBINSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ Ahead of an international
conference on peace in Bosnia, the top international official in
the country Thursday announced his goals for the new year: to make
peace self-sustaining and to prepare the country to live without
foreign aid.
	   The Peace Implementation Council that will meet Dec. 10 in
Madrid, Spain, should send a clear signal to Bosnian leaders that
international assistance in implementing peace accords is at its
height, and will begin diminishing after 1999, said Simon Haselock,
the spokesman for Carlos Westendorp, the top international official
in Bosnia.
	   ``Its leaders must use the time that remains to prepare their
country for a life without foreign aid,'' he said.
	   Westendorp is convinced that ``any exit strategy of the
international community from Bosnia-Herzegovina must be accompanied
by an entry strategy for Bosnia-Herzegovina into European
institutions,'' like the Council of Europe and the European Union,
Haselock said.
	   To accomplish this, local and international leaders must work to
strengthen Bosnia's free-market economy, develop political
institutions and the rule of law, and bolster ties with Europe,
Haselock said.
	   Next year's priorities also will include a dramatic push for the
return of refugees and making Bosnia ``a country fit for the
returnees to live in,'' he said.
	   In 1996, Bosnia received dlrs 5.1 billion in reconstruction aid,
and dlrs 1 billion remains to be spent in 1999.
	   Asked how far the country has come since the Dayton peace
agreement was signed in late 1995, Haselock said it was a matter of
``looking at the bottle being half-empty or half-full. ... I would
say we have come more then half the way.''
	   While political structures have been established, work still
needs to be done to ensure they function properly, he said.
	   (acr/asd/scl)
</TEXT>
