<SLUG> BC-Algeria, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: bomb in western Algeria kills 14, injures 24
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS that 19 other people killed in recent attacks, background
on visit by U.N. Secretary General

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ A bomb exploded at a market in western Algeria on
Thursday, killing 14 people and injuring 24 others, French radio
reported.
	   The explosion occurred shortly before midday in Khemis Miliana,
about 125 kilometers (78 miles) west of Algiers, France Info radio
reported.
	   It was not immediately possible to confirm the attack, and no
further details were available.
	   If confirmed, it would be the sixth violent attack in a week, a
week that saw the visit of U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan.
	   The Muslim holy month of Ramadan, which begins this year on Dec.
20, has been marred by waves of violence since the insurgency
began. This year has proved no exception.
	   Twelve villagers were slaughtered in their sleep in a massacre
early Wednesday. Algerian security forces immediately launched a
search for the armed attackers in the Sidi Rached region about 60
miles west of Algiers.
	   The attack on the villagers came as Annan met with Algerian
President Liamine Zeroual, on a visit aimed at ending the conflict
in the Western Sahara.
	   On Sunday, officials said four attacks in the western mountains
of Algeria had left seven people dead.
	   More than 75,000 people have died in an insurgency that erupted
when Algeria's military-backed government canceled January 1992
elections that an Islamic fundamentalist group, the Islamic
Salvation Front, was poised to win.
	   (ip-jn) 	   
