<HEADLINE>
Moldova trade unions call rally against unpaid wages, budget cuts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CHISINAU, Moldova (AP) _ Moldovan trade unions called Thursday
for a mass rally in the nation's capital to protest unpaid wages
and deep state budget cuts.
	   Moldova's General Federation of Unions will gather at least half
its 60,000 members in front of the government headquarters Friday
in the largest protest here since the 1992 fall of communism,
deputy federation leader Petru Chiriac said.
	   The protest is sponsored mainly by disgruntled employees in the
state-dominated industry, education and agriculture sectors.
	   Moldovan Premier Ion Ciubuc last week promised to subsidize some
basic foods in an unsuccessful attempt to avert the threatened
protest.
	   Meanwhile, municipal authorities vow to take legal action
against the protesters under a national law that prohibits rallies
in front of the government building. Authorities say the protest
will snarl traffic throughout downtown.
	   Facing a harsh winter, tens of thousands of workers haven't been
paid for months as its already lagging economy follows Russia, its
main trading partner, into a downturn.
	   The representative of the International Monetary Fund in
Chisinau, Mark Horton, warned the government it must further cut
spending in order to receive a badly-needed loan of dlrs 35
million.
