<HEADLINE>
Court agrees to extradite Turkish mafia boss
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with lawyers saying they will appeal &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AIX-EN-PROVENCE, France (AP) _ A French appeals court on
Thursday agreed to extradite an alleged Turkish mafia boss to
Turkey. But it said it would set conditions for the extradition.
	   Alaatin Cakici, 45, who is believed to be one of Turkey's top
mafia bosses, was arrested in France in August on an international
arrest warrant.
	   Court officials said the extradition would be subject to
conditions set by the French court. They did not immediately
elaborate.
	   But Cakici's lawyers said they would appeal the ruling, Turkey's
Anatolia news agency reported.
	   A French court sentenced him to six months in prison for using a
false passport and a fake identity card.
	   Cakici has been on the run from Turkish justice for years. He
was caught Aug. 17 in Nice by French police using a diplomatic
passport.
	   He is wanted in Turkey for a series of murders since 1978.
