<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Million Dollar Challenge </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Price takes lead in first round of Million Dollar Challenge
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SUN CITY, South Africa (AP) _ Zimbabwe's Nick Price takes a
two-shot edge into the second round of the Million Dollar Challenge
after a five-under 67 over the windswept Gary Player Country Club
course Thursday.
	   Price, the defending champion in the tournament that carries the
biggest single check in golf, was two shots up on a three-way
logjam of double Major winner Mark O'Meara, Justin Leonard and
Germany's Bernhard Langer. South African hometown hero Ernie Els
was a shot back at 70.
	   Price had six birdies in his round, picking up shots at the
par-5 2nd, the short 7th, par-5 10th and 14th before finishing
back-to-back birdies on No. 17 and 18, both par 4.
	   O'Meara, holder of the U.S. Masters and British Open titles,
reached 4-under to share the lead on the 14th in the two-ball ahead
of Price, but surrendered this when Price birdied No. 14 and
O'Meara made his second bogey of a five-birdie round on No. 15.
	   O'Meara had started the day a relieved man after his clubs
finally arrived in Sun City Wednesday night. They had been lost en
route from Florida to South Africa Sunday night.
	   Els, who had been four under after four, made bogey on numbers
6, 11 and 17 against a solitary relieving birdie on the 10th.
	   ``It was really a long course out there today,'' he said of the
layout that had been battered by heavy rain and a day where a
swirling wind made things even more difficult for the elite 12-man
field.
	   The final round is Sunday at the 7,597-yard (6,947-meter),
par-72 Gary Player Country Club course. Prize money totals dlrs
2.57 million.
	   (str/djw)	   
