<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Government </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Schroeder's coalition pledges unity after crisis talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TONY CZUCZKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Leaders of Germany's new center-left ruling
alliance pledged better cooperation Thursday to stop squabbling
that has marred Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's debut.
	   The comments followed emergency talks between the Social
Democrats and the environmentalist Greens to counter growing
disunity in the 6-week-old government over taxes and foreign
policy.
	   Schroeder pledged in the Wednesday night talks to work more
closely with the Greens, his junior coalition partner, by attending
their policy meetings.
	   Both sides also agreed to hold regular coalition strategy
sessions, which they had previously resisted as smacking of former
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's top-down governing style.
	   ``Two parties that govern together need a framework to
coordinate regularly between Cabinet, parliamentary group and
party, and also to clear up atmospheric differences,'' Greens
co-leader Gunda Roestel said Thursday on German radio.
	   Schroeder has struggled both with the Greens and his own Social
Democrats over tax reform plans, part of the fight to lower
unemployment stuck above 10 percent.
	   Wolfgang Clement, a Schroeder ally and powerful state governor,
openly called for more tax relief for small and medium-size firms,
prompting a meeting with the chancellor this week to get him to
back down.
	   Schroeder also was reportedly angered by a Greens leader's call
to raise gasoline taxes well beyond the 6 pfennigs (3.5 cents) per
liter agreed to by both parties.
	   Despite occasionally chaotic preparation by the coalition,
parliament is expected to pass the first new law Friday, including
a slight cut in income taxes and an increase in aid to families
with children.
	   Regular meetings by the coalition's lawmakers should now provide
early warning on ``where problems are developing,'' said Social
Democratic lawmaker Wilhelm Schmidt.
	   Other signs of disunity have included a Greens politician's call
to lift the ban on the Kurdistan Workers Party, which was promptly
rejected by Interior Minister Otto Schily.
	   And while Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping met U.S. officials
in Washington last week, Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer called on
NATO to consider dropping its doctrine allowing a nuclear strike
without first being targeted.
	   U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen dismissed the proposal.
 &UR; (tc-cb)
</TEXT>
