w2053 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-France-JewishAssets     12-03 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Jewish Assets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: postwar commission was pressured to drop investigation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Unpublished government documents show the French
government pressured a postwar restitution commission to drop an
inquiry into state agents who got rich selling off Jewish property,
a French newspaper reported Thursday.
	   The pressure was so great that the restitution service, created
in 1946 and headed by a former Resistance leader, was disbanded
after a year, Le Parisien reported. With a few exceptions, no state
agents were prosecuted, it said.
	   The newspaper said documents retrieved from a French Finance
Ministry cellar describe the function of the agents, appointed by
the pro-Nazi Vichy regime, as ``to make money and to serve the
enemy.''
	   In 1941, Vichy officials passed a series of anti-Jewish laws
banning Jews from many professions and ordering the liquidation of
all Jewish-owned real estate and businesses, large and small. About
7,000 agents handled the so-called ``aryanization'' process.
	   The proceeds went into state coffers, with agents taking a 10
percent commission, but sometimes much more.
	   The revelations come amid heated criticism of France in
Washington this week for what some call half-hearted efforts to
find the rightful owners of some 2,000 unclaimed art works, looted
by the Nazis and now held in French museums.
	   Stung by such charges, the government last year created a
commission to study the issue of wartime Jewish assets. The
Matteoli Commission has not seen the newly revealed documents, Le
Parisien said, and its final report _ scheduled by 2000 _ may be
incomplete.
	   A member of the Matteoli Commission, speaking to The Associated
Press on condition of anonymity, confirmed it had not reviewed the
documents, and added that an exhaustive anaylsis of wartime
archives was impossible.
	   The documents contain the private correspondence of a Resistance
leader ``Professor Terroine,'' who went on to head the restitution
service in 1946. But he quickly ran into a wall of protest.
	   One high-ranking local official from Alsace-Lorraine, quoted by
Le Parisien, wrote to Terroine urging him to stop the
investigation.
	   In the letter, Georges Tessier defended the agents, saying they
``acted in good faith, like father figures.''
	   ``They shouldn't be hauled in as if they'd made money
illegally,'' he wrote.
	   Terroine quit in 1947 and the service dissolved.
	   Another document fingers a bank employee in the city of
Clermont-Ferrand who appropriated shares of stock after learning
its owners had been exterminated in Nazi death camps.
	   And a box of archives contained detailed information about
diamonds, gold bars, watches and wedding rings seized by the Nazis
in Marseilles.
	   American troops later returned the goods to France, but
according to the documents, ``the government did not identify their
rightful owners and kept the booty,'' Le Parisien wrote.
	   (ma-parf-jn) 	   
</TEXT>
