<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Hemp Shop </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police raid store selling hemp products
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Police on Thursday raided a shop selling
hemp merchandise in the latest step in a crackdown on stores
selling items from the European Union-subsidized crop.
	   Police also detained the shop owner, Yuli Kalofolia, but did not
immediately charge her with any crime.
	   Owners of the Greek chain, known as Kannabishop, appear to be
fighting a losing battle to sell products manufactured from
industrial hemp, including clothing, beauty products, shoe
polishes, furniture oils, cough lozenges and building insulation.
They do not sell drug paraphernalia.
	   Industrial hemp, or Cannabis sativa, is a cousin of the
marijuana plant. It contains only traces of tetrahydrocannabinol,
or THC, the substance that makes pot smokers high.
	   Hemp production is legal in nearly all EU states and is heavily
subsidized by the 15-nation bloc. Greece's commerce ministry not
only freely allows its import, but the agriculture ministry has
been considering its introduction as a cash crop.
	   In the past month, police have raided more than half the 15
Kannabishop stores around Greece, seized merchandise and charged
some of the owners on felony counts of promoting narcotics use.
	   Prosecutors supporting the crackdown claim the industrial hemp
shops indirectly promote drug use.
	   (pq-bm) 	   
</TEXT>
