<HEADLINE>
Dollar firms after European rate cuts, gold down
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with afternoon rates &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The U.S. dollar firmed in European trading
Thursday afternoon following a round of interest rate cuts by the
11 countries which will launch Europe's new single currency next
year.
	   Gold was lower.
	   Ten of the 11 countries adopting the euro _ including Germany,
France, and the Netherlands _ dropped their interest rate to 3
percent. Italy dropped to 3.5 percent from 4 percent.
	   Dollar rates compared with late Wednesday:
	   _1.6745 German marks, up from 1.6733
	   _118.85 Japanese yen, down from 120.59
	   _1.3695 Swiss francs, up from 1.3694
	   _5.6175 French francs, up from 5.6102
	   _1.8876 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8857
	   _1,658.25 Italian lire, up from 1,656.50
	   _1.5337 Canadian dollars, down from 1.5362
	   The British pound was quoted at dlrs 1.6613, up from dlrs
1.6588.
	   Switzerland and Britain are not part of the European currency.
	   Gold dealers in London fixed a recommended price of dlrs 292.95
bid per troy ounce at midmorning, down from dlrs 293.70 on
Wednesday.
	   In Zurich the bid price was dlrs 292.50, down from dlrs 294.00.
	   Gold fell 90 cents in Hong Kong to dlrs 293.35.
	   Silver opened in London at dlrs 4.65 bid per troy ounce, down
from dlrs 4.77.
	   (rb)
