w2067 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Lithuania-StalinistMa     12-03 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lithuania-Stalinist Massacre </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ex-agents found guilty of Stalinist-era murders
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VILNIUS, Lithuania (AP) - In the first conviction under
Lithuania's broad genocide law, three former agents of the Soviet
NKVD were found guilty Thursday of killing a family of four in
1945.
	   The three were serving in a unit of the NKVD, a predecessor of
the KGB, when they burned down a house in the village of Saliniu
and killed four of its inhabitants, including a pregnant woman.
	   The killing took place a year after the Soviet takeover of
Lithuania, when the NKVD was brutally suppressing dissent.
	   One of those convicted, 76-year-old Kiril Kurakin, was sentenced
to six years in prison. Petras Bartasevicius and Juozas Sakalys,
both 75, were handed three-and-a-half year sentences. The court
also ordered that all their property be confiscated.
	   After sentencing, however, the judge said he would reduce the
prison terms by a third because all three men were partially
physically handicapped.
	   Under Lithuanian law, the killing of Lithuanians by Soviet
functionaries is considered genocide.
	   Prosecutors have also indicted several Lithuanians in the
killings of Jews during the 1941-44 Nazi occupation. But many
Jewish groups accuse Lithuania of not pushing hard enough to
convict and sentence alleged Nazis.
	   Genocide trials against Aleksandras Lileikis and Kazys
Gimzauskas, both in their 90s, were recently postponed pending a
decision about whether they were fit enough for their court cases
to continue.
	   (mt-jh)
</TEXT>
