<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Lords, 2nd Ld - Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tory leader faces rebellion in House of Lords
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: AMs; updates with comment, background &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT BARR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Unwilling to shed blue blood in a hopeless cause,
Britain's hereditary nobles were ready to go quietly from the House
of Lords _ only to get into a fight with the commoner who leads
their party.
	   Conservative Party leader William Hague was caught by surprise
when the Tory leader in the Lords accepted a compromise with Prime
Minister Tony Blair's government to retain some hereditary nobles
in the house during a transition period.
	   ``It was a deal which, if accepted, would mean that the
Conservative party would support the government's changes to the
House of Lords lock, stock and barrel,'' Hague said Thursday.
	   Hague said he cannot support the abolition of the voting rights
of 759 Lords with inherited titles until the government spells out
how it will choose members in the future. At present, the
aristocrats sit alongside some 500 peers with lifetime titles,
mostly former politicians, in the unelected upper chamber.
	   Blair plans to refer that issue to a commission, while going
ahead with the eviction of most of the hereditary members.
	   Given the government's large majority in the House of Commons,
Hague conceded he was bound to lose the fight. ``But that does not
mean that the Conservative Party has to withdraw its objections,''
Hague said in a radio interview Thursday.
	   A day earlier he had dismissed Lord Cranborne as Conservative
leader in the Lords. Cranborne, one of the Cecil family who have
been politically prominent since the Elizabethan age, confessed
that he had behaved ``like an ill-trained spaniel'' by going behind
Hague's back.
	   Cranborne's deputy, Lord Fraser of Carmyllie, resigned on
Thursday _ ``disgusted and appalled'' that Hague had sacked
Cranborne. Three more Conservative leaders in the Lords _ Lord
Bowness, Lord Pilkington and the Earl of Home _ resigned later in
the day.
	   The Conservatives' infighting, ultimately, is only a sideshow.
By a long-settled convention and by law, a government that promised
to do something before an election gets its way.
	   At most, the Conservatives could have delayed the Lords reform
for one year. The falling out between Hague and Cranborne, and the
Lords' evident distaste for a fight, is likely to make the
government's task easier.
	   For the young and struggling Conservative leader, the ruckus is
partly about stamping his authority on a party dispirited by its
disastrous defeat a year ago.
	   ``It is my job to rebuild my party ... with some discipline, and
when people behave without authority in that way, I'm afraid they
have to go,'' said Hague, 37, who became leader last year.
	   Cranborne's deal called for 91 of the hereditary peers to remain
in the House of Lords until there was agreement on a new method of
selection. Some members of the Labor Party have been pressing for
an elected upper house.
	   The Conservatives' position was not entirely clear. Hague said
he accepted the government's concession on the 91 hereditary peers,
but would not promise to abstain from opposing the legislation.
	   The government's leader in the Lords, Baroness Jay, said the
deal was off unless the Conservatives kept their end of the
bargain.
	   Cranborne argued that saving a few seats was better than
nothing.
	   ``There are purists who feel it is more honorable to die like
James IV at Flodden Field in 1513,'' Cranborne said. ``But the
difficulty about dying is that you are dead.''
	   (rb-mj)
</TEXT>
