<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-IMF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukraine's president hopeful about outcome of loan talks with IMF
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukraine's President Leonid Kuchma voiced
hope Thursday that the government would win a delayed tranche of a
dlrs 2.2 billion loan during negotiations with an International
Monetary Fund delegation.
	   An IMF mission arrived in Ukraine on Tuesday for a four-day
visit to check whether this former Soviet republic was meeting
conditions for further disbursement of the three-year loan approved
in September.
	   Kuchma said the negotiations in Kiev were proceeding
``normally,'' and said he hoped their outcome would be ``successful
for Ukraine.''
	   ``(The IMF) understands our position, and we are making steps to
implement as fully as possible the fund's conditions for the loan
deal,'' Kuchma was quoted as saying by the Interfax news agency.
	   Ukraine so far has received dlrs 335 million of the IMF loan,
but the November tranche was delayed after the fund's previous
delegation to Kiev expressed disapproval over the government's
compliance with the deal.
	   The IMF was worried about the government's persistent failure to
raise enough budget revenues, and sharply criticized proposals to
print money to pay off some government debts.
	   Ukraine badly needs the IMF money to meet its 1999 foreign debt
obligations of more than dlrs 2 billion. Its lending credibility
has been undermined by the economic crisis in neighboring Russia
that scared away most foreign investors.
	   Ukraine's economy, plagued by lack of reforms, has been
declining since the 1991 Soviet collapse.
	   The government is owed more than 9 billion hryvna (dlrs 2.6
billion) in unpaid taxes, while its own debt in unpaid pensions and
wages totals more than 3 billion hryvna (dlrs 875 million).
	   Ukrainian leaders have urged the IMF to soften its lending
conditions, saying the cash-poor country is unlikely to implement
them.
	   (vl/adc)
</TEXT>
