<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkmenistan-Currency </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkmenistan bans most currency trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Turkmenistan has sharply tightened limits on
residents' access to foreign currency in an effort to protect its
dwindling hard currency reserves, a news report said Wednesday.
	   The only people allowed to exchange the Turkmen manat for
foreign currency are: those who need medical treatment outside the
impoverished central Asian nation, and then only with a certificate
from the Health Ministry; students going to school abroad; and
government employees traveling to other countries.
	   Companies operating in Turkmenistan can exchange money only to
buy medicines or raw materials or to repay government loans,
according to a Central Bank statement quoted by the Interfax news
agency.
	   Foreigners in the former Soviet republic can only buy foreign
currency they previously sold to the Central Bank.
	   The bank's hard currency reserve department said the move was
indefinite and was an effort to save the bank's hard currency
reserves, which have been depleted because of a plunge in natural
gas exports and the bank's intervention to keep the manat stable.
	   Turkmenistan's natural gas reserves are among the world's
largest, but revenues from gas exports have been constrained by
non-payment for deliveries by neighboring countries and the lack of
pipelines to access other markets.
	   Turkmenistan has also suffered some fallout from the economic
crisis in Russia.
	   The country inherited a highly specialized economy from the
Soviet period, and has failed to diversify since the 1991 Soviet
collapse or introduce any serious economic reforms.
	   It has also built up a huge foreign debt _ 75 percent of gross
domestic product, Interfax said.
	   In the absence of a fully convertible currency, the black market
for dollars has flourished.
	   (adc)
</TEXT>
