<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Evacuation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Heating shortages forces families to leave homes in northern
</HEADLINE>
Russia &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ More than 130 families have moved out of their
homes and into office buildings and a military base in Russia's far
northeast due to a lack of heating fuel, a news report said
Thursday.
	   Blizzards and temperatures of minus 25 Celsius (minus 13
Fahrenheit) forced the families out in Cape Schmidt, on the
northern coast of the Chukotka Peninsula, which juts out toward
Alaska, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   The region has been plagued by chronic fuel shortages in recent
years, and last month the government evacuated more than 1,000
people because it was too expensive to supply them with food and
fuel during the winter.
	   The cash-strapped Russian government has been unable to provide
subsidies as the Soviet Union did, and as a result, Chukotka's
population has shrunk by half to 80,000 during this decade.
	   Meanwhile, in the Kamchatka Peninsula, which is south of
Chukotka, a local legislator began a hunger strike to protest the
federal government's failure to deliver fuel and other supplies to
the region.
	   Lawmaker Alexander Ivanov noted that Sergei Shoigu, the minister
for emergency situations, visited the region last month and agreed
to provide urgent help. But Ivanov said conditions have only been
getting worse.
	   Power supplies were cut Wednesday to apartments in the main
city, Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky. Electricity was being supplied only
to hospitals and other places that provide essential services.
	   (gm)
</TEXT>
