<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukraine's top opposition party protests arrest of its leader
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Switzerland-Ukraine-Corruption &QL; 
 &UR; By VIKTOR LUHOVYK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukraine's top opposition party on Thursday
protested the arrest of its controversial leader by Swiss police,
and said the news of his detention was invented by authorities to
diminish the party's position.
	   Pavlo Lazarenko, a former prime minister who now leads the
opposition Hromada party, was arrested by customs officials on the
Swiss-French border Wednesday evening. He was later transferred to
Geneva, where a judge had ordered his arrest.
	   Hromada said in a statement that the information about
Lazarenko's arrest distributed by Ukrainian media Thursday had not
been confirmed and could be seen as ``the latest provocation'' by
authorities who ``are continuing their course aimed at destroying
the opposition and its leaders.''
	   Swiss prosecutors later confirmed the details of the arrest.
	   Lazarenko, who is also a lawmaker in Ukraine's parliament, is at
the center of a corruption probe focusing on his time as prime
minister in 1996-97.
	   Lazarenko's critics have accused him of abusing his authority
for personal gain, in particular reaping huge profits from gas
imports to Ukraine by giving preferential status to private energy
trader Unified Energy Systems (UES).
	   The company recently lost an appeal in Ukraine's Supreme
Arbitration Court over a 1.4 billion hryvna (dlrs 409 million) fine
imposed by tax authorities for evading taxes and illegally
transferring abroad dlrs 690 million received from gas sales.
	   The chief prosecutor's office in Kiev, which is investigating
several charges against Lazarenko, recently asked Swiss police to
assist in tracking down money Lazarenko allegedly illegally stashed
in Swiss banks.
	   Investigations against Lazarenko are under way in several
cantons in Switzerland.
	   The country's influential Neue Zuercher Zeitung newspaper
reported last month that about dlrs 40 million in bank accounts
linked to Lazarenko already had been frozen.
	   Hromada and UES officials say the corruption probe and tax fine
have no grounds and describe the scandal as politically motivated
and organized by President Leonid Kuchma and his close supporters.
Kuchma appointed Lazarenko prime minister and later fired him.
	   Lazarenko recently told the opposition daily Kievskie Vedomosti
that authorities were planning to kill him to get rid of a powerful
opposition leader.
	   ``I've never committed any crimes. Moreover, I never did
anything to deserve killers being sent to me,'' Lazarenko said at
the time.
	   Ukraine's chief prosecutor Mykhailo Potebenko has dismissed any
suggestions of politics in the corruption case.
	   (vl/adc)
</TEXT>
