<SLUG> BC-Russia-Lithuania-Food Aid </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lithuania gives food aid to Russian region
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The first batch of Lithuanian food aid was
delivered Thursday to Russia's Baltic enclave of Kaliningrad to
stave off potential shortages, a news report said.
	   Authorities in Kaliningrad _ which is sandwiched between
Lithuania and Poland _ previously declared an ``emergency
situation'' to make sure the region does not run out of food and
fuel during the winter.
	   The federal government in Moscow insists that Russia has enough
food, but a lack of money has delayed deliveries to outlying
regions. The problem is especially acute in Kaliningrad, which is
cut off from the rest of Russia.
	   Lithuania delivered 100,000 cans of condensed milk, 100,000 cans
of meat, and 40 tons of cheese to Kaliningrad on Thursday, the
Interfax news agency reported.
	   In all, Lithuania plans to provide 220 tons of food worth 3.5
million litai (dlrs 875,000) to the Kaliningrad region, said the
Lithuanian consul in Kaliningrad, Jonas Voronavicius.
	   The food will be distributed among hospitals and kindergartens,
Voronavicius said, according to Interfax.
	   Russia is to receive food aid from the European Union and the
United States worth about dlrs 1 billion this winter.
	   (ad/gm)
</TEXT>
