r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Yeltsin     12-03 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Yeltsin </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin's surgeon: Yeltsin needs to listen to his doctor
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Boris Yeltsin needs to stay in bed to recover from
his latest bout of pneumonia, but the president has a long history
of ignoring the advice of his doctors, the president's heart
surgeon said Thursday.
	   Yeltsin has in the past rushed back to work without fully
recuperating from his ailments, and this has contributed to his
recurring illnesses, doctors have said.
	   The president's aides say Yeltsin is again urging doctors to
discharge him from a government clinic where he remained
hospitalized for a 12th straight day Thursday.
	   Yeltsin must ``fulfill all orders of his doctors as pilots obey
air traffic controllers,'' said Dr. Renat Akchurin, who performed
Yeltsin's heart bypass surgery in 1996.
	   ``I have had pneumonia in my life and I can say that it is not
at all easy to live through the disease,'' Akchurin told the
ITAR-Tass news agency.
	   And Yeltsin was likely to make it even more difficult, Akchurin
said.
	   ``As far as I know the president, he will not stay in bed as
told, but will return to work,'' Akchurin was quoted as saying.
	   Akchurin said he has not examined Yeltsin for eight months, but
believed that the president was not suffering from any heart
problems.
	   Yeltsin's deputy chief of staff Yuri Yarov said that the
president was to remain in the hospital through the end of the
week, but may return to the Kremlin on Monday.
	   Yeltsin has been handling limited paperwork and telephone
conversations in the clinic, the presidential press service has
said.
	   Yeltsin's bout of pneumonia is his second in as many years and
the latest in a long string of illnesses that have diminished the
president's authority and raised doubts about his ability to stay
in office through the end of his term in 2000.
	   Yeltsin's foes in the State Duma, the lower house of parliament,
adopted a non-binding resolution Wednesday demanding the release of
Yeltsin's medical records.
	   Russian law gives parliament no power to make an inquiry into
the president's health, and Yeltsin's envoy to the legislature,
Alexander Kotenkov, quickly dismissed the resolution as having no
legal meaning.
	   ``No one will fulfill the decision made by the house because it
has no legal force,'' he said.
	   (ad/gm)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Russia-Yeltsin; CT:i; 
(REG:PSOV;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
