r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-FoodAid     12-03 0248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Food Aid </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official: Russia to keep close control over food aid
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia intends to keep tight control over food aid
being shipped from the United States and the European Union, a top
agriculture official said Thursday.
	   Past aid deals have been tainted by corruption, and U.S.
officials have said they stressed in their negotiations with Russia
that they wanted to avoid any hint of scandal in the aid program
this winter.
	   In an interview with the Interfax news agency, First Deputy Food
and Agriculture Minister Alexei Gordeyev said strict guidelines
have been drafted for the companies allowed to bid on contracts to
deliver the aid.
	   Wholly state-owned companies will be given preference, he said,
and other companies must be at least 20 percent state-held and have
at least one government representative on their board of directors.
	   The bidders also must not have any debts to the government, and
must have at least three years' experience in buying and supplying
food, Gordeyev said.
	   A government commission will send tender offers to more than 10
Russian companies considered to be potential distributors of the
aid.
	   The Russian government has tentatively agreed to food aid deals
with the United States and the European Union valued at at a total
of roughly dlrs 1 billion. There have been concerns that some
Russians could go hungry this winter as a result of a poor grain
harvest and the country's economic crisis.
	   (ml/adc)
</TEXT>
