w2105 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-IronFelix     12-03 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Iron Felix </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Deputy mayor: Moscow may restore statue of secret police chief
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Moscow's deputy mayor said the city will restore a
statue of a dreaded Soviet secret police chief if parliament
formalizes its request to do so, news reports said Thursday.
	   The Communist-dominated State Duma, the lower house of
parliament, voted 237-69 on Wednesday to give tentative approval to
a resolution asking the Moscow city government to return the statue
of Felix Dzerzhinsky to the spot it occupied for decades in front
of the old KGB headquarters.
	   ``If the State Duma makes a final decision of restoring to
monument to Felix Dzerzhinsky, then the government of Moscow, as
executive power, will fulfill that decision,'' said Moscow Deputy
Mayor Valery Shantsev, according to reports by the Interfax news
agency and the daily Segodnya.
	   However, the Moscow city parliament must also approve the plan,
according to city laws, Segodnya reported.
	   ``What monument will stand on Lubyanka Square may be decided
only by Muscovites, through their representatives in the city
Duma,'' deputy speaker of the city's legislature Alexander Krutov
was quoted as saying.
	   Communists have significantly less weight in the Moscow city
parliament than in its national counterpart, and the city
legislature is likely to block the decision to restore the statue.
	   Moscow's powerful Mayor Yuri Luzhkov has so far kept silent on
the issue. In the past, Luzhkov did not exhibit particular
Communist sympathies. But the populist mayor is a leading potential
contender in Russia's next presidential elections in 2000, and
recently has seemed to be courting some of the country's many
hard-liners.
	   The towering bronze statue of ``Iron Felix,'' head of the Cheka,
the first Soviet secret police, was a landmark during the Soviet
era. It was toppled by pro-democracy protesters in 1991 and has
since languished with other Soviet-era statues in a city park.
	   Human rights activists have denounced the proposal to restore
the statue, saying Dzerzhinsky was a symbol of murderous repression
during the Soviet era.
	   Dzerzhinsky headed the secret police after the Bolshevik
Revolution and oversaw the ruthless crackdowns on political
opponents.
	   Lubyanka Square, where the statue stood, is used by human rights
groups for vigils to honor the millions of victims of Soviet rule.
Relatives of victims whose remains were never found use the square
as a gravesite, bringing flowers every year.
	   (ad/adc)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
