w2108 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-BadShot     12-03 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Bad Shot </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security agent convicted of shooting at subordinate
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A senior Russian intelligence officer has been
convicted of badly wounding his subordinate while shooting at a
glass placed on top of his head, news reports said Thursday.
	   The incident happened several months ago when a young agent
asked Lt. Col. Vladimir Popov, the head of the Federal Security
Service branch in the Evenkia region of central Siberia, to send
him on a mission to some of Russia's more volatile regions. The
Federal Security Service, or FSB, is the main successor to the
Soviet KGB.
	   Popov, who was drunk at the time, said he should test the
officer first. He placed a glass on his head, took out his service
pistol and opened fire. After the first shot, the agent asked Popov
to stop and test somebody else.
	   Popov ignored his plea and the next bullet ricocheted from the
wall into the agent's head, badly wounding him. The young officer
has become an invalid and had to quit the service, the daily
Kommersant reported.
	   Facing a military court in the Siberian city of Krasnoyarsk on
Wednesday, Popov said he regretted his action but insisted he was
an excellent marksman and wounded his subordinate by accident.
	   The court sentenced Popov to 2 1/2 years in prison and ordered
him to pay his subordinate 30,000 rubles (dlrs 1,600) in damage.
The reports did not give the younger officer's name.
	   Shootings, suicides and other fatal accidents have become
increasingly common in the cash-strapped and demoralized Russian
military and security services.
	   Kommersant quoted military prosecutors as saying that FSB
officials are trying to hush up most of the incidents. ``Only the
most notorious cases usually become known,'' it said.
	   Last month, prosecutors in the Ural Mountains city of
Chelyabinsk launched criminal proceedings against three FSB
officers who detained a local man on suspicion of having a forged
passport and put him in the trunk of their car.
	   The agents were allegedly drunk and forgot about the man,
driving around in temperatures of -30 degrees C (-22 F). The man
nearly froze to death before they finally remembered he was there.
	   Another FSB officer in Chelyabinsk was recently stabbed to death
by his 19-year-old son when he was harassing his family while
drunk, police said.
	   There were no immediate comments Thursday from FSB officials.
	   (vi/adc)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
