<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Million Dollar Challenge, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Price takes lead in first round of Million Dollar Challenge
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quotes, Woods result; ADDS byline; no pickup;
CORRECTS lead sequence &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photo &QL; 
 &UR; By DANIEL WAKIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SUN CITY, South Africa (AP) _ Nick Price of Zimbabwe, fighting
off swirling winds on one of his favorite courses, took a two-shot
lead Thursday with a five-under 67 at the Million Dollar Challenge.
	   The defending champion at the Gary Player Country Club was two
shots up on a three-way logjam of double Major winner Mark O'Meara,
Justin Leonard and Germany's Bernhard Langer. South African
hometown hero Ernie Els -- a seven-time veteran of the challenge
and seeking his first win -- was a shot back at 70.
	   Tiger Woods was level at 72 in the field of 12 of the world's
top golfers, vying for the largest single check in golf.
	   Price had six birdies in his round, picking up shots at the
par-5 2nd, the short 7th, par-5 10th and 14th before finishing
back-to-back birdies on No. 17 and 18, both par 4.
	   ``This course likes me,'' said Price, also winner in 1993 with a
record 24-under par. ``It makes me focus a lot more than I do
normally.''
	   Unusually strong, shifting winds, more Scottish style than
African, caused some of the players to guess on the right club, he
said.
	   Price is coming off his third win at the Zimbabwe Open in four
years, closing with a Royal Harare-record 9-under-par 63 for a
five-stroke victory.
	   ``This is a game of momentum. No doubt about it,'' he said.
	   O'Meara, named U.S. player of the year last week and holder of
the U.S. Masters and British Open titles, reached 4-under to share
the lead on the 14th in the two-ball ahead of Price. He surrendered
the spot when Price birdied No. 14 and O'Meara made his second
bogey of a five-birdie round on No. 15.
	   In his first round of African golf, Woods birdied on the 2nd,
10th, 12th, 16th and 17th, but went a stroke over par on four other
holes. He said he felt in better form than two months ago. ``I'm
very pleased with the way I'm striking the ball,'' he said. ``It
feels like I'm making progress.''
	   Woods said playing in South Africa had special meaning for him
as ``a person of color.''
	   ``To play golf in Africa, particularly South Africa -- it's
something I've wanted to do,'' he said.
	   Els came out blazing on the first four holes, with birdies on
each. But he made bogey on numbers 6, 11 and 17 against a solitary
birdie on the 10th.
	   ``It was really a long course out there today,'' he said of the
layout that had been battered by heavy rain.
	   The final round is Sunday at the 7,597-yard (6,947-meter),
par-72 course. Prize money totals dlrs 2.57 million.
	   (str/djw) 	   
</TEXT>
