<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Terrorism Memorial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
France unveils memorial to terrorism victims
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos PAR101-2 &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE CHAVRANSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ French President Jacques Chirac on Thursday
unveiled a memorial dedicated to the victims of terrorism, on the
second anniversary of a bombing at a Paris train station in which
four people died.
	   The bronze tribute stands in a garden near the gold-domed Hotel
des Invalides, where Napoleon is entombed. It depicts an abstract
human form cradling its severed head. Water flows at its feet.
	   ``The struggle (against terrorism) is, and will always be,
without mercy,'' Chirac told a group of about 200 people, including
many survivors of the Dec. 3, 1996 bombing of Paris' Port Royal
station.
	   Some 170 others were injured in the attack which remains
unsolved. Authorities have long suspected Muslim extremists who
waged a 1995 bombing campaign in France that killed eight people,
but have been unable to make a direct connection.
	   The group S.O.S. Terrorism commissioned the memorial by Nicolas
Alquin. Francoise Rudetzki, the group's president and herself a
victim of a 1980s bombing in Paris, said she hoped the sculpture
would enable people to confront loss and to begin mourning.
	   Some people in the crowd were in tears. One man, a former
hostage in Lebanon, Jean-Paul Kauffmann, strayed from the crowd,
listening to the dedication from under the branches of a tree.
	   After the dedication, survivors and family members addressed the
group. Dominique Brocheriou, whose sister died in a 1995 bombing in
the St. Michel metro station, urged listeners not to be afraid to
speak to victims' families.
	   ``We must continue to talk about her,'' Brocheriou said. In a
memorial booklet, she wrote a tribute to her sister, giving advice
for those who have lost family members.
	   ``Nobody talks about her anymore,'' she wrote. ``Death and those
who have died have become taboo. But I can't bear that.''
	   (parf-ad-ip)
</TEXT>
