<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Fugitive Banana, 1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Zimbabwe demanding return of Banana after sodomy conviction
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo JOH103
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with Zimbabwe demanding Banana's return; No Pick Up
 &UR; By PAT REBER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ A Zimbabwe official said
Thursday his country would demand the return of a former president
convicted of sodomy after the fugitive, Canaan Banana, met with
President Nelson Mandela in Pretoria.
	   Banana, titular president of Zimbabwe from 1980 to 1987, was
convicted last week of sodomy and homosexual assault. He had been
free on bail and fled Zimbabwe for neighboring Botswana shortly
before his conviction.
	   It is not clear when he arrived in South Africa.
	   ``We want Banana back, that is our requirement,'' said George
Charamba, spokesman for President Robert Mugabe, in the Zimbabwe
capital of Harare.
	   Banana met the South African president Wednesday in Pretoria at
Mandela's official residence, Mandela's spokesman Parks Mankahlana
told The Associated Press.
	   Banana requested the meeting, but did not indicate he would seek
asylum or residence in South Africa, Mankahlana said.
	   Zimbabwe has strict laws against homosexuality and sodomy, but
South Africa's highest court in October struck down apartheid-era
laws banning homosexual relations.
	   ``This is a very sensitive matter,'' said Mankahlana. ``South
Africa and Zimbabwe have adopted totally different approaches to
this issue (of homosexual sex). What is considered unlawful in
Zimbabwe is not considered unlawful in South Africa.''
	   In Zimbabwe, Charamba said his government had not been informed
of the meeting with Mandela. Mankahlana said the meeting took place
with full knowledge of the Zimbabwe government.
	   Zimbabwe has no extradition treaty with South Africa but
criminals have been exchanged by non-binding mutual agreement.
	   A demand for Banana's hand over could put the two countries on a
collision course. South Africa's courts would likely reject any
extradition request for crimes that are not punishable under South
African law, said Paul Setsetse, spokesman for Justice Minister
Dullah Omar.
	   ``This man has not broken any laws in South Africa,'' Mankahlana
told APTN.
	   He dismissed suggestions the issue would add tension to
relations between the two countries. Mandela has objected to
Mugabe's sending arms and troops to back Congolese President
Laurent Kabila in his fight against a rebel incursion.
	   Mugabe has launched a campaign against homosexuality, describing
same-sex partners as ``lower than pigs and dogs.''
	   Banana, a 62-year-old Methodist minister, was convicted on Nov.
26 in Harare of 11 counts of sodomy and homosexual assault. While
he was president, he allegedly threatened his bodyguards, a cook
and a gardener with their jobs unless they performed homosexual
acts.
	   Banana was brought to trial after a police inspector who worked
as his bodyguard killed a colleague who had taunted him for his
alleged relationship with the former president.
	   In his defense during a three-week trial in June, Banana said
the charges were an attempt to destroy his character and standing
amid rumors he was planning a political comeback.
	   Sentencing for Banana has been scheduled for Dec. 10 in Harare.
He faces a possible maximum jail term of 22 years.
	   (pr-aos)
</TEXT>
