<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Bank privatized </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government privatizes first state-owned bank
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ The Romanian Bank for Development
became the first Romanian bank to turn private when France's
Societe Generale de France won the bid for a majority stake,
privatization authorities said Thursday.
	   Details of the deal will be announced next week, said Radu
Sarbu, head of the State Ownership Fund, the Romanian privatization
agency.
	   According to initial plans, the government was offering a 51
percent stake in the bank, conditional on the investor agreeing to
raise the bank's capital by 20 percent to 50 percent.
	   Romania's government wants at least dlrs 600 million from the
sale. The bank is the country's fourth-largest state-owned bank,
and had a net profit of dlrs 100 million last year.
	   Societe Generale is one of France's big retail lenders and has
operations worldwide.
	   The Banque Nationale de Paris SA also made a bid, but Sarbu said
its offer was less interesting.
	   The International Monetary Fund, which is expected to resume
negotiations for a new stand-by loan for Romania in January, has
conditioned further loans on the privatization of banks.
	   The IMF suspended a dlrs 430 million loan for the country in
May, due to political bickering and an economic crisis.
	   The agreement with IMF is badly needed to help the government
pay off dlrs 2.2 billion of foreign debts next year.
	   Analysts said the sale of some state banks and the reform of the
others would help solve the country's antiquated, underfinanced and
inefficient banking system.
	   (dj/ma/am/scl)
</TEXT>
