</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Estonia-Russia Talks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Estonian-Russian talks begin in Tallinn
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TALLINN, Estonia (AP) - Rare, high-level talks between Estonia
and Russia began Thursday in Tallinn and were expected to focus on
disputes between the countries.
	   The discussions, the highest-level talks between the countries
in years, are being headed by Russian Deputy Prime Minister
Valentina Matviyenko and Estonian Prime Minister Mart Siimann.
	   Matviyenko said she hoped the discussions would lead to improved
relations.
	   ``We're interested in the harmonious development of relations,
where one would arrive, step by step, at solutions to problems that
have emerged,'' she was quoted by the Baltic News Service as
saying.
	   After the breakup of the Soviet Union, relations between the two
countries have often been strained. Moscow has accused Estonia of
discriminating against its large Russian-speaking minority, while
Tallinn says Russia is still playing the role of regional bully.
	   Estonia has also angered the Kremlin by seeking membership in
NATO alliance, which Russia says would threaten its own security
interests.
	   Relations have also been strained over a failure to sign a
treaty fixing the countries' border.
	   While Estonia has largely reoriented its trade to the West,
Russia still accounts for more than 10 percent of Estonia's total
trade. At the two-days of talks, Tallinn is also expected to push
for a reduction of high Russian tariffs on imports from Estonia.
	   (mt-jh)
</TEXT>
