w2140 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mexico-ToxicDumping     12-03 0287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Toxic Dumping,0291 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Greenpeace says Pemex dumped toxic waste in wetlands
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Greenpeace has filed a criminal complaint
against Mexico's oil monopoly Pemex, accusing it of dumping
thousands of gallons of toxic waste in wetlands along Mexico's Gulf
coast.
	   The environmental group described one incident Aug. 10 in the
town of Ixhuatlan, in which it said villagers saw a truck owned by
a Pemex contractor dumping 16 53-gallon (200-liter) drums of toxic
waste into a pond, Mexican newspapers reported Thursday.
	   According to the complaint, the driver said the company had been
dumping waste in the same place for two weeks, totaling 11,600
gallons (44,000 liters). Greenpeace also named the contractor, J
and M Industrial Construction, in the complaint.
	   None of the newspapers specified what the toxic waste was.
	   Greenpeace spokesman Alejandro Calvillo demanded that health
officials check residents of nearby villages to see how the toxic
waste was affecting them.
	   He said Pemex _ as the oil monopoly Petroleos Mexicanos is
commonly known _ had set up more than 60 such dumping sites in the
state of Veracruz. The sites were on land expropriated by the
government for Pemex to build access roads, pipelines and dams _
but not to dump waste.
	   ``Company employees were caught in the act,'' the daily The News
quoted Calvillo as saying. ``Authorities must stop behaving as
accomplices of Pemex, which is without doubt the top environmental
criminal in Mexico.''
	   Calvillo said Pemex, which takes in nearly a third of the
Mexican government's income, has long been considered above the
law.
	   A Pemex spokeswoman said Thursday the company had no comment.
</TEXT>
