<SLUG> BC-Russia-US-Slain Lawmaker </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US congresswoman suggests Nobel prize for slain Russian lawmaker
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A U.S. congresswoman suggested Thursday that a
prominent Russian liberal lawmaker recently shot to death be
nominated for a Nobel Peace Prize.
	   Marcy Kaptur, a Democrat from Ohio who is visiting Moscow, said
members of the U.S. Congress considered Galina Starovoitova ``a
sister in liberty and an outspoken advocate for the democratic rule
of law and human rights,'' the Interfax news agency reported.
	   Kaptur said that if Starovoitova wins the peace prize
posthumously, some of the winnings should be used to support
democratic reforms in Russia.
	   Since Soviet times, Starovoitova had been a staunch defender of
political and market reforms and human rights, and she traveled
often to the United States for speaking and teaching engagements.
	   She was killed Nov. 20 in her apartment building in St.
Petersburg. Police have announced no major breakthroughs in the
case, but many believe the motive was political and may have been
connected to an upcoming local election.
	   (adc)
