w2152 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Bosnia-WarCrimes 1stLd-Writethru   12-03 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-War Crimes, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top general instigated executions of thousands, indictment says
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS throughout to ADD reaction from Srebrenica
survivors; UPDATES with Krstic's arrival in The Hague. TRIMS. &QL; 
 &UR; By JENIFER CHAO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ Survivors of the Bosnian war's
worst massacre expressed joy Thursday that a top Serb military
leaders charged with orchestrating the killings would soon stand
trial for genocide.
	   Gen. Radislav Krstic, indicted on U.N. charges that he and
others guided the soldiers who massacred thousands of Muslims and
dumped them in mass graves, was arrested by U.S. members of the
NATO peacekeeping force on Wednesday.
	   He arrived late Thursday in The Hague, where the Yugoslav war
crimes tribunal will try him for genocide, war crimes, crimes
against humanity and grave breaches of the Geneva Conventions.
	   Krstic is the most senior Bosnian Serb military figure yet to be
arrested for U.N. trial on genocide and war crimes charges. An
arraignment date has not been set.
	   Details of his indictment _ unsealed and made public Thursday _
allege that offenses allegedly committed by his troops occurred
following the rebel Serb takeover of the U.N. so-called ``safe
haven'' of Srebrenica in eastern Bosnia in July 1995.
	   According to the indictment, forces under Krstic and Bosnian
Serb wartime military chief Gen. Ratko Mladic ``either expelled or
killed'' most of the members of the Bosnian Muslim population of
the Srebrenica enclave, using automatic weapons, hand grenades and
other weaponry.
	   In Sarajevo, survivors of the Srebrenica massacre applauded
Krstic's arrest.
	   ``Since July 13, 1995, I've never felt happiness in my heart,''
Kada Hotic told The Associated Press, referring to the date the
Serbs overran the town. ``Last night when I heard he was arrested,
I felt happy.''
	   Another survivor, Munira Subasic, said she hoped Krstic ``will
give answers to where are our relatives, our children.''
	   Krstic planned and assisted in the ``preparation or execution of
a planned and organized mass execution of thousands of captured
Bosnian Muslim men,'' reads the indictment, which was issued in
October. It had been kept secret so he wouldn't be prompted to
flee.
	   The killings, described in the indictment as ``wide-scale and
organized,'' allegedly occurred in several locations in and around
the enclave, including a warehouse and schools.
	   Soldiers under Krstic's command used heavy equipment to bury the
victims in mass graves. When the international community learned of
the killings, Krstic and his units dug up the bodies and
transferred them to other graves, the indictment alleges.
	   Krstic, who held the rank of general-major during the Srebrenica
operation, is believed to be a close associate of Mladic and former
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic.
	   Both Karadzic and Mladic _ the tribunal's top two suspects _
also have been indicted on genocide charges for allegedly
orchestrating the massacres at Srebrenica. Both remain at large.
	   Krstic was the ninth war crimes suspect to be arrested in the
former Yugoslavia by international forces.
	   The tribunal was established in 1993 by the U.N. Security
Council to prosecute genocide and war crimes stemming from the
armed clashes in the breakup of the former Yugoslavia.
	   (jc/bk)
</TEXT>
