<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-England-SAfrica </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
England bids to foil Springboks 18-win record
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT MILLWARD &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ This time last year, England halted New Zealand's
streak of 11 straight wins in 1997 by gaining a draw at Twickenham.
	   Now Lawrence Dallaglio's team aims to stop South Africa from
setting a world record of 18 wins in a row.
	   The Springboks arrive at Twickenham saying all they want to do
is beat the English. But the big prize is achieving a Grand Slam
sweep of all British Isles nations _ having already beaten Wales,
Scotland and Ireland _ and improving on the 17-match winning streak
it now shares with New Zealand.
	   ``The world record is not as important as beating England,''
South African coach Nick Mallett said in a bid to take his players'
minds off the streak.
	   ``We cannot afford to lose any game and we will not class this
as a successful tour if we don't beat England,'' he said. ``A world
record and a Grand Slam is just an addendum to winning this game.''
	   South Africa needs little motivation for this match and has the
players capable of teaching England a lesson in fast-handling,
all-action rugby.
	   Fly half Henry Honiball is in standout form with his visionary
play, long passes and tactical kicking, and speedy back row forward
Bobby Skinstad is emerging as one of the best runners, handlers and
tacklers in the game.
	   Toronto-born Christian Stewart, who played 14 times for Canada
before switching to South Africa where he was raised, is part of a
fast, well-organized three-quarter line. Scrum half Joost van der
Westhuizen will become only the second South African, after lock
forward Mark Andrews, to make 50 international appearances.
	   The Springboks, who defend their World Cup title next year, are
expected to beat England. But the All Blacks were favored to do the
same in early December last year and were held 26-26 after trailing
20-3.
	   England has the power and the expertise to surprise South Africa
on Saturday. The problem is, the English are not playing well.
	   They struggled to beat Italy in a World Cup qualifying game last
month. Last week, they lost 12-11 to below-strength Australia,
despite scoring the only try of the match.
	   Coach Clive Woodward knows his players are underperforming as he
tries to get them tuned for the upcoming Five Nations championship
and the World Cup next October.
	   Roared on by 75,000 fans at Twickenham, however, England could
rise to the occasion and beat the South Africans, who are at the
end of a gruelling tour.
	   The Springboks will field an unchanged team if hooker Grant
Dalton shakes off a hamstring injury. The big contest of the match
will be between the two back rows _ Johan Erasmus, Skinstad and
team captain Gary Teichman against England captain Dallaglio, Neil
Back and Richard Hill.
	   The same England back row played against New Zealand last year
and Hill and Dallaglio both scored tries. Tim Rodber replaces
Garath Archer at second row in the only change in the pack from
that game.
	   Behind the scrum, however, only center Phil de Glanville keeps
his place. The rest are all changed from 12 months ago, with South
African-born Mike Catt returning to fly half, Jeremy Guscott back
at center, Tony Underwood on the right and Dan Luger replacing
Austin Healey on the left wing.
	   Dallaglio saluted the Springboks' achievement at winning 17 in a
row but said that was a huge motivation for his team to stop it
going any further.
	   ``Equalling New Zealand's record of 17 is a fantastic
achievement, given the caliber of the opposition and the fact that
the bulk of their matches have been away from home,'' the England
captain said.
	   ``They have played all the top sides in the world and I am sure
that if they beat us they will think that they can extend the
record through the 20 mark at the start of their season.
	   ``But we don't need any other motivation than the fact that we
are playing the world champions and want to end a disappointing
year on a memorable high.''
	   Lineups:
	   England _ Nick Beal; Tony Underwood, Phil de Glanville, Jeremy
Guscott, Dan Luger; Mike Catt, Matt Dawson; Jason Leonard, Richard
Cockerill, Darren Garforth, Martin Johnson, Tim Rodber, Lawrence
Dallaglio (captain), Neil Black, Richard Hill.
	   South Africa _ Percy Montgomery; Stefan Terblanche, Andre
Snyman, Christian Stewart, Pieter Rossouw; Henry Honiball, Joost
van der Westhuizen; Adrian Garvey, James Dalton, Robbie Kempson,
Mark Andrews, Krynauw Otto, Johan Erasmus, Bobby Skinstad, Gary
Teichmann (captain).
	   (rjm) 	   
</TEXT>
