<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Train Accident,0169 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Train derails in western India, 8 killed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ A high-speed train jumped the tracks in
western India on Thursday, killing eight people and injuring 42 in
the latest in a series of railroad accidents.
	   Eleven cars of the Kurla-Howrah Express tumbled over the tracks
near the town of Jalgaon in Maharashtra state, Press Trust of India
said. Details of the accident were sketchy but the domestic news
agency quoted officials as saying five cars were badly damaged.
	   At least 211 people died last week when the Sealdah Express
collided with the Frontier Mail near Khanna in the state of Punjab.
	   On Wednesday, a passenger train derailed just as a freight train
was passing by in the western state of Rajasthan. No one was
injured.
	   India has around 300 accidents a year on its railways, the
largest rail network under one management in the world. Three years
ago, a train slammed into a stationary train, killing 358 people.
</TEXT>
