w2184 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Lebanon-Government     12-03 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Government,0385 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lebanon's Hariri dispels rumors he was ousted premier
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BEI101,102 &QL; 
 &UR; By SAM F. GHATTAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Outgoing Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri said in his farewell remarks Thursday that the ``painful''
decision to quit was his own and denied he was ousted in a
political coup.
	   Hariri declined to form a government after what appeared to be a
power struggle with the new president, Emile Lahoud.
	   On Wednesday, Lahoud appointed Salim Hoss, a U.S.-educated
economist, to become Lebanon's next prime minister after a majority
of the 128-member Parliament expressed support for him.
	   Hoss spent Thursday discussing with legislators the makeup of
his Cabinet, which is expected to be formed early next week.
	   Rumors, fueled by Hariri's sudden and surprise departure,
suggested that the premier may have lost a power struggle to the
assertive Lahoud, the 62-year-old army commander who was
unanimously elected president by Parliament in October and took
office Nov. 24.
	   But at a news conference Thursday, Hariri, who had been certain
to be renamed as prime minister, said he bowed out because of what
he described was the president's violation of constitutional rules
in naming him as premier.
	   When Lahoud first asked legislators who they wanted as prime
minister, 31 of 128 lawmakers declined to name a candidate and
effectively gave their vote to the president. Lahoud named Hariri,
who had been backed by 83 legislators.
	   Hariri said it was wrong to ``put the president in a position
where he can be part'' of the political bargaining.
	   However, experts say the constitutional clause on which Hariri
bases his argument is open to interpretation.
	   Lahoud had initially been inclined to re-appoint Hariri, the
billionaire businessman who had been prime minister since 1992.
	   As the architect of the multibillion dollar drive to rebuild the
country from the devastation of the 1975-90 civil war, Hariri is
credited with restoring economic confidence and attracting new
investment to Lebanon.
	   Hoss, in his acceptance speech Wednesday, sought to calm fears
that Hariri's departure would undermine the reconstruction program
or devalue the currency.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Lebanon-Government; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
