<HEADER>
w2195 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Jordan-Prayers     12-03 0206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Jordan-Prayers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jordanians beseech God for rain
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo AMM-102-103

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordan's prime minister and thousands of
other citizens prayed for rain Thursday as a drought threatened
crops in this desert kingdom.
	   Muslim clerics had called for nationwide prayers in the belief
that God will grant rain if one asks for His forgiveness. Women,
children and animals usually take part in the ceremony in order to
beseech God to be merciful for their sake.
	   In Amman, about 1,500 people took part in the prayers, including
Prime Minister Fayez Tarawneh and senior security officials, at an
empty lot on the city's outskirts.
	   Thousands more people attended similar prayer ceremonies in
other towns, the state-run Petra News Agency reported.
	   ``I am here to ask forgiveness from God and beg him to bring us
rain,'' said housewife Fayzeh Khalil after finishing her prayers in
Amman.
	   Rainfall constitutes two thirds of the water supply in Jordan.
	   Israel, Jordan's western neighbor, pumped water to the country
in 1996 when it was suffering an acute drought after successive dry
winters.
	   The Weather Department has warned that this year's drought could
kill crops.
 &UR; jjh-jbm
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Jordan-Prayers; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
