r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CostaRica-PrisonRiot     12-03 0203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Costa Rica-Prison Riot,0206 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Inmates riot in Costa Rica's main prison
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) _ Inmates rioted in Costa Rica's main
prison Thursday after guards killed a prisoner and wounded six as
they tried to escape.
	   Riot police, carrying shields and launching tear gas, stormed La
Reforma prison in northeastern San Jose early Thursday to end the
uprising of 500 inmates.
	   At least 25 prisoners identified as leaders of the riot were
transferred to other prisons, Channel 6 television reported.
	   The riot began after guards foiled the escape attempt. The
inmates dug a tunnel under a wall, and guards opened fire as they
tried to run, said Justice Minister Monica Nagel.
	   Violence in Costa Rica's overcrowded prisons is nothing new. On
Monday, two prisoners were killed and two were wounded in the same
prison in what authorities called a fight between gangs in the
prison.
	   Escape attempts are common, and President Miguel Angel Rodriguez
has given guards specific orders to open fire on any prisoners who
try to escape. Human rights groups have criticized the
instructions.
	   Costa Rica has 5,300 prisoners, while its prisons have a
capacity of less than half that.
</TEXT>
