<HEADER>
w2206 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Poland-NATO     12-03 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-NATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Naumann: Poland needs years to reach full NATO integration
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo WAR154 &QL; 
 &UR; By MONIKA SCISLOWSKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Poland will need a ``couple of years'' to
achieve full ``interoperability'' with NATO, but can take initial
steps toward that goal next year, a top official of the Western
alliance said Thursday.
	   Gen. Klaus Naumann, chairman of NATO's military committee,
listed several conditions that Poland, a former Warsaw Pact nation
and NATO enemy, has to meet before it reaches interoperability _
meaning Polish forces can interchange with NATO forces.
	   Those conditions for Poland's military include adapting to all
NATO standards and commands, a working knowledge of English, and
integrating the Polish air defense system with the NATO system.
	   Poland is scheduled to join the Czech Republic and Hungary as
the first former Soviet bloc countries to become NATO members at
the NATO summit in Washington in April.
	   Marek Siwiec, the head of Poland's National Security Office,
said Poland would like to join NATO before the summit so that it
can take part as a full member in the policy discussions at the
meeting, the PAP state news agency reported Thursday.
	   But Siwiec, on a trip to Washington, said Poland must first
adopt a new law on classified information to bring it in line with
Western standards, PAP reported.
	   A bill on protecting state secrets has been approved by the
government and needs approval from parliament.
	   Ending a three-day visit to Poland, Naumann said Poland's
earliest date for joining NATO would be in March, because of
procedural reasons. He also said Poland could reach an initial
stage of ``interoperability'' with NATO in 1999.
	   But he stressed it would take a few years for Polish forces to
achieve full interoperability, and said the government must support
the transition process with enough money to make it happen.
	   Facing broad social needs in the transition from decades of
communist rule to a market-led economy, government officials say
they lack the money to make all the needed changes right away.
	   Naumann also expressed his support for a NATO doctrine that
allows the alliance to use nuclear weapons before being attacked by
them _ the so-called ``first-use'' doctrine.
	   Germany has called for NATO to drop the policy, but also said it
would go along with whatever decision NATO reaches on the matter.
	   ``As a military, I strongly believe that we should retain
uncertainty in the opponent's risk calculation in order to preserve
peace,'' Naumann said. ``For that reason I am strongly opposed to
this idea of no-first use policy because it would make peace less
likely and war more likely.''
	   (ms-tsc)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Poland-NATO; CT:i; 
