<HEADER>
w2208 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Golf-MillionDo     12-03 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Million Dollar Challenge,0458 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Price takes first-round lead with 67
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: Stands as 3rd Ld-Writethru to African, European lines to
CORRECT to O'Meara playing in twosome ahead of Price; CORRECT
Woods' birdie-bogey sequence. &QL; 
 &UR; By DANIEL WAKIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SUN CITY, South Africa (AP) _ Zimbabwe's Nick Price shot a
5-under-par 67 and took a two-stroke lead over Americans Mark
O'Meara and Justin Leonard and Germany's Bernhard Langer in
Thursday's first round of the Million Dollar Challenge.
	   The defending champion finished with consecutive birdies in his
six-birdie, one-bogey round over the windswept 7,597-yard
(6,947-meter) Gary Player Country Club course.
	   South African hometown hero Ernie Els was three strokes back at
70 while American Tiger Woods shot an even-par 72 in the elite
12-man field of the world's top golfers vying for the largest
single prize in golf.
	   ``This course likes me,'' said Price, who won the event in 1993
with a record 24 under par. ``It makes me focus a lot more than I
do normally.''
	   Unusually strong, shifting winds, more Scottish style than
African, caused some of the players to guess on the right club, he
said.
	   Price is coming off his third victory in four years at the
Zimbabwe Open, closing with a Royal Harare-record 9-under-par 63
for a five-stroke victory.
	   ``This is a game of momentum. No doubt about it,'' he said.
	   O'Meara, winner of the U.S. Masters and British Open titles and
playing in the twosome ahead of Price, momentarily held the the
lead with a quick start on the back nine.
	   After making the turn at 1 under, he birdied Nos. 11, 13 and 14
to reach 4 under, but he gave the lead right back on the next hole
when Price also birdied 14 and O'Meara proceeded to bogey 15.
	   O'Meara started the day a relieved man after his clubs finally
arrived from Florida Wednesday night.
	   Els birdied each of the first four holes to go 4 under but
slowly gave it nearly all back, with bogeys on 6, 11 and 17. He
also birdied 10.
	   ``It was really a long course out there today,'' he said of the
layout that had been battered by heavy rain and a day where a
swirling wind made things even more difficult for the elite 12-man
field.
	   In his first round of African golf, Woods started with a birdie
on No. 2 hole but dropped to 2 over by the turn with a bogey at 7
and a double bogey on the par-4 eighth.
	   ``I'm very pleased with the way I'm striking the ball,'' he
said. ``It feels like I'm making progress.''
	   Woods said playing in South Africa had special meaning for him
as ``a person of color.''
	   ``To play golf in Africa, particularly South Africa _ it's
something I've wanted to do,'' he said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Golf-Million Dollar Challenge; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
