<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Morocco,0203 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Morocco submits official World Cup 2006 bid
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) _ Morocco has formally notified FIFA of
its interest in hosting the 2006 World Cup finals, world soccer's
governing body confirmed Thursday.
	   The north African country, which submitted its notification on
Wednesday, is the sixth country to confirm it wants the tournament.
	   It follows Germany, England, Brazil, Egypt and Ghana.
	   Prospective candidates have until Dec. 31 to signal their intent
and until the end of July to submit their full bid documents.
FIFA's 24-member Executive Committee will decide in March 2000.
	   In Johannesburg last week, FIFA President Sepp Blatter declared
that FIFA had a ``responsibility'' to make sure the tournament
takes place in Africa.
	   South Africa is expected to formally signal its interest this
month. Blatter has long made it clear that he wants the finals to
be awarded to the country.
	   The case of both Germany and England has been weakened by the
fact that they are both from the same continent. The 2002 finals
are being split between Japan and South Korea _ but FIFA has said
co-hosting would be a one-time exception.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Morocco; CT:s; 
