<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Phone Tax </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU Commission denies it eying phone tax to help finance EU
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The EU head office denied Thursday it
planned to propose a telephone tax to help fund the European Union
and its ambitious aspirations to take in a dozen newcomers.
	   In a statement it said a story to that effect in the German
tabloid daily Bild ``is wrong.''
	   Spokeswoman Martine Reichert said the commission had looked at
studies dealing with new income for the EU.
	   One mentioned a ``communications'' or ``telephone tax'' but that
had been dismissed as unrealistic. ``There is no proposal
whatsoever of the commission in this context,'' Reichert added.
	   The urgency with which the EU head office denied the report
follows the emergence of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's leftist
government in Germany that has led to a split among EU members
about tax issues.
	   Schroeder favors EU governments deciding on such issues by
majority voting. EU rules now require unanimous decisions and
Britain and other EU members want to keep it that way.
	   In Britain's tabloid press has been on a virulent crusade of
late against German Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine, calling him
Europe's ``most dangerous man.''
	   The EU's annual budget _ some dlrs 100 billion this year _ is
funded largely through sales tax contributions and a flat fee that
reflects each EU member's gross national product. Pressure is
rising to find a new source of income as the EU looks at taking in
12 newcomers in the decade ahead.
 &UR; (rw)	   
</TEXT>
