<SLUG> BC-Mitch-Inflation,0138 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
El Salvador blames sharp rise in inflation on hurricane
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) _ El Salvador blamed a sharp rise
in inflation for November on Hurricane Mitch, saying price-gouging
after the disaster had caused prices to rise across the board.
	   November's inflation was 2.2 percent, the highest monthly rate
in three years and double the rates of previous months, which were
between 1 percent and 1.3 percent, the Central Reserve Bank said
Thursday.
	   It said food prices in particular had risen, despite the arrest
of some price-gougers.
	   El Salvador's agricultural sector was heavily affected by the
storm, which killed 239 people here a month ago. Across Central
America, Mitch killed more than 9,000 people and caused at least
dlrs 4 billion in damage.
</TEXT>
