<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Saudi-Illegal Workers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Saudis launching new campaign against illegal workers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) _ Saudi authorities are to revive their
campaign against illegal workers in order to create jobs for their
own citizens, a regional newspaper reported Thursday.
	   The Arab News said Saudi police are to raid workplaces,
including shops and restaurants, and the government will introduce
tougher laws against illegally employed foreigners.
	   The raids will begin Friday, the Jiddah-based newspaper said.
	   The Saudi government began cracking down on illegal labor in
October 1997. Since then some 700,000 workers have been deported to
their home countries in Asia, Africa and the Middle East, the paper
said, quoting official statistics by the immigration department.
	   The campaign aims to provide hundreds of thousands of jobs for
Saudis, reduce crime and curb the estimated dlrs 16 million sent
abroad each year by foreign laborers.
	   Saudi Arabia has a population of 18 million, including six
million foreigners. About 4.3 million foreigners have work permits.
