w2287 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  US-Clinton-Impeachment 4thLd-Writethru   12-03 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> US-Clinton-Impeachment, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Livingston wants impeachment inquiry ended this month
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Combines, editing throughout to tighten &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURIE KELLMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Incoming U.S. House Speaker Bob Livingston
said Thursday he hopes the House wraps up its impeachment inquiry
this year but held out the possibility it could carry over to the
next Congress in January unless the Judiciary Committee completes
its work next week.
	   ``I can't say I'd be perfectly happy'' if the fight extends into
the new year, Livingston said during a news conference with Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott.
	   As the Judiciary Committee prepares to end its impeachment
inquiry, White House lawyers are readying a ``vigorous defense'' of
President Bill Clinton and demanding sensitive fund-raising memos
and other material gathered by Republican investigators.
	   Livingston said it is too early to make any decision on whether
the House should consider censuring Clinton as an alternative to
impeachment _ an option that has support in both parties. ``I'm
just not going to make a decision on that,'' Livingston said.
	   Rep. Peter King, a Republican, was circulating a censure
proposal Thursday . It would include a strong condemnation of
Clinton and require him to pay a financial penalty and issue a
statement acknowledging wrongdoing, according to King's spokesman,
Kevin Fogarty.
	   Clinton was asked by a reporter whether he would accept a
censure. Aide Bruce Lindsey responded, ``I have no earthly idea.''
	   Lott said ``we're not making any plans or any preparation at
this time'' for a Senate trial of Clinton in case the House votes
impeachment. He said he knows of no constitutional requirement that
the Senate hold a trial but ``it would be very hard not to'' if the
House impeached the president.
	   Livingston told reporters he had discussed impeachment briefly
in meetings this week with two senior House Republican leaders.
DeLay. And he took a shot at Democratic complaints, joining the
partisan brawling that has characterized the proceedings.
	   ``I think it's interesting that just about a month ago, people
on the Democratic side of the House were complaining because the
process was either moving too fast or later too slow and they were
condemning the speaker (Rep. Newt Gingrich) for being too
involved,'' Livingston said. ``Now they're mad at me for not being
involved enough.''
	   Whether or not Republicans turn over investigative materials on
Clinton, the president's lawyers plan to press a defense before the
Judiciary Committee.
	   Republican aides and Rep. Henry Hyde, who chairs the panel, are
not saying whether the inquiry would be expanded to include
information on Clinton's campaign finances and Kathleen Willey, who
has accused the president of groping her.
	   The White House legal team accepted an invitation from the
committee Wednesday to make a defense before the inquiry next
Tuesday and possibly even call witnesses, but demanded access to
the fund-raising memos and additional investigative material
related to Monica Lewinsky and Ms. Willey.
	   Ms. Willey, a former White House aide, contends that Clinton
made an unwanted sexual advance, and the committee is trying to
determine whether anyone tried to intimidate her from testifying
about the alleged incident. Clinton denies making the advance.
	   Heading into what lawmakers of both parties hope is the final
two weeks of the impeachment inquiry, the committee is preparing
for four days of hearings next week, beginning with the White House
defense and ending with votes on at least one article of
impeachment. If such a proposal passes, the full House is likely to
vote the following week. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
