r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Greece-TourismConfere     12-03 0332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Tourism Conference </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMU will impact tourism around Europe
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Monetary union will impact tourism around
Europe, and countries must modernize their industries to take
advantage of the change.
	   Experts said Thursday that even countries such as Greece, which
will not be part of the Eurozone in 1999, must nonetheless begin
improving the services they provide.
	   ``More emphasis will be given to the quality of services offered
as the `value for money' approach from the tourists will prevail,''
said Marios Raphael, former chairman of the executive committee of
the World Tourism Organization.
	   He made the comments at a two-day conference on ``Tourism: The
foundation for growth and prosperity in Greece.''
	   Greece is the only country of the 15-member EU that failed to
qualify for the first round of the single currency. It will join
the Eurozone on Jan. 1, 2001, and the Euro will replace national
currencies by July 2002. Britain, Denmark and Sweden opted out of
joining.
	   Tourism is one of Greece's most important industries, with an
estimated 12 million foreigners having visited this year. Foreign
arrivals are expected to increase in 1999.
	   According to Raphael and others, the Euro will make tourist
industries around Europe more competitive as there will be a stable
financial environment defined by a lack of monetary fluctuations,
and low inflation.
	   ``He will also save money from not having to change foreign
currency,'' said Raphael, who added that an estimated 50 percent of
the value of a tourist's money is lost by exchanging currencies in
several countries.
	   The drop in interest rates in countries such as Greece will
encourage new investments in tourism, Raphael said.
	   With the 2004 Summer Olympic games to be held in Athens, Greece
must take advantage of lower rates to improve its tourism
infrastructure, said Theodoros Pandalakis, deputy governor of the
National Bank of Greece.
	    &UR; tt-pq	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
