<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Finland-Nokia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nokia hits 100 million mobile phone mark, bullish on growth
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ Finnish telecommunications company
Nokia has manufactured its 100 millionth cellular phone, and
expects high growth next year, Nokia said Thursday.
	   Its 100 millionth cellular phone was a Nokia 9110, which also
has a keyboard and can send and receive telefaxes, Nokia said.
	   The company expects to maintain 25 to 35 percent sales growth in
1999, despite global economic uncertainty, Nokia's president Jorma
Ollila told analysts in London.
	   ``An increasing part of all personal communications, be it
voice, images, data or video, will be mobile in the future,'' Matti
Alahuhta, chief of Nokia Mobile Phones said in a statement.
	   Nokia expects 1 billion global mobile phone users by 2005,
Alahuhta said.
	   In a seperate report, the Dataquest market research and
consulting firm said Nokia had become the market leader in mobile
phone sales in the United States, the Finnish news agency STT said.
	   During January to September Nokia's U.S. market share was 40.3
percent, compared to 19.8 percent during the same period in 1997,
STT said.
	   In October, Nokia reported a near-doubling of cellular phone
sales worldwide in the third quarter, and a 75-percent increase in
pretax profit of 9.6 billion markkaa (dlrs 1.9 billion) for the
first nine months of the year.
	   Net sales for all Nokia's divisions jumped to 53.3 billion
markkaa (dlrs 10.6 billion), compared to 36.7 billion markkaa for
the January-September period last year.
	   Ollila said preliminary market data indicate Nokia has overtaken
its major rival, Motorola Inc., based in Schaumburg, Illinois, in
mobile phone sales.
	   Nokia is a world leader in digital mobile phone technology, and
has supplied GSM equipment to 67 operators in 35 countries. It has
sales in 130 countries, and employs 42,000 people.
	   (mhh-jh)
</TEXT>
