<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Drugs-Media </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia wants to restrict publications about drugs
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government on Thursday approved a bill that
would ban publishing or broadcasting material about methods of
manufacturing or using drugs, or places where drugs could be
bought, news reports said.
	   The bill _ actually an amendment to Russia's media law _ would
outlaw such coverage in the print and broadcast media and on the
Internet, the ITAR-Tass and Interfax news agency reported.
	   It would also ban ``propaganda about any advantages of (drug)
use,'' or publication of arguments about the advantages of one type
of drug over another, ITAR-Tass reported.
	   Drug use in Russia has soared in recent years. The most popular
kinds are cheap opium derivatives and home-made chemical
concoctions.
	   However, there are no specialized publications that cater to
drug users, and mainstream media rarely publish anything that could
be used as instructions for obtaining or using drugs.
	   The bill would still have to be approved by Russia's parliament
and signed by the president.
	   (ad/adc)
</TEXT>
