<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Spanish Preview,0610 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Barcelona in crisis, Real Madrid in intercontinental heaven
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: Stands as 1st Ld-Writethru to clarify Celta in second place
and Atletico in third in 13th graf. &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHANNA TUCKMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Much more than just a league match, FC
Barcelona's game Saturday against Deportivo La Coruna could prove
decisive for Dutch coach Louis Van Gaal.
	   ``Van Gaal knows his head could roll, and the team knows that
there is much more at stake than just a result,'' the
Barcelona-based daily El Mundo Deportivo said Thursday regarding
the 13th-round match.
	   Upset at being eliminated from contention in the European
Champions League with a match still remaining, and languishing in
fifth place in the domestic league, Barcelona want Van Gaal sent
back to the Netherlands.
	   Sports dailies reported that the dour coach on Tuesday pleaded
with the players to help him stay by giving an extra effort against
Deportivo.
	   Relatively humble Deportivo sits in fourth place with 20 points,
two behind league leader Mallorca and one ahead of Barcelona.
	   Meanwhile, the imminent return of team captain Pep Guardiola
after more than a year because of injury is being seen as a glimmer
of hope.
	   ``Guardiola carries the heavy load of savior,'' wrote La
Vanguardia Thursday.
	   It pointed to the midfielder's reputation for team play and his
status as the only link to Johan Cruyff's ``dream team'' that won
the European Champions Cup and three consecutive league
championships.
	   ``If the fans want to ask me for the moon, let them ask for it.
I am not a magic solution but I will do my best,'' said Guardiola,
one of Spain's most respected internationals.
	   In the meantime, El Mundo Deportivo published an unconfirmed
report that club chairman Jose Luis Nunez is thinking of hiring
Italian coach Fabio Capello to replace Van Gaal.
	   The paper said a three-year agreement already exists that if
signed would be worth 500 million pesetas (dlrs 3.5 million) a year
to Capello.
	   Real Madrid, the other traditional Spanish powerhouse, also
plays away from home on Saturday, against lower-half Espanyol.
	   Although Madrid also is struggling in league play, in eighth
place four points behind Mallorca, the team already has a major
title this season _ the biggest of all _ the Toyota
(Intercontinental) Cup, which it won 2-1 over Vasco da Gama on
Tuesday in Tokyo.
	   ``We needed this great victory,'' Raul Gonzalez, scorer of the
82nd-minute goal that won the game, told the state-owned news
agency EFE Thursday.
	   ``We had had many defeats and a lot of criticism and we were not
receiving the respect we deserve.''
	   Also in action Saturday are Mallorca, second-placed Celta and
third-placed Atletico Madrid.
	   Mallorca, which has lost two of its last three, will host Betis,
which has won three of its last four and climbed from last to ninth
since Javier Clemente replaced Vicente Cantatore.
	   Fresh from its 1-0 victory over Barcelona last week, Atletico
Madrid hosts Athletic Bilbao.
	   Like Barcelona, Bilbao also is celebrating its centennial
season, and also like Barca, has been disappointing.
	   Celta, meanwhile, travels to play lower-half Salamanca in search
of the victory that could restore it to the league lead.
	   Saturday's only other game pits mid-table Real Sociedad against
struggling Extremadura.
	   The 13th round wraps up Sunday with Valencia traveling to play
division newcomer Alaves, last-placed Tenerife at home against
Zaragoza, Oviedo vs. Racing and a lower-half tussle pitting
Villarreal against Valladolid
</TEXT>
