w2307 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Norway-Russia-CFE     12-03 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Russia-CFE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia demands ratification of new arms treaty before NATO expands
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DOUG MELLGREN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ Russia's foreign minister on Thursday said a
revised conventional arms reduction treaty for Europe must be
ratified before NATO admits former East Bloc nations or the pact
could end up mired in problems.
	   Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic will join the Western
military alliance during a NATO summit in Washington D.C. in April.
Russia has repeatedly objected to such NATO expansion into the
former East Bloc.
	   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, in Oslo for a meeting of
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, said the
revised Conventional Forces in Europe treaty must be ratified
before the NATO summit.
	   ``We think there is a new reality in Europe,'' he through an
interpreter. ``A ratification has to be done before the NATO summit
in Washington, where NATO accepts three new members.''
	   ``If we don't agree on ratification of the CFE before the NATO
summit, it will be even harder to realize an agreement
afterwards,'' he said.
	   The CFE treaty was negotiated in 1990, before the Warsaw Pact
ceased to exist. It took effect in 1992, and was being revised to
reflect the demise of the Warsaw Pact.
	   In July 1997, 30 European nations, including the United States
and Russia, agreed to set conventional arms limits for Europe and
set weapons limits for new members of NATO. However, the details
remain to be settled.
	   Ivanov appeared at a brief news conference with Norwegian
Foreign Minister Knut Vollebaek after bilateral talks in Oslo. The
Russian foreign minister did not say why the treaty had to be
ratified by April.
	   However, admitting members of the former Warsaw Pact into NATO
raises the question of whether their treaty ceilings for
conventional weapons go with them. During last year's talks on the
revised treaty, diplomats predicted that Russia would try to commit
the new 19-nation NATO not to exceed the weapons ceilings already
set for the current 16-nation alliance.
	   Vollebaek, who takes over the OSCE chairmanship in January, said
he did not know whether the treaty could be ratified by April.
	   (dm-jh)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Norway-Russia-CFE; CT:i; 
