<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Ukraine-Corruption, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Ukrainian premier arrested in Switzerland
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with further details. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) _ Former Ukrainian premier Pavlo
Lazarenko has been arrested in Switzerland, a spokesman for the
Basel state prosecutor's office said Thursday.
	   Lazarenko, 45, was arrested by customs officials as he crossed
by car from France into Switzerland on Wednesday, spokesman Markus
Melzl said.
	   Geneva state authorities requested his transfer from Basel.
	   ``He will be questioned Friday morning in connection with an
inquiry in Geneva into the laundering of dirty money,''
investigating judge Laurent Kasper Ansermet said.
	   Folco Galli, spokesman for the Swiss Office of Police Affairs
said customs officials had made inquiries over Lazarenko with the
office, which then informed Geneva authorities of the arrest.
	   Switzerland says it has received 20 separate requests from
Ukraine for legal aid in the case of Lazarenko, accused of
corruption, since February 1997.
	   The federal police office last month said Switzerland is helping
Ukrainian authorities in their attempts to track down money he
allegedly stashed away in Swiss banks. Switzerland has handed over
some bank documents to Ukraine.
	   Lazarenko was prime minister in 1996-97, when he was sacked by
President Leonid Kuchma. He now leads the centrist opposition
Hromoda party and has accused Kuchma and his allies of trying to
blacken his name by the corruption charges.
	   In October, he alleged that authorities were plotting to kill
him.
	   As well as Geneva, investigations are under way in the cantons
(states) of Fribourg and Zurich.
	   Under Switzerland's decentralized legal system, individual
cantons are responsible for investigating charges of money
laundering.
 &UR; (gm)
