<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Russia-Mafia Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian mafia reached U.S. cities, ex-FBI agent tells Swiss court
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS for AMs with new material. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo GEV101 &QL; 
 &UR; By NAOMI KOPPEL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ Assassination brigades of the Russian mafia
relaxed in Miami after a hit, while their organization ran
operations in New York, Los Angeles and Houston, a former FBI agent
testified Thursday.
	   Retired special agent Robert Levinson, giving evidence in
Switzerland in the trial of Sergei Mikhailov, the reputed head of
the Solntevskaya organization, said Mikhailov had personal control
of two so-called combat brigades, which specialized in
assassination.
	   ``They would commit murders in Russia and other countries in
Europe and then come to Miami, Florida, where they would stay by
the beach and wait for the heat to cool off,'' said Levinson.
	   He said that during four years of investigating the Russian
mafia for the FBI he was able to assemble an overview of
Solntsevskaya, which he was founded in the late 1980s by a group of
people including Mikhailov.
	   Another founding member, Sergei Timoviev, was killed in a 1994
car bombing in Moscow, Levinson said. The bomb was set off by
remote control, he added, but didn't suggest who might have killed
Timoviev, although he did say he had links to another criminal
organization.
	   The court heard from other witnesses Tuesday that the
organization is made up of 1,700 people. Levinson said they are
organized in brigades of at least 10 people each under a brigade
leader, who reported to Mikhailov and his partner Viktor Averin.
	   Solntsevskaya has taken over nightclubs in New York's Brighton
Beach area and in Los Angeles, he said, adding that that clubs
these became ``a center for drugs and a meeting place for
racketeers.''
	   Mikhailov, who is being tried in Geneva on charges of membership
in a criminal organization, also invested several hundred thousand
dollars in a Houston car dealership, added Levinson.
	   ``When the individual who was involved didn't come up with the
cars that Mr. Mikhailov had ordered, he became in fear of his life.
He thought he was going to be murdered,'' said Levinson. He gave no
more details.
	   Mikhailov, 40, denies he has anything to do with the
organization. He also is charged with breaking Swiss laws on
purchase of property by foreigners and has been in custody in
Geneva for more than two years.
	   Levinson also worked on the case of Russian mafia godfather
Vyacheslav Ivankov, imprisoned for nearly 10 years in New York last
year.
	   ``In Miami one or more meetings took place between the
Solntsevskaya leaders, including Mikhailov, with Ivankov during
which time the takeover and control of several Moscow hotels was
discussed,'' said Levinson.
	   The trial of Mikhailov, which began on Nov. 30, is expected to
hear evidence from more than 90 witnesses speaking six different
languages. If convicted, he faces a maximum of seven-and-a-half
years in prison.
 &UR; (nk-agh)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
