<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Wedding Vandalism,0168 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police arrest 11 for setting fire to wedding tent
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CALCUTTA, India (AP) _ Police arrested 11 people Thursday after
they set fire to a tent at a Calcutta museum where an industrial
tycoon's son was getting married.
	   Members from the youth wing of the opposition Congress party set
the fire to protest the government's decision to let steel magnate
Lakshmi Mittal celebrate the wedding of his son there. No one was
injured.
	   The protesters had shouted slogans before setting the blaze,
saying the party would damage the museum.
	   The government said Thursday that no damage was caused either to
the lawns or to the building, which houses rare paintings and other
memorabilia connected with the British rule of India.
	   Police charged the protesters with vandalism.
	   The state government in Calcutta has been trying to woo Mittal
to invest in West Bengal state. Mittal, whose base is in London,
owns several steel plants throughout the world.
</TEXT>
