<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tunisia-Annan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. chief reconfirms Saturday trip to Libya
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) _ U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on
Thursday reconfirmed his plans to travel to Libya this weekend to
try to resolve differences with Tripoli about putting two suspects
on trial in the 1988 Pan Am bombing.
	   ``Yes, I will travel to Libya on Saturday to discuss the
Lockerbie affair,'' Annan said referring to the bombing over
Lockerbie, Scotland, that killed 270 people.
	   ``We will try to resolve some problems and to find solutions
together,'' he said in answer to reporters' questions.
	   Asked if he would meet with Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi,
Anna replied ``Yes, I think so.''
	   The remarks expanded upon comments by Annan on Wednesday in
Algiers as he prepared to fly to neighboring Tunisia, the last
scheduled stop on a swing through North Africa aimed at unblocking
plans for a U.S.-sponsored referendum on the fate of the disputed
Western Sahara territory.
	   It was not immediately known whether the U.N. chief would seek a
dispensation from U.N. sanctions that ban flights to and from
Libya. He could travel to Libya overland from neighboring Tunisia.
	   The sanctions were leveled in 1992 to try to force Libya to hand
over two suspects in the bombing.
	   A Libyan legal team has been meeting regularly with Annan's
legal counsel to discuss a U.S.-British proposal to try the
suspects in the Netherlands according to Scottish law and using
Scottish judges.
	   Annan had said last week he had hoped for a breakthrough in the
case by the end of November. He said then that a trip to Libya ``to
bring the issue finally to closure ... has not been excluded.''
	   Annan's North African tour has taken him, in two separate
visits, to Mauritania, Morocco, which claims the Western Sahara,
the Western Sahara itself, a refugee camp in southern Algeria for
the Polisario Front and Algiers.
	   (eg-parf-uni-dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
