<SLUG> BC-Russia-Yeltsin, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin's surgeon: Yeltsin needs to listen to his doctor
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with DeBakey saying no heart trouble, new grafs 9-10. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Boris Yeltsin needs to stay in bed to recover from
his latest bout of pneumonia, but the president has a long history
of ignoring the advice of his doctors, the president's heart
surgeon said Thursday.
	   Yeltsin has in the past rushed back to work without fully
recuperating from his ailments, and doctors have said this has
contributed to his recurring illnesses.
	   The president's aides say Yeltsin is again urging doctors to
discharge him from a government clinic where he remained
hospitalized for a 12th straight day Thursday.
	   Yeltsin must ``fulfill all orders of his doctors as pilots obey
air traffic controllers,'' said Dr. Renat Akchurin, who performed
Yeltsin's heart bypass surgery in 1996.
	   ``I have had pneumonia in my life and I can say that it is not
at all easy to live through the disease,'' Akchurin told the
ITAR-Tass news agency.
	   And Yeltsin was likely to make it even more difficult, Akchurin
said.
	   ``As far as I know the president, he will not stay in bed as
told, but will return to work,'' Akchurin was quoted as saying.
	   Akchurin said he has not examined Yeltsin for eight months, but
believed that the president was not suffering from any heart
problems.
	   Dr. Michael DeBakey, a renowned American cardiologist who
consulted on the 1996 surgery, also said Thursday that renewed
heart problems were unlikely.
	   DeBakey, who was visiting a medical center under construction in
the former Soviet republic of Azerbaijan on Thursday, said that
Yeltsin looked fine when DeBakey examined him several months ago,
ITAR-Tass reported.
	    &UR; Yeltsin's deputy, pickup 9th pvs
	   (ad/adc)
