<HEADLINE>
Lewinsky interview set for British TV
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Monica Lewinsky has agreed to do an interview with
a British television network for broadcast in Britain in February,
Channel 4 announced Thursday.
	   Channel 4 said its interview, to be taped in the United States,
will be transmitted ``within a few hours'' of the NBC interview Ms.
Lewinsky has already agreed to for North American television, and
before publication of the book on which she is collaborating.
	   The network said Ms lewinsky had agreed to talk about ``her life
and the events of the past year, including her relationship with
President Clinton.
	   Channel 4 did not announce what it was paying for the interview,
but the British national news agency Press Association reported the
sum was 400,000 pounds (dlrs 664,000). NBC's interview is free, as
major U.S. networks don't pay for interviews.
	   Channel 4 will be able to sell the rights for the interview to
all countries outside North America.
