w2353 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iraq-Cancer     12-03 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Cancer,0463 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq says cancer rates up, blames U.S., British weapons
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraqi scientists said Thursday that birth
defects and childhood cancers have risen dramatically since the
1991 Gulf War and blamed the surge on depleted uranium used in
American and British tank-piercing shells.
	   A two-day medical conference which ended Thursday was attended
by about 600 Iraqi doctors and scientists, who urged the government
and individual families to seek redress from the United Nations and
international courts.
	   At the conference, Iraqi scientists showed pictures and slides
of babies born without hands or legs or with distorted heads.
	   They said that the number of children born with birth defects
had increased three-fold around the city of Basra in the south,
which was close to Gulf War battlefields.
	   Hospital statistics, they said, indicated that the number of
Iraqi children with cancer rose to 130,000 in 1997 from 32,000 in
1990.
	   The sole Western scientist attending the symposium _ Dr. Hari
Sharma, a radiology specialist from Waterloo University in Ontario,
Canada _ cautioned the Iraqis not to jump to conclusions.
	   ``The numbers are impressive and the deformations we have seen
are heart-breaking,'' Sharma told The Associated Press. ``But the
weakness in (Iraqi) presentation is the absence of causative
agent.''
	   He suggested that the increase in cancer cases could be due to
chemical particles in the huge oil well fires during the war.
	   ``Or simply they may be a result of trade sanctions,'' he said.
	   He was referring to U.N. sanctions, imposed after Iraq's 1990
invasion of Kuwait, that have led to shortages of food and medicine
in the country. The invasion sparked the Gulf War.
	   Depleted uranium is a metal residue left when natural uranium is
refined. It is used in artillery shells and bombs designed to
penetrate the armor of tanks. On impact, the shells create an
airborne dust, which if inhaled or ingested, can be poisonous.
	   Some American veterans groups have suggested that the shells
could be a factor in Gulf War syndrome _ the name for a variety of
ailments that have afflicted scores of veterans.
	   American researchers also have looked into whether U.S. troops
could have been affected by chemical agents released by allied
bombing of Iraqi ammunition sites or, possibly, by vaccines or
pesticides in use in the war theater.
	   Three western Gulf War veterans _ former Sgt. 1st Class Carol
Picou from the United States and Raymond Bristow and Colin
Dursell-Lee from Britain _ participated in the conference. All said
they were seeking relief from Gulf War-related illness.
</TEXT>
