<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Paraguay-Rebel General,0243 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Paraguayan general says he's not going to jail
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) _ A former army commander will not
return to prison despite a Supreme Court ruling that ordered him to
finish serving a 10-year-sentence for rebellion, his lawyer said
Thursday.
	   Gen. Lino Cesar Oviedo was convicted in March by a military
court for refusing an order by then-President Juan Carlos Wasmosy
to resign as army chief-of-staff in April 1996, setting off a
crisis that tested Paraguay's young democracy.
	   But Oviedo was released from prison in August after being
pardoned by his friend, newly inaugurated President Raul Cubas _ an
act that prompted calls for Cubas' impeachment.
	   Incensed lawmakers in this landlocked South American nation
appealed Cubas' decision to the Supreme Court, which ruled
Wednesday that Oviedo should serve out the sentence.
	   However, Oviedo's attorney, Jose Francisco Appleyard, said
Thursday he believes the Supreme Court ruling does not mean his
client has to return to prison.
	   The ruling, he said, means Cubas' presidential decree freeing
Oviedo was ``inapplicable'' but ``did not annul it.''
	   Many lawmakers who were angered by Cubas' decision to free
Oviedo have now called on the president to uphold the Supreme Court
decision.
	   ``If Cubas does not respect the decision, he will be subjected
to a political trial,'' said Sen. Luis Gonzalez.
</TEXT>
