<HEADER>
w2362 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-Degussa     12-03 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Degussa </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German TV reports Degussa, not IG Farben, produced gas for death
</HEADLINE>
camps &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ German television reported Thursday
that the chemical firm Degussa AG was primarily responsible for
production of the gas used for death-camp executions, not IG Farben
as long held.
	   The report by ARD is based on new information taken from files
recently made available in Poland.
	   Degussa, based in Frankfurt, declined to comment on specifics of
the report, pointing to a class-action suit charging it with
willingly helping the Nazis produce Zyklon B and in assisting in
processing gold seized from Jews. The suit, filed in the United
States in August, seeks all of Degussa's assets, which totaled
about dlrs 2.1 billion at the end of the 1997 fiscal year.
	   Degussa and IG Farben each owned equal 42.2 percent shares in
Degesch GmbH, which delivered to the Nazis the Zyklon-B cyanide
tablets used to gas hundreds of thousands of concentration camp
inmates. IG Farben, a chemical company dissolved after the war, has
long been identified as the chief producer of Zyklon B through a
subsidiary.
	   But citing documents at the High Commission for Investigating
Nazi Crimes in Poland, ARD reported that Degussa's sales division
actually controlled Degesch, not IG Farben.
	   The gas was produced by a facility in Dessau under contract for
Degussa, ARD reported. Degussa paid for the gas, and turned it over
to Degesch without receiving commission. Degesch then delivered it
to the Nazis.
	   Degussa also controlled two known Zyklon B production sites east
of Prague.
	   ARD said Degesch earned a profit of 300,000 Reichs marks, or 300
million marks (dlrs 176 million) in today's currency, through the
delivery of 20 tons of Zyklon B to the former Nazi death camp
Auschwitz from 1942-43.
	   After the war, Degussa chief Hermann Schlosser denied any
knowledge of Zyklon-B production. He remained on the board of
directors into the 1950s.
	   Degussa, the largest precious metals refiner in Europe in the
1930s and '40s, has opened its archives to researchers to
``clarify'' its smelting of gold, silver and jewelry confiscated
from Jews by the Nazis during that period, as well as its part in
making the gas Zyklon-B.
	   (cb)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
