<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Slain couple </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Slain couple identified as Chinese
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) _ A young man and woman whose bodies were
found at the bottom of a remote cliff have been identified as
Chinese students, police said Thursday.
	   Their bodies were apparently thrown over a cliff near the
mountain monastery of Trooditissa, 30 miles (50 kilometers) north
of Limassol, after having been strangled, police said after they
were discovered Wednesday.
	   The man and woman were both 23 and had arrived in Cyprus on Oct.
11, police said in a statement Thursday. They registered at a
college in the port of Limassol.
	   The police declined to name the couple as their next of kin had
not yet been informed.
	   The couple's apartment in Limassol had been ransacked and there
were bloodstains on its doorstep, a policeman said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
	   This is a ``most unusual crime for Cyprus,'' District Police
Chief Miltiades Neocleous told The Associated Press.
	   ``We are trying to establish a motive, but for the moment we
don't have a clue,'' he said.
	   Robbery has been ruled out as a motive as they were found
wearing jewellery.
	   Police said the couple's fellow students last saw them on
Tuesday. Neighbors described the couple as very quiet and likeable
and said they spent most of their time studying.
 &UR; ae-jbm
</TEXT>
