<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Oceans </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prince Philip: Countries not doing enough to protect oceans
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MITCH STACY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Countries around the world haven't done nearly
enough to protect the seas, Prince Philip said Thursday, calling
for more participation in a United Nations agreement to control
over-fishing.
	   The prince, husband of Queen Elizabeth II, made a rare public
appearance to help draw the curtain on the globally recognized
``International Year of the Ocean.'' Prince Philip serves as
president emeritus of the World Wide Fund for Nature, which was
behind the campaign.
	   Fund officials said the oceans campaign this year raised
awareness around the world, but was only marginally successful at
prompting conservation measures. A major disappointment has been
the failure of most major fishing countries to adopt the U.N. Fish
Stocks Agreement aimed at conserving fisheries.
	   Prince Philip called the efforts ``depressingly inadequate.''
	   ``Fishing nations ought to sign up to ratify the fish stocks
agreement,'' the prince said in an interview with The Associated
Press. ``I think they should be thinking much more about
controlling the fishing that takes place in their own economic
zones. I think they need to look at the conservation of coastal
zones and estuaries, many of which are important breeding areas for
fish.''
	   The U.N. reports that as much as 70 percent of the world's fish
stocks require urgent intervention to avoid further decline or
restore depleted species. But many nations are hesitant to put any
controls on fishing for fear of disrupting the marine economy.
	   ``It's a Catch-22 situation,'' the prince acknowledged. ``If you
don't conserve it, there won't be any fish for the next generation,
and if you do conserve it, you're going to put some people out of a
job.
	   ``It's not an easy answer, but if you're stupid enough to get
into government, then these are the sort of problems you have to
deal with,'' the prince said with characteristic bluntness.
	   Fund director Claude Martin said changes aren't coming fast
enough.
	   ``The world oceans are in a perilous state,'' Martin said.
``While some governments made measurable progress during the past
12 months, most governments failed to take the critical steps
needed to manage this last wild frontier and to ensure that its
resources are safeguarded for future generations.''
	   Prince Philip said the future of the oceans depends on raising
awareness and getting people to pressure their lawmakers for
changes.
	   ``It's something that unless it is taken up by the media as an
issue, I don't think the (conservation organizations) on their own
can do very much,'' he said.
	   (ms-acw)
</TEXT>
