<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Davis Cup, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italy counting on crowd against favored Sweden
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS.
 &UR; By HOWARD FENDRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ Italy figures it has an extra weapon for the
Davis Cup final.
	   Defending champion Sweden may have the richer tradition, and the
better players, but the hosts can count on sellout partisan crowds
to rattle the opposition.
	   ``It's a big occasion _ I couldn't miss this,'' Italy's Andrea
Gaudenzi said. ``What's going to make it really special is the
crowd and 13,000 people cheering for us.''
	   And, perhaps, more than just cheering.
	   Italy's raucous fans have been known to toss everything from
coins to sandwiches onto tennis courts, yell during the course of
play, and chant like a soccer crowd.
	   The final on slow clay indoors at the Assago Forum opens Friday.
Sweden captain Carl-Axel Hageskog dropped his highest ranked
player, Thomas Johansson, right before Thursday's draw.
	   Magnus Norman steps in and will face Gaudenzi in the opening
singles, followed by Sweden's Magnus Gustafsson vs. Davide
Sanguinetti.
	   Johansson is No. 17 in the ATP rankings, but has been battling a
sore knee.
	   ``The thing is, Norman likes to play on clay,'' said former
doubles specialist Anders Jarryd, now Hageskog's assistant.
``Johansson still doesn't feel as good there as he does on other
surfaces.''
	   Guadenzi will pair with lefthander Diego Nardiso in Saturday's
doubles. Jonas Bjorkman and Niklas Kulti are expected to form the
Swedish doubles team.
	   The Davis Cup has never had a final without any singles players
ranked in the world's top 30.
	   Until now.
	   Gustafsson is No. 31, Gaudenzi No. 44, Norman No. 52 and
Sanguinetti No. 47.
	   Gaudenzi has not played a match since helping Italy shock an
understrength U.S. squad 4-1 in September. He has been sidelined
with a sore right shoulder.
	   Only in the rah-rah atmosphere of Davis Cup does Gaudenzi
approach the promise he showed as a teenager. Gaudenzi is 16-8
overall in Davis Cup play.
	   Predictions are tough, since neither of the Swedes has ever
faced either of the Italians.
	   Norman, who had heart surgery a year ago, is new to tennis' top
team event, playing previously only against first-round foe
Slovakia. He did not advance past the second round at any of the
year's four Grand Slam tournaments.
	   While Sweden is after its seventh Davis Cup title, Italy's lone
triumph came in 1976. The Italians have lost in five other finals
appearances _ but this is their first chance to play at home.
	   Bjorkman played down the fans' potential impact.
	   ``We have too much experience,'' Bjorkman insisted, ``to get
into a situation where it bothers us.''
	   But plenty of players, including Sweden's own best ever, have
been undone.
	   The most infamous examples come from former Italy Davis Cup
captain Adriano Panatta's run to the final at the 1978 Italian Open
in Rome.
	   During the semifinal, spectators launched coins and batteries at
opponent Jose Higueras of Spain and the umpire. Both fled the
court, allowing Panatta to advance by default.
	   Swedish great Bjorn Borg, who defeated Panatta that year for his
second Italian title, also was hit by debris tossed from the
stands. After winning the five-set final, Borg vowed he'd never
return _ and didn't.
	   (hjf)
</TEXT>
