<SLUG> BC-Germany-Ukraine </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Germany to use G7 chair to seek money to close last Chernobyl
</HEADLINE>
reactor &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer pledged
Thursday to secure funds to close the last working nuclear reactor
at Ukraine's Chernobyl plant while Germany holds the rotating chair
of the G-7 nations next year.
	   Fischer made the pledge after meeting with his Ukranian Foreign
Minister Boris Tarasiuk, who said Ukraine doesn't have the money to
keep its 1995 agreement with the G-7 to close all of Chernobyl's
reactors by 2000.
	   The G-7 group of industrialized nations said it would help with
the costs. Ukraine wants dlrs 3 billion to replace the plant.
	   Concern is growing about the safety of the final reactor after
Ukraine nuclear regulatory officials ordered it shut down on Dec.
1. An inspection showed some of its safety equipment was close to
the end of its operational life.
	   But Ukraine energy officials have refused to shut it down,
saying the reactor is needed to get the country through the winter.
	   Reactor No. 3 has been Chernobyl's only working reactor since
1996, when its other unit was shut down in compliance with the
Ukrainian government's pledge to fully close the plant.
	   There have been frequent malfunctions at the reactor recently
despite lengthy repairs between July, 1997 and May, 1998.
	   One Chernobyl reactor was destroyed in the 1986 explosion and
fire, the world's worst nuclear accident, while another was stopped
after a 1991 fire.
 &UR; dkt-cb
</TEXT>
