<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli jets raid guerrilla bases in south Lebanon
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TYRE, Lebanon (AP) _ Israeli warplanes struck suspected
guerrilla bases in southern Lebanon on Thursday after attacks on
Israeli outposts.
	   An Israeli jet fired two missiles at targets between the
villages of Siddiqine and Jebal al-Butom, 18 kilometers (11 miles)
southeast of the port of Tyre, Lebanese security officials said,
speaking on customary condition of anonymity. A second Israeli jet
provided cover.
	   There was no immediate word on casualties from the 6:50 p.m.
(16:50 GMT) raid.
	   In Jerusalem, an Israeli military spokesman said warplanes
attacked ``terrorist targets '' in southwest Lebanon.
	   The targeted area is believed to be used by guerrillas as a base
to launch attacks on Israeli troops and their allied Lebanese
militiamen in the Israeli-occupied zone.
	   The air strike came about an hour after guerrillas of the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah group claimed responsibility for mortar
and rocket attacks on Israeli positions in the occupied zone.
	   No casualties were reported in those attacks.
	   Israeli warplanes have attacked suspected Hezbollah bases in the
south almost daily since Nov. 8. There have been no reports of
casualties from the raids.
	   Seven Israeli soldiers were killed in bomb attacks by Hezbollah
guerrillas last month.
	   Hezbollah, or the Party of God, has been waging a guerrilla war
to oust an estimated 1,500 Israeli soldiers and their 2,500 allied
militiamen from the zone that Israel set up in 1985 to protect its
northern territory from guerrilla attacks.
