<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Banks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia's state bank begins repaying frozen accounts
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Russia-Economy &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo MOSB108 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's giant state savings bank on Thursday
finally freed up some individual accounts transferred months ago
from six huge ailing private banks, news reports said.
	   The economic crisis that hit in August crippled the country's
six largest commercial banks. They reacted by freezing private
accounts, saying they had no money to repay depositors, prompting
public outrage and massive crowds at the few banks that were
releasing money.
	   The government in September offered the depositors to transfer
their accounts from the troubled banks to the state Sberbank,
saying all deposits would be guaranteed.
	   However, all foreign-currency deposits were to be paid out in
rubles _ and at about half the current exchange rate. Many Russians
keep their money in dollars because of its relative stability.
	   Many holders of ruble accounts took the offer, and a few of the
holders of foreign-currency accounts. Some have kept their money in
commercial banks, which are still struggling to survive.
	   Sberbank has taken over between 6 billion and 9 billion rubles
(dlrs 300 million-450 million) of deposit liabilities from the
ailing banks.
	   It promised to start paying out the deposits on Nov. 30, but
missed its own deadline by three days.
	   On Thursday, Sberbank reopened access to deposits transferred
from four of the commercial banks _ Menatep, Most Bank,
Mosbiznesbank, and Promstroibank. Deposits moved from Inkombank and
SBS-Agro remained frozen.
	   ``Regarding SBS-Agro, we've carried out our talks with them and
we will make a joint announcement, but no date has been set yet,''
Sberbank spokesman Alexander Torkonov said Thursday.
	   Many Russians, scarred by the banking crisis, have gone back to
keeping cash at home, in jars or under mattresses.
	   (ad/adc)
</TEXT>
