<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Kidd-Blackburn, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brian Kidd takes Blackburn manager's job
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS quotes, background

<TEXT>
	   BLACKBURN, England (AP) _ After eight years as Alex Ferguson's
assistant at Manchester United, Brian Kidd on Thursday became the
manager of his own Premier League club.
	   Kidd, who helped United win four league titles in five years,
took over at last place Blackburn Rovers, signing a contract that
runs until June 2002.
	   He succeeds Roy Hodgson, who was fired last month after
Blackburn's 2-0 defeat to Southampton.
	   ``Brian was always our first choice, and I am delighted he has
accepted,'' said Blackburn owner Jack Walker, who has made his
third change in three years since the club won the Premier League
title in 1995.
	   While Kidd was No. 2 to Ferguson, United finished in the top two
in the league seven years in a row, four times as champion, and
twice won the FA Cup.
	   His decision to leave Old Trafford couldn't have come at a
busier time for United. On Saturday, Ferguson's team visits Premier
League leader Aston Villa with the chance to go top and, on
Wednesday, it hosts Bayern Munich with a European Champions Cup
quarterfinal place at stake.
	   ``While I have only been here three months he has been my mentor
around the place,'' said United's Tobagan striker Dwight Yorke, who
moved to the club in August from Aston Villa for a 12.6 million
pound (dlrs 20.9 million) transfer fee.
	   ``He will certainly be a massive loss. Manchester United has
been part of his life for a long time and he has been part of the
players' lives for a long time.
	   ``To have such an influential person leaving the camp is always
going to be a big loss, but such is life and such is football,''
Yorke said.
	   ``Good things come to an end, people come and go and what can we
say but good luck to him.''
	   United had agreed reluctantly to let Kidd talk with last-place
Rovers about filling their managerial vacancy.
	   ``He wants to progress his career and he wants to have the
chance of being a No. 1,'' chief executive Martin Edwards said.
``He wants that opportunity to speak to them and so reluctantly we
have agreed to that.''
	   Only last week Edwards claimed the only way Kidd would leave
United would be ``over my dead body.''
	   Rovers' dismal season continued Wednesday night with a 1-0 loss
to Leicester in the quarterfinals of the League Cup.
	   Blackburn is now bottom of the table with only two victories in
15 games.
	   Kidd has been associated with Manchester United throughout his
career. As a 19-year-old, he scored a goal in the club's European
Cup victory over Benfica in 1968.
	   He managed Preston for three months in 1986 before moving to
United as a junior coach. He became Ferguson's No. 2 in 1991,
replacing Archie Knox.
	   (sw-rjm) 	   
</TEXT>
