<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0782 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. envoy presents Serbs with new Kosovo peace plan draft
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds UPDATES with more incidents reported; statement from
Milutinovic, Hill and KLA; no pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By DUSAN STOJANOVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Yugoslav border guards killed eight
ethnic Albanian rebels Thursday in the worst violation of a Kosovo
cease-fire reached in October under threat of NATO airstrikes.
	   Several other armed incidents were reported Thursday as U.S.
envoy for Kosovo presented Serb leaders with a revised draft plan
for the future of the troubled province. The envoy, Christopher
Hill, said slow progress was being made toward a permanent peace.
	   But Hill also warned that time was at a premium because of fears
that fighting, now at a relative lull, could resume with the onset
of warmer weather in the spring.
	   ``I feel a sense of urgency,'' Hill said.
	   The eight armed ethnic Albanians were killed near the town of
Prizren when nine of them reportedly opened fire on Yugoslav
soldiers guarding the border with Albania.
	   The Serbian Media Center in Kosovo's capital Pristina, which
reflects government views, said there were no injuries among the
Yugoslav troops. Kosovo Albanian rebels, who have been fighting for
Kosovo's independence, have frequently used illegal border routes
to arm themselves in neighboring Albania.
	   Yugoslavia's army command later confirmed the incident and said
the ethnic Albanians were trying to cross the border into Kosovo
``illegally.''
	   The border clash took place one day after three ethnic Albanians
were gunned down in their car in Kosovo's capital Pristina. Serbian
police said they found three automatic weapons and two hand
grenades in the car, which was raked by machine-gun fire.
	   Rebel spokesman Adem Demaci blamed the killings on Serbia's
secret police, saying one of the victims was a leading member of
the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army while the two others were
civilians: a journalist of the main Albanian language newspaper
Bujku and a university student.
	   The journalist, Afrim Malici, had complained that he had been
followed by Serbia's secret service, colleagues said.
	   Prior to the meeting with Serbian President Milan Milutinovic in
Belgrade, Hill said the new draft reflects previous comments by
rival Serb and ethnic Albanian officials on how to achieve a
settlement for the Serbian province, which is 90 percent ethnic
Albanian.
	   Last week, Serbia moved to impose its own peace deal for Kosovo,
defying an earlier U.S. plan and warning that anything beyond some
sort of self-rule for the province would trigger a regional war.
	   Secessionist ethnic Albanian leaders have rejected the Serbian
proposal. They have called for independence from Serbia but are
willing to settle for full autonomy as a first step.
	   Hundreds of people were killed and up to 300,000 were left
homeless in the Serb crackdown against Kosovo Albanian separatists
that started in February. Bloodshed abated _ but did not end _
after Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic agreed with U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke on Oct. 12 to end the Kosovo campaign and begin
political negotiations on the province's future.
	   In a statement after meeting Hill, Milutinovic said he would
``carefully study'' the new U.S. proposal, but added that the
Serbian plan should be ``the main basis for the political
solution'' of the Kosovo crisis.
	   Serbia and the Serb leaders of Yugoslavia are strongly opposed
to any plan on Kosovo that would sidestep Serbia.
	   Hill did not elaborate on the plan, but said it doesn't
explicitly specify whether Kosovo will become the third Yugoslav
republic or would remain a Serb province. Republic status for
Kosovo would give it equal say with Serbia and Montenegro, the two
republics that make up Yugoslavia.
	   The Oct. 12 agreement was reached as NATO was preparing an
airstrike campaign to force an end to the bloodshed.
	   While Hill said that the plan was still not in its final stage,
he said he would like to have a settlement by spring because of
fears that warmer weather could bring a resumption of fighting.
	   ``Spring should be the time for plowing and not for fighting,''
he added.
	   In separate incidents Thursday, a Serb man was injured on the
main Pristina-Pec road when ethnic Albanian rebels shot at his car
when he refused their order to stop, the Serb media center
reported.
	   It also said that an ethnic Albanian was killed ``by a masked
gunman'' with Kosovo Liberation Army markings while traveling on
the same road Wednesday.
</TEXT>
