r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-RubberBullets     12-03 0285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Rubber Bullets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Human Rights group crusades against deadliness of rubber bullets
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ A leading Israeli human rights group said
Thursday that at least 57 Palestinians have been killed by the
rubber-coated steal bullets the Israel army says they use in an
effort to prevent unnecessary deaths.
	   The so-called rubber bullets are routinely used by Israeli
troops as a method of dispersing Palestinian street demonstrations.
	   According to a report released by the Betselem group, since the
outbreak of the six-year Palestinian uprising against Israel which
began in 1987, over half of the 57 killed were minors.
	   An statement from the army spokesman responding to the report
did not dispute the numbers of those killed but defended use of the
bullets. The spokesman said troops only fired the bullets in
dangerous situations after other methods of crowd dispersal had
been exhausted and on instructions from commanding officers in the
field.
	   The statement criticized the Betselem report for not taking the
context of the shootings into consideration.
	   ``The Betselem report describes soldiers using rubber bullets
while ignoring the types of violent incidents that troops and
citizens are involved in that require the army to use this
method,'' the statement said.
	   Betselem also criticized the army for disciplining soldiers
involved in only three of the 57 cases. Betselem said the lack of
punitive actions revealed the army's ``shameful disregard for the
lives of Palestinians.''
	   The group urged the army to consider rubber-coated bullets
lethal ammunition whose use should be restricted to
life-threatening situations alone.
 &UR; dk-dl
</TEXT>
