w2446 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Bosnia-WarCrimes 1stLd   12-03 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-War Crimes, 1st Ld,0358 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top general instigated executions of thousands, indictment says
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with reaction, suspect arriving at
The Hague. &QL; 
 &UR; By JENIFER CHAO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ Survivors of the Bosnian war's
worst massacre expressed joy Thursday that a top Serb military
leader charged with orchestrating the killings would soon stand
trial for genocide.
	   Gen. Radislav Krstic was arrested in Bosnia Wednesday by U.S.
members of the NATO peacekeeping force there. He is the most senior
Serb military officer seized so far in the effort to bring to trial
Bosnians accused of war crimes.
	   He arrived late Thursday in The Hague, where the Yugoslav war
crimes tribunal has indicted him on charges of genocide, war
crimes, crimes against humanity and grave breaches of the Geneva
Conventions. An arraignment date has not been set.
	   His indictment _ unsealed Thursday _ alleges the offenses
occurred following the Serb takeover of the U.N. ``safe haven'' of
Srebrenica in eastern Bosnia in July 1995.
	   According to the indictment, forces under Krstic and Bosnian
Serb wartime military chief Gen. Ratko Mladic ``either expelled or
killed'' most of the members of the Bosnian Muslim population of
the Srebrenica enclave, using automatic weapons, hand grenades and
other weaponry.
	   In Sarajevo, survivors of the Srebrenica massacre applauded
Krstic's arrest.
	   ``Since July 13, 1995, I've never felt happiness in my heart,''
Kada Hotic said in an interview, referring to the date the Serbs
overran the town. ``Last night when I heard he was arrested, I felt
happy.''
	   Another survivor, Munira Subasic, said she hoped Krstic ``will
give answers to where are our relatives, our children.''
	   Krstic planned and assisted in the ``preparation or execution of
a planned and organized mass execution of thousands of captured
Bosnian Muslim men,'' reads the indictment, which was issued in
October. It had been kept secret so he wouldn't be prompted to
flee.
