<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Rugby-Dubai Sevens </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fiji, New Zealand and Australia show their class on sevens opening
</HEADLINE>
day

<TEXT>
	   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) _ Defending champions New
Zealand, Fiji and Australia showed their class on the opening day
of the dlrs 50,000 Dubai International Rugby Sevens on Thursday to
cruise into the quarter-final.
	   The three southern hemisphere teams finished their league
matches unbeaten with New Zealand and Fiji easily looking the best
equipped to win the dlrs 25,000 first prize on Friday.
	   New Zealand, led by 35-year-old Dallas Seymour, began their
defense with a 43-0 drubbing of former winners, Scotland, before
swamping Chinese Taipei 57-0 in Group W. South African side, Natal,
stretched the New Zealanders in the final league match before going
down 15-0.
	   The New Zealanders and Natal were involved in a scuffle at the
end of their bruising encounter, which also saw Seymour serve out a
two-minute sin bin penalty for a rough tackle.
	   ``This is the first time some of the players are playing
together in the tournament but we are pleased with our performance
as there have been no injuries,' said New Zealand coach Gordan
Tietjens.
	   Fiji, the world sevens champions, were also among the high try
scorers as they strolled over England Select 35-5, the United
States 36-7 and Warblers International from New Zealand 34-12.
	   Australia, who made heavy work of beating Canada 31-21 in their
first match, began to find their feet as the tournament progressed,
beating Hong Kong 33-7 and Tonga 29-12.
	   The Canadians proved the surprise team, qualifying for the
quarter-finals behind Australia after beating Hong Kong 14-12 in a
thriller to take the second spot in the group.
	   The top two teams from the four groups qualified for the
quarter-finals. Australian coach Mark Ella tipped New Zealand and
Fiji to make it to the final.
	   ``Both teams are a cut above the rest and should battle it out
for the title,'' said the former Australian great. ``I am not
satisfied with our performance so far.''
</TEXT>
