<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-War Crimes, UPDATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bosnian Serb officials protest arrest of Gen. Krstic
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANJA LUKA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ The Bosnian Serb president
and army leaders Thursday blasted the arrest of a Serb general
accused of war crimes, calling it a ``terrorist act.''
	   Nikola Poplasen, president of Serb-run half of Bosnia, lodged a
protest over the arrest of Gen. Radislav Krstic by NATO-led troops
with the Office of High Representative, the top international body
in Bosnia.
	   After meeting members of Bosnian Serb army headquarters,
Poplasen said the arrest of Gen. Krstic presented ``a sadistic act
typical of highwayman banditry.'' Poplasen said Bosnian Serb
sub-state with do all in its power to defend Krstic.
	   The Bosnian Serb army headquarters praised Gen. Krstic as ``an
honorable man of high moral values.'' It said Krstic was
``kidnapped'' by masked people and harassed as he was dragged out
of his car toward a helicopter.
	   Bosnian Serbs decided Wednesday to reduce contact with NATO-led
Stabilization Force in Bosnia to the minimum. Poplasen said the
peace troops had overstepped their authority by snatching Gen.
Krstic. He said the Serb general, as an active duty officer, had
cooperated closely with the peace troops in the past three years.
	   (jg/rr)
</TEXT>
