<SLUG> BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
London share prices rise after European rate cuts
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UDPATES with closing figures &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Coordinated interest rate cuts in 11 European
countries produced a late rally on the London Stock Exchange on
Thursday.
	   Ten of the 11 countries that will adopt Europe's new single
currency next year_ including Germany, France, and the Netherlands
_ dropped their interest rate to 3 percent. Italy dropped to 3.5
percent from 4 percent. Britain is not part of the European
currency.
	   ``The market's taken heart from the surprise rate cuts in
continental Europe, which make a U.K. cut more likely,'' said Andy
Hartwill, U.K. strategist at SG Securities.
	   The blue-chip Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
closed up 58.9 points, or 1.07 percent, at 5,566.1, and the
provisional volume for the entire market was 966.8 million shares
compared with 1.04 billion on Wednesday.
	   (acw) 	   
