w2474 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EditorialRoundup 2Takes   12-03 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Editorial Roundup, 2 Takes,0852 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Editorial roundup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Here are excerpts from editorials in publications in various
countries:
	   Il Manifesto, Rome, on Chilean Gen. Augusto Pinochet's
extradition:
	   Some say Pinochet's possible extradition to Madrid could
jeopardize Chile's transition to democracy. The question is: Is it
at risk from Pinochet's arrest and possible trial or from his
shameless impunity which makes any reconciliation theories
impossible?
	   Others say extradition would be a dangerous precedent
irresponsibly set by Spanish judge (Baltasar) Garzon and Britain's
House of Lords. Though still unknown, the effects will surely be
devastating ... The question is: Is this more dangerous than
Pinochet's consecrated immunity and impunity?
	   The Chilean right, left and center have to settle costly and
dangerous accounts with the past. Accounts which this decade's
democratic transition left open and suspended. The right time and
opportunity have come to close them. ...
	   Pinochet's extradition and trial might be a much-needed push to
complete this (so far) imperfect transition.
	    &UR; __
	   Le Monde, Paris, on World AIDS Day:
	   If it serves only to remind us of the inevitable progression of
the pandemic, the ritual of World AIDS Day is important. ...
	   This year, out of the 6 million people who have contracted the
AIDS virus, 95 percent live in developing countries. And the worst
is to come. ...
	   A dramatic paradox underlies this situation: As the pandemic
loses force in industrialized countries, doctors, researchers and
associations the disease receive fewer means to combat the virus.
	   It's as if, yet again, an unwritten rule is applied: What
determines the priority of research is not the number of patients
concerned, but rather the creditworthiness of patients who are or
will be affected.
	   The international community must beware of such reasoning. In
too often considering the profitability of research programs, we
forget that this pandemic will have economic and financial
repercussions for creditor countries. It is not the moment for
eloquent speeches and superficial initiatives: We must have real
mobilization.
	    &UR; ___
	   The Bradenton Herald, Bradenton, Florida, on AIDS:
	   In the near future, we hope we can write an editorial for World
AIDS Day that begins: ``Thanks to an effective education campaign,
research that led to a vaccine against AIDS and cure for those
infected with the disease, the deadly HIV virus has been
defeated.''
	   Unfortunately, it's far too soon to write those words, primarily
because politics, prejudice and bigotry continue to influence how
our society responds to this disease. ...
	   Indeed, the threat is as serious as ever, even though AIDS
dropped off the list of the top 10 causes of death in the United
States this year. ...
	   Convinced that AIDS is on the decline, some political leaders
may be less willing to provide the money for continued research and
desperately needed outreach to minority communities where the virus
is gaining ground.
	   Convinced that AIDS is no longer a threat, people of all
backgrounds ... may turn a deaf ear to education efforts. ...
	    &UR; ___
	   The Independent, London, on the awarding of a prestigious arts
award to a painter who incorporates elephant dung into his works:
	   Yes, the Turner Prize's entries include, and have included,
everything from dung and bricks to preserved sheep. And yes, it has
seemed more concerned with video performances and bits and pieces
tied together than we art as the man in the street, or the visitor
to the nation's galleries, would recognize it.
	   Nonetheless, the fact is that the Turner Prize has added to the
gaiety of the nation in one of the areas of culture where Britain
is now paramount: contemporary visual arts. ... What the Turner
Prize has succeeded in doing is to show where some of the action in
modern art is taking place, and to display what at least a few
artists are up to as they challenge past conventions and redefine,
as every generation must do, the terms of their craft. ...
	    &UR; ___
	   Neue Zuercher Zeitung, Zurich, Switzerland, on India:
	   Bad students get bad marks: In India on Sunday, Prime Minister
(Atal Bihari) Vajpayee and his Hindu nationalist coalition had to
take note of this simple equation.
	   The devastating defeat in parliamentary elections in the
politically important states of Delhi, Rajastan and Madhya Pradesh
... amounts to a withdrawal of confidence from voters from the BJP
and its fragile alliance, in power for just eight months.
	   In contrast, the Congress party under its new leader, Sonia
Gandhi ... has made an impressive return to the political stage.
	   The effect of the outcome on national politics is unclear. The
premier should try immediately to win back voters' trust through
new reforms.
	   For its part, Congress ... will not for now try for power,
although it appears to be within reach.
	    &UR; ___
	    &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
