<SLUG> BC-Editorial Roundup, 1st Add,1055 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: within reach.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	    &UR; ___
	   The Jordan Times, Amman, Jordan, on Israel and the West Bank:
	   ``A sampling of yesterday's headlines that traveled around the
world on international news wire services included: ``Israel takes
delivery of first Arrow missile;'' ``Prisoner issue sparks new
crisis in Wye River accord;'' ``Palestinian protesters clash with
Israeli police in Jerusalem''....
	   The repetition of such news headlines day after day, month after
month, and year after year is no surprise, since nothing seems to
be changing for the Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza.
	   The recent news that Israel has agreed to several measures that
would facilitate Jordan's economic relations with the West Bank are
encouraging, but these measures are only a small part of a
comprehensive package. Israel must recognize that restoring the
Palestinians' national rights are equally vital to Jordanians'
confidence in the peace process, but Israel seems to have failed to
acknowledge that by undermining peace with the Palestinians, it is
also pulling the rug from under its treaty with Jordan.
	   Forty-five countries (met Monday) in Washington for a
Palestinian donors conference. Hopefully, they remember that peace
takes more than money; it needs political will, not the least of
which should come from Israel.
	    &UR; ___
	   The Sydney Morning Herald, Sydney, Australia, on the spreading
economic crisis:
	   ``I have no hesitation in asserting that the global capitalist
system will succumb to its defects, if not on this occasion then on
the next one _ unless we recognize that it is defective and act in
time to correct the deficiencies.''
	   This warning comes from George Soros, in his latest book, ``The
Crisis of Global Capitalism.'' ...
	   It is a warning worth heeding not because Soros is a renowned
economist or an eminent political theorist. He is neither of these.
But he is a major international financier and as such much closer
to the action than many intellectuals writing about the state of
the international economy at the moment. ...
	   First and most importantly, he sees capitalism as a victim of
its own success. Social, political and legal institutions have not
kept pace with the globalization of the economy. ... What is
needed, he argues, is a capacity to regulate the excesses of the
financial markets, but this cannot be done at the level of the
nation-state because the problem is bigger than individual states
and because national politics have failed in the task up to now.
...
	   Second, Soros argues that a fundamentalist approach has come to
dominate economic thinking. The approach is one in which ``monetary
values and transactional markets do not provide an adequate basis
for social cohesion.''
	    &UR; ___
	   The Times, London, on Quebec elections:
	   The solid victory by the secessionist Parti Quebecois in the
province's general elections is a personal triumph for Lucien
Bouchard, the former federal minister who took over the embattled
party's leadership in the wake of the bitter fallout from the
failed referendum on independence in 1995 ... But the victory is by
no means the landslide his supporters had hoped, and leaves a
bitter taste in the mouths of those ready to proclaim the immediate
holding of a new referendum on separation from Canada.
	   Mr. Bouchard now faces a dilemma. He can not afford another
failed referendum. He would be better advised to wait until he is
assured of victory before going to the polls. The risk here,
however, is not just the disappointment of the party faithful. Time
is not necessarily on the separatists' side. The federal government
has made enormous efforts to woo Quebec.
	   Little by little Quebeckers may be persuaded that the fight for
`sovereignty' is hardly worth the bitterness ... The polls show
that support for independence is falling. Mr. Bouchard is an astute
and popular leader. He should use his victory to ensure that
Quebec's pragmatic relationship with Ottawa yields benefits for all
Canada.
	    &UR; ___
	   South County Journal of Kent, Washington, on Jack Kevorkian:
	   The decision by ``60 Minutes'' to air a videotape of a
terminally ill man being euthanized by Dr. Jack Kevorkian was a
shabby excuse for television. It's galling enough when TV parades
Jerry Springer and Jenny Jones before our eyes. Now CBS, the
network of Edward R. Murrow and Walter Cronkite, is down there,
too.
	   The death of David Youk, terminally ill from Lou Gehrig's
disease, was not ``news'' in the commonly understood sense of that
word. He had died more than nine weeks earlier, on Sept. 17. Nor is
Kevorkian, a tireless advocate of assisted suicide, particularly
news.
	   But November is a sweeps month, when ratings, which determine
how much programs can charge advertisers, are measured, and
Kevorkian had this self-made videotape _ and an agenda. ...
	   Kevorkian's actions, particularly the way they were staged,
threaten to turn that serious debate into a sideshow.
	    &UR; ___
	   Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Fort Worth, Texas, on the Starovoitova
slaying:
	   They have sent one woman to her final rest, but they may have
awakened a slumbering giant.
	   The slaying of Galina Starovoitova, an outspoken liberal member
of the Russian Parliament, obviously was intended to frighten other
advocates of democracy and reform into submission. But those who
ordered the atrocity in St. Petersburg may have miscalculated
greatly.
	   Those who gunned Starovoitova down on the staircase to her
apartment transformed her into an instant martyr who may serve the
cause of Russian freedom better in death than she did as a living
advocate of it.
	   Already that staircase has blossomed into an impromptu shrine.
Hundreds of mourners have visited it, probed with their fingers the
bullet holes left in the concrete walls by the assassins' rifles,
and obscured the bloodstains with flowers and candle wax.
	   Because of Russia's economic woes and the leadership vacuum
caused by President Boris Yeltsin's declining health, the liberal
and reform forces have fallen into ... disarray, leaving the field
to the gangsters, communists and authoritarian nationalists.
</TEXT>
