<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Striking Miners </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-Ukraine-Mine Accident
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Ukraine's government moves to satisfy striking miners' demands &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ About 40,000 miners across Ukraine
continued their strike Thursday, pushing the government and the
legislature to take steps to meet their demands.
	   Parliament on Thursday overwhelmingly approved a resolution
ordering the Cabinet to speed up repayment of mounting wage arrears
to coal workers by Dec. 15.
	   Twenty of Ukraine's 276 mines were on indefinite strike for a
second day Thursday, demanding more state support for their
deteriorating industry and payment of back wages, the Independent
Miners' Union said.
	   The miners want budget allocations for their industry to be
nearly doubled to 5.5 billion hryvna (dlrs 1.6 billion) next year,
and also demand the payment of back wages that already have topped
2.5 billion hryvna (dlrs 730 million), according to government
figures.
	   The government, meanwhile, began to respond to miners' appeals,
ordering mines to give payment of salaries a top priority, the
Interfax news agency reported.
	   The Cabinet also granted mines land tax breaks for 1999 and put
next year's expenditures for the coal sector on the list of budget
items banned from subsequent reduction.
	   The miners' walkout is the latest in a series of strikes, which
idled dozens of mines in Ukraine last spring and summer.
	   Despite frequent protest actions, the government has so far
failed to improve the situation in the mining industry. It has been
slow in closing loss-making mines and lacks the money to modernize
equipment and make management more efficient.
	   As a result, Ukraine's coal industry has been increasingly
plagued by accidents that have already claimed more than 340 lives
so far this year, about 100 more than in 1997.
	   (vl/adc)
</TEXT>
