<SLUG> BC-Tunisia-Annan, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. chief reconfirms Saturday trip to Libya
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Annan receiving clearance to fly to Libya; report
meeting to be in Sirte; quotes from U.N. spokesman, U.S. deputy
rep. at U.N.

<TEXT>
	   TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) _ U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on
Thursday reconfirmed plans to travel to Libya this weekend. A U.N.
official said Annan has received clearance to fly in, bypassing
U.N. sanctions.
	   Annan told reporters he hoped to resolve differences with Libya
about putting on trial two suspects in the 1988 Pan Am bombing.
	   ``Yes, I will travel to Libya on Saturday to discuss the
Lockerbie affair,'' Annan told reporters in Tunis.
	   ``We will try to resolve some problems and to find solutions
together,'' he said, answering questions.
	   Asked if he would meet with Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi,
Anna replied ``Yes, I think so.''
	   There was no official word on where the meeting would take
place. A diplomatic source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said it will be held in Sirte, a town east of Tripoli.
	   Annan has received clearance to bypass U.N. sanctions banning
flights in and out of Libya, said Deputy U.N. spokesman Manoel de
Almeida E Silva, speaking at the United Nations in New York.
	   The dispensation on U.N. sanctions came from the U.N. Sanctions
Committee.
	   The sanctions have been in place since 1992 to try to force
Libya to hand over two suspects in the bombing over Lockerbie,
Scotland, which killed 270 people.
	   Annan's remarks Thursday expanded upon comments a day earlier in
Algiers before leaving for Tunisia, the last scheduled stop on a
swing through North Africa aimed at unblocking plans for a
U.S.-sponsored referendum on the fate of the disputed Western
Sahara territory.
	   A Libyan legal team has been meeting regularly with Annan's
legal counsel to discuss a U.S.-British proposal to try the
suspects in the Netherlands according to Scottish law and using
Scottish judges.
	   In New York, the deputy U.N. spokesman said Annan's efforts ``to
work out the details for the transfer'' of the two suspects to the
Netherlands was among issues discussed with Tunisian officials.
	   A deputy U.S. representative at the United Nations, Nancy
Soderberg, said any meeting between Annan and the Libyans should
yield results.
	   ``We would expect a meeting between the secretary-general and
Libyan officials to produce the hand over of the suspects,'' she
told The Associated Press.
	   ``The U.S. and Britain have gone the extra mile and Libya has
been given every opportunity to comply with the U.N. Security
Council resolutions,'' she said.
	   Annan said last week he had hoped for a breakthrough in the case
by the end of November. He said then a trip to Libya ``to bring the
issue finally to closure ... has not been excluded.''
	   (eg-parf-uni-dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
