Clinton considering whether to land at Palestinian airport
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS top. Leads with new comments from Bar-Illan saying no
official request was made &QL; 
 &UR; By DINA KRAFT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LOD, Israel (AP) _ The United States is deciding whether
President Bill Clinton will land at the newly opened Palestinian
airport amid Israeli concerns that doing so would boost Palestinian
sovereignty claims, a U.S. official said Thursday.
	   Clinton is to arrive in Israel in the evening of Dec. 12 and on
Dec. 14 is to fly to the Gaza Strip to usher in the second stage of
the Wye River land-for-peace agreement he helped negotiate.
	   A possible Clinton landing at Gaza International, which opened
last week as part of the agreement, had been considered by the
White House.
	   David Bar-Illan, a senior adviser to Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said earlier Thursday that the Israeli government felt a
presidential landing in Gaza ``was tantamount to recognizing
(Palestinian) sovereignty,'' something Israel rejects.
	   However, Bar-Illan said later that Israel had not officially
requested that Clinton refrain from using the airstrip.
	   The U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Clinton's final travel plans had not yet been finalized. The
official said the administration was considering the Israeli
concerns.
