<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Lesotho </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Africa withdraws more troops from Lesotho
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) _ South Africa would withdraw
another 650 peacekeeping troops from the tiny mountain kingdom of
Lesotho, the country's top military commander said Thursday.
	   The troops were among the 3,500 South African and Botswanan
troops that entered Lesotho in September to quell an army mutiny
and unrest linked to a May election.
	   The ruling party won by a landslide but opposition parties
claimed the election was rigged. Lesotho's bickering opposition
parties have since agreed to a proposed interim committee that will
prepare for new elections.
	   The arrival of the troops triggered widescale rioting and
firebombing in the capital of Maseru, and scores of South Africans
and Lesotho citizens died.
	   The 650 troops would be withdrawn starting Sunday, the National
Defense Force Chief Siphiwe Nyanda said. The step is part of a
gradual withdrawal that began last month.
	   After the withdrawal, 750 South African and 350 Botswanan troops
will be left in the country.
	   Nyanda said the decision to withdraw more troops resulted from
the restoration of normalcy to Lesotho.
	   The Southern African Development Community, a regional
organization of 14 countries, made the original decision to help
the Lesotho government restore order.
	   ``This further down-scaling of the force is a clear indication
of the success of the efforts by the SADC soldiers,'' Nyanda said.
	   Lesotho, which has a population of 2 million, is a poor,
mountainous country within South Africa's borders.
	   (sapa-pr) 	   
</TEXT>
