<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Angola,0347 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Council blames renewed crisis in Angola on UNITA opposition
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The U.N. Security Council on Wednesday
blamed the renewed crisis in Angola on the former rebel group UNITA
and demanded that it disarm and adhere to a 1994 peace accord.
	   A council resolution expressed dismay that Angola appears headed
back to civil war, which has ravaged the southern African nation
for most of its nearly quarter-century of independence.
	   There have been increasing clashes between government troops and
opposition UNITA forces, and diplomats have been unable to get both
sides together to try to patch up the peace accord.
	   The resolution, approved by a 15-0 vote, extended the mission of
a U.N. observer force monitoring the peace agreement until Feb. 26.
It called on the government and especially UNITA to ensure the
safety of the observers.
	   Blaming UNITA's leadership for the current impasse in the peace
process, the council demanded that UNITA immediately withdraw from
territories it has reoccupied and comply with its obligations to
completely disarm and allow the government to operate throughout
the country.
	   The council stressed that there can be no military solution to
the conflict in Angola, and called on the government and UNITA to
cooperate fully with Secretary-General Kofi Annan's special
representative ``to seek a peaceful resolution of the crisis.''
	   Renewed fighting has chased 331,300 people from their homes
since April, bringing the total displaced population to over 1.3
million, according to U.N. officials.
	   There is no access to about 50 percent of the country, so it is
difficult to help those in need. And U.N. officials have expressed
alarm that mines are being used in the latest fighting.
	   The Security Council called on the government and especially
UNITA to cooperate with humanitarian organizations delivering
emergency relief assistance, to stop laying new mines, ``and to
respect international humanitarian, refugee and human rights law.''
</TEXT>
