<SLUG> BC-Sports-Skiing-Women-Slalom,0198 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egger leads after first run
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: Second run scheduled for 2100 GMT start. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MAMMOTH MOUNTAIN, California (AP) _ Sabine Egger of Austria,
taking advantage of an early start number, held a lead of .09
seconds over Australia's Zali Steggall after the first run of a
women's World Cup slalom on Thursday.
	   On a cold, windy day on a course that rutted early, only those
with low start numbers had a chance. Egger, who started seventh,
skied well on the steep and carried speed across the flats to
finish in 50.18 seconds.
	   Steggall, who started second, was timed in 50.27 and Urska
Hrovat of Slovenia, the third starter, was third in 50.76.
	   American Kristina Koznick was fourth as the No. 5 starter, .04
seconds back of Hrovat, who won the season-opening slalom two weeks
ago at Park City, Utah.
	   The slalom was rescheduled from Friday to Thursday by the race
jury because of an approaching storm. It proved to be a wise move,
because the fog and wind on the course would have made it
impossible to stage a super-giant slalom. Instead, that speed event
was set back to Friday, when conditions were expected to improve.
</TEXT>
