<SLUG> BC-Turkmenistan-Death Penalty </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkmenistan suspends death penalty
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Turkmenistan has become the latest former Soviet
republic to declare a moratorium on the death penalty, its foreign
minister said Thursday.
	   Boris Shikhmuradov was speaking at a conference of Europe's
security and human rights watchdog, the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe, in Oslo, Norway, the Interfax news
agency reported.
	   Turkmenistan may still hand down death sentences until the death
penalty is formally repealed, Shikhmuradov said. In the meantime,
no prisoners will be executed in this impoverished central Asian
nation.
	   Russia also declared a moratorium on the death penalty in 1996,
but its efforts to formally outlaw it have been stymied by the
opposition-dominated parliament. Ukraine, Azerbaijan and other
ex-Soviet states have also suspended it.
	   The OSCE is opening an office in Turkmenistan early next year.
	   (adc)
</TEXT>
