w2521 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-World-Churches-Openin     12-03 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World-Churches-Opening 1st Ld-Writethru,0742 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Council of Churches averts full Orthodox boycott as
</HEADLINE>
anniversary assembly opens &QL; 
 &UR; By RICHARD N. OSTLING &QC; 
 &UR; AP Religion Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ With multicultural pomp, the World
Council of Churches launched its fiftieth anniversary assembly
Thursday at a worship service that Orthodox church delegates from
Russia and Greece refused to attend.
	   The festivities opened with a drum and a trumpet heralding a
biblical reading from Leviticus 25 to announce the assembly's
theme: ``You shall hallow the fiftieth year and you shall proclaim
liberty throughout the land to all its inhabitants...''
	   But delegations from the Russian and Greek Orthodox churches _
angered over the increasingly liberal stand of some Protestant
delegations on homosexuality and other church issues _ boycotted
the ceremony.
	   A recent WCC decision would allow presentations by gay rights
advocates during the assembly's open forum.
	   Although other Orthodox delegations attended the opening
festivities, in protest they said they would send fewer
participants to the worship and business parts of the assembly.
	   The Orthodox dispute is expected to hang over the conference of
the pioneering ecumenical organization. But past and future debates
were sidelined temporarily as worshippers from every continent
gathered for the ceremonial opening in a huge open-air tent.
	   Befitting one of the most variegated Christian gatherings ever
held, the worshippers joined in chants and songs from Argentina,
India, Jamaica, Mozambique, Nigeria, Russia, Sweden, Syria,
Pakistan, Taiwan, the United States and the assembly's host nation
of Zimbabwe.
	   The 960 delegates at the assembly, which meets through December
14, come from 330 denominations on all continents, representing a
constituency of 350 million to 450 million Christians.
	   The biggest nonmember, by far, is the Roman Catholic Church. The
assembly is also being attended by 3,500 visitors.
	   Along with internal church matters the delegates are likely to
pronounce on world economic and political problems.
	   Zimbabwe's Vice President Simon Muzenda has already appealed to
the assembly for moral support in the regime's policy of
nationalizing white-owned farmlands and seeking cancellation of
international debts.
	   Muzenda is Zimbabwe's acting president while President Robert
Mugabe visits the Vatican and other centers in Europe. Mugabe, a
sharp critic of homosexuality, was openly opposed to the WCC
decision to allow gay rights advocates to speak.
	   The Orthodox delegations to the WCC have been unable to come up
with a common strategy of protest.
	   The Orthodox Bulgarian and Georgian delegations have quit the
WCC altogether.
	   Istanbul's Ecumenical Patriarchate, the symbolic center of
Eastern Orthodoxy, has decided to attend sessions without playing a
leading role.
	   The Oriental Orthodox of Africa and the Mideast will participate
in full. The Russians may vote on key matters, but symbolically
sent a radically downgraded delegation.
	   The Very Rev. Leonid Kishkovsky of the United States, one of
four Orthodox members of the WCC executive committee, said the
Russians' stand in particular ``underscores the serious challenge
faced by the ecumenical movement as a whole and the World Council
of Churches in particular.''
	   Sexual morality is not the only problem the Orthodox have with
the WCC's liberal Protestant members from Europe and North America.
	   At a crisis meeting in Thessaloniki, Greece, seven months ago,
Eastern Orthodox leaders complained that they are constantly cast
in a minority role and unable to influence ``the general trend and
ethos of the WCC.''
	   They cited inclusive language in worship, ordination of women
and ``tendencies relating to religious syncretism'' (the mingling
of Christianity with other religions).
	   The issue of homosexuality also divides the western liberals
from many rapidly growing Protestant churches in the Southern
Hemisphere.
	   Contrary to pre-assembly indications the problem seems certain
to reach the floor, at least obliquely. A message from a
pre-assembly women's festival will refer to ``human sexuality in
all its diversity.''
	   Aruna Gnanadason, who runs WCC women's programs, apologized that
``our lesbian sisters'' had been left off the festival program.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-World-Churches-Opening 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
