<HEADER>
w2548 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo UPDATE   12-03 0214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, UPDATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslav parliament denounces U.S. pressure on Milosevic
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ In a show of defiance, the Yugoslav
parliament on Thursday denounced U.S. pressure on President
Slobodan Milosevic and declared support for his policy.
	   The state-run Tanjug news agency said parliament passed a
declaration ``which resolutely rejects and denounces all pressure,
threats and gross interference of the United States in the internal
matters of Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.''
	   ``The parliament fully supports Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic in his efforts to defend vital national and state
interests ...'' the declaration said.
	   The show of support for Milosevic followed intense U.S.
diplomatic activities over Kosovo and a reported change in American
policies toward Milosevic. State Department spokesman James Rubin
blamed Milosevic earlier this week for much of the Balkan troubles,
adding that the Serb leaders' grip on power was weakening.
	   Tanjug said the declaration was prompted by ``attacks of the
American administration against our country and its interests.''
Pro-Western deputies from Montenegro, the smaller republic which
forms Yugoslavia together with Serbia, did not attend the session.
	   (jg)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, UPDATE; CT:i; 
