and has warned repeatedly that it would resort to printing money
unless it gets more foreign loans.
	   While Camdessus showed no sign of releasing the IMF money, he
praised Primakov's ``pragmatic'' course in dealing with the crisis,
and said an IMF team would return to Russia next month for further
negotiations. A World Bank delegation is due in Moscow next week.
	   The IMF, World Bank and other lenders froze a dlrs 22.6 billion
aid package to Russia after the government defaulted on its
treasury debts and devalued the ruble in August.
	   The speaker of the lower house of parliament called Thursday for
breaking with the IMF and cranking up the money-printing presses.
	   ``Look how they are mocking our government, sending one group
after another,'' said Gennady Seleznyov, a Communist. ``Now
Camdessus has come and again asked us to wait until tomorrow.''
	   Seleznyov suggested that Russia print money to pay off its debts
and then refuse to take any more loans.
	   ``It's high time to take these shackles off Russia's feet,'' he
told reporters.
	   The leader of the reformist party Our Home is Russia ridiculed
Seleznyov's proposal. ``If the IMF accepted rubles for debt
payments, it would be a brilliant method,'' Alexander Shokhin said
on the ``Hero of the Day'' television program.
	   Russia has also asked foreign creditors to restructure payments
of dlrs 9 million in Soviet-era debts due next year, former deputy
Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov said Thursday.
	   ``We cannot repay this money,'' Nemtsov was quoted as saying by
the Interfax news agency.
	   Inflation has calmed since shooting up in August and September,
and stood at 5.7 percent in November, the State Statistics
Committee said Thursday. But inflation is up about 70 percent since
last December.
	   Officials have said that international loans would help it keep
inflation under 30 percent in 1999.
	   Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, apparently still hopeful about
IMF money, said Thursday the government needs to come up with a
more detailed plan for economic recovery.
	   Primakov's government has produced a general anti-crisis
program, but the measures have not reversed the country's economic
slide, nor have they found favor with the IMF.
	   Also Thursday, the giant state-savings bank, Sberbank freed up
individual accounts that were transferred to the bank months ago
from six commercial banks crippled by the crisis.
	   (ad/adc)
</TEXT>
