<HEADLINE>
Minister says Pakistani sugar imports hurt Indian producers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ A Cabinet minister told Parliament
Thursday that sugar imports from neighbor and longtime rival
Pakistan should be stopped because they hurt domestic producers.
	   Replying to questions from lawmakers, Parliamentary Affairs
Minister M.L. Khurana was quoted by Dow Jones News Service as
saying ``some steps should be undertaken to stop (imports from
Pakistan) .... Some will be taken very soon in a day or two. Some
final decision will be taken.''
	   ``The government of India agrees with the view that Indian sugar
should be protected because it is suffering due to imports from
Pakistan,'' he said in Hindi.
	   India allowed zero-duty sugar imports until April 28 this year
when it imposed a 5 percent import duty plus an 850 rupees (dlrs
20) a ton countervailing duty.
	   Domestic producers have long been demanding higher duties to
protect them from cheap imports from neighboring Pakistan.
</TEXT>
