<SLUG> BC-Israel-Goldstein's Grave </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Court delays removal of tributes from killer's tombstone
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel's Supreme Court issued a temporary
injunction against a government decision Thursday to remove the
words `holy' and `martyr' from the tombstone of a Jewish settler
who massacred 29 Muslim worshipers.
	   The gunman, New York-born Baruch Goldstein, opened fire on the
Palestinian worshipers in the Tomb of the Patriarchs in the West
Bank town of Hebron in February 1994, and was killed by survivors
of the attack.
	   Goldstein was called a hero by fellow settlers and was buried in
the center of the nearby Jewish settlement of Kiryat Arba. The
Israeli army, which is responsible for administering the West Bank,
decided two months ago to delete the words of praise from the
inscription on the tombstone in an effort to discourage Jewish
extremists from making pilgrimages to the site.
	   In its decision the army invoked a new law making it illegal to
erect monuments to militants.
	   However, Goldstein's father Israel Goldstein petitioned the
Supreme Court to prevent any changes at the tomb, which includes
elaborate lighting, benches, a glass cabinet for prayer books, a
limestone plaza and rose bushes.
	   The Supreme Court Thursday issued a temporary injunction against
the changes and ordered the government to show cause within 45 days
why the words of praise should be deleted.
	   Goldstein said Thursday at the court that his son really was a
saint. ``People came to us with tears in their eyes when we were
sitting shiva (in mourning) saying: your son saved us. We would
have been there later on. They found weapons there.''
	   The court's decision on whether the army may delete the words
from the tombstone will be given at a later date.
