<HEADLINE>
Prime Minister says French economy will grow 2.7 percent in 1999
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said on Thursday that
the French economy would grow 2.7 percent in 1999, a day after his
Finance Minister said the country couldn't meet that target.
	   Jospin told the French parliament that growth would be achieved
if consumption were to hold up and if there was a pickup in
investment as a result of consumer spending.
	   On Wednesday, Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn said
France could not meet the 2.7 percent growth target because of the
international financial crisis.
	   Jospin's comments came as 11 European central bank in their
first coordinated move ahead of the introduction of Europe's new
single currency cut interest rates to 3.0 percent, except Italy,
which cut its rate to 3.5 percent.
	   Following the announcement of the rate cut, Bank of France
Governor Jean-Claude Trichet would not comment on his expectations
for 1999 French growth, saying the international environment
remains uncertain.
	   (dj-dgs) 	   
