<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Shrine Controversy, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0380 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police patrol, Hindu fundamentalists pray
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with details of minor stone throwing incident. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BANGALORE, India (AP) _ Hundreds of police officers patrolled a
southern Indian shrine where Hindus and Muslims have traditionally
worshipped together in peace, fearing violence as Hindu
fundamentalists held a rally.
	   A gathering held by the Vishwa Hindu Parishad, or World Hindu
Council, started with prayers and was fairly peaceful, except for
stone-throwing by a few young men that was quickly quelled, United
News of India said.
	   The council, known as the VHP, says the Muslim family that has
traditionally maintained the site, located in the southern Indian
city of Chikamagalur, should hand it over to Hindus.
	   The VHP, a sister organization of the Bharatiya Janata Party
that leads India's national governing coalition, initially
threatened to take over the site by force, but later said it only
planned to hold a rally.
	   Muslims believe a Sufi holy man is buried in a cave. Hindus say
one of their gods entered the cave in ancient times and
disappeared, but will one day re-emerge at the site 300 kilometers
(190 miles) south of the Karnataka state capital of Bangalore.
	   A top security official, Phillipose Matthai, said some VHP
activists hurled rocks at a restaurant that served fish, which
protesters said violated the custom of local Hindus to eat only
vegetarian food on important days of the religious calendar.
	   Police quickly restored peace in the area and no arrests were
made, Matthai said.
	   Some 10,000 people, mostly VHP activists, took part in the
rally, he said. However, Matthai said most of the local residents
stayed away.
	   More than 2,000 police officers were deployed at barricades
erected to control crowds.
	   The tussle over the shrine comes just days before the sixth
anniversary of the day a Hindu mob tore down a mosque at Ayodhya in
northern India.
	   The campaign to raze the mosque _ believed by some Hindus to be
located at the birthplace of their god Ram _ was spearheaded by the
VHP.
	   The Ayodhya issue helped bring the BJP to political prominence,
while the mosque's destruction sparked a wave of deadly religious
rioting across India.
</TEXT>
