<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Germany-Athletes of the Year </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Skier Seizinger, luger Hackl win annual awards in Germany
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BADEN-BADEN, Germany (AP) _ Georg Hackl, the three-time Olympic
luge champion, and Katja Seizinger, the two-time Olympic downhill
champion, were crowned Germany's athletes of the year Thursday.
	   In the traditional year-end poll of Germany's sports
journalists, the Bundesliga champion Kaiserslautern won the title
of the Team of the Year.
	   Hackl, 32, won his third consecutive Olympic gold medal at the
Winter Games in Nagano in February.
	   He collected 3,444 votes to beat Jan Ullrich, the 1997 Tour de
France winner and second in this year's race, who got 1,879 votes.
Discus thrower Lars Riedel, who added the European title this year
to his Olympic and world titles, got 1,717 votes to take third
place.
	   Seizinger, 26, became the first woman to retain the Olympic
downhill title. She won another gold medal in Nagano and also
clinched the World Cup title.
	   After winning the Athlete of the Year poll also in 1994 and
1996, Seizinger earned her third honor by receiving 3,751 votes.
Seizinger has been out of action this season after knee surgery.
	   Sprinter Grit Breuer, the European 400-meter champion, finished
second with 2,192 and Olympic speedskating champion Gunda
Niemann-Stirnemann was third with 2,138 votes.
	   (ns)	   
</TEXT>
