<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-French Roundup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lyon upsets leader Bordeaux; Marseille concedes late equalizer
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Lyon scored a 2-1 win over league leader Bordeaux
on Thursday, but second-placed Marseille failed to take the chance
to regain top spot, conceding a late penalty to draw 1-1 at
Auxerre.
	   After an even first half, Lyon outclassed Bordeaux, which had a
one point lead over Marseille at the start of play.
	   Steed Malbranque, the 18-year-old midfielder reported to be a
target for English champion Arsenal, created both goals.
	   In the 51st minute, Malbranque played a one-two to break through
the Bordeaux defense. His first shot was saved by goalkeeper Ulrich
Rame and his follow up struck the post, but Alain Caveglia buried
the rebound.
	   Vikash Dhorasoo scored the second after Malbranque had stormed
down the right and again had his shot stopped by Rame.
	   Sylvain Wiltord pulled one back for the league leader in the
82nd minute, his 11th goal of the season.
	   Lyon, which beat Marseille in its last home match, moved up to
fourth with the win.
	   At Auxerre, Laurent Blanc put Marseille in the lead with a
classy 60th minute goal against his former team.
	   But seven minutes from time, Daniel Bravo, standing on his goal
line, handled a goal-bound Auxerre shot.
	   Stephane Carnot scored from the penalty spot.
	   Bravo was also shown the red card for the infringement.
	   Earlier, Auxerre's Steve Marlet hit post with a sharp 15 yard
(meter) shot.
	   Monaco, returning to full strength after an early-season injury
crisis, easily beat Nancy 3-0 to move into third place, 11 points
behind Bordeaux, and keep alive its slim championship hopes.
	   David Trezeguet scored a pair, bringing his season's total to
eight. Victor Ikpeba also got on the scoresheet.
	   (ae)
</TEXT>
