w2672 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-Italian     12-03 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italian Cup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Salas' double leads Lazio past Ronaldo-less Inter 2-1
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Chile's Marcelo Salas struck early in each half
Thursday to give defending Italian Cup titlist Lazio of Rome a 2-1
win over Internazionale of Milan and new coach Mircea Lucescu in a
first-leg quarterfinal.
	   Salas connected on a penalty kick 13 minutes into the game and
then was left completely alone to slot in a left-wing cross from
steps away in the 46th.
	   In between, French striker Youri Djorkaeff scored for Inter in
the 30th with a beautifully lofted 18-meter (yard) free kick that
tucked under the crossbar.
	   Lazio has now defeated Inter two straight times since losing to
the Milan club in last season's UEFA Cup final.
	   Inter was without two-time FIFA Player of the Year Ronaldo, who
told the Gazzetta dello Sport newspaper for Thursday's editions
that his return to full health will take time.
	   ``At this point, we have decided to go forward day by day,
without making plans,'' the Brazilian was quoted as saying. ``When
I am completely healed, I will say so and I will play.''
	   Hampered by knee tendinitis, the striker has missed two-thirds
of the club's matches this season.
	   Fellow forwards Roberto Baggio and Nicola Ventola also missed
the game for Inter.
	   But Lazio had good news on the injury front, as national team
defender Alessandro Nesta played for the first time since he tore
right knee ligaments at the World Cup.
	   He came off the substitutes bench at the start of the second
half.
	   Lucescu, a Romanian, joined Inter on Tuesday, the day after
predecessor Luigi Simoni was fired.
	   Three players who received yellow cards will miss the second
leg, slated for Jan. 26: Inter defender Fabio Galante and Lazio
midfielders Dejan Stankovic of Yugoslavia and Pavel Nedved of the
Czech Republic.
	   In earlier quarterfinals, Atalanta of Bergamo, the only
second-division club left in the competition, rallied for a 3-2
upset of Serie A leader Fiorentina on Wednesday, and Udinese beat
AC Parma 3-2 Tuesday.
	   Juventus plays Bologna Jan. 13 in a match postponed when UEFA
moved the Turin club's political charged Champions League match at
Turkey's Galatasaray to this week.
	   (hjf)
</TEXT>
