<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Milosevic,0296 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With Yugoslavia-Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Yugoslav parliament denounces U.S. pressure on Milosevic &QL; 
 &UR; By JOVANA GEC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ In a show of defiance, the Yugoslav
parliament on Thursday denounced ``destructive'' U.S. policies in
the Balkans and declared support for President Slobodan Milosevic.
	   A declaration, approved by the assembly, accused the United
States of ``directly supporting separatism and terrorism and
financing the adversaries'' of Yugoslavia, according to a text
distributed by the state-run Tanjug news agency.
	   The strongly-worded declaration followed intensified U.S.
diplomatic efforts over Kosovo and a reported change of American
policies toward Milosevic.
	   Washington has blamed Milosevic for instigating ethnic conflict
in the Balkans and imposed diplomatic and economic sanctions
against his government. But since 1995 it has also worked closely
with the Yugoslav leader in efforts to ensure a lasting peace in
Bosnia.
	   This week, however, State Department spokesman James Rubin
claimed the Milosevic's grip on power was weakening. Some media
reports suggested the Clinton administration was prepared to
opponents of the regime inside Yugoslavia itself.
	   The U.S. ``presents support for separatism and terrorism in
Kosovo, causing destabilization of the region,'' the declaration
said.
	   ``The parliament fully supports Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic in his efforts to defend vital national and state
interests ...,'' it said.
	   Reformist deputies from Montenegro, who enjoy U.S. support, did
not attend the session, not did some opposition deputies from
Serbia. The republics of Montenegro and Serbia make up the
Yugoslavia federation.
</TEXT>
