<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Copa America,0265 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Paraguay's Oviedo still heads Copa America despite legal troubles
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) _ A former general will remain the chief
organizer of the 1999 Copa America tournament despite his mounting
legal troubles, Paraguayan league officials said Thursday.
	   Paraguay's Supreme Court on Wednesday ordered that former Gen.
Lino Cesar Oviedo return to jail to finish serving out his 10-year
sentence for rebellion.
	   However his layers argue the ruling doesn't mean a return to
prison for Oviedo, because a military tribunal organized by
President Raul Cubas had already overturned the previous military
court ruling.
	   But congressional critics are pressing for his return to jail.
	   Oviedo was convicted in March by an armed forces' court for
refusing an order by then-President Juan Carlos Wasmosy to resign
as army chief-of-staff in April 1996, setting off a crisis that
tested Paraguay's young democracy.
	   He was released from prison in August by a presidential decree
from Cubas, who later named him head of Paraguay's effort to host
the South American championship.
	   ``Oviedo is not going to prison according to his lawyers...and
he will continue as the head coordinator of the Copa America,''
said Jose Medina, a Paraguayan Football Federation official.
	   Medina added that Oviedo had already resumed working to improve
the country's highly underdeveloped infrastructure which still
remain a huge obstacle in pulling off next year's tournament.
	   Copa America is scheduled for July 1-18.
</TEXT>
