w2713 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Skiing-Women-S 1stLd-Writethru   12-03 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Skiing-Women-Slalom, 1st Ld-Writethru,0490 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swedish teen wins first World Cup race
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with second run. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MAMMOTH MOUNTAIN, California (AP) _ Anja Paerson of Sweden, a
17-year-old circuit rookie, stunned a veteran field by coming from
15th place to win a women's World Cup slalom by .01 seconds over
Australia's Zali Steggall.
	   Paerson, as the 15th-place finisher in the first run, had the
advantage of starting first in the afternoon session, and
capitalized, recording a time of 48.82 seconds that was 1.08
seconds faster than anyone else.
	   She completed two runs in a combined 1 minute, 40.84 seconds on
a gray, windy, icy cold day at this resort in the Sierra.
	   ``I just wanted to come down and make points. Winning, I can't
believe it,'' Paerson said. ``I know I was fast but not that fast.
They were two seconds before me.''
	   Steggall, the Olympic slalom bronze medalist last year, held a
1.75-second lead over Paerson after the first run, but even that
huge margin wasn't enough to get her past the Swedish teen.
	   ``It's tough, but it's the way racing goes,'' Steggall said.
``You never know when maybe it'll be your day and you'll be on top.
I had two good runs in really tough conditions, with the wind and
the ruts.''
	   Ingrid Salvenmoser of Austria, seventh after the first run,
claimed third on the day in 1:41.29. She had the second-fastest
afternoon run, but at 49.90 seconds it was over a second slower
than Paerson.
	   Paerson's eyes grew wide when Pernilla Wiberg, a former World
Cup overall champion and the top star of the Swedish team, came in
1.05 seconds behind. As succeeding racers tried and failed to
overcome her time, Paerson stood with Wiberg, shaking her head and
grinning.
	   ``Pernilla told me, `You're going to win,' but I said, `No
way,''' Paerson said. ``I mean, I was two seconds back of the
leaders!''
	   When first-run leader Sabine Egger of Austria finished in
1:41.49, the other Swedish racers cheered and crowded around their
newest star, slapping her on the back.
	   Paerson became the third racer from her little village of
Tarnaby to win a World Cup race. The first and most famous was
Ingemar Stenmark, whose 86 victories still ranks tops among all
racers in World Cup history. Stig Strand, who grew up next door to
Stenmark and just a few blocks from Paerson, won two races and
shared the 1983 World Cup slalom title with Stenmark.
	   Paerson said she has skied many times with Stenmark while
growing up, absorbing little racing tips from him. Her first
victory mirrored that of her skiing partner, who came from 17th
place for his first slalom victory back in 1974.
	   After Egger in fourth, Wiberg and Norway's Trine Bakke tied for
fifth. Slovenia's Urska Hrovat, winner of the season-opening slalom
at Park City, Utah two weeks ago, was seventh, followed by
Germany's Martina Ertl and the Swiss duo of Sonja nef and Karin
Roten.
</TEXT>
