<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Canada-Tax Breaks,0497 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Canadian lawmakers propose tax breaks for pro sports teams
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DAVID CRARY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TORONTO (AP) _ Seeking to prevent more Canadian teams from
leaving for the United States, a parliamentary subcommittee
Thursday recommended federal tax breaks for professional franchises
and athletes.
	   But opposition lawmakers objected to the plan, saying it would
be politically unacceptable to help out millionaire owners and
players at a time when many other Canadians face hard times.
	   The committee's report was compiled after months of public
hearings that included testimony from the owners of Canada's six
National Hockey League teams.
	   Noting that NHL teams from Quebec City and Winnipeg had moved to
the United States, the owners said it was difficult to compete with
U.S. franchises which paid less taxes and used publicly financed
arenas.
	   Under the subcommittee proposal, a franchise would be eligible
for a dlrs 5-million (dlrs 3.3-million U.S.) tax credit on its
first dlrs 50 million (dlrs 33 million) in revenues. Teams with
greater revenues would get a lower rate of tax break and those with
revenues over dlrs 80 million (dlrs 52 million U.S.) would not
qualify.
	   To qualify for the breaks, teams would have to boost their
support of local amateur sports, making their arenas available on a
regular basis and encouraging community involvement by players.
	   The report also recommends a lower tax burden for pro athletes.
	   The entire subcommittee backed most of the recommendations in
the report, which dealt largely with amateur sport. But the four
opposition parties refused to join the governing Liberal Party in
endorsing tax breaks.
	   ``We have a health care system in dire straights, we have a
country that pays too much tax. At the same time, we're talking
about giving rebates to millionaire hockey teams,'' said Inky Mark
of the right-wing Reform Party. ``It just wouldn't fly.''
	   Dennis Mills, the Liberal legislator who chaired the
subcommittee, said pro sports owners had a duty to address the
issue of skyrocketing player salaries. But he said it would be
foolish for Canada to make no policy changes, and risk losing three
or four more NHL teams.
	   ``The easy way out, but I think somewhat irresponsible, would be
to just say, `Let them all go,''' he said.
	   Among other recommendations in the report:
	   _Canadian TV networks should concentrate on more home-grown
events, and perhaps be restricted in how many U.S. sport programs
they can show.
	   _The justice minister should consider legalizing sports
wagering.
	   _Families with children competing in amateur sports should be
eligible for tax credits to compensate for the costs of
registration and equipment.
	   The fate of the recommendations probably depends on which
receive backing over the coming months from Prime Minister Jean
Chretien and his Cabinet.
</TEXT>
