<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Boxing-Tapia-Konadu,0375 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Johnny Tapia's only losses have all been outside the ring
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOHN CURRAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATLANTIC CITY, New Jersey (AP) _ To unbeaten bantamweight Johnny
Tapia, there's no time like the present. With a past like his, who
can blame him?
	   ``I forgot yesterday, 'cause it's gone. And I don't think about
tomorrow, because it may never come,'' he says.
	   His father was murdered when he was still in his mother's womb.
When he was 8, his mother was murdered. Tapia, meanwhile, survived
a bus crash, a long battle with cocaine addiction, a series of jail
terms and a 3 1/2-year ban from fighting.
	   ``Sometimes I ask, `Why did I have to go through so many
obstacle courses to get where I am?' But I'm still here,'' he said
Thursday.
	   Tapia, 31, of Albuquerque, New Mexico, puts his 44-0-2 record on
the line Saturday against WBA bantamweight champion Nana Konadu in
the main event of a Don King fight card at the Atlantic City
Convention Center.
	   In the co-feature, WBA welterweight champion James Page takes on
No. 1 contender Jose Luis Lopez.
	   Tapia's career got a boost last year, when he won a 12-round
decision over Albuquerque arch rival Danny Romero. In his last
outing Aug. 29, he posted a 10-round decision over Carlos
Hernandez.
	   But he says he isn't taking the champion Konadu lightly.
	   ``He's no pushover. He's the best and the strongest at 118,''
Tapia said.
	   Konadu, 33, of Sunyani, Ghana, won his title in 1996, lost it
nine months later to Daorung Chuwatana and then won it back in a
1997 rematch with Chuwatana. This year, he has won both of his
fights.
	   ``I'll go in and fight my 12 rounds. That's all,'' was all
Konadu had to say at a news conference Thursday.
	   The fight card is the first in Atlantic City promoted by Don
King since 1990.
	   King was barred from doing business with casinos in 1994 because
of a an indictment in New York state, but the ban was lifted this
year when he was cleared of the charge.
	   He missed Thursday's news conference, however. He was in Los
Angeles promoting the March 13 heavyweight championship fight
between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis, a spokesman said.
</TEXT>
