<SLUG> BC-Japan-Standard and Poor's-New Indexes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Standard and Poor's and TSE in talks to create new stock indexes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: `Standard and Poor's' and `S and P' both take ampersands &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Standard and Poor's said it is in talks with the
Tokyo Stock Exchange about a possible tie-up to create new indexes
based on Japanese and Asian stock markets.
	   New York-based Standard and Poor's, the creator of the widely
used U.S. stock index the S and P 500, said in a statement Thursday
that the two sides hoped to reach an agreement next year.
	   They will also consider developing futures, options and other
securities based on the new indexes, the statement said.
	   While the statement didn't go into detail, it suggested these
securities would be created for Japanese investors and possibly
traded in Japan.
	   ``The objective is to provide ... investable equity indices, as
well as index related products, that would give Japanese companies
greater exposure to global investors,'' the statement said.
	   An official for the Tokyo Stock Exchange, a company that runs
Japan's largest stock exchange, confirmed that discussions were
under way but said no decisions have been reached.
	   The Tokyo Stock Exchange compiles Japan's version of the S and P
500: the Tokyo Stock Price Index, or TOPIX, which gives an average
price of the country's 1,300 largest listed companies.
 &UR; (mef-dj)
