<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Child Murders </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Man, 86, questioned over 1970 child murders
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ An 86-year-old man will appear in
court Friday charged with one of Australia's most infamous crimes _
the abduction and sex murder of two young sisters in north
Queensland almost 30 years ago, police said.
	   Sisters Judith Mackay, 7, and Susan Mackay, 5, were raped,
strangled and stabbed after they were abducted from a bus stop only
1,000 feet (300 meters) from their family home in Aitkenvale in
August 1970.
	   Their naked bodies were found in a dry creek bed south of
Townsville two days later, sparking one of the biggest manhunts in
Australian history.
	   Police questioned the man Thursday for several hours before
arresting him.
	   He is also expected to be questioned over the disappearance of
14-year-old Marilyn Wallman who vanished while cycling to school in
Mackay, 205 miles (330 km) south of Townsville, in March 1972.
	   Her body has never been found.
	   The elderly man is believed to have worked as a
government-employed carpenter in schools in the Townsville area,
including the Mackay sisters' Aitkenvale school.
	   It is understood a breakthrough in the investigation occurred
when the man's granddaughters supplied information to police.
	   Police yesterday successfully applied to the Townsville
Magistrates Court to take a DNA sample from the man. 	   
</TEXT>
