<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Twins-Molitor,0165 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Molitor says playing days are over
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos MP105, MP106 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) _ Paul Molitor refused to use the word
retirement, but all indications are his 21-year baseball career is
over.
	   The Minnesota Twins star said Thursday he has decided to end his
playing career.
	   ``My heart tells me I'm done,'' he said at a news conference.
	   In the next breath, Molitor said he wants to look at other
opportunities and refused to call his announcement a retirement.
	   But Molitor, 42, said he will not accept offers from the
Milwaukee Brewers or Toronto Blue Jays.
	   The Brewers had been talking to Molitor about a front-office
job. Molitor said earlier this month he had been contacted by
several teams, both about playing and off-field possibilities.
	   Molitor played his first 15 seasons in Milwaukee, three with
Toronto and his last three with Minnesota. He's eighth on the
career hits list after 21 seasons.
</TEXT>
