<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0669 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   Here is a summary of news from The Associated Press. Stories
carried ``i'' or ``f'' category codes. Some of the items below have
moved on this circuit in expanded form:
	   JERUSALEM_ In defiance of the United States, Israel's prime
minister said Thursday he will not back down from a decision to
suspend the Wye River peace agreement over what called Palestinian
violations. ``We are not to be made fools,'' said an angry Benjamin
Netanyahu, who won unanimous backing from his Cabinet ministers
after they watched footage of an attack on an Israeli soldier by a
Palestinian mob. Ministers watched a video of Wednesday's brutal
attack. When the tape ended, the decision was unanimous: Israel
would suspend its West Bank troop withdrawal. The latest crisis to
plague the Mideast peace accord cast a pall over the upcoming visit
of U.S. President Bill Clinton, just days before he was to arrive
in the region to oversee implementation of the second phase of the
deal he helped broker. (ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS)
	   ALGIERS, Algeria _ A homemade bomb exploded Thursday at a market
in western Algeria, killing 14 people and injuring 23 others, local
police said. The bomb went off in the morning in the Ain Defla
area, about 125 kilometers (80 miles) west of Algiers, police said.
It was the sixth violent attack in a week, and came the day that
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan met Algeria's president to try to
end the conflict in the Western Sahara. The Muslim holy month of
Ramadan, which begins this year on Dec. 20, has been marred by
waves of violence since the insurgency began. Twelve villagers were
slaughtered in their sleep early Wednesday in the Sidi Rached
region about 60 miles (100 kilometers) west of Algiers. (ALGERIA)
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands _ A key Bosnian Serb general arrested by
NATO troops on genocide charges commanded the soldiers who executed
thousands of Muslims fleeing the U.N. safe haven of Srebrenica, his
U.N. indictment revealed Thursday. Gen. Radislav Krstic, seized by
U.S. members of the NATO peacekeeping force on Wednesday, is the
most senior Serb military officer arrested so far in the effort to
bring to trial Bosnians accused of war crimes. Krstic arrived late
Thursday in The Hague, where the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal will
try him for genocide, war crimes, crimes against humanity and grave
breaches of the Geneva Conventions. An arraignment date has not
been set. Details of his indictment _ unsealed and made public
Thursday _ allege that troops under his command committed offenses
after the rebel Serb takeover of the U.N. safe haven of Srebrenica
in eastern Bosnia in July 1995. (BOSNIA-WAR CRIMES)
	   WASHINGTON _ Paintings by old masters such as Picasso and
Cezanne that were confiscated from Jews by Nazi Germany could be
returned to prewar owners or their heirs or sold to benefit
Holocaust survivors under guidelines endorsed Thursday by 44
countries at a conference in Washington. The international meeting,
designed to get nations, museums, galleries and individuals to
reexamine collections and archives in an unprecedented post-World
War II search, produced an immediate breakthrough: The Russian
delegation delivered documents on art looted from Austrian Jews
including one that listed 700 pieces the Nazis confiscated in
Vienna before World War II. (HOLOCAUST-CONFERENCE)
	   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Republicans jettisoned campaign fund raising
from their impeachment inquiry on Thursday, likely clearing the way
for a vote next week on President Bill Clinton's relationship with
a White House intern and his effort to cover it up. At the same
time, incoming Speaker Bob Livingston signaled his desire for the
full House to meet before Christmas to vote on any articles of
impeachment the committee approves. ``If the Judiciary Committee
could complete its work next week, it would be my expectation that
we could have a vote on the following week,'' the Republican leader
said. (CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT)
</TEXT>
