</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0847 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The Dow industrials plunged back below 9,000
Thursday, nearly posting its second 200-point loss of the week, as
a fourth straight day of profit-taking finally seeped into the
technology sector. Extending a rapid retreat from the new high set
just last week, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 184.86
points _ or by 2 percent _ to 8,879.68, about 500 points below the
record of 9,374.27 set Nov. 23. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Making their first collective decision
about monetary policy, the 11 European nations launching a common
currency on Jan. 1 cut interest rates Thursday in a surprise move
that won market confidence. Ten of the 11 countries joining
European economic union dropped their key interest rate to 3
percent, with Portugal making the most significant plunge, from
3.75 percent. Austria made the smallest cut, from 3.2 percent. The
exception was Italy, which cut from 4 to 3.5 percent. It is
expected to drop to the common rate by the time the euro is
launched. Unifying the interest rate is a critical step in laying
the groundwork for monetary union. (EUROPE-INTEREST RATES)
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ European Central Bank President Wim
Duisenberg on Thursday suggested governments reform rigid labor
markets to create jobs rather than pressure him to cut interest
rates. ``The high unemployment rate in Europe is far more the
consequence of structural rigidities within the European labor and
product markets than a result of adverse cyclical developments,''
Duisenberg said in a speech. Duisenberg has been under pressure
from the left-leaning French and German governments to lower rates
when his bank takes over monetary policy for the 11 nations that
adopt the euro currency on Jan. 1. With inflation in the euro-zone
nations at just 1 percent, and unemployment stubbornly high at 10.9
percent, governments are urging Duisenberg to boost business by
setting lower rates. (EU-CENTRAL BANK)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The productivity of U.S. workers grew at a
healthy 3 percent annual rate over the summer even as manufacturers
struggled with sales lost to the Asian economic slump. The increase
in the productivity of nonfarm, nonsupervisory workers in the
July-September quarter _ measured as output per hour of work _ was
even better than the 2.3 percent seasonally adjusted rate reported
in an initial estimate last month. Economists said Thursday's
report from the Labor Department shows that businesses, especially
manufacturers, have been quick to economize to preserve profit
margins threatened by the loss of export sales to Asia and other
economically troubled parts of the world. (US-ECONOMY)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's giant state savings bank on Thursday
finally freed up some individual accounts transferred months ago
from six huge ailing private banks, news reports said. The economic
crisis that hit in August crippled the country's six largest
commercial banks. They reacted by freezing private accounts, saying
they had no money to repay depositors, prompting public outrage and
massive crowds at the few banks that were releasing money. The
government in September offered the depositors to transfer their
accounts from the troubled banks to the state Sberbank, saying all
deposits would be guaranteed. However, all foreign-currency
deposits were to be paid out in rubles _ and at about half the
current exchange rate. (RUSSIA-BANKS)
	   PARIS (AP) _ Labor unrest escalated across France on Thursday,
with rail workers on strike, jobless protesters marching to demand
a year-end government bonus, and school monitors walking off the
job. The rail strike, which began last Friday, hit 20 out of 23
regions, with services severely disrupted. The strike was set to
continue Friday. Rail workers say there is insufficient staff and
are concerned about how the government will implement a plan to cut
the work week from 39 to 35 hours. Many workers fear a 35-hour
week, aimed at spreading jobs around and cutting unemployment, will
lead to salary cuts. (FRANCE-STRIKES)
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Transatlantic trade relations took a
turn for the worse Thursday with the European Union calling U.S.
demands over a banana dispute ``ridiculous,'' and warning
Washington's threat of sanctions bodes ill for next year's world
trade negotiations. Chief EU trade negotiator Leon Brittan appealed
to U.S. authorities to reconsider a European proposal to settle the
banana dispute at a special panel at the World Trade Organization
instead of threatening sanctions. Washington alleges the new EU
banana import regime is unfair to South American distributors, most
of which are owned by U.S. companies. The WTO had already condemned
an earlier EU banana import system, but Brittan said the new regime
met all the WTO concerns. (EU-US-BANANAS)
</TEXT>
