<SLUG> BC-Jamaica-Death Row,0306 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jamaican judges to rule on death row case by January
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CARROLL ORR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ A panel of judges will rule before
January on the fate of death row inmate Neville Lewis, condemned to
hang earlier this year.
	   The Constitutional Court ruling will probably also decide
whether three prisoners scheduled for the gallows last week can be
executed. Jamaica's supreme court stayed the executions of the
convicted murderers _ Dalton Daley, Peter Blaine and Milton
Montague _ until the Constitutional Court decision.
	   In court on Thursday, lawyers representing Lewis asked the
Constitutional Court to commute his death sentence to life
imprisonment because of ``inhuman and degrading'' prison conditions
he has suffered.
	   They claimed there are flies and cockroaches in his cell, and
that there is not enough light for reading.
	   Government lawyers called the claims untrue and presented public
health inspectors, a medical doctor and a prison supervisor to
refute the complaints.
	   They also argued that a six-month limit on death-row appeals
imposed by the government does not conflict with the Inter American
Convention on Human Rights, which Jamaica has signed but plans to
abandon.
	   Some Caribbean countries accuse the Interamerican Human Rights
Commission, which was created by the convention, of deliberately
delaying its appeals from prisoners in member nations to prevent
hangings.
	   On Oct. 15, the Bahamas ignored a last-minute protest by the
commission and hanged two convicted killers.
	   Jamaica, Guyana, Trinidad and other Caribbean countries say the
death penalty deters crime linked to drug trafficking in the
region. Together, they have resisted pressure from Britain to
eliminate executions in its former colonies.
</TEXT>
