<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Davis Cup,0393 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italy's No. 2 player could be key to Davis Cup final
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous; first singles match scheduled to start at
1330 GMT. &QL; 
 &UR; By PIERO VALSECCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ After a rough start, Davide Sanguinetti is
on a Davis Cup hot streak.
	   Italy's No. 2 singles player debuted in tennis' team competition
with a straight-set first-round loss against India in April. Since
then, though, he's undefeated in Davis Cup matches that count.
	   And Sanguinetti may be the key player in the best-of-5 final
against defending champion Sweden, which opened Friday.
	   ``Playing at home and on clay could give us an extra kick,''
said Sanguinetti, an UCLA student in economics who turned pro in
1993.
	   The 26-year-old was scheduled to take on Sweden's Magnus
Gustafsson in the second singles match Friday, following the match
between Italy's No. 1 Andrea Gaudenzi and Magnus Norman.
	   ``It brings me good luck to play after Andrea in Davis Cup
action. I hope to keep up the tradition in the final,'' said
Sanguinetti, a very consistent baseline player with a punishing
backhand passing shot.
	   He won his second match against India, both outings against
Zimbabwe in the quarterfinals, and beat favored Todd Martin in
Italy's 4-1 semifinal rout of the United States.
	   The Italian broke through with a quarterfinal run at Wimbledon
this summer and won one ATP challenger circuit title this year.
	   ``He's a player of great class, with an iron will,'' said
Italy's non-playing captain Paolo Bertolucci, who played doubles in
1976 as Italy captured its only Davis Cup title.
	   Sanguinetti had never faced Gustafsson before Friday, and had
Gaudenzi, who has been nursing a sore shoulder, had never played
Norman.
	   Sanguinetti is currently 47th in the ATP lists, three places
behind Gaudenzi.
	   Gustafsson is ranked 31st and Norman 52nd, meaning there is no
one in the ATP's top 30 playing singles in the final for the first
time in Davis Cup history.
	   Thomas Johansson, Sweden's highest-ranked player at No. 17, was
dropped from the team at the last minute because of a sore right
knee and his inconsistency on clay.
	   Jonas Bjorkman, who is ranked 24th, will only play Saturday's
doubles for Sweden, teaming with Nicklas Kulti.
</TEXT>
