<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Million Dollar Challenge,0449 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Price takes lead in first round of Million Dollar Challenge
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo
 &UR; By DANIEL WAKIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SUN CITY, South Africa (AP) _ He's five strokes off the lead and
far from the betting favorite. But the Tiger phenomenom has
definitely come to South Africa.
	   Organizers of the Million Dollar Challenge here say attendance
was up 30 percent on Thursday's opening round, which saw American
star Tiger Woods hit a level 72, in back of leader and defending
champion Nick Price, who shot a five-under 67.
	   Woods was trailed by the usual crowds as he made his way along
the 7,597-yard (6,947-meter) Gary Player Country Club course. Black
kids mobbed him during practice.
	   He said he missed ``a lot of opportunities ... and made a few
mistakes'' during his first round of African golf. He birdied on
the 2nd, 10th, 12th, 16th and 17th holes, but lost three strokes on
two consecutive holes -- a bogey on the 7th and double bogey on the
8th.
	   But he called his form ``not too bad. Obviously, it's a little
better than two months ago. I'm very pleased with the way I'm
striking the ball,'' he said. ``It feels like I'm making
progress.''
	   Price of Zimbabwe, the defending champion, was two shots up on a
three-way logjam of double Major winner Mark O'Meara, Justin
Leonard and Germany's Bernhard Langer. South African hometown hero
Ernie Els _ a seven-time veteran of the challenge and seeking his
first win _ was a shot back at 70.
	   Price had six birdies in his round, picking up shots at the
par-5 2nd, the short 7th, par-5 10th and 14th before finishing
back-to-back birdies on No. 17 and 18, both par 4.
	   ``This course likes me,'' said Price, also winner in 1993 with a
record 24-under par. ``It makes me focus a lot more than I do
normally.''
	   Unusually strong, shifting winds, more Scottish style than
African, caused some of the players to guess on the right club, he
said.
	   Price is coming off his third win at the Zimbabwe Open in four
years, closing with a Royal Harare-record 9-under-par 63 for a
five-stroke victory.
	   ``This is a game of momentum. No doubt about it,'' he said.
	   O'Meara, named U.S. player of the year last week and holder of
the U.S. Masters and British Open titles, reached 4-under to share
the lead on the 14th in the pairing ahead of Price. He surrendered
the spot when Price birdied No. 14 and O'Meara made his second
bogey of a five-birdie round on No. 15.
	   Play begins at 11:40 a.m. (0940 gmt) Friday when Jim Furyk of
the United States tees off, paired with Sweden's Jesper Parnevik.
</TEXT>
