<SLUG> BC-Guatemala-Bishop Slain,0291 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Guatemalan prosecutor resigns from case of slain bishop
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALFONSO ANZUETO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) _ The public prosecutor investigating the
bludgeoning death of Roman Catholic Bishop Juan Gerardi has said he
will resign his post and leave the case. He didn't say why.
	   The church's Human Rights Office of the Archbishop had called on
Otto Ardon Medina to step down, accusing him of wrongly accusing a
priest in the April 26 slaying.
	   Attorney General Adolfo Gonzalez Rodas will designate Ardon's
replacement. On Thursday, he said the resignation, which takes
effect Dec. 15, ``has no effect'' on the prosecution of the case.
	   The 75-year-old Gerardi was beaten to death in the garage of his
home two days after he presented a report blaming the Guatemalan
military and pro-military death squads for most of the human rights
violations committed during the country's 36-year civil war.
	   Suspicion quickly fell on soldiers or death squad members, and
church officials were shocked when the Rev. Mario Orantes Najera
was arrested July 22.
	   Monsignor Victor Martinez, president of the Episcopal Conference
of Guatemala, welcomed Ardon's resignation.
	   ``There was a public clamor for the departure of Otto Ardon. His
work was very bad,'' Martinez said.
	   A researcher with the Complutense University in Madrid had
suggested that apparent bite marks on Gerardi's body could have
been caused by a German shepherd belonging to Orantes.
	   Investigators exhumed Gerardi's body on Sept. 17 and presented a
report to Judge Isaias Figueroa Medina, who has yet to decide
whether to start judicial proceedings against Orantes as Ardon
requested in October.
</TEXT>
