<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Italy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian president begins visit to Australia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Australia's one-million strong
Italian community will be out in force from Saturday when Italian
President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro begins a seven-day official visit to
Melbourne, Canberra and Sydney.
	   Australia's Italian community is second in numbers only to those
of British descent.
	   Federal and state political leaders on both sides are keen to be
seen with the first Italian head of state to visit Australia since
the Bicentenary in 1978.
	   Scalfaro arrives in Melbourne on Saturday. Over the next two
days will be feted at a state reception thrown by Victoria state
Premier Jeff Kennett, open a new Italian education center and meet
the local Italian community.
	   In Canberra early next week, Parliament will hold an official
luncheon in his honor. President Scalfaro will talk with Prime
Minister John Howard, opposition leader Kim Beazley, the
Governor-General and will meet Canberra's Italian community.
	   A similar itinerary is scheduled for Sydney at the end of the
week with another state reception, this time thrown by New South
Wales Premier Bob Carr, and meetings with the local Italian
community.
	   Italy's ambassador to Australia Giovanni Castellaneta, said the
visit was formal recognition of the importance of Australia's
Italian community, and the relationship between Australia and
Italy.
	   ``The cultural link which unites the Italo-Australian community
to Italy and which allows second and third generations of Italians
to rediscover the authentic Italy -- does not diminish the interest
of the sons and daughters of Italians in the Australian way of life
and politics,'' he said.
	   ``On the contrary, it provides a store of knowledge without
equal and inspirational examples in areas such as industrial
innovation, family values etc., on which to base their own lives
and, by doing so, contributing to the Australian society.''
	   Italy is now Australia's 13th biggest trading partner and third
biggest in Europe with two way trade worth 3.5 billion Australian
dollars (U.S. dlrs 2.2 billion) a year and growing strongly.
	   pjs
</TEXT>
