<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0723 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexico.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Colombia, Brazil, Argentina, Guatemala and
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ Ten civilians seized at a guerrilla
roadblock were freed Thursday during clashes between rebels and
government troops in northern Colombia, the army said.
	   Five hostages remained in the hands of the rebel National
Liberation Army, which funds its operations largely through
kidnappings.
	   No deaths or injuries were reported in the fighting in rural La
Gloria, 300 miles north of the capital, Bogota.
	   Troops intercepted the rebels while they were transporting 15
people seized Wednesday, said army spokesman Luis Enrique
Hernandez. Ten of the hostages, including three children, were left
behind when the 150-rebel unit retreated. Authorities did not
identify the remaining hostages.
	   The rebels often set up random roadblocks, hoping to catch rich
Colombians or foreigners who may garner large ransoms.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ Authorities are trying a new
weapon in their crackdown on prostitution in one Brazilian town:
shame.
	   Police officers in Novo Hamburgo, 1,000 miles southwest of Rio,
will tell the families of brothel users about their loved one's
illicit activities, according to the O Jornal do Brasil daily
newspaper.
	   ``Families should know what these individuals are doing,'' local
police chief Flavio Agenor Ferraz de Amorim was quoted as saying.
	   The police policy in Novo Hamburgo, which took effect Thursday,
has upset prostitutes who say most of their customers are married
men who will now stay away, the newspaper said.
	   A local human rights group was quoted as saying the policy
violates privacy rights.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) _ Guatemala's attorney general wants to
suspend all foreign adoptions of Guatemalan children after
complaints that unscrupulous lawyers are taking advantage of poor
women.
	   Carlos Garcia Regas urged the public magistrate and the Supreme
Court on Thursday to suspend adoptions while new regulations are
drafted to better protect birth parents.
	   Human rights groups have denounced widespread abuses in
adoptions in Guatemala, saying lawyers coerce women into giving up
babies in return for fees that average dlrs 15,000.
	   In a nation of 10 million people, the attorney general's office
reviews between 170 and 200 adoption cases a month, almost all
involving foreigners. This year, the U.S. Embassy expects Americans
alone to adopt 1,000 Guatemalan children.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Logging has seriously damaged 13 butterfly
sanctuaries in central Mexico and could lead to the deaths of many
of the Monarchs that migrate each fall from Canada, an
environmental group warned Thursday.
	   The Group of 100 urged the Mexican government to halt the
logging of Mexican fir trees in the Michoacan state sanctuaries.
	   It said local authorities reported that five to 10 logging
trucks carried lumber each day from the area near El Rosario
sanctuary. The tree loss leaves the Monarchs vulnerable to sunlight
and cold, the group said.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   OAXACA CITY, Mexico (AP) _ A land dispute in the southern state
of Oaxaca this week left at least nine people dead, local
authorities said Thursday.
	   Justino Diaz Perez, mayor of Santo Domingo Teojomulco, said
three men from his town were killed in the gun battle Tuesday.
Eight were wounded and five were missing, the mayor said.
	   In neighboring San Lorenzo Texmelucan, 50 miles southwest of
Oaxaca, the president of communal property, Felix Martinez, said
six villagers had died, four were hurt and two were missing.
	   The two villages have fought for 60 years over 40 acres of land.
In the past 30 years, about 130 people have been killed in the
dispute.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ More than 300 people remain missing three
months after floods devastated the southern state of Chiapas'
coast, a newspaper reported Thursday.
	   The government's official death count relating to the week of
rain and flooding in Chiapas is 177, although estimates vary
widely. Chiapas state Secretary Rodolfo Soto Monzon said another
331 were missing, the Mexico City daily La Jornada reported.
	   The state government was planning to place newspaper ads to try
to contact those still believed missing, Soto Monzon was quoted as
saying.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ Carlos Alvarez, a leading
opposition politician, will be tapped as the vice-presidential
candidate for the Alliance coalition's 1999 ticket, local media
reported Thursday.
	   The official announcement is expected on Monday, leading daily
Clarin said, after a series of meetings between high-ranking
members of the Radical Civic Union and Frepaso parties which form
Argentina's largest opposition group, known as the Alliance.
	   Alavarez is one of the principal directors of the center-left
Frepaso party, made up of former Peronists, socialists and
Christian democrats.
	   Buenos Aires mayor Fernando De la Rua won Sunday's primary
elections to become the coalition's presidential candidate and is
widely-regarded as the early favorite in the 1999 race.
	   The Peronist party of President Carlos Menem's is scheduled to
chose its candidate in primaries scheduled for April. Buenos Aires
governor Eduardo Duahlde is largely considered as the front-runner.
</TEXT>
