w2863 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Europe-MergerFever     12-03 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Europe-Merger Fever,0606 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cutting costs rather than euro give impetus to Europe's merger wave
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PAUL AMES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Forget the euro, Europe's flurry of
billion-dollar mergers owes less to the upcoming common currency
than to old-fashioned concerns about cutting costs, reviving
flagging profits and muscling into foreign markets.
	   After a lull over the summer, European merger fever came back
with a vengeance over the past few days with a spate of
cross-border link-ups in banking, oil, pharmaceuticals and metals.
	   The imminent launch of the euro as the shared currency of 11
European nations has been seen as the catalyst for such mergers as
companies seek to combine forces to take advantage of a unified
euro-zone market of 270 million consumers.
	   But take the latest batch one-by-one, and economists say there
are more basic reasons behind them than grasping benefits of the
euro, or tackling the increased competition that comes in its wake.
	   France's Total SA grabbed Belgium's Petrofina SA for dlrs 11.76
billion on Tuesday and formed the world's 5th largest oil company.
The deal was sandwiched between British Petroleum PLC's link up
with Amoco Corp and Tuesday's huge Exxon-Mobil merger and was done
for much the same reason - staying afloat in the face of deflated
crude prices.
	   ``Oil prices have practically been cut in half over the past
year. All companies are seeking to survive in this new situation,''
said Total Chairman Thierry Desmarest. ``The business environment
will be tougher than in the past years.''
	   Traders seemed to agree, sending Total shares downward on the
deal. ``The market sees it as a merger out of desperation,'' says
Sharon Coombs, European strategist at the London office of the
investment bank HSBC James Capel.
	   Coombs sees similar doubts about the planned fusion of Germany's
Hoechst AG and Rhone-Poulenc SA of France to create one of the
world's biggest pharmaceutical concerns with a sales potential of
dlrs 20 billion.
	   ``The two companies are merging to get out of difficult
circumstances, rather than because its the right thing to do,'' she
said.
	   The companies hope the merger will save them dlrs 1.2 billion a
year. But there too investors expressed dissatisfaction.
Rhone-Poulenc stock fell 7 percent in Paris trading after the deal
was announced Monday.
	   In other deals in the last few days, Deutsche Bank took over
Bankers Trust of the United States for dlrs 10 billion to expand in
North America as the world's largest financial institution. Then it
snapped up Credit Lyonnais Belgium for dlrs 590 million.
	   Viag AG, a German industrial conglomerate, merged with the Swiss
metal maker Alusuisse Lonza Group Ltd will have a market value of
40 billion marks (dlrs 23.5 billion).
	   Although the motivation behind the megadeals differs, analysts
say the timing is linked to the rebound of stock markets after the
summer's slump. The revival makes it easier for companies to raise
cash for acquisitions.
	   ``Economic conditions have not turned out as bad as expected ...
it's refocused companies' interest,'' says Elisabeth
Waelbroeck-Rocha, European economist at the Standards and Poor
ratings agency.
	   And the euro? It may not have been spark for the latest mergers,
but it is seen encouraging more, especially in the banking,
transport and retail sector after its launch on Jan. 1, 1999.
	   ``The euro will create a real open market,'' says Betty
Pestiaux, senior researcher at Belgium's Banque Bruxelles Lambert.
``I'm sure we're just at the beginning of the merger mania.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
