<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar lower against yen, stocks slip in early trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar was sharply lower against the yen
in early trading Friday following an overnight decline on Wall
Street. Japanese stocks fell moderately.
	   The dollar bought 117.84 yen in early trading, down 1.39 yen
from late Thursday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level
of 118.60 yen overnight.
	   The U.S. currency weakened as investors were discouraged by the
continuing decline in U.S. stocks and concerns over the Brazilian
economy, traders said.
	   In New York Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell
184.86 points to 8,879.68.
	   The decline also pushed down Japanese stocks with traders saying
Friday's early trading was thin ahead of the weekend.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 83.92 points,
or 0.57 percent, to 14,613.16 in the first 30 minutes of morning
trading. On Thursday, the index had shed 289.54 points, or 1.93
percent.
	   Traders said the largely expected drop in Japan's third quarter
gross domestic product data released Thursday had little impact on
Friday's trading.
	   The Economic Planning Agency said GDP contracted 0.7 percent in
the July-September quarter from the previous quarter for an
annualized drop of 2.6 percent.
	   The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 5.21 points, or 0.46 percent, to 1,123.68. The
TOPIX fell 18.26 points, or 1.59 percent, the previous day.
	   The benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government bond fell to
1.070 percent from Thursday's close of 1.090 percent, driving its
price up to 106.31 yen from the previous day's finish of 106.13
yen.
 &UR; (may-dj)
</TEXT>
