<SLUG> BC-Thailand-American Runner </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
American running in Thailand against child prostitution
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Hoping to heighten awareness about the
problem of child prostitution, a 46-year-old American is attempting
to be the first person to run Thailand north to south, a newspaper
said Friday.
	   Butch Colvin, an ex-U.S. navy officer from Oklahoma, set off
from the town of Mai Sai along the border with Myanmar on Nov. 22.
He plans to reach the southernmost point in Thailand, on the border
with Malaysia, by February.
	   The Bangkok Post says Colvin has been rising before sunset and
running around 30 kilometers (18.6 miles) each day, stopping when
the temperatures begin to soar.
	   The newspaper says drivers sound their horns and police stop
traffic and wave as Colvin runs by.
	   ``People are asking what I'm doing. When I tell them I'm trying
to heighten awareness of child prostitution worldwide they shake my
hand,'' he was quoted as saying.
	   Thailand attracts large numbers of foreign men seeking sex with
children. A number have been arrested in recent years. 	   
</TEXT>
