<SLUG> BC-Australia-Child Murders </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
86-year-old man questioned over 1970 child murders
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous to UPDATE with man claiming innocence, ADDS
identity &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ An 86-year-old man on Friday denied
he committed one of Australia's most infamous crimes _ the
abduction and sex murder of two young sisters in north Queensland
almost 30 years ago.
	   Sisters Judith Mackay, 7, and Susan Mackay, 5, were raped,
strangled and stabbed after they were abducted from a bus stop only
1,000 feet (300 meters) from their family home in Aitkenvale in
August 1970.
	   Their naked bodies were found in a dry creek bed south of
Townsville two days later, sparking one of the biggest manhunts in
Australian history.
	   Arthur Stanley Brown, 86, was charged with the murders. A frail
old man, he sat quietly in court as his defense lawyer said he
would strenuously and unequivocally deny the charge.
	   A committal hearing was set for February 10 next year.
	   Brown is also expected to be questioned over the disappearance
of 14-year-old Marilyn Wallman who vanished while cycling to school
in Mackay, 205 miles (330 km) south of Townsville, in March 1972.
	   Her body has never been found.
	   Brown is believed to have worked as a government-employed
carpenter in schools in the Townsville area, including the Mackay
sisters' Aitkenvale school.
	   It is understood a breakthrough in the investigation occurred
when the man's granddaughters supplied information to police.
	   Police on Thursday successfully applied to the Townsville
Magistrates Court to take a DNA sample from Brown. 	   
</TEXT>
