<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Palace-Legionnaires' Disease </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Legionnaires' disease bacteria found in Buckingham Palace
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Traces of the potentially fatal Legionnaires'
disease bacteria were found in the Buckingham Palace water supply,
The Sun reported on Friday.
	   The bacteria, which causes pneumonia-like symptoms, was
discovered during routine checks of Queen Elizabeth II's London
residence on Oct. 13, a palace spokesman said, confirming The Sun's
story.
	   ''It was dealt with immediately in the normal way by flushing
out the system,'' the spokesman said, speaking with customary
anonymity. ``Another sample was taken and 10 days later the
all-clear was given.''
	   He said the queen and her husband, Prince Philip, remained at
the palace throughout the scare because the bacteria was only found
in an isolated section of the water system. The palace, built in
1705 and bought by King George III in 1762, has 78 bathrooms and
miles of water pipes.
	   ''Nobody had to flee Buckingham Palace and there were no
reported cases of the disease,'' the spokesman said.
	   Legionnaires' disease is caused by inhaling a common bacteria,
Legionella, often found in moist environments such as
air-conditioning cooling towers, hot water tanks, whirlpool spas
and humidifiers.
	   The pneumonia-like symptoms include fever, headache, shortness
of breath and chest pain. Most at risk are heavy smokers, the
elderly and those with weakened immune systems.
	   The illness was first documented at an American Legion
convention in Philadelphia in July 1976, when 34 died and 221
became sick.
	   During the scare, all 335 palace staff were put on alert to
check with doctors immediately if they came down with any symptoms,
The Sun reported.
	   ''We were all scared,'' The Sun, Britain's largest selling daily
tabloid, quoted an unnamed palace source as saying. ''Any one of us
from the queen down could have been breathing in those bugs.''
	   In February 1997, parts of the palace became infested with mice
and beetles and the palace had to call in a commercial pest control
company.
	   (mb) 	   
</TEXT>
