w2919 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-IraqiZiggurat     12-03 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Iraqi Ziggurat,0571 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Archaeologists say Nebuchadnezzar's ziggurat modeled on Tower of
</HEADLINE>
Babel &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY321 &QL; 
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BORSIPPA, Iraq (AP) _ After 20 years of digging, Austrian
archaeologists say they've determined the layout of a Mesopotamian
ziggurat built by King Nebuchadnezzar about 2,500 years ago _ and
believe it is modeled on the Tower of Babel.
	   Archaeologists say that the Temple of Borsippa, 120 kilometers
(75 miles) south of Baghdad, was a center of learning in ancient
Mesopotamia. The 70-meter (230-foot) temple tower was dedicated to
Nabu, the god of science and learning and the king's protector.
	   ``It must have looked really fantastic,'' said Helga
Trenkwalder, leader of the seven-member Austrian team excavating
the site, which contains remnants of blue-glazed brick, black
layers made of bitumen and millions of mud bricks.
	   The seven-story temple was probably the best preserved of many
ziggurats built by Nebuchadnezzar, said Wilfrid Allinger-Csollich
of the University of Innsbruck. The king is perhaps best remembered
for ordering the destruction of the ancient Jewish temple in
Jerusalem during his 40-year rule.
	   The team found several tablets and a foundation stone that say
the king modeled the Borsippa tower after the Tower of Babel _
whose foundation is 12 kilometers (7 miles) to the north.
	   One text quotes Nebuchadnezzar saying Nabu's tower should reach
the skies and be no less grand than Babel, which was dedicated to
the god Marduk.
	   For 20 years, the archaeological team has shoveled thousands of
tons of debris to uncover most of the 52-meter-tall (172-foot-tall)
remains of the ziggurat.
	   They used equally basic means to determine the original height
of the tower constructed atop a 90-by-90-meter (297-by-297 foot)
foundation.
	   ``We just counted the number of bricks,'' said
Allinger-Csollich.
	   The tower's square bricks were 33 centimeters (13 1/4 inches) on
each side and 8 centimeters (3 1/4 inches) deep.
	   More than 1 million fired bricks were used for the first level's
meter-tall (3-foot-tall) outer wall, Allinger-Csollich said. Each
level was filled with tens of millions of unfired bricks held in
place with beams of cedar from Lebanon.
	   Their picture of the temple's exterior is almost complete. The
first two levels were covered with bitumen and were black. The
third, fourth and fifth were decorated with blue-glazed bricks and
possibly adorned with bulls and lions.
	   The sixth and seventh level, close to the sanctuary, were wholly
made of mud brick.
	   ``For cultic purposes, the Mesopotamians thought mud to be the
purest of substances,'' Trenkwalder said.
	   She said that Nabu's residence was on top and had rooms for
servants and priests ``and wings for his wife, Tachmitum, his
children and daughters.''
	   Allinger-Csollich said texts and detail from the excavations
indicate that a tower of ``greater dimensions than ours existed in
Babylon.''
	   Iraq has another impressive ziggurat in Ur, which was built in
about 2500 B.C. But Nawal al-Mutawali of the Iraq Museum said
Borsippa's remains are ``greater, higher and more elegant.''
	   Dony Youkhanna, assistant director of Iraq's Antiquities
Department, said the government is trying to persuade the United
Nations to declare Borsippa a world heritage site to give it
international protection.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
