<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Australian Open </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With AP Photos
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Faldo gets timely advice from golf legend &QL; 
 &UR; By DENNIS PASSA
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   ADELAIDE, Australia (AP) _ Englishman Nick Faldo, taking advice
from an Australian golf legend, overcame his first-round troubles
to shoot a 3-under-par 69 Friday at the Australian Open.
	   Faldo, following up a disappointing 77 on Thursday, was 2-under
after the front nine that included a run of consecutive birdies on
the sixth, seventh and eighth holes.
	   After his Thursday round, Faldo said he was given some advice by
Norman Von Nida, who won the Australian Open in 1950, 1952 and 1953
and finished second three other times.
	   ``He said the grip pressure in my left hand was too tight, and
gave me a little putting lesson as well,'' Faldo said. ``He told me
to put my right hand stronger to get my right elbow and right
shoulder in the right place.''
	   ``I practiced last night and it was like a new day today.''
	   Faldo bogeyed the toughest hole at Royal Adelaide _ the par-4
15th _ for his only blemish on the back nine, then finished with
birdies on 17 and 18.
	   American Fred Couples, who will play for the U.S. team in next
week's Presidents Cup at Royal Melbourne, double-bogeyed the 14th
and 15th holes Friday en route to his second consecutive 76, giving
him a two-round total of 152, a stroke higher than the projected
cut of 7-over 151.
	   Australian Anthony Edwards shot a 2-under 70 to be among the
first finishers of the day in blustery conditions and under cloudy
skies.
	   Australian Stuart Appleby, the overnight leader by a stroke over
a fivesome that included Greg Norman, had just begun his round
Friday, while Norman had three early bogeys after a 70 Thursday.
	   Norman is playing in his first 72-hole event since coming back
from shoulder surgery.
	   England's Justin Rose, bidding to make his first cut in his
ninth attempt at a professional tournament, was also a late starter
after shooting an opening-round 72. As an amateur, Rose finished
tied for fourth in this year's British Open.
	   On Thursday over the 6,565-meter (7,178-yard) par-72 course,
only 13 players in the 126-man field broke par.
	   (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
