<SLUG> BC-Australia-Indonesia-Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australia welcomes Indonesian election, will assist in
</HEADLINE>
computerizing voting rolls &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Australia on Friday welcomed the
embattled Indonesian government's decision to hold elections next
year and promised to help computerize the electoral rolls to ensure
fair and democratic balloting.
	   Foreign Affairs Minister Alexander Downer said here he hoped the
election would settle a country facing mounting social unrest.
	   ``We welcome the news of an election in Indonesia which we hope
will create a degree of certainty and predictability,'' Downer
said.
	   Indonesian parliamentary elections will be held June 7 and the
nation's highest legislative assembly, the People's Consultative
Assembly, will elect a new president Aug. 29.
	   Downer said Australia will assist with the implementation of a
computerized system of electoral rolls to ensure Indonesia's 202
million people voted in a fair and democratic election.
	   ``This election is likely to be the most democratic Indonesia
has had since the mid-1950s so we very much welcome the advent of
genuine democracy there,'' he said.
	   A democratic government would make Indonesia an ``easier
neighbor to deal with'' than under former President Suharto's
32-year authoritarian rule.
	   There were no immediate plans to evacuate Australians from
Jakarta despite reports of increasing violence, he said.
	   ``We have contingency plans in place should this be the case but
we are monitoring the situation and the plans have not been
upgraded or changed since May when we evacuated Australians,''
Downer said.
	   pjs
