<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Finance chief casts doubt on Japan achieving economic target
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Amid more gloomy news on the economy, Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa expressed doubt Friday that Japan will
achieve its economic target for this fiscal year.
	   The comments came a day after the government announced the
Japanese economy had shrunk at an annualized rate of 2.6 percent in
the July-September quarter.
	   Miyazawa told reporters ``it will be a bit difficult'' to
achieve the government's target for a contraction of 1.8 percent
for the fiscal year ending March 31, 1999.
	   In order to achieve that target, Japan's real gross domestic
product would have to expand by 0.7 percent in both the
October-December and January-March quarters, Miyazawa said.
	   Thursday's quarterly growth announcement marked the first time
the economy has contracted for four consecutive quarters since the
government started compiling growth statistics in 1955.
	   Miyazawa also ruled out more steps to boost Japan's economy in
response to the decision Thursday by European Union governments to
slash interest rates.
	   All countries adopting a single European currency next year cut
their key official interest rates to 3.0 percent, except for Italy,
whose discount rate remained at 3.50 percent.
	   Japan's government recently implemented a record 24 trillion yen
(dlrs 201 billion) economic stimulus package in an attempt to lift
the country out of its worst recession since World War II.
	   The troubles afflicting the world's second-largest economy have
stifled domestic demand, and many business are being starved for
cash as debt-ridden banks scale back on lending.
 &UR; (js-apdj)
