<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar lower against yen, Japanese stocks fall at midday
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with midday trading &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar fell against the yen Friday
morning, pressured by concern over Brazil's economy and an
overnight decline on Wall Street. Japanese stocks continued to lose
ground.
	   The dollar bought 118.37 yen at late morning, down 0.86 yen from
late Thursday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of
118.60 yen overnight.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 159.87 points,
or 1.09 percent, to 14,537.21 points at the end of the morning
session. On Thursday, the index had shed 289.54 points, or 1.93
percent.
	   In currency dealings, the dollar weakened as investors were
discouraged by the continuing decline in U.S. stocks and
Wednesday's defeat in the Brazilian Congress of an important
government austerity measure, traders said.
	   In New York Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell
184.86 points to 8,879.68, largely affected by the Brazilian stock
market's plunge following the move by Congress.
	   On the stock market, share prices were lower as selling was led
by international blue chip shares in line with an overnight fall on
Wall Street.
	   Trading remained quiet as investors retreated to the sidelines
to watch what impact a coordinated rate cut by major European
central banks Thursday will have on the global economy, traders
said.
	   ``Trade is thin because there are many factors in Japan and
overseas working to keep investors out of the market,'' said
Masatoshi Sato, manager of the investor information group at
Kankaku Securities.
	   On the domestic front, market players were monitoring policy
coordination between the ruling Liberal Democratic Party and
opposition Liberal Party, traders said.
	   On Thursday, the Economic Planning Agency said Japan's gross
domestic product contracted 0.7 percent in the July-September
quarter from the previous quarter for an annualized drop of 2.6
percent.
	   The latest GDP, which measures all goods and services produced
in a given period, showed Japan remains mired in its worst
recession since World War II.
	   The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 10.87 points, or 0.96 percent, to 1,118.02. The
TOPIX fell 18.26 points, or 1.59 percent, the previous day.
	   The benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government bond fell to
1.060 percent from Thursday's close of 1.090 percent, driving its
price up to 106.40 yen from the previous day's finish of 106.13
yen.
 &UR; (may-dj-km)
</TEXT>
