<SLUG> BC-Sports-Asian Games </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai police want liquor sales banned at Asian Games
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Some members of Thailand's police force
want liquor sales banned at Asian Games venues following arrests of
drunken fans at a soccer match, the Bangkok Post reported on
Friday.
	   The proposal was denounced by the Thai distributor of Carlsberg,
a Danish brewer which has sponsored the games to the tune of dlrs
10 million and has set up beer stalls at all the stadiums, the Post
said.
	   ``It will be difficult to maintain law and order at sports
complexes if alcoholic drinks are sold there,'' Gen. Ukrit
Patchimsawat, assistant Bangkok police chief, was quoted as saying
by the paper.
	   Ukrit said the proposal will be discussed with Pracha Promnok,
chief of the national police.
	   Police decided to ask for the ban after arresting several
intoxicated fans who threw water bottles on the field during a
Thailand-Hong Kong soccer match on Wednesday.
	   A spokesman for Carlsberg told the Post that the incident may
have been contrived by a rival brewer to discredit Carlsberg. He
said that Carlsberg had sold alcohol at the Southeast Asian Games
in Chiang Mai in 1995 without any negative incidents.
</TEXT>
