<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Asian Games-Ticket Trouble,0692 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian Games ticket sales meet with serious hitches
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By THAKSINA KHAIKAEW &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Ticket sales for the 13th Asian Games
which begin Sunday are a huge mess, disappointing sports fans and
volunteer sales agents alike, say the sellers.
	   Some who booked tickets for the expensive opening ceremony,
paying cash up front, have not received their tickets and have been
abruptly told they will have to pick them up at the stadium on
Sunday.
	   The ticket branch of the games' organizing committee said
Thursday that the more than 38,000 seats available to the general
public were sold out, but outlet operators interviewed by The
Associated Press said they doubted that was true.
	   Most ticket outlets on Thursday were told to stop taking
bookings for the opening.
	   Opening day seats sell for between 1,000 and 5,000 baht (dlrs
27.80 and 139.00).
	   Kanit Isadul, a ticket branch official, said all opening day
ceremony tickets have been sold, but was unable to give a breakdown
by price category, saying the computer system had failed.
	   He claimed 65 million baht (dlrs 1.8 million) in sales for the
opening ceremony, the same amount for the closing ceremony, and 70
million baht (dlrs 1.9 million) so far for all the sporting events
in between, for which ticket prices are considerably lower.
	   Almost half of the 60,000 stadium seats for the opening are
being given away to VIP guests, sports officials and athletes'
families.
	   Some ticket sellers outside Bangkok have not yet received any
tickets for any events, and are adding slight surcharges or paying
out of their own pockets for expenses such as calling in booking to
the head office.
	   The sellers are volunteers working on a not-for-profit basis.
	   At a ticket sales outlet in the northern city of Chiang Mai, a
worker said they haven't received any tickets even though booking
reports and money were sent to the distribution agent in Bangkok
weeks ago.
	   ``Everyday, upset fans call in and ask for the tickets,'' the
worker, who asked not to named, said in a telephone interview.
``They need to see if they have tickets for sure before making
flight and hotel reservations.''
	   Asked about ticket distribution outside Bangkok, Kanit said
sellers were supposed to travel to the capital to collect the
tickets for which they had sold bookings.
	   In the southern city of Hat Yai, a government official selling
tickets at a teachers' college, said he had no such problems.
	   No tickets had been sold there.
	   ``I have not received any calls for ticket bookings,'' said the
	   official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``It could be
either they do not know where to book or they cannot afford it.''
	   An operator of a ticket outlet in Bangkok said she was puzzled
and uncomfortable when the distributor informed her bookings had
been stopped and fans would be required to pick up their tickets in
front of the stadium at Sunday's opening.
	   ``I have made more than 200 bookings and could deliver only
about half to fans,'' she said. ``I have no idea what is going
on.''
	   She said she has been flooded with complaints.
	   Many of the problems are undoubtedly attributable to budget
constraints caused by Thailand's economic crisis, forcing the
organizers to rely on volunteer labor and barter deals.
	   Many sellers are civil servants called upon to volunteer their
labor. They receive a per diem payment which hardly covers their
transport and meal costs.
	   The high-tech tickets sold for the opening ceremony are touted
as ``smart cards'' containing a microchip which allows them to be
used as electronic cash cards.
	   A private company, Power Telecom, agreed to handle production of
the cards in exchange for the right to print its name on them and
have its technology publicized.
	   Games officials said Thursday that tickets for the opening
ceremony can still be purchased directly from the company. But
phone calls to Power Telecom went unanswered all Thursday
afternoon.
</TEXT>
