<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Asian Games-Ball at Home Only,0440 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Goals galore, but for Asian soccer it happens at home only
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DILIP GANGULY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Goals are coming dime a dozen in at the
Asian Games.
	   But the international record of Asia's soccer playing nations
shows that Asian strikers can have a ball with the ball only at
home.
	   Four Asian nations _ Iran, Japan, South Korea and Saudi Arabia _
were among the 32 countries that took part in the 1998 World Cup in
France.
	   The four played a total of 12 games in group competition.
Together they scored a total of only seven goals and conceded 24.
Their performance record was one win _ Iran over the United States
in an emotion-charged match _ two draws and nine losses.
	   In the three days of preliminary matches at the 13th Asian
Games, a goalfeast has produced a total of 60 goals.
	   The South Koreans are at the top of any single highest goal
scoring match with their 11-0 defeat of Mongolia which equaled
Seoul's similar feat at the last games in Hiroshima four years ago.
	   The Mongolians were so upset that at one stage of the match they
placed a defender at the goal line to help out the hapless keeper.
	   The high scoring matches in Thailand do not signify any sudden
change in Asian soccer potential. Instead, the feat is produced by
weaker countries taking beatings.
	   The Nepal team, for example, is fielding a team of mostly
16-year old players. It conceded five goals against the Japanese.
	   Although football is highly popular in each of the more than 40
affiliated members of the Asian Games domain, participation has
been lackluster. In Hiroshima, only 18 countries took part.
	   Twenty-three teams have come to Bangkok, but a strong Saudi
Arabian team pulled out along with its entire national squad.
	   The current tournament has added significance because the 2002
World Cup will be jointly staged by South Korea and Japan.
	   Iran is seen as Asia's best team and favorite at the Games with
Japan having strong potential, fielding some top talents like Naoki
Soma.
	   However, Japan is looking more to the 2000 Olympics and 2002
World Cup and is fielding a team of mostly 20-year-olds.
	   South Korea has the most experienced players and has won three
Asian Games golds.
	   India, with 980 million people and Asia's second most populous
country after China, is unlikely to win any medals.
	   India's Asian Games soccer record lives in history, with a gold
medal in the Game's inaugural tournament in 1951 and a second gold
a decade later at Jakarta.
</TEXT>
