<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Volcano,0158 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican volcano spits ash, red-hot rock
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ The Popocatepetl volcano near Mexico City has
spit a column of ash 2 1/2 miles (4 kms) into the air and showered
red-hot rock onto the flanks of the peak.
	   The brief eruption Thursday, which lasted about one minute, was
expected to cause ash showers in some towns at the foot of the
18,000-foot (5,490-meter) volcano located just 50 miles (80 kms)
southeast of Mexico City, the National Center for Disaster
Prevention reported.
	   The volcano _ whose name means `Smoking Mountain' in the Aztec
Indian language _ had been relatively quiet for several days after
staging similar eruptions last week.
	   Authorities said there was no immediate risk to the 300,000
people who live on the mountain's slopes. About 15 million people
live within a 50-mile (80-km) radius of the volcano, which has been
active since 1994 and regularly emits gas and steam.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Mexico-Volcano; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
