<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Nuclear </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan to sign protocol for stricter nuclear safeguards
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan will sign a nuclear safeguard protocol
designed to give the international nuclear watchdog greater
inspection access amid concerns in Iraq and North Korea, the
government said Friday.
	   The signing was scheduled to take place at the International
Atomic Energy Agency headquarters in Vienna, Austria, later Friday,
making Japan the 34th country to join the new protocol, said
Foreign Ministry spokesman Kunio Nakamura.
	   Japan will also join other signatory countries in urging North
Korea and Iraq to sign the protocol.
	   The document allows IAEA to inspect undeclared nuclear
facilities within 24 hours of the scheduled inspection. The member
countries also will have to declare a wider range of nuclear
facilities and materials.
	   Currently, agency inspectors only have access to facilities
already declared by a member nation.
	   The protocol is expected to give the international nuclear
watchdog a better chance to detect suspicious nuclear facilities
and materials.
	   IAEA approved the new protocol in May 1997 following
international calls for tighter surveillance after inspectors
discovered undeclared nuclear facilities in Iraq and had difficulty
verifying facilities in North Korea.
	   Japan's Cabinet will seek parliamentary approval for
ratification during its next regular session beginning January.
</TEXT>
