w2978 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-LetterBomb 1stLd-Writethru   12-03 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Letter Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Man accused of letter bombings in custody in hospital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with suspect in custody. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos available
 &UR; By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ The man police believe terrorized
Australia with a letter-bombing campaign against tax officials and
human rights officials was detained Friday in a hospital in
Canberra.
	   Australian Federal Police launched a nationwide manhunt on
Wednesday for 43-year-old Colin George Dunstan, a former Australian
Tax Office employee, after 22 parcel bombs were discovered at the
Canberra mail center, addressed mainly to tax office staff.
	   Police spokesman Daryl Webb said police are looking forward to
speaking to Dunstan.
	   A further five potentially lethal bombs have been found in
Sydney, Melbourne and the Gold Coast.
	   It is not clear yet how Dunstan came to be in the hospital or
how police learned of his whereabouts.
	   On Friday police found a 27th letter bomb in a Sydney post
office and a train was halted and evacuated for a search.
	   The bomb at the Darlinghurst post office in Sydney was detonated
safely by police shortly after it was discovered at 8:15 a.m. The
train, also in Sydney, continued its journey when no suspicious
package was found aboard.
	   Police, ambulance and fire crews were also called to the Penrith
branch of the Australian Taxation Office in western Sydney after
the discovery of another suspicious package.
	   Government and business offices as far apart as Melbourne, on
Australia's southeast coast and its northernmost capital of Darwin,
as well as the Centrepoint Tower shopping center and office tower
in Sydney were evacuated Thursday in a series of false alarms.
	   ``It's a reminder that that kind of urban terrorism, I suppose,
is a modern day reality in every society,'' Prime Minister John
Howard said Friday on radio.
	   ``We've been refreshingly freer of it than most other societies
and I hope that continues to be the case.
	   ``But unhinged human nature can become a very lethal weapon if
it's triggered off by particular events,'' he said.
	   Twenty-seven potentially lethal parcel bombs have been found at
addresses in Sydney, Canberra, Melbourne and the Gold Coast over
the past 48 hours.
	   Most of the potentially deadly parcels had been addressed to
former or current Australian Taxation Office staff, but some
members of the Human Rights Commission also were targeted.
	   Police have named as the sole suspect Dunstan, a suspended tax
officer who got embroiled in an affair with a woman at his office.
	   Dunstan has been involved in a sexual harassment case at the tax
office in Canberra involving the woman he had the relationship
with, and was appealing his dismissal to the Federal Court.
	   Only the first of the letter bombs has caused any injury.
	   Two postal workers, at the Canberra mail sorting center were
slightly injured, after one of them threw one of the letter bombs
into a mail bag early Wednesday morning.
	   Police say they cannot be sure there are no more letter bombs in
Australia's mail system, which is presently overflowing with
Christmas parcels.
	   They have urged people throughout Australia to be cautious if
they see suspicious parcels in their mail.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
