<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Drug Seizure,0172 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police seize three-ton cocaine shipment in Caribbean port
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ Police on Thursday seized at least three
tons of cocaine in a maritime warehouse in the Caribbean port city
of Cartagena.
	   The cocaine was hidden in a shipment of paint destined for the
United States, police spokesman Col. Bejamin Munoz said in a radio
interview. Police were continuing their search and believed they
might find more cocaine, he said.
	   Cartagena was the location this week of a conference of the
hemisphere's defense ministers at which military leaders from
around the Americas pledged greater cooperation in the fight
against illegal narcotics.
	   The seizure Thursday was the second major cocaine discovery this
year in Cartagena, a popular tourist destination 400 miles (650
kilometers) north of Bogota.
	   In July, authorities seized seven tons of cocaine hidden in
metal containers marked as containing nylon. The shipment was
headed for the United States by way of Mexico.
</TEXT>
