<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Yasuda-Cigna </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yasuda Fire and Marine, Cigna International to form joint venture
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Yasuda Fire and Marine Insurance Co., a major
Japanese non-life insurer, and U.S.-based Cigna International
Holdings Ltd. have agreed to set up a joint venture brokerage, a
Yasuda official said Friday.
	   The two companies will set up an equally owned joint venture in
April 1999 to enter the defined contribution-type pension business
in Japan, said Yasuda spokesman Shin Toyofuku.
	   Other details, including the name of the new venture and its
working capital, have yet to be decided, he said.
	   The agreement between Yasuda and Cigna comes as Japan implements
its ``Big Bang'' financial deregulation measures aimed at
invigorating the economy by opening up markets to greater
competition.
	   Earlier this week, Tokio Marine and Fire Insurance Co., a major
Japanese insurer, said it is looking into a possible joint venture
in Japan with U.S. discount brokerage Charles Schwab and Co.
	   Yasuda Fire and Marine and the Philadelphia, Pa.-based Cigna,
have maintained a close business relationship since 1972. Yasuda
Fire has a 10 percent stake in Cigna's Japanese unit, INA Himawari
Life Insurance.
	   Cigna International is a unit of Cigna Corp., which provides
insurance, health care and financial services.
 &UR; (km-dj)
</TEXT>
