<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Executions </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese courts put 22 to death in two cities
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ A brother-and-sister team of bank robbers and a
factory worker who raped 11 school girls were among 22 people put
to death in two Chinese cities, state media reported Friday.
	   Courts in Beijing and Urumqi, capital of China's
northwesternmost region of Xinjiang, ordered the executions
Thursday after appeals courts upheld the previously issued death
sentences, the reports said.
	   In Urumqi, all 15 convicted criminals ordered put to death were
taken out and shot, the Legal Daily reported. The Beijing Daily did
not say how the seven were executed, although firing squad is the
usual method.
	   The Legal Daily said Zou Lilun and his sister Zou Liqun were
executed for robbing an Urumqi bank of 693,000 yuan (dlrs 84,000)
on Sept. 11. Zou Lilun and his older brother, whose case is being
handled separately, killed one person in the bank; she drove the
getaway car, the newspaper said.
	   Beijing's No. 2 Intermediate People's Court ordered Liu Gang, an
electronics factory worker, to pay 24,000 yuan (dlrs 2,900) in
compensation to the victims of his four-month raping and robbing
spree that started in Sept. 1997, the Beijing Daily reported.
	   Liu targeted 10- to 14-year-old girls; he followed them home
from school and then posed as someone delivering a letter to get
inside, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
