<SLUG> BC-Sports-Swimming-World Cup,0241 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Belgian swimmer sets breaststroke record in FINA World Cup
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) _ Frederik deBurghgraeve of Belgium
broke his own short-course world record in the 100-meter
breaststroke Thursday night in the FINA Swimming World Cup.
	   DeBurghgraeve considered not swimming in the 100 breaststroke
final to save his strength for other races.
	   ``Normally I would stretch and swim only the 50-meter freestyle
in the finals,'' deBurghgraeve said. ``But I had second thoughts
and decided to swim the 100-meter breaststroke.''
	   DeBurghgraeve broke Jeremy Linn's U.S. Open record of 1 minute,
.08 seconds, finishing in 58.79 seconds.
	   Josh Davis, Megan Quann, Natalie Coughlin set American and U.S.
Open records.
	   Davis of Texas Aquatics won the 200 individual medley in
1:56.66, breaking the American record of 1:57.47 set last year by
Ron Karnaugh, and Pablo Morales' 1987 U.S. Open record of 1:58.16.
	   Davis came back later in the competition and won the 200
backstroke in 1:54.55.
	   Quann, 14, of Puyallup Aquatics swam a 1:07.41 in the 100
breaststroke, breaking Tracy Caulkins 1981 records of 1:07.47.
	   Quann also recorded the American and U.S. Open records in the 50
breaststroke with a split of 31.86 in the 100 breast. The old
record was 31.88.
	   Coughlin, 16, of Terrapins Swim Club swam the 200 back in
2:07.46, breaking Lia Oberstar's time of 2:07.52.
</TEXT>
